<L N="1604">For I woll paye you / wele and redily</L>
<L>From daye to daye / and yf so be I faile</L>
<L>I am your wyf / score it vp on my taill/</L>
<L>And I shall paye / as sone / as euere I may</L>
<L N="1608">For by my trouth / I haue on myn array</L>
<L>And nat on wast bestowed euery dele</L>
<L>And for I haue bestowed it so wele</L>
<L>For your honour / for goddes sake I sey</L>
<L N="1612">As beth nat wroth / but let vs laugh and pley</L>
<L>Ye shull my ioly body / han to wedd</L>
<L>By god I woll nat paye you but a-bedde
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="401"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="180"></L>
<L>Foryeve it me / myn owen spouse dere</L>
<L N="1616">Turne hiderward / and maketh better chere</L>
<L>This Merchaunt sawe / ther was no remedye</L>
<L>And for to chide / it were but folye</L>
<L>Seth that the thyng/ may nat amended be</L>
<L N="1620">Now wyf he seid/ and I foryeve it the</L>
<L>But by thy lyf/ ne be no more so large</L>
<L>Kepe bet thy gode / this yeve I the in charge</L>
<L>Thus endeth my tale / and god vs send.</L>
<L N="1624">Taillyng ynough / vn-to our lyves end.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endeth the Shipmannes tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="402">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="181">
<HEAD>and the Hoost begynneth to speke</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wele seid by Corpus Dominus / koth our Hoost/.<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="177a"></L>
<L>Now long mot &thorn;ou saill/ by the coost/</L>
<L>Sire gentill Maister / gentill Marynere</L>
<L N="1628">God yeve the Monk / a thousand last quadyere</L>
<L>A ha felawes / beth ware / of soch a iape</L>
<L>The monk put / in the mannes hode an ape</L>
<L>And in his wyfes eke / by seint Austyn</L>
<L N="1632">Draweth monkes no more vn-to your in</L>
<L>But now passe ouere / and let vs seke about/</L>
<L>Who shall now tell first/ of all this rout/</L>
<L>Another tale / and with that worde he seid.</L>
<L N="1636">As curteisly / as it hade ben a meid.</L>
<L>My lady Prioresse / by your leue</L>
<L>So that I wist/ I shold you nat agreve</L>
<L>I wold deme / that ye tellen shold</L>
<L N="1640">A tale next/ yf so were that ye wold</L>
<L>Now woll ye vouche it saaf/ my lady dere</L>
<L>Gladly koth she / and seid as ye shull here
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000425.tif" N="403"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="182">
<HEAD>Here begynneth &thorn;e Prioresse prolog of Dominus dominus noster<NOTE PLACE="head">[No gaps in the MS. between the stanzas.]</NOTE> </HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O Lord our lord / thy name / How merveilous</L>
<L>Is in this large world ysprad koth she</L>
<L>For nat onely thy laude / precious</L>
<L N="1646">Perfourmed is / by men of dignitee</L>
<L>But by the mouth of children thy bountee</L>
<L>Perfourmed is / for on the brest soukyng</L>
<L N="1649">Som tyme / shewen they / thyn herying</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wherfore in laud / as I best can or may</L>
<L>Of the / and of the white lilly flour</L>
<L>Which that the bare / and is a maide all-way</L>
<L N="1653">To tell a storie I woll do my labour</L>
<L>Nought that I may encrece hir honour</L>
<L>For she hir-self/ is honour and &thorn;e rote</L>
<L N="1656">Of bounte next hir son / and soules bote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O moder maide / o maide moder free</L>
<L>O bussh vnbrent/ brennyng in Moises sight/.</L>
<L>That ravysshedest doun / from the deitee<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="177b"></L>
<L N="1660">Thurgh thyn humblesse / the gost &thorn;at in the light/</L>
<L>Of whos vertue / whan he thy goost light/</L>
<L>Conceyued was / the faders sapience</L>
<L>Helpe me to tell it/ in thy reuerence]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Eg. 2726</B> <I>ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lady thyn bountee / thyn magnificence<MILESTONE N="156a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thy vertu / and thyn gret humylitee</L>
<L>There may no tonge expresse / in no science</L>
<L N="1667">ffor som tyme lady / or men preyen to the</L>
<L>Thow gost biforn / of thyn benygnytee</L>
<L>And getest vs the light / of thyn preyere</L>
<L N="1670">To gyden vs / vn-to thy sone so deere
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="404"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My konnyng is so weyke / o blisful Quene</L>
<L>ffor to declare / thyn gret worthynesse</L>
<L>That I ne may / the weight nat sustene</L>
<L N="1674">But as a child / of twelmoneth old or lasse</L>
<L>That can vnethe / any word expresse</L>
<L>Right so fare I / &amp; therfore I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L N="1677">Gydeth my song / that I shal of &yogh;ow seye</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&para; Here bigynneth the Prioresse hire Tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There was in Assye / in a gret Citee</L>
<L>A-monges cristene folk / a Iewerie</L>
<L N="1680">Sustened by a lord / of that contree</L>
<L>ffor foul vsure / and lucre of vilenye<NOTE PLACE="marg">turpe lucrum</NOTE></L>
<L>Hateful to crist / and to his compaignye</L>
<L>And thurgh this strete / men myght ride or wende</L>
<L N="1684">ffor it was free / and open at either ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A litel scole / of cristene folk there stode</L>
<L>Doun atte ferthere ende / in which there were</L>
<L>Children an hep / I-comen of cristene blode</L>
<L N="1688">That lerned in that scole / &yogh;er by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Swich manere doctrine / as men vsed there</L>
<L>This is to seyn / to syngen and to rede</L>
<L N="1691">As smale children doon / in here childhede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A-monges theise children / was a wydewes sone</L>
<L>A litel clergeoun / seuene &yogh;er of age</L>
<L>That day by day / to scole was his wone</L>
<L N="1695">And eke also / where as he sey the ywage</L>
<L>Of cristes moder / had he in vsage</L>
<L>As him was taught / to knele adoun and seye</L>
<L N="1698">his Aue marie / as he goth by the weye
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="405"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus hath this wydewe / hire litel sone I-taught</L>
<L>Oure blisseful lady / cristes moder deere</L>
<L>To worshipe ay / and forgat it nought</L>
<L N="1702">ffor sely child / wil alwey sone lere</L>
<L>But ay whan I remembre / on this matere</L>
<L>Seynt Nicholas stant euere / in my presence</L>
<L>ffor he so &yogh;ong / to criste dide reuerence<MILESTONE N="156b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This litel child / his litel bok lernynge</L>
<L>As he sat in the scole / at his prymer</L>
<L>he Alma redemptoris / herde synge</L>
<L N="1709">As children lerned / here Antiphoner</L>
<L>And as he durste / he drow him ner &amp; ner</L>
<L>And herkened ay the wordes / &amp; the note</L>
<L N="1712">Til he the first vers coude / al by rote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nat wist he / what this latyn was to seye</L>
<L>ffor he so &yogh;ong / and tendre was of age</L>
<L>But on a day / his felawe gan he preye</L>
<L N="1716">To expounden him this song / in his langage</L>
<L>Or telle him why this song / was in vsage</L>
<L>This preyed he him / to construen and declare</L>
<L N="1719">fful ofte tyme / vp-oon his knees bare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His felawe / which / that eldere was than he</L>
<L>Answered him thus / this song I haue herd seye</L>
<L>Was maked / of oure blisseful lady free</L>
<L N="1723">Hire to salue / and eke hire for to preye</L>
<L>To ben oure help / and socour whan we deye</L>
<L>I can no more expounde / in this matere</L>
<L N="1726">I lerne song / I can but smal gramere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And is this song / maked in reuerence</L>
<L>Of cristes moder / seide this Innocent</L>
<L>Now certes / I wol do my diligence</L>
<L N="1730">To conne it al / or cristemasse be went
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="406"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="185"></L>
<L>Though that I / for my primer / shal be shent</L>
<L>And shal be betyn / thries in an houre</L>
<L N="1733">I wol it conne / oure lady for to honoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his felawe taught him homward / pryuely</L>
<L>ffro day to day / til he coude it by rote</L>
<L>And thanne / he song it wel and boldly</L>
<L N="1737">ffor word to word / a-cordyng with the note</L>
<L>Twyes a day / it passed thurgh his throte</L>
<L>To scoleward &amp; homward / whan he wente</L>
<L N="1740">On Cristes moder / set was his entente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; As I haue seid / thurgh-out the Iuerye</L>
<L>This litel child / as he come to and froo</L>
<L>fful myrily wold he synge / and crie</L>
<L N="1744">O Alma redemptoris / euere moo</L>
<L>The swetnesse his herte / perced so</L>
<L>Of cristes moder / that to hire to preye</L>
<L N="1747">he can nat stynt / of syngynge by the weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oure first foo / the serpent Sathanas</L>
<L>That hath in Iewes herte / his waspes nest</L>
<L>Vp swal and seide / o Hebrayk peeple allas<MILESTONE N="157a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1751">Is this to &yogh;ow a thyng / that is honest</L>
<L>That swich a boy / shal walken as him lest</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure despit / and synge of swich sentence</L>
<L N="1754">Which is a-geyns / oure lawes reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffro thens-forth / the Iewes han conspired</L>
<L>This Innocent / out of this world to chace</L>
<L>An homycyde / ther-to han they hyred</L>
<L N="1758">That in an aleye / had a pryue place</L>
<L>And as the child / gan forby for to pace</L>
<L>This cursed Iew / him hente / and helde him fast</L>
<L N="1761">And kyt his throte / and in a pyt him cast
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="407"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I seye that in a wardrope / they him threwe</L>
<L>Where as theise Iewes / purgen here entraille</L>
<L N="1764">O cursed folk / of herodes al newe</L>
<L>what may &yogh;oure euele entent / &yogh;ow a-vaille<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; legamus apocalipsim Iohannis &amp; ibi reperi|mus agnum super montem syon &amp; cum illo cxliiij<SUP>or</SUP> milia signatorum &amp;c. qui cantant canticum nouum &amp;c. Isti sunt qui cum mulieri|bus se non coinquinauerunt virgines autem permanserunt / hii sunt qui secuntur agnum quocunque vadit &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mordre wol out / certeyn it wol nat faille</L>
<L>And namely there / as the honour / of god / shal sprede</L>
<L N="1768">The blod out crieth / on &yogh;oure cursed dede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O martir souded / to virginite</L>
<L>Now maistow syngen / &amp; folwen euere in oon</L>
<L>The white lamb / celestial quod she</L>
<L N="1772">Of which the gret Ewangelist seynt Iohn</L>
<L>In pathmos wrot / which seith / that they that gon</L>
<L>Biforn this lamb / &amp; synge a song al newe</L>
<L>That neuere flesshly wommen they ne knewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">i. e. carnaliter</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This pouere wydewe / a-waiteth al that nyght</L>
<L>After hire litel child / but he cam nought</L>
<L>ffor which as sone / as it was dayes light</L>
<L N="1779">With face pale of drede / and bisy thought</L>
<L>She hath atte scole / and elles where him sought</L>
<L>Til finaly / she gan so fer a-spie</L>
<L N="1782">That he last seyn was / in the Iuerie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With modres pitee / in hire brest enclosed</L>
<L>She gooth as she were half / out of hire mynde</L>
<L>To euery place / where she hath supposed</L>
<L N="1786">By lyklied / hire litel child to fynde</L>
<L>And euere on cristes moder / meke and kynde</L>
<L>She criede and at the laste thus she wroughte</L>
<L N="1789">Amonges the cursed Iewes / she him soughte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; She freyneth and she preyeth / pitously</L>
<L>To euery Iew / that dwelled in thilke place</L>
<L>To telle hire if hire child / went ought for-by</L>
<L N="1793">They seiden nay / but ihesu of his grace
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="408"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="187"></L>
<L>&YOGH;af in hire thought / with-Inne a litel space<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That in that place / after hire sone she criede</L>
<L N="1796">Where as he was casten / in a pyt byside</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O grete god / that performest thy laude</L>
<L>By mouth of Innocentes / lo here thy myght</L>
<L>This gemme of chastite / this Emeraude</L>
<L N="1800">And eke of Martirdom / the rubie bryght</L>
<L>There he with throte / I-koruen / lay vpright</L>
<L>he Alma redemptoris / gan to synge</L>
<L N="1803">So loude / that al the place / gan to rynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The cristene folk / that thurgh the strete wente</L>
<L>In comen / for to wondre vp-oon this thyng</L>
<L>And hastifly / they for the Prouost sente</L>
<L N="1807">he com a-noon / with-outen tariyng</L>
<L>And herieth crist / that is of heuene kyng</L>
<L>And eke his moder / honour of mankynde</L>
<L N="1810">And after that / the Iewes let be bynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This child with pitous lamentacion</L>
<L>vp taken was / syngyng his song alwey<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De puero qui cantauit de gloriosa virgine.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with the honour / of gret procession</L>
<L N="1814">They carien him / vn-to the next abbey</L>
<L>his moder swoughnyng / by his bere lay</L>
<L>vn-ethe myght the peeple / that was there</L>
<L>This newe Rachel / bryngen froo his bere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Rachel plorans filios suos &amp; noluit conso|lari &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With turment / and with shameful deth echon</L>
<L>This Prouest / doth the Iewes for to sterue<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De maria quicquit puer sciuit / cantum enu|triuit / maternam inopiam hunc Iudeus nequam strauit domo sua quem humauit diram per inuidiam Mater querens / hunc vocauit / hic in terra recantauit / solita preconia // Puer liber mox exiuit mortis reos lex puniuit / Iudeos &amp; cetera.</NOTE></L>
<L>That of this morder wist / &amp; that a-noon</L>
<L N="1821">he nolde no swich cursednesse / obserue</L>
<L>Iuel shal haue / that euel wol deserue</L>
<L>Therfore with wilde hors / he dede hem drawe</L>
<L N="1824">And after that / he heng hem by the lawe
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="409"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vp-on this bere / ay lith this Innocent</L>
<L>Biforn the chef auter / while the masse laste</L>
<L>And after that / the Abbot with his couent</L>
<L N="1828">han sped hem / to burien him ful faste</L>
<L>And whan they haly water / on him kaste</L>
<L>&YOGH;et spak this child / whan spreynt was the hali water</L>
<L N="1831">And sang / O Alma redemptoris mater</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Abbot / which that was / an holy man</L>
<L>As monkes ben / or elles oughten be</L>
<L>This &yogh;onge child / to coniure he bigan</L>
<L N="1835">And seide / o dere child / I halse the</L>
<L>In vertu / of the holy Trynyte<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>leaf</I> 158<I>gone</I></NOTE></L>
<L>[Tell me what is thy cause for to syng<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>Egerton 2726</B>, <I>on leaf</I>179, <I>back</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1838">Seth &thorn;at thy throte is kut / to my semyng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My throte is kut / vn-to my nek bone</L>
<L>Seid this child and as by weye of kynd.</L>
<L>I shold haue died / ye long tyme agone</L>
<L N="1842">But Ihesu Crist / as ye in bokes fynd.</L>
<L>woll that his glorie last / and be in mynd.</L>
<L>And for the worshipe of his moder dere</L>
<L N="1845">Yitte may I syng / o Alma loude and clere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This well of mercy / cristes moder swete</L>
<L>I loued all wey / as after my kunnyng</L>
<L>And whan that I / my lyf shold forlete</L>
<L N="1849">To me she cam / and bad me for to syng/</L>
<L>This antym verrely in my dying/.</L>
<L>As ye han herd / and whan &thorn;at I hade song</L>
<L N="1852">Me thought she leid a greyn / vp on my tong /.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wherfore I syng/ and syng I mot certeyn<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="180a"></L>
<L>In honour / of that blisfull maiden free</L>
<L>Till from my tung / of taken is &thorn;e corn</L>
<L N="1856">And after that / this seid she to me
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="410"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="189"></L>
<L>My litle child/ now woll I fecche the</L>
<L>Whan that the greyn / is from thy tung ytake</L>
<L N="1859">Be nat agast/ I woll the nat forsake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This holy monk/ this Abbot / hym mene I.</L>
<L>His tung out caught/ and toke awey &thorn;e greyn</L>
<L>And he yave vp the gost / full softely</L>
<L N="1863">And whan this Abbot / hade this wonder seyn</L>
<L>His salt teres/ trykled doun as reyn</L>
<L>And gruff he fell all plat / vp-on &thorn;e ground</L>
<L N="1866">And still he lay / as he hade leyn ybound.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Couent eke / lay vp-on tha pament/</L>
<L>wepyng/ and herien cristes moder dere</L>
<L>And after that/ they rise / and forth ben went/</L>
<L N="1870">And toke awey / this martir / from his bere</L>
<L>And in a toumbe / of marbell stones clere</L>
<L>Enclosen they / this litle body swete</L>
<L N="1873">There he is now / god lene vs for to mete</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O yong Hugh of Lyncoln slayn also</L>
<L>with cursed Iewes / as it is notable</L>
<L>ffor it is but a litle while agoo</L>
<L N="1877">Pray eke for vs / we synfull folk vnstable</L>
<L>That of his mercy / god so merciable</L>
<L>On vs his grete mercy / multiplie</L>
<L N="1880">ffor the reuerence / of his moder marie / Amen /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit fabula Priorisse /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="411">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="190">
<HEAD>&amp; incipit/ prologus de Sir Thopas per Chaucer narratus</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan seid was this myracle / euery man</L>
<L>As sobre was / that wonder was to se</L>
<L>Till that our hoost / Iape to began</L>
<L N="1884">And than at erst/ he loked vp-on me /</L>
<L>And seid thus / what man art &thorn;ou koth he</L>
<L>Thow lokest / as &thorn;ou woldest fynd an hare</L>
<L N="1887">ffor ever vp-on the ground I se the stare<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="180b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Approche nere / and loke vp merely</L>
<L>Now ware &thorn;ou sirs / and let &thorn;is man haue place</L>
<L>He in the waste / was shape as wele as I.</L>
<L N="1891">This were a popet/ in an arme to enbrace</L>
<L>ffor ony womman small / and feire of face</L>
<L>Hym semeth elvissh / by his countenaunce</L>
<L N="1894">ffor vn-to no wight / doth he daliaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sey &thorn;ou now somwhat/ sen other folk han seid.</L>
<L>Tell vs a tale of merth / and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>Hoste koth he / ne beth nat/ euyll appayed.</L>
<L N="1898">ffor other tale certes / kan I none</L>
<L>But of a Ryme / I lerned long agone</L>
<L>Ye / that is gode koth he / now shull we here</L>
<L N="1901">Som deyntous thyng/ me thynketh/ by his chere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit prologus de Chaucers</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="412">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="191">
<HEAD>et incipit fabula sua de Sir Thopas</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Fit I.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[Each third line is on the right of its couple, in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Listeneth lordynges / in gode intent/</L>
<L>And I woll tell verament</L>
<L N="1903">Of merth and of solace</L>
<L>All of a kyng was / faire and gent/</L>
<L>In bataill and in turnement</L>
<L N="1907">His name was Sir Thopace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yborn he was / in fer cuntre</L>
<L>In flaundres all by-yond &thorn;e se</L>
<L N="1910">At Poperyng in the place</L>
<L>His fader was a man full fre</L>
<L>And lord he was / of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="1913">As it was goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sir Thopas wax / a doughti swayn</L>
<L>white was his face / as payndemayn</L>
<L N="1916">His lippes rede as nose</L>
<L>His rode is like / Scarlet in greyn</L>
<L>And I you tell / in gode serteyn</L>
<L N="1919">He hade a semely nose</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His here his berd was like saffron</L>
<L>That to his girdle raught adoun</L>
<L N="1922">His shone of Cordwane</L>
<L>Of brugges were his hosen broun</L>
<L>His robe was of Syklatoun</L>
<L N="1925">That cost many a Iane
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="413"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He coude hunt at wild dere</L>
<L>And ride an haukyng by Ryvere</L>
<L N="1928">with grey goshauke / on honde</L>
<L>There-to he was / a grete Archere</L>
<L>Of wrastlyng / was &thorn;er noon his pere</L>
<L N="1931">There ony Ram shold stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffull many a maide bright in bour<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="181a"></L>
<L>They mourne / for his paramour</L>
<L N="1934">whan hem were bet/ to slepe]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Eg. 2726 <I>ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>But he was chast and no lechour<MILESTONE N="159a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And swete as is the brambel flour</L>
<L N="1937">That bereth the red hepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so it fel vp-on a day</L>
<L>ffor sothe as I &yogh;ow telle may</L>
<L N="1940">Sire Thopas wold out ride</L>
<L>he worth vp-on his steede gray</L>
<L>And in his hond a launce gay</L>
<L N="1943">A long swerd by his side</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he pryketh thurgh a fair forest</L>
<L>Ther-Inne is many a wylde best</L>
<L N="1946">&YOGH;a bothe Buk and hare</L>
<L>And as he priketh North and Est</L>
<L>I telle it &yogh;ow him had almest</L>
<L N="1949">bitidde a sory kare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There springen erbes grete &amp; smale</L>
<L>The lycoris and the cetewale</L>
<L N="1952">And many a clowe gylophre</L>
<L>And Notemuge to putte in ale</L>
<L>Wheither it be moyst or stale</L>
<L N="1955">Or for to leyn in coffre
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="414"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The briddes songen it is no nay</L>
<L>The Sparhauk and the Popyngay</L>
<L N="1958">That ioye it was to heere</L>
<L>The thrustelcok mad eke hire lay</L>
<L>The wode-dowe vp-on a spray</L>
<L N="1961">she sang ful loude &amp; clere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire Thopas fel in loue longyng</L>
<L>Al whan he herd / the thrustel syng</L>
<L N="1964">&amp; pryked as he were wood</L>
<L>his fair steede in his prekyng</L>
<L>So swatte / &thorn;at men myght him wryng</L>
<L N="1967">his sides were al blod</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire Thopas eke so wery was</L>
<L>ffor prikyng on the softe gras</L>
<L N="1970">So fiers was his corage</L>
<L>That doun he leid him in that place</L>
<L>To make his steede som solace</L>
<L N="1973">and &yogh;af him good forage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Seynte Mary benedicite</L>
<L>What eyleth this loue at me</L>
<L N="1976">To bynde me so sore</L>
<L>Me dremed al this nyght parde</L>
<L>An Elf Quene shal my lemman be</L>
<L N="1979">And slepe vnder my gore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An Elf Quene wil I loue I-wys</L>
<L>ffor in this world no womman is</L>
<L N="1982">worthy to be my make //</L>
<L>In towne</L>
<L>Alle othere wommen I forsake</L>
<L>And to an Elf Quene I me take</L>
<L N="1986">by dale and eke by downe
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="415"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="194"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In-to his sadel he clom a-noon</L>
<L>And priketh ouer stile and ston</L>
<L N="1989">An Elf Quene for to espie</L>
<L>Til he so longe hath ryde &amp; gon</L>
<L>That he fond in a pryue won</L>
<L N="1992">The contreye of fairie</L>
<L>So wylde</L>
<L>ffor in that contrey was &thorn;ere noon</L>
<L>That to him durst ride or gon</L>
<L N="1996">Neither wyf ne childe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Til that &thorn;ere com a gret geaunt</L>
<L>his name was sire Olifaunt</L>
<L N="1999">a parilous man of dede</L>
<L>he seide child by Termagaunt</L>
<L>But if thow prike out of myn haunt<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2002">Anoon I slee thyn steede //</L>
<L>With Mace</L>
<L>heere is the Quene of fairye</L>
<L>With harpe &amp; pipe &amp; symphonye</L>
<L N="2006">Dwellyng in this place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The child seide also mot I the</L>
<L>To-morwe wol I mete the</L>
<L N="2009">Whan I haue myn Armoure</L>
<L>And &yogh;et I hope par ma fay</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou shalt with this launce gay</L>
<L N="2012">abyen it ful soure</L>
<L>Thy mawe</L>
<L>I shal perce if I may</L>
<L>Or it be fully prime of day</L>
<L N="2016">ffor heere thow shalt be slawe
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="416"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="195"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire Thopas drow a-bak ful faste</L>
<L>This Geaunt at him stones caste</L>
<L N="2019">Out of a fel staf slynge</L>
<L>But faire a-skapith child Thopas</L>
<L>And al it was thurgh goddes gras</L>
<L N="2022">And thurgh his fair berynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et listeneth lordes to my tale</L>
<L>Meriere than the Nyghtyngale</L>
<L N="2025">I wol &yogh;ow rowne</L>
<L>how sire Thopas with sydes smale</L>
<L>Prykyng ouer hil and dale</L>
<L N="2028">Is come a-geyn to towne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his merie men comaunded he</L>
<L>To make him bothe game &amp; gle</L>
<L N="2031">ffor nedes must he fighte</L>
<L>With a Geaunt with hedes thre</L>
<L>ffor paramour and Iolite</L>
<L N="2034">Of on that shon ful brighte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Do come he seide my Mynestrales</L>
<L>And gestoures for to telle tales</L>
<L N="2037">A-non in myn armyng</L>
<L>Of romaunces that ben reals</L>
<L>Of Popes and of Cardynales</L>
<L N="2040">And eke of loue longyng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>They fette him first swete wyn</L>
<L>And Mede eke in a Maselyn</L>
<L N="2043">And real spicerie</L>
<L>Of gyngerbred that was ful fyn</L>
<L>And lycoris and eke Comyn</L>
<L N="2046">with sugre &thorn;at is trie
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="417"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="196"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he dede next his white ler</L>
<L>Of cloth of lake fyn &amp; cler</L>
<L N="2049">A breche &amp; eke a sherte</L>
<L>And next his shert an Aketon</L>
<L>And ouer that an haberion</L>
<L N="2052">ffor percyng of his herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ouer that a fyn hauberk</L>
<L>Was al I-wrought of Iewes werk</L>
<L N="2055">fful strong it was of plate</L>
<L>And ouer that his cote armour</L>
<L>As white as is a lilie flour</L>
<L N="2058">In which he wol debate</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his sheld was al of gold so red</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere Inne was a Bores hed</L>
<L N="2061">A charbocle be his syde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he swor on ale &amp; bred</L>
<L>how that the Geaunt shal be ded</L>
<L N="2064">bityde what bytyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hise Iambeus were of quyrbuly</L>
<L>his swerd shede of yuory</L>
<L N="2067">helme of laton bright</L>
<L>His sadel was of rewel bon<MILESTONE N="160a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his brydel as the sonne shon</L>
<L N="2070">Or as the Mone light</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his spere was of fyn Cypres</L>
<L>That bodeth werre &amp; no thyng pes</L>
<L N="2073">the hed ful sharp I-grounde</L>
<L>his steede was al appel gray</L>
<L>It goth an aumble in the wey</L>
<L N="2076">fful softly &amp; rounde
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="418"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="197"></L>
<L>In londe</L>
<L>loo lordes myn heere is a fyt</L>
<L>If &yogh;e wyln any more of it</L>
<L N="2080">To telle it I wol fonde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Second Fit.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now holde &yogh;oure mouth par charite</L>
<L>Bothe knyght and lady free</L>
<L N="2083">and herkeneth to my spelle</L>
<L>Of bataille and of cheualry</L>
<L>And of ladies loue drury</L>
<L N="2086">A-noon I wol &yogh;ow telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men speken of romaunces of pris</L>
<L>Of horn Child and of ypotis</L>
<L N="2089">Of Beus and Sire Guy</L>
<L>Of sire libeus and pleyndamour</L>
<L>But sire Thopas he bereth the flour</L>
<L N="2092">Of real Chyualrie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his good steede al he bystrod</L>
<L>And forth vp-on his weye he wold<NOTE PLACE="inter">rod</NOTE></L>
<L N="2095">As sparcle out of the brond</L>
<L>Vp-on his creste he bar a Tour</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-Inne stiked a lilye flour</L>
<L N="2098">god shilde his cors fro shonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And forth he was knyght Auntrous</L>
<L>he nolde slepen in noon hous</L>
<L N="2101">But lyggen in his hode</L>
<L>his bright helm was his wonger</L>
<L>And by him baiteth his destrer</L>
<L N="2104">Of Erbes fyve &amp; goode
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="419"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="198"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>him self drank water of the welle</L>
<L>As dede the knyght sire Parcyuelle</L>
<L>so worthy vnder wede;</L>
<L N="2108">Til on a day
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="420"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="199"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No more of this / for goddes dignytee</L>
<L>Quod oure hoost / for thow makest me</L>
<L>So wery / of thyn verray lewednesse</L>
<L N="2112">That also wysly / god my soule blisse</L>
<L>Myne Eres aken / of thy drasty speche</L>
<L>Now swich a ryme / the deuele I be-teche</L>
<L>This may wel be ryme dogerell / quod he</L>
<L N="2116">&para; Why so quod I / why woltow lette me</L>
<L>More of my tale / than another man</L>
<L>Syn that it is / the best ryme I can</L>
<L>&para; By god quod he / for pleynly at a word</L>
<L N="2120">Thy drasty rymyng / is nat worth a tord</L>
<L>Thow doost nat elles / but despendest tyme</L>
<L>Sire at o word / thow shalt no lengere ryme</L>
<L>lat se / wher thow kanst tellen ought in geste</L>
<L N="2124">Or tellen in prose / somwhat atte leste</L>
<L>In which there be som myrthe / or som doctrine</L>
<L>&para; Gladly quod I / by goddes swete pyne<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ow telle / a litil thyng in prose</L>
<L N="2128">That oughte like &yogh;ow / as I suppose</L>
<L>Or elles certes / &yogh;e be to daungerous</L>
<L>It is a moral tale / vertuous</L>
<L>Al be it told / somtyme / in sondry wyse</L>
<L N="2132">Of sondry folk / as I shal &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
<L>As thus / &yogh;e wot that euery Euaungelist</L>
<L>That telleth vs / the peyne of Ihesu crist</L>
<L>Ne seith nat alle thyng / as his felawe doth</L>
<L N="2136">But nathelees / his sentence is al soth</L>
<L>And alle accorden / as in here sentence</L>
<L>Al be there / in here tellyng difference
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="421"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="200"></L>
<L>ffor somme of hem seyn more / &amp; some sey lasse</L>
<L N="2140">Whan they / his pitous passion expresse</L>
<L>I mene of Mark / Mathew / luke and Iohn</L>
<L>But doutelees / here sentence is al oon</L>
<L>Therfore lordyngges alle / I &yogh;ow byseche</L>
<L N="2144">If &yogh;ow thynke I varie / as in my speche</L>
<L>As thus / though that I telle / somwhat more</L>
<L>Of prouerbes / than &yogh;e han herd bifore</L>
<L>Comprehended / in this litel tretys heere</L>
<L N="2148">To enforce with / the effect of my matere</L>
<L>And though I nat / the same wordes seye</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd / &yogh;et to &yogh;ow alle I preye</L>
<L>Blameth me nought / for as in my sentence</L>
<L N="2152">Shuln &yogh;e no wher / fynden / difference</L>
<L>ffro the sentence / of this tretys lite</L>
<L>After the which / this mery tale I wryte</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore herkeneth / what that I shal seye</L>
<L N="2156">And lat me tellen al my tale / I preye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth Chaucers tale of Thopas / &amp; the Prologe of Melibeus</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="422">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="201">
<HEAD>And heere bigynneth the Tale of Melibeus:</HEAD>
<P>[2157]</P>
<P>A&yogh;ong man called Melibeus myghty and riche / bygat vp-on his wyf / that called was Prudence / a doughter / which that called was Sophie / [2158] Vp-on a day bifel / that he for his disport / is went in-to &thorn;e feldes / him to pleye / [2159] his wyf &amp; eke his doughter hath he laft, with-Inne his hous / of which the dores / weren fast I-shette / [2160] three of his olde foos / han it espied / and setten laddres / to the walles of his hous / and by wyndowes ben entred / [2161] &amp; beten his wyf / and <MILESTONE N="161a" UNIT="folio">wounded his doughter / with fyue mortal woundes / in fyue places sondry / [2162] this is to seyn / in hire feet / in hire handes / in hire Erys / in hire Nose / and in hire mouth / and leften hire for ded / and wenten a-wey.</P>
<P>[2163] &para; Whan Melibeus / retorned was in-to his hous / and sey al this mischief / he like a mad man / rendynge hise clothes / gan to wepe &amp; crye</P>
<P>[2164] &para; Prudence his wyf / as ferforth as she dorste / bisoughte him / of his wepyng for to stynte / [2165] but nat for-thy / he gan to crie and wepyn / euere lengere the more //</P>
<P>[2166] This noble wyfe Prudence / remembred hire vp-on the sentence of Ouyde in his book / that cleped is / the<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ouidius de re|medio amoris</NOTE> remedie of loue / where as he seith / [2167] he is a fool that destourbeth the moder to wepe in the deth of hire child / til she haue wept hire fille / as for a certeyn tyme / [2168] and thanne shal man don his diligence / with amyable wordes hire to reconforte / and preye hire / of 
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="423"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="202"> hire wepyng for to stynte / [2169] for which reson / this noble wyf Prudence / suffred hire housbond for to wepe and crye / as for a certeyn space / [2170] And whan she say hire tyme / she seide to him in this wyse / Allas my lorde quod she / why make &yogh;e &yogh;oure self / for to be like a fool / [2171] for sothe / it apparteneth nat to a wys man / to maken swich a sorwe / [2172] &yogh;oure doughter / with the grace of god / shal warisshe and escape / [2173] and al were it so / that she right now were ded / &yogh;e ne ought nat / as for hire deth / &yogh;oure self to destroye / [2174] Senec<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Seneca</NOTE> seith / the wyse man shal nat take to gret discomfort / for the deth of hise children / [2175] but certes he shulde suffren it in pacience / as wel / as he abideth the deth / of his owene propre persone</P>
<P>[2176] &para; This Melibeus answered a-noon &amp; seide / what man quod he shulde of his wepyng stynte / that hath so gret a cause for to wepe [2177] &para; Ihesu Crist<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Qualiter ihesus <I>christus</I> fleuit propter mortem la&yogh;ari</NOTE> oure lord / him self wepte / for the deth of la&yogh;arus his frend. [2178] Prudence answered / Certes wel I wot attempree wepyng is no thyng defended to him that sorweful is / amonges folk in sorwe / but it is rathere graunted him to wepe [2179] &para; The Apostle Poule / vn-to the<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Apostolus ad romanos</NOTE> Romayns wryteth / Man shal reioise / with hem that maken ioye / And wepen with swich folk as wepyn / [2180] But though attempre wepyng / be I-graunted / outrageous wepyng / certes is defended / [2181] Mesure of wepyng / shulde be considered / after the loore that techeth vs Senek / [2182] whan that thy frend is ded quod he / lat nat thyne eyen to moiste ben of teeres / ne to meche drye / al-though the teeris / come to thyne eyen / lat hem nat falle; [2183] And whan thow hast for-gon thy frend / do dili|gence / to gete a-geyn a-nother frend / and this is more wysdom / than for to wepe / for thy frend / which that &thorn;ou hast lorn / for there-Inne is no bote / [2184] And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e gouerne &yogh;ow by sapi<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio">ence / put a-wey sorwe out of &yogh;oure herte. [2185] &para; Remembre &yogh;ow that Ihesus Syrak seith / 
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="424"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="203"> a man that is ioyous in herte and glad / it him con|seruyth florisshyng in his age / but soothly . . [2186] <NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in Dd., or the</I> 4 <I>Hodson MSS., or in Eg.</I> 2726, <I>lf.</I> 183 <I>at foot</I></NOTE> sorwe in herte sleeth ful many a man [2187] &para; Sa|lamon seith / that right as moththes in the shepes flees / a-noyen to the clothes / and the smale wormes to the tree; right so anoyeth sorwe to the herte [2188] &para; Wherfore vs oughte as wel in the deth of oure children / as in the losse of oure goodes temporeles / haue pacience.</P>
<P>[2189] &para; Remembre &yogh;ow vp-on the pacient Iob / whan he hadde lost his children / and his temporel sub|staunce / and in his body endured and receyued ful many a greuous tribulacion / &yogh;et seide he thus / [2190] Oure lord hath &yogh;eue it me / Oure lord hath biraft it me / right as oure lord hath wold / right so is it don / I-blissed be the name of oure lord [2191] &para; To theise forseide thyngis answered Melibeus vn-to his wyf &para; Prudence / Alle thyne wordes quod he ben sothe and &thorn;er-to pro|fitable / but trewely myn herte is troubled / with this sorwe so greuously / that I not what to done [2192] &para; lat calle quod Prudence thyne trewe frendes alle / and thy lynage / which that ben wyse / telleth &yogh;oure caas / and herkeneth what they seye in counseillynge / and &yogh;ow gouerne after here sentence [2193] &para; Salamon seith: werke all thynges by counseille / and &thorn;ou shalt neuere repente</P>
<P>[2194] &para; Thanne by the counseil of his wyf Prudence; this Melibeus / let callen a gret congregacion of folk / [2195] as surgiens / Phisiciens / olde folk and &yogh;onge / and some of hise old enemyes reconsiled / as bi here semblaunt / to his loue / and in-to his grace / [2196] and ther-with-al / ther comen somme of his neyghbores / that diden him reuerence / more for drede than for loue / as it happeth ofte [2197] &para; Ther comen also ful many subtile flaterers and wyse aduocat&yogh; lerned in the lawe /</P>
<P>[2198] And whan this folk togydre assembled weren / This Melibeus in sorweful wyse / shewed hem his cas / 
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="425"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="204"> [2199] And by the manere of his speche / it semed that in herte he bar a crewel Ire / redy to don venge|aunce vp-oon his foos / &amp; sodeynly desired / that the werre shulde bigynne / [2200] but nathelees / &yogh;et axid he his counseil vp-oon this matere / [2201] A surgien by licence and assent of swich as weren wyse / vp roos / and vn-to Melibeus / seide / as &yogh;e moun heere /</P>
<P>[2202] Sire quod he / as to vs Surgiens apparteneth / that we do to euery wyght the beste that we kan / where as we ben with-holde / and to our pacient&yogh; / that we do no damage / [2203] wherfore it happeth many tyme and ofte / that whan twey men han euerych wounded other / O same surgien heleth hem bothe / [2204] wherfore vn-to oure art / it is nat pertinent to norice werre / ne parties to supporte / [2205] but certes as to the warisshynge of &yogh;oure doughter / al be it so / that she parllously be <MILESTONE N="162a" UNIT="folio">wounded / we shuln do so ententyf besinesse / fro day to nyght / that with the grace of god / she shal be hool &amp; sound / as sone as is possible [2206] &para; Almost right in the same wyse the Phisiciens answerden / saue that they seiden a fewe wordes more / [2207] that right as maladies ben cured / by here contraries / right so shal man warisshe werre / by vengeaunce [2208] &para; hise Neygh|bores ful of Envie / hise feyned frendes / that semed reconsiled / hise flatereres [2209] maden sembant of wepyng and empeired and aggregged mechel of this matere / in preisyng gretly Melibee / of myght / of power of richesse and of frendes / despisyng the power of hise aduersaries [2210] and seiden outrely / that he a-noon / shulde wreke him on his foos / and bigynne werre</P>
<P>[2211] &para; vp ros thanne / an aduocat that was wys by leue and by counseil / of othere that were wyse / And seide / [2212] lordynges the nede / for the which we ben assembled in this place / is ful heuy thyng / &amp; an heigh matere [2213] by cause of the wrong and of the wykkednesse that hath be doon / and eke by reson of the grete damages / that 
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="426"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="205"> in tyme comynge ben possible to fallen / for the same cause / [2214] and eke bi reson of the gret richesse and power of the parties bothe / [2215] for the which resons / it were a ful gret perile to erren in this matere / [2216] wherfore Melibeus / &thorn;is is oure sentence / we counseille &yogh;ow a-bouen alle thyng / that ri&yogh;t a-noon &thorn;ou do thy diligence in kepyng of thy propre persone / in swich a wyse / that &thorn;ou ne wante noon espie ne wacche / thy body for to saue [2217] &para; And after that we counseille / that in thyn hous thow sette suffisaunt garnyson / so that they moun / as wel thy body as thyn hous defende [2218] &para; But certes for to meeue werre / ne sodeynly for to doon vengeaunce / we moun nat deme in so litel tyme / that it were profit|able / [2219] wherfore we axen leiser and espace to haue deliberacion / in this cas to deme / [2220] for the comune prouerbe seith this / he that sone demeth; soone shal repente / [2221] And eke men seyn / that thilke Iuge is wys / that sone vnderstondeth a matere / and Iuggeth by leyser / [2222] for al be it so / that al tariyng be a-noyful / algates it is nat to repreeue in &yogh;euyng of Iugement ne in vengeaunce takyng / whan it is suffisaunt and resonable / [2223] And that shewed oure lord Ihesu crist by en|sample / for whan that the womman that was taken in aduoutrie / was brought in his presence to knowen what shulde be don with hire persone / al be it / that he wist wel him self / what that he wolde answere / &yogh;et ne wolde he nat answere sodeynly / but he wolde haue deliberacion / And in the ground he wroot twies / [2224] and by theise causes we axen deliberacion / and we shuln thanne by the grace of god / counseille the thyng / that shal be profitable</P>
<P>[2225] &para; vp stirte thanne / the &yogh;onge folk atones / and the most partie of that compaignye / han skorned &thorn;eise <MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio">olde wyse men / and bygonnen to make noyse / and seiden / that [2226] right so / as whil that Iren is hoot / men shulde myte / right so men shuln do wreken here wronges / whils 
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="427"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="206"> that they ben fresshe &amp; newe / And with loude vois / they cryden / werre / werre /</P>
<P>[2227] vp roos tho / oon of theise olde wyse / &amp; with his hond mad countenaunce / &thorn;at men shulde holde hem stille / &amp; &yogh;eue him audience [2228] &para; lordynges quod he / there is ful many a man that crieth werre / werre / &thorn;at wot ful litel what werre amounteth / [2229] werre at his bigynnyng hath so gret an entryng / &amp; so large / &thorn;at euery wight may entre whan him liketh &amp; lightly fynde werre / [2230] But certes to what ende / that shal &thorn;erof bifalle / it is nat light to knowe / [2231] for sothly / whan &thorn;at werre / is ones bygonne / there is ful many a child vn-born of his moder that shul sterue &yogh;ong / by cause of thilke werre / or elles lyue in sorwe / &amp; dye in wrecchednesse / [2232] And therfore / er that any werre be bigonne / men must haue gret counseil / &amp; gret deliberacion / [2233] &amp; whanne this olde man wende to enforce his tale by resouns / wel ny alle attones bigonne they to ryse / for to breken his tale / &amp; beden him ful ofte / hise wordes for to a-bregge / [2234] for sothly he that precheth to hem / that listen nat heren his wordes / his sarmoun hem anoyeth [2235] &para; ffor Ihesus Syrak seith / That Musyk in wepyng / is a noyous thyng / This is to seyn / as muche auailleth to speken biforn folk / to which his speche a-noyeth / as it is to synge biforn him &thorn;at wepeth [2236] &para; And whan this wys man sey / &thorn;at him wanted audience / Al shamefast / he sette him doun a-geyn / [2237] for Salamon seith / &thorn;ere as thow ne maist haue noon audience / enforce the nat to speke / [2238] I se wel quod this wyse man / &thorn;at the comune prouerbe is soth / &thorn;at good counseil wanteth / whan it is most nede.</P>
<P>[2239] &para; &YOGH;et had this Melibeus in his counseil / many folk / that priuely in his Ere / counseilled him certeyn thyng / and counseilled him the contrarie in general audience.</P>
<P>[2240] &para; whan Melibeus had herd / that the grettest / 
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="428"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="207"> partie of his counseil / were acorded / that he shulde make werre / a-noon he consented to here counseillynge / &amp; fully affermed here sentence [2241] &para; Thanne Dame Prudence / whan that she sey / how &thorn;at hire housbonde shop him / for to wreke him oon his foos / and to bigynne werre / she in ful humble wyse / whan she sey hire tyme / seide him theise wordes [2242] &para; My lord quod she / I &yogh;ow byseche / as hertily as I dar &amp; kan / ne haste &yogh;ow nat to faste / and for alle gerdouns / as &yogh;if me audience / [2243] &para; ffor Piers Alfonse seith / who-so that doth to the outher good or harm / haste the nat to quyte it / for in this wyse / thy frend wol a-bide / &amp; thyn enemy / shal the lengere lyue in drede [2244] &para; The prouerbe seith he hasteth wel / that wysly kan a-byde / And in wykked hast / is no profyt /</P>
<P>[2245] This Melibe answered vn-to his wyf / Prudence / I purpose nat quod he / to werkyn by thy counseil / for many causes &amp; resons / ffor certes euery wight / wold holde me thanne a fool / [2246] this is to seyn; If I for thy counseillyng / wolde chaunge thynges / that <NOTE PLACE="foot">[Dd. 4. 24, <I>leaf</I> 163<I>gone</I>. Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf</I>184, <I>back</I>.]</NOTE>[ben ordeined and affermed by so many wise / [2247] Sec|undly I seye / that all wommen ben wykke / and none gode of hem all / for of a thousand men seith Salamon I fonde o gode man but certes of all wommen / gode womman fond I neuer / [2248] And also certes yf I gouerned me by thy counseill / it shold seme / that I hade yeve to the ouer me the maistrie / And goddes forbode &thorn;at it so were / [2249] ffor Ihesus Syrac seith / Yf the wyf haue maistrie she is contrarious to the housbond [2250] And Salamon seith / neuere in thy lyve / to thy wyf ne to thy child / ne to thy frende / ne yeve no power ouer thy self for better it were / that thy children / axen of thy persone thynges that hem nedeth &thorn;an &thorn;ou see thy self in the hondes of thy children / [2251] And also if I wold werk by thy counseill certes my counceill / most som tyme be secree / till it were tyme / &thorn;at it most be 
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="429"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="208"> knowe / and this may nat be / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in this MS. or in any of the four Hodson MSS.</NOTE></P>
<P>[2254] Whan Dame Prudence full debonairly and with grete pacience / hade herd / all that hir housbond liked for to sey &thorn;an axed she of hym licence / for to speke / and seid in this wise / [2255] My lord koth she as to your first reson / it may lightly be answerd / for I seye / that it <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="185a">Is no folye to chaunge counseill whan the thyng / is chaunged / or elles whan &thorn;e &thorn;yng semeth other wise / than it was byforn [2256] And more ouere I seye / that though ye han [sworn<NOTE PLACE="foot">[Hod. 39.]</NOTE>] and behight to perfourme your emprise / and natheles ye wene to fulfyll and perfourme thilk same emprise / by Iust cause men shold nat seye therfore / &thorn;at ye were a lyer ne forsworn / [2257] for the boke seith the wise man maketh no lesyng / whan He turneth his corage / in-to the better / [2258] And all be it so / that your emprise / be establysshed and ordeyned / by grete multitude of folk / yitte dare you nat / accomplice / thilk ordenaunce but you like / [2259] for the trouth of thynges / and &thorn;e perfite ben rather founde in fewe folk / that ben wise / and full of reson / than by grete multitude of folk / there euery man crieth and clatereth what that him lyketh / Sothly soch multitude is nat honestee / [2260] And to the secunde reson / where as ye seyn / that all wommen ben wyk / Saue your grace / certes ye despise all wommen in this wise / and he that all despiseth / all displeseth as seith the boke / [2261] And Senec seith who so woll haue sapi|ence / shall no man dispreise / but he shall gladly teche the science &thorn;at he can without presumpcon of pride / [2262] And soch thynges as he nat can / he shall nat be ashamed to lerne hem and enquere of lesse 
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="430"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="209"> folk than hym self / [2263] And sire that there hath be many a gode womman / may lightly be preved [2264] ffor certes sire / our lord Ihesu Crist wold neuere haue discended / to be born of a womman / yf all wommen hade ben wykke / [2265] And after that / for the grete bountee / &thorn;at is in womman / our lord Ihesu Crist / whan he was risen from deth to lyf / appered rather to a womman than to his Apostles / [2266] And though that Salamon sey / that he ne fonde [neuer woman good / it folowith not &thorn;erfor &thorn;at all women be wik [2267] ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;at he fond / neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">[Hodson 39, <I>leaf</I> 130; <I>not in the other</I> 3 <I>Hodson MSS.</I>]</NOTE>] no gode womman / certes many another man hath founde / many a womman full gode and true / [2268] Or elles perauenture / the entente of Salamon was this / &thorn;at as in souerayn bountee he fonde no womman / [2269] this is to seyn / that there is no wight &thorn;at hath souerayn bountee / save god allone / as he hym self recordeth / in His Euaun|gelie / [2270] for there nys no creature so gode / that hym ne wanteth som what of the perfeccion of god / &thorn;at is his maker / [2271] Your thirde reson is this / ye seyn &thorn;at yf ye gouerne you / by my counseill / it shold seme / that ye hade yeve me / the maistrie and the lordshipe ouer your persone / [2272] Sire save your grace / it is nat so / for yf so were / that no man shold be counseilled but onely of hem / that hade lordshipe and maistrie of his persone / men wold nat be counceilled so oft / [2273] for sothely &thorn;at man that axeth counseill of a purpose / yitte hath he free choise / whether he woll werk by that counseill / or noo / [2274] And as to you / serche reson / there ye seyn that the Iangelrie of wommen / kan hide thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ey wote nought / as who seith / that a womman kan nat hide / that she wote / [2275] Sire &thorn;ise wordes ben vnder|stonde / of wommen &thorn;at ben Iangelers and wykked [2276] Of which Wommen men seyn / that .iij. thynges dryven a man out of his hous / &thorn;at is to sey Smoke / Droppyng of Reyn / and Wykked wyfes [2277] and 
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="431"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="210"> of soch wommen seith Salamon / that it were better dwelle in desert / &thorn;an with a womman that /<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="185b">Is riotous [2278] And sire by your leve / that am nat I / [2279] for ye han full oft / assaied my grete scilence / and my grete pacience / and eke how wele / that I can hide and hele thynges that mendoon / and right secrely to hide / [2280] And sothly as to your fyfte reson / where as ye seyn / that in wykked coun|seill wommen venquessh men // God wote &thorn;at reson / stant here in no stede / [2281] ffor vnderstonde now / Ye axen counseill to do wykkednesse / [2282] and yf ye woll werke wykkednes and your wyf rstreyneth you &thorn;at wykked purpoos / and ouercommeth you by reson and by gode counseill / [2283] Certes your Wyf ought rather to be praised &thorn;an yblamed [2284] Thus shold ye vnder|stonde the Phili&yogh;ophre &thorn;at seith / In wykked counceill wommen venquesshen her housbondes [2285] And there as ye blame all wommen and her resons I shall shewe by many ensaumples / that many a womman hath ben full gode / and yitte ben / and her counseils holsom and profitable / [2286] Eke som men han seid. &thorn;at the counseillyng of wommen is outher to dere / or els to litell of price / [2287] but all be it so / that full many a womman / is badde / and hir counseill vyle and nought worth / yitte han men founde full many a gode womman and full discrete / and full wise / in counseillyng [2288] Loo Iacob by gode counceill of his moder Rebecca / wan the beneson of Isaak his fader / and &thorn;e lordshipe ouer all his brethern / [2289] Iudyth by hir gode counseill deliuered / &thorn;e Cites of Bethulee in which she dwelled out of the hondes of Olofernus] <NOTE PLACE="foot">[Eg. 2726 <I>ends</I>. Dd. 4. 24, leaf 164.]</NOTE>that had it biseged / and wolde it al destroye [2290] &para; Abigail delyuerede Nabal hire housbonde fro Dauyd the kyng / that wolde han slayn him / &amp; apaised the Ire of the kyng / by hire wyt / and by hire good coun|seillyng [2291] &para; Hester by hire counseil / enhaunced gretly the peeple of god / in the regne / of Assureus the kyng / [2292] And &thorn;e same bountee in good counseillyng / of 
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="432"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="211"> many a good womman / moun men telle [2293] &para; And more|ouer / whan that oure lord / had creat Adam oure forme fader / he seide in this wyse / [2294] It is nat good / to be a man allone / make we to him an helpe / semblable to him self / [2295] heere moun &yogh;e se / that if that wommen weren nat goode / &amp; here counseil good &amp; profitable / [2296] oure lord god of heuene / wolde neither han wrought hem / ne called hem helpe of man / but rathere confusion of man / [2297] &amp; there seide oones a Clerk in two vers what is bettre than gold; Iaspre / what is bettre than Iaspre; wysdom / [2298] &amp; what is bettre than wysdom; womman / and what is bettre than good womman; no &thorn;ing / [2299] And sire / by manye of othere resons / moun &yogh;e sen / &thorn;at many wommen ben goode / &amp; here counseil good &amp; profitable [2300] &para; And &thorn;erfore sire If &yogh;e wole troste to my counseil / I shal restore &yogh;ow &yogh;oure doughter hool &amp; sound / [2301] &amp; I wol don to &yogh;ow so muche / that &yogh;e shuln haue honoure in this cause.</P>
<P>[2302] &para; Whan Melibe had herd the wordes of his wyf Prudence / he seide thus / [2303] I se wel / that the word of Salamon is soth / he seith &thorn;at wordes &thorn;at ben spoken discretly by ordynaunce / ben honycombes / for they &yogh;euen swetnesse to the soule / &amp; holsumnesse to the body / [2304] And wyf / by cause of thyne swete wordes / &amp; eke for I haue assaied / &amp; preeued thy grete sapience / &amp; thy gret trouthe / I wol gouerne me by thy counseil / in alle thyng</P>
<P>[2305] &para; Now sire quod Dame Prudence / &amp; syn &yogh;e vouchesaf / to be gouerned by my counseil / I wol enforme &yogh;ow / how &yogh;e shuln gouerne &yogh;oure self / in chesyng of &yogh;oure counseillours / [2306] &yogh;e shuln first in alle &yogh;oure werkes / mekely byseken / to the heigh god / that he wol be &yogh;oure counseillour / [2307] And shapeth &yogh;ow to swich entente that he &yogh;eue &yogh;ow counseil &amp; comfort / as taughte Tobye his sone [2308] At alle tymes / &thorn;ou shalt blisse 
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="433"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="212"> god / &amp; preye him to dresse thyne weyes / &amp; loke &thorn;at alle thyne counseils / ben in him for euere-moore // [2309] &para; Seynt Iame eke seith / If any of &yogh;ow haue nede of sapience axe it of god / [2310] and afterward / thanne shuln &yogh;e take counseil / in &yogh;oure self/ and examyne wel &yogh;oure thoughtes / of swich thynges / as &yogh;ow thynketh / that is best for &yogh;oure profyt / [2311] And thanne shuln &yogh;e dryue fro &yogh;oure herte / thre thynges / &thorn;at ben contrarious to good counseil / [2312] that is to seyn; Ire / Coueitise / &amp; hastynesse</P>
<P>[2313] &para; ffirst he that axeth counseil of him self / certes he muste ben withouten Ire / for manye causes / [2314] the firste is this / he &thorn;at hath gret Ire and wrathe in him self / he weneth alwey / &thorn;at he may do thyng / &thorn;at he <MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio">may nat do / [2315] And secoundly / he that is Irous &amp; wroth / he ne may nat wel deme / [2316] And he that may nat wel deme / may nat wel counseille / [2317] The thridde is this / that he &thorn;at is Irous &amp; wroth / as seith Senek / ne may nat speke / but blameful thynges / [2318] and with hise vicious wordes / he stereth o&thorn;ere folk / to angre &amp; to Ire [2319] &para; And eke sire / &yogh;e muste dryue coueitise out of &yogh;oure herte / [2320] for the Apostle seith / &thorn;at coueitise is the rote of alle harmes / [2321] And trosteth wel / &thorn;at a coueitous man / ne kan nat deme / ne thenke / but oonly to fulfille the ende of his coueitise / [2322] &amp; certes &thorn;at ne may neuere ben acomplised / ffor euere the more habundaunce &thorn;at he hath of richesse / the more he desireth [2323] &para; And sire &yogh;e muste also dryue out of &yogh;oure herte / hastifnesse / for certes [2324] &yogh;e ne moun nat deme for the beste / a sodeyn thou&yogh;t / &thorn;at falleth in &yogh;oure herte / But &yogh;e muste avyse &yogh;ow on it ful ofte / [2325] for as &yogh;e herde here biforn / the comune prouerbe is this / that he &thorn;at sone demeth / sone repenteth /</P>
<P>[2326] Sire / &yogh;e ne be nat alwey / in like disposicion / [2327] for certes som thyng / &thorn;at somtyme semeth to &yogh;ow / &thorn;at it is good for to doo / A-nother tyme / it semeth to &yogh;ow the contrarie /
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="434"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="213"></P>
<P>[2328] whan &yogh;e han taken counseil vn-to &yogh;oure self / And han demed by good deliberacion / swich thyng as &yogh;ow semeth best [2329] &para; Thanne rede I &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e kepe it secree / [2330] by-wreye nat &yogh;oure counseil to no persone / but if so be / &thorn;at &yogh;e wenen sikerly / &thorn;at thurgh &yogh;oure bywreiynge / &yogh;oure condicion shal ben to &yogh;ow more profitable / [2331] ffor Ihesus Syrak seith / Neyther to thy foo / ne to thy frend / diskeure nat thi secree / ne &thorn;i folie / [2332] for they woln &yogh;eue &yogh;ow audience &amp; lokyng &amp; supportacion in thy presence / &amp; skorne the in thyn absence [2333] &para; A-nother clerk seith / &thorn;at skarsly shalt &thorn;ou fynden any persone / &thorn;at may kepe thy counseil secrely [2334] &para; The book seith / whil &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepest thy counseil in thyn herte / &thorn;ou kepest it in thy prison / [2335] And whan &thorn;ou bewreyest thy counseil / to any wight / he holdeth the in his snare / [2336] &amp; &thorn;erfore &yogh;ow is bettre / to hide &yogh;oure counseil in &yogh;oure herte / than preye him to whom &yogh;e han by-wreyed &yogh;oure counseil / &thorn;at be wol kepe it clos &amp; stille [2337] &para; ffor Seneca seith / If so be /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne maist nat / thyn owen counseil hide / how darstow preyen / any o&thorn;er wight / thyn counseil secrely to kepe [2338] &para; But nathelees / if &thorn;ou wene sikerly / &thorn;at thy biwreiyng of &thorn;i counseil to a persone / wol make thy condicion / to stonden in the bettre pli&yogh;t / thanne shalt &thorn;ou telle him thy counseile in this wyse [2339] &para; ffirst &thorn;ou shalt make no semblaunt / whei&thorn;er the were leuere pees or werre / or this / or that / ne shewe him nat thy wil / and thyn entente / [2340] for troste wel / &thorn;at comunely theise counseillours ben flatereres / [2341] namely the counseillours of grete lordes / [2342] ffor they enforcen hem alwey / rather to speken plesaunte wordes / enclynyng to the lordes lust / than wordes / that ben trewe or profitable / [2343] &amp; &thorn;erfore men seyn / &thorn;at &thorn;e riche man hath selde good coun|seil / but if he <MILESTONE N="165a" UNIT="folio">haue it of him self / [2344] And after &thorn;at / &thorn;ou shalt considre &thorn;ine frendes / &amp; thyne enemys / [2345] And as touchyng thy frendes / &thorn;ou shalt con|sidre 
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="435"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="214"> which of hem ben most feithful / &amp; most wyse / &amp; eldest &amp; most appreued in counseillyng / [2346] And of hem shalt &thorn;ou axe thy counseil / as the cas requireth.</P>
<P>[2347] &para; I seye / &thorn;at first &yogh;e shuln clepe to &yogh;oure coun|seil / &yogh;oure frendes that ben trewe / [2348] ffor Salamon seith / &thorn;at for right as the herte of a man / deliteth in sauour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> &thorn;at is swote / right so the counseil of trewe frendes / &yogh;eueth swetnesse to the soule // [2349] he seith also / there may no thyng / be likned to &thorn;e trewe frend / [2350] for certes / gold ne siluer ben nat so meche worth as the good wil / of a trewe frend // [2351] And eke he seith / that a trewe frend / is a strong defence / who-so &thorn;at it fyndeth / certes he fyndeth a gret tresor [2352] &para; Thanne shuln &yogh;e eke considre / if &thorn;at &yogh;oure trewe frendes / ben discrete &amp; wyse / for the book seith / Axe alwey thy counseil of hem / &thorn;at ben wyse / [2353] &amp; by this same reson / shuln &yogh;e clepen to &yogh;oure counseil of &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at ben of age / swich as han seyn / &amp; ben expert in manye thynges / &amp; ben appreued in counseillynges [2354] &para; ffor the book seith / in olde men is al the sapience / &amp; in longe tyme the prudence [2355] &para; And Tullyus seith / &thorn;at grete &thorn;inges ne ben ay acomplissed by strengthe / ne be delyuernesse of body / but by good counseil / by auctorite of persones &amp; by science // The which thre thynges / ne ben nat fieble by age / but certes &thorn;ei enforcen / &amp; en|cresen day by day / [2356] &amp; thanne shuln &yogh;e kepe this / for a general reule // ffirst &yogh;e shuln clepe to &yogh;oure counseil a fewe of &yogh;oure frendes &thorn;at ben especiale [2357] &para; ffor Salamon seith / many frendes haue &thorn;ou / but a-mong a thousand / chese the oon / to be thy counseil|lour / [2358] for al it so be / &thorn;at &thorn;ou first ne telle thy counseil / but to a fewe / &thorn;ou maist afterward / telle it to moo folk / if it be nede / [2359] but loke alwey / &thorn;at &thorn;ine counseillours haue thilke thre condicions / &thorn;at I haue seid 
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="436"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="215"> bifore / &thorn;at is to seye; &thorn;at they be trewe / wyse / &amp; olde experience / [2360] and werk nat alwey in euery nede / by oo counseillour allone / for somtyme bihoueth it to be counseiled by manye /// [2361] ffor Salamon seith / Saluacion of thynges / is where as &thorn;ere ben many counseillours.</P>
<P>[2362] &para; Now sithe &thorn;at I haue told &yogh;ow / of which folk / &yogh;e shulde be counseilled / now wol I teche &yogh;ow / which counseil &yogh;e oughte eschue [2363] &para; ffirst &yogh;e shuln eschue / &thorn;e counseil of fooles &para; ffor Salamon seith / take no coun|seil of a fool / for he ne can nat counseille / but after his owen lust / &amp; his affeccion / [2364] the book seith / the proprete of a fool / is this; he troweth lightly harm / of euery wight &amp; lightly troweth al bounte / in him self [2365] &para; Thow shalt eke eschue the counseillyng of alle flatereres / swich as enforcen hem / rathere to preysen &yogh;oure persone / by flaterye / than for to telle &yogh;ow / the soth|fastnesse of thynges /.</P>
<P>[2366] &para; wherfore Tullyus seith / A-mong alle &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio">pestilences &thorn;at ben in frendshipe / the grettest is flaterie / And &thorn;erfore it is more nede / &thorn;at &thorn;ou eschue &amp; drede flatereres / than any other peeple // [2367] The book seith / &thorn;ou shalt rathere / drede &amp; flee / fro the swete wordes of flateryng preysers / than fro the egre wordes of thy frend / &thorn;at seith the thyne sothes [2368] &para; Salamon seith / &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes of a flaterere / is a snare / to cacchen Innocente&yogh; / [2369] he seith also / &thorn;at he &thorn;at speketh to his frend / wordes of swetnesse / &amp; of plesaunce / setteth a nette biforn his feet to cacchen him [2370] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Tullyus // Enclyne nat thyne Eres to flatereres / ne take no counseil / of wordes of flaterye [2371] &para; and Caton seith &para; Auyse the wel / &thorn;ou shalt eschue / wordes of swetnesse &amp; of plesance / [2372] And eke &thorn;ou shalt eschue the counseillyng of thyne olde enemys / that ben reconsiled [2373] &para; The book seith / &thorn;at no wight retourneth safely / in-to the 
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="437"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="216"> grace / of his old enemy [2374] &para; And ysope seith / Ne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> trust nat to hem / to which &thorn;ou hast had somtyme werre / or enemytee / ne telle hem nat thy counseil / [2375] And Seneca telleth the cause why / It may nat be / seith he / &thorn;at where as gret fyr / hath longe tyme endured / &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne dwelleth som vapour / of warmnesse // [2376] And &thorn;erfore seith Salamon &para; In &thorn;in olde ffoo / trost neuere / [2377] for sikerly / though &thorn;in enemy be reconsiled / &amp; make&thorn; &thorn;e chere of humilitee / &amp; louteth to the with his hed / ne trost him neuere / [2378] ffor certes / he maketh thilke feyned humilitee / more for his profyt / than for any loue of thy persone / by cause &thorn;at he dem|eth to haue victorie ouer &thorn;i persone / by swich feyned countenance / &thorn;e which victorie / he myght nat haue by strif of werre [2379] &para; And Peter Alfonce seith / Make no felaweshipe with thyne olde enemys / for if &thorn;ou do hem bounte / they wol peruerten it / in-to wykkednesse / [2380] And eke &thorn;ou must eschue / the counseillyng of hem / &thorn;at ben &thorn;ine seruant&yogh; / &amp; beren the gret reuerence / for parauenture they seyn it more for drede / &thorn;an for loue / [2381] And &thorn;erfore seith a Philosophre in this wyse / There is no wyght parfytly trewe / to him / &thorn;at he sore dredeth [2382] &para; and Tullius seith / &thorn;ere nys no<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> myght so gret of any Emperour / &thorn;at longe may endure / but if he haue more loue of the peeple / than drede [2383] &para; &thorn;ou shalt also eschue / &thorn;e counseillyng of folk &thorn;at ben dronkelewe / for they ne can / no counseil hide [2384] &para; ffor Salamon seith / &thorn;ere is no priuetee / ther as regneth dronkenesse [2385] &para; &yogh;e shuln also han in suspect / &thorn;e counseillyng of swich folk / as counseille &yogh;ow a thyng priuely / &amp; counseille &yogh;ow the contrarie openly [2386] &para; ffor Cassidorie seith / &thorn;at it is a manere sleighte / to hyndree / whan he sheweth to don a thyng openly / &amp; werk priuely the contrarie [2387] &para; Thow shalt also haue in suspect / &thorn;e counseillyng of wykked folk / <NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in Dd., the</I> 4 <I>Hodson MSS., or Eg.</I></NOTE> for here counseil is alwey / ful 
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="438"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="217"> of fraude [2388] &para; And Dauid seith / Blisful is &thorn;at man / &thorn;at hath nat folwed / the counseillyng of shrewes [2389] &para; Thow shalt also eschue / the counseillyng of &yogh;onge folk / for here counseil is nat ripe.</P>
<P>[2390] &para; Now sire / sithe I haue shewed &yogh;ow / of which folk / &yogh;e shullen <NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in Dd., the</I> 4 <I>Hodson MSS., or Eg.</I></NOTE> folwe &thorn;e counseil [2391] &para; Now wol I teche &yogh;ow / how &yogh;e shuln examynen &yogh;oure counseil / after the doctrine of Tullius [2392] &para; In the <MILESTONE N="166a" UNIT="folio">examynynge thanne of &yogh;oure counseillour / &yogh;e shuln considre manye thynges [2393] &para; Alderferst &thorn;ou shalt considre / &thorn;at in thilke &thorn;ing / &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest / &amp; vp-oon what thyng / &thorn;ou wolt haue counseil / &thorn;at verray trouthe be seid &amp; conserued / this is to seyn; telle trewely thy tale / [2394] ffor he &thorn;at seith fals / may nat wel be counseilled in &thorn;at cas / of which he lyeth [2395] &para; And after this / &thorn;ou shalt considre &thorn;e thynges / &thorn;at acorden to that &thorn;ou purposest for to do / be thyne counseil|lours / if resoun acorde &thorn;er-to / [2396] and eke if thy myght / may attenye &thorn;er-to / And if the more part / &amp; the bettre part of &thorn;ine counseillours / acorde &thorn;er-to or no // [2397] Thanne shalt &thorn;ou considre / what thyng shal folwe of &thorn;at counseillyng / as hate / pees / werre / grace / profyt / or damage / &amp; manye o&thorn;ere &thorn;inges [2398] And in alle theise thynges / &thorn;ou shalt chese the beste / And weyue alle othere thynges [2399] &para; Thanne shaltow considere / of what roote is engendred / &thorn;e matere of thy counseil / &amp; what fruyt it may conceyue &amp; engendre [2400] &para; Thow shalt eke considre / alle theise causes / from whennes they ben sprongen / [2401] And whan &yogh;e haue examyned &yogh;oure counseil / as I haue seid / &amp; which partie is the bettre / &amp; more profitable And han appreued it / by manye wyse folk &amp; olde / [2402] than shaltow considere / if &thorn;ou maist performe it / &amp; maken of it a good ende / [2403] ffor certes / resoun wol nat / &thorn;at any man shulde bygynne a thyng / but if he myghte performe it / as him oughte / [2404] Ne no wight shulde 
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="439"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="218"> take vp-oon him so heuy charge / &thorn;at he myght nat beren it [2405] &para; ffor &thorn;e prouerbe seith; he &thorn;at to muche embraceth / distreyneth litel [2406] &para; and Caton seith; Assay to do swich thyng / as &thorn;ou hast power to don / lest &thorn;at the charge / oppresse the so sore / &thorn;at the byhoueth to weyue thyng / &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bygonne / [2407] And if so be / &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in doute / wheither &thorn;ou maist performe a thyng or noo / ches rather to suffre / &thorn;an bigynne [2408] &para; And Peter Alfonse seith; If &thorn;ou hast myght to doon a thyng / of which &thorn;ou must repente / it is bettre / nay / than &yogh;a / [2409] this is to seyn; &thorn;at the is bettre to holde thy tonge stille / than for to speke [2410] &para; Thanne moun &yogh;e vnderstonde / by strengere resons / &thorn;at if thow hast power to performe a werk / of which &thorn;ou shalt repente / thanne is the bettre / &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffre / &thorn;an bigynne / [2411] wel seyn they / &thorn;at defenden euery wight / to assaye a thyng / of which he is in doute / whei&thorn;er he may performe it / or no [2412] &para; And after / whan &yogh;e han examyned &yogh;oure counseil / as I haue seid biforn / &amp; knowen wel / &thorn;at &yogh;e moun per|forme &yogh;oure emprise / conferme it thanne sadly / til it be at an ende.</P>
<P>[2413] &para; Now is it reson &amp; tyme / &thorn;at I shewe &yogh;ow / whanne &amp; wherfore / &thorn;at &yogh;e moun chaunge &yogh;oure counseil|lours / with-oute &yogh;oure repreue [2414] &para; Sothly a man may chaunge his purpos / &amp; his counseil if the cause ceseth / or whan a newe cas bitydeth / [2415] for the lawe seith / vp-on thynges &thorn;at newely bityden / bihoueth newe counseil; [2416] And Seneca seith; If thy counseil is comen / to the Eris of &thorn;in enemy / chaunge thy counseil [2417] &para; Thow maist also chaunge thy counseil <MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio">if so be / &thorn;at &thorn;ou fynde / &thorn;at by errour / or by other cause / harm or damage / may bitide / [2418] Also if thy counseil be dishoneste / or elles cometh of dishoneste / cause / chaunge thy counseil / [2419] ffor the lawes seyn / &thorn;at alle byhestes / &thorn;at ben dishoneste / ben of no value / 
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="440"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="219"> [2420] And eke if so be / &thorn;at it be inpossible / or may nat goodly be performed or kept /</P>
<P>[2421] And take this for a general reule &para; That euery counseil / &thorn;at is affermed so strongly / &thorn;at it may nat be chaunged / for no condicion &thorn;at may betide I seye / &thorn;at thilke counseil is wykked.</P>
<P>[2422] &para; This Melibeus / whan he had herd the doctrine / of his wyf Dame Prudence / Answered in this wyse [2423] &para; Dame quod he / as &yogh;et in-to this tyme / &yogh;e han wel &amp; couenably taught me / as in general / how I shal gouerne me / in &thorn;e chesyng / &amp; in the withholdyng of my counseillours / [2424] But now wolde I fayn / &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde condescende in special / [2425] &amp; telle me how liketh &yogh;ow / or what semeth &yogh;ow / by oure counseillours / &thorn;at we han chosen in our present nede.</P>
<P>[2426] &para; My lord quod she / I biseke &yogh;ow in alle hum|blesse / &thorn;at &yogh;e wol nat wilfully / replie a-geyn my resons / ne distempre &yogh;oure herte / though I speke thyng / &thorn;at &yogh;ow displese / [2427] ffor god wot / &thorn;at as in myn entente / I speke it for &yogh;oure beste / for &yogh;oure honour / &amp; for &yogh;oure profyte eke / [2428] And sothly I hope / &thorn;at &yogh;oure be|nygnytee wil taken it in pacience [2429] &para; Trusteth me wel quod she / &thorn;at &yogh;oure counseil as in this cas / ne shulde nat / as to speke proprely / be called a counseillyng / but a mocion or a meeuyng of folie / [2430] in which counseil / &yogh;e han erred / in many a sondry wyse.</P>
<P>[2431] &para; ffirst &amp; forward &yogh;e han erred in the assem|blyng / of &yogh;oure counseillours / [2432] for &yogh;e shulde first / han cleped a fewe folk to &yogh;oure counseil / &amp; after &yogh;e myghte han shewed it / to mo folk / if it hadde be nede / [2433] But certes &yogh;e han sodeynly cleped to &yogh;oure coun|seil a gret multitude of peeple ful chargeant / &amp; ful a-noyous for to heere [2434] &para; Also &yogh;e han erred / for &thorn;ere as &yogh;e shulde oonly han cleped to &yogh;oure counseil / &yogh;oure trewe frendes / olde &amp; wyse [2435] &yogh;e han I-cleped straunge folk / &yogh;onge folk / false flatereres / &amp; enemys 
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="441"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="220"> reconsiled / &amp; folk &thorn;at doon &yogh;ow reuerence / with-outen loue [2436] &para; And eke also &yogh;e han erred / for &yogh;e han brought with &yogh;ow to &yogh;oure counseil / Ire / Coueitise / and hastifnesse / [2437] the which thre thynges ben con|trarious to euery counseil / honest &amp; profitable / [2438] the which thre thynges / &yogh;e ne han natanientissed or destroyed hem / neither in &yogh;oure self / ne in &yogh;oure counseillours / as &yogh;ow oughte [2439] &para; &YOGH;e han erred also / for &yogh;e han shewed to &yogh;oure counseillours / &yogh;oure talent &amp; &yogh;oure affeccion / to make werre a-noon / &amp; for to do vengeaunce / [2440] they han espied by &yogh;oure wordes / to what thyng &yogh;e han enclyned / [2441] &amp; &thorn;erfore han &thorn;ei counseilled &yogh;ow / rather to &yogh;oure talent / than to &yogh;oure profit [2442] &para; &yogh;e han erred also for it semeth &thorn;at &yogh;ow suffiseth / to han ben coun|seiled by theise counseillours oonly / &amp; with litel a-vys / [2443] where-as in so gret / &amp; so heigh a nede / it hadde ben necessarie / mo counseillours &amp; more deliberacion to performe &yogh;oure emprise [2444] &para; &YOGH;e han erred also / for &yogh;e han nat ex<MILESTONE N="167a" UNIT="folio">amyned &yogh;oure counseil / in the forseide manere / ne in due manere as the cas requyreth [2445] &para; &yogh;e han erred also / for &yogh;e han maked / no diuision / bitwixe &yogh;oure counseillours / this is to seyn; bitwixe &yogh;oure trewe frendes / &amp; &yogh;oure feyned counseillours / [2446] ne &yogh;e han nat knowe / &thorn;e wil of &yogh;oure trewe frendes / olde &amp; wyse / [2447] but &yogh;e han cast alle here wordes in an hochepot / And enclyned &yogh;oure herte / to the more part / &amp; to the grettere noumbre / &amp; there be &yogh;e condescended / [2448] And sithe &yogh;e wot wel / &thorn;at men shuln alwey fynde / a grettere nombre of fooles / than of wyse men / [2449] And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e counseilles &thorn;at ben at congregacions &amp; mul|titudes of folk / there as men take more reward to the noumbre / than to the sapience of persones / [2450] &yogh;e se wel &thorn;at in swich counseillynges / fooles han the maistrie [2451] &para; Melibeus answerde a-geyn / &amp; seide / I graunte wel &thorn;at I haue erred / [2452] but there as &thorn;ou hast told me heere biforn / &thorn;at he nys nat to blame / &thorn;at chaungeth his coun|seillours 
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="442"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="221"> in certeyn cas / &amp; for certeyn iuste causes [2453] &para; I am al redy to chaunge my counseillours / right as &thorn;ou wolt deuyse [2454] &para; The prouerbe seith / ffor to do synne is mannyssh<NOTE PLACE="inter">.i. humanum</NOTE> / but certes for to perseuere longe in synne / is werke of the deuele.</P>
<P>[2455] &para; To this sentence / answered a-noon Dame Pru|dence / and seide / [2456] Examyneth quod she / &yogh;oure coun|seil / and lat vs se / the which of hem / han spoken most resonably / and taught &yogh;ow best counseil / [2457] And for as muche / as that &thorn;e examinacion is necessarie / lat vs bigynne / at the Surgiens &amp; at the phisiciens / &thorn;at first speken in this matere / [2458] I seye / &thorn;at Surgiens and phisiciens / han seid &yogh;ow in &yogh;oure counseil / discretly / as hem oughte [2459] And in here speche / seiden ful wysly / that to the office of hem apperteneth / to don to euery wight / honour &amp; profyt / &amp; no wyght for to anoye / [2460] And after here craft / to don gret diligence / vn-to &thorn;e cure of hem / which &thorn;at &thorn;ei han in here gouern|aunce / [2461] And sire right as &thorn;ei han answered wysly &amp; discretly / [2462] right so rede I &thorn;at &thorn;ei be heighly &amp; souereynly gerdoned / for here noble speche / [2463] And eke for &thorn;ei shullen do / the more ententif bisinesse / in the curacion of &thorn;i doughter deere [2464] &para; ffor al be it so / &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben &yogh;oure frendes / &thorn;erfore shuln &yogh;e nat suffren / &thorn;at &thorn;ei serue &yogh;ow for nought / [2465] but &yogh;e oughte rathere gerdone hem / &amp; shewe hem &yogh;oure largesse [2466] &para; And as touchyng the preposicion / which &thorn;at the Phisiciens / encresceden in this cas this is to seyn; [2467] &thorn;at in maladies / that a contrarie is warisshed / by another contrarie / [2468] I wolde fayn knowe / how &yogh;e vnderstonde &thorn;ilke text / &amp; what is &yogh;oure sentence [2469] &para; Certes quod Melibeus / I vnderstonde it / in this wyse / [2470] &thorn;at right as &thorn;ei han don me a contrarie / ri&yogh;t so shulde I don hem a-nother / [2471] ffor right as they / han venged hem oon me / &amp; don me wrong / right so shal I venge me vp-oon hem 
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="443"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="222"> &amp; don hem wrong / [2472] And thanne haue I cured a contrarie / by a-nother //</P>
<P>[2473] lo <MILESTONE N="167b" UNIT="folio">Lo quod Dame Prudence / how lightly is euery man enclyned / to his owene desire / and to his owene plesance [2474] &para; Certes quod she / &thorn;e wordes of the phisiciens / ne shulden nat han ben vnderstonden in that wise [2475] &para; ffor certes wykkednesse is not contrarie to wykkednesse / ne vengeance to vengeance / ne wrong to wrong / but &thorn;ei ben semblable [2476] &para; And &thorn;er|fore a vengeance is nat warisshed / by a-no&thorn;er venge|ance / ne a wrong by a-nother wrong / [2477] but euerych of hem / encresceth &amp; aggreggeth other. [2478] &para; But certes the wordes of the phisiciens / shulden ben vnderstonde in this wyse / [2479] ffor good &amp; wykked|nesse / ben two contraries / And pees &amp; werre / venge|ance &amp; suffraunce / discord &amp; acord / &amp; manye othere thynges [2480] &para; But certes wykkednesse / shal be warisshed / by goodnesse / discord by a-cord / werre by pees / &amp; so forth of othere thynges [2481] &para; And here-to acordeth seynt Poule the Apostle in many places / [2482] he seith / ne &yogh;eldeth nat harm for harm / ne wykked speche for wykked speche / [2483] but do wel to him / &thorn;at doth to the harm / &amp; blisse him &thorn;at seith to the harm [2484] &para; And in manye othere places / he amonesteth pees &amp; acord [2485] &para; But now wil I speke to &yogh;ow / of &thorn;e coun|seil / which &thorn;at was &yogh;euen to &yogh;ow / by the men of lawe / &amp; the wise folk / [2486] &thorn;at seiden alle by oon acord as &yogh;e han herd bifore [2487] &para; That ouer alle thynges / &yogh;e shuln do &yogh;oure diligence / to kepe &yogh;oure persone / &amp; to warnestore &yogh;oure hous / [2488] And seiden also / &thorn;at in this cas / &yogh;ow oughte for to werke ful auysely / &amp; with gret deliberacion [2489] &para; And sire as to the first poynt / &thorn;at toucheth to the kepyng / of &yogh;oure persone / [2490] &yogh;e shuln vnderstonde / &thorn;at he &thorn;at hath werre / shal euere more deuoutly &amp; mekely preyen biforn alle thynges / [2491] &thorn;at Ihesus crist of his mercy / wil 
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="444"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="223"> han him / in his proteccion / &amp; ben his souereyn helpyng at his nede / [2492] for certes in this world / &thorn;ere is no wight / &thorn;at may be counseilled ne kept sufficeantly / with|oute the kepyng of oure lord ihesu crist [2493] &para; To this sentence / acordeth / the prophete Dauid / &thorn;at seith / [2494] If god ne kepe &thorn;e Citee / in Idel waketh he / &thorn;at kepeth it [2495] &para; Now sire / than shuln &yogh;e committe the kepyng of &yogh;oure persone / to &yogh;oure trewe frendes / &thorn;at ben appreued and I-knowe / [2496] &amp; of hem shuln &yogh;e axen helpe / &yogh;oure persone for to kepe / ffor Caton seith / if &thorn;ou hast nede of helpe / axe it of thyne frendes / [2497] ffor &thorn;ere nys noon so good a phisicien / as thy trewe frend [2498] &para; And after this / thanne shuln &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow / fro alle straunge folk / &amp; fro lyeres / &amp; haue alwey in suspect here compaignye / [2499] ffor Piers Alfonce seith / Ne take no compaignye by the weye of a straunge man / but if so be / &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue knowe him of a lengere tyme [2500] / And if so be / &thorn;at he falle in-to thy compaignye / par|auenture / withouten thyn assent / [2501] enquere thanne as subtilly as &thorn;ou maist / of his conuersacion / &amp; of his lyf byfore &para; And feyne thy wey sey &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt go thider / as &thorn;ou wolt nat go / [2502] and if he bereth <MILESTONE N="168a" UNIT="folio">a spere / hold the oon the right syde / &amp; if he bere a swerd / holde the oon his lift syde / [2503] And after this / than shuln &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow wysely / from alle swich manere peeple / as I haue seid bifore And hem &amp; here counseile eschue [2504] &para; and after &thorn;is / &thorn;anne shuln &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow in swich manere / [2505] &thorn;at for any presumpcion of &yogh;oure strengthe / &thorn;at &yogh;e ne dispise nat / ne attempte nat the myght of &yogh;oure aduersarie / so lite / &thorn;at &yogh;e lete the kepyng of &yogh;oure persone / for &yogh;oure presumpcion / [2506] for euery wys man / dredeth his enemy / [2507] And Salamon seith; welful is he / that of alle hath drede / [2508] ffor certes / he that thurgh the hardynesse of his herte / &amp; thurgh the hardynesse of him-self / hath to gret presumpcion / him shal yuel bitide // [2509] Thanne 
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="445"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="224"> shuln &yogh;e euere mo / countrewayte emboyssement&yogh; / &amp; alle espialle / [2510] ffor Senek seith / &thorn;at the wyse man / &thorn;at dredeth harmes / escheweth harmes / [2511] ne he ne falleth in-to perils / &thorn;at perils eschueth [2512] &para; And al be it so / &thorn;at it seme / &thorn;at &thorn;ou art in syker place / &yogh;et shaltow alwey / do &thorn;i diligence / in kepyng of thy persone / [2513] this is to seyn; ne be nat necligent to kepe thy persone / nat oonly fro thyne grettest enemys / but fro thy leste enemy [2514] &para; Senek seith / a man &thorn;at is wel a-vised / he dredeth his leste enemy [2515] &para; Ouyde seith / &thorn;at the litel wesele / wol slee the gret bole / &amp; &thorn;e wylde hert [2516] &para; And &thorn;e book seith / A litel thorn / may prikke a kyng ful sore / &amp; an hound / wil holde the wilde Boor // [2517] But nathelees / I seye nat / &thorn;ou shalt be so coward / &thorn;at &thorn;ou doute there / where as is no drede [2518] &para; The book seith / &thorn;at somme folk han gret lust to deceyue / but &yogh;et they dreden hem / to be de|ceyued / [2519] &para; &yogh;et shaltow drede to be empoysened / &amp; kepe the fro the compaignye of skorneres [2520] / ffor the book seith / with scorners make no compaignye / but flee here wordes / as venym</P>
<P>[2521] &para; Now as to the secund poynt / where as &yogh;oure wyse counseillours/counseilled &yogh;ow/to warnestore &yogh;oure hous/ with gret diligence / [2522] I wolde fayn knowe / how &thorn;at &yogh;e vnderstode thilke wordes / &amp; what is &yogh;oure sentence</P>
<P>[2523] &para; Melibeus answerde &amp; seide / Certes I vnder|stonde it / in &thorn;is wyse / &thorn;at I shal warnestore myn hous / with toures / swich as han Castelles / &amp; othere manere edifices / &amp; armure / &amp; artelries / [2524] by which thynges / I may my persone &amp; myn hous / so kepen &amp; defenden / &thorn;at myne enemys / shuln ben in drede / myn hous for to approche.</P>
<P>[2525] &para; To this sentence / answerde a-noon Prudence; warnestoryng quod she / of heighe Toures / &amp; of grete edifices / . . . . .[2526] <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in Dd. or Eg., or in any of the four Hodson MSS.</NOTE> with grete 
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="446"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="225"> costages / &amp; with gret trauaille / And whan &thorn;at they ben acompliced / &yogh;et be they nat worth a stree / but if &thorn;ei ben defended / by trewe frendes / &thorn;at ben bolde &amp; wyse / [2527] And vnderstonde wel / &thorn;at the grettest &amp; strongeste garneson / &thorn;at a riche man may haue / as wel to kepen his persone / as hise goodes / is / [2528] &thorn;at he be biloued with his subget&yogh; / &amp; with his neyghebores [2529] &para; ffor thus seith Tullius; That &thorn;ere is a manere garneson / &thorn;at no man may venquisse ne discomfite / &amp; that is [2530] a lord / to be biloued of hise Cite&yogh;eins / &amp; of <MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio">his peeple</P>
<P>[2531] &para; Now sire as to the thridde poynt / where as &yogh;oure olde &amp; wyse counseillours seiden / &thorn;at &yogh;ow ne oughte nought sodeinly ne hastily proceden in this nede / [2532] but &thorn;at &yogh;ow oughte purueyen &amp; appareilen &yogh;ow in this cas / with gret diligence / &amp; gret deliberacion / [2533] trewely I trowe / &thorn;at they seiden right wysely / &amp; right soth [2534] &para; ffor Tullius seith / In euery nede / er &thorn;ou bigynne it / apparaile the wi&thorn; gret diligence [2535] &para; Thanne seye I / &thorn;at in vengeance takyng / in werre in bataille / and in warnestoryng / [2536] er &thorn;ou bigynne / I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou apparaile the &thorn;er-to / and do it / with gret deliberacion [2537] &para; ffor Tullius seith; &thorn;at longe apparailyng biforn the bataille / maketh short victorie [2538] / And Cassidorus seith; the garneson is strengere / whan it is longe tyme a-vysed</P>
<P>[2539] &para; But now lat vs speken / of &thorn;e counseil &thorn;at was acorded by &yogh;oure neyghebores / swich as don &yogh;ow reuerence / withouten loue / [2540] &yogh;oure olde enemys recon|siled / &yogh;oure flatereres / [2541] &thorn;at counseileden &yogh;ow cer|teyne thynges priuely / &amp; openly counseiled &yogh;ow the contrarie; [2542] The &yogh;onge folk also / &thorn;at counseileden &yogh;ow / to venge &yogh;ow &amp; make werre a-noon / [2543] And certes sire as I haue seid biforn / &yogh;e han gretly erred / to han cleped swich manere folk / to &yogh;oure counseil / [2544] which counseillours / ben y-now reproued by the resons aforseid [2545] &para; But natheles / lat vs now descende to 
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="447"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="226"> the special &para; &yogh;e shuln first proceden after the doctrine of Tullius; [2546] Certes the trouthe of this matere or of this counseil / nedeth nat diligently enquere / [2547] for it is wel wist / which they ben / &thorn;at han don to &yogh;ow this trespas &amp; vyleynye / [2548] &amp; how manye trespassours / &amp; in what manere they han don to &yogh;ow / al this wrong / &amp; al this vileynye / [2549] And after this / thanne shuln &yogh;e examyne / the secund condicion / which &thorn;at the same Tullius addeth in this matere / [2550] ffor Tullius put a thyng/which &thorn;at he clepeth/consentynge / This is to seyn; [2551] who ben they &amp; which ben they / &amp; how manye/&thorn;at consentyn to thy counseil in thy wilfulnesse/ to do hastif vengeaunce / [2552] And lat vs considre also / who ben they / &amp; how manye ben they / &amp; which ben they &thorn;at consenteden to &yogh;oure aduersaries [2553] &para; And certes as to the firste poynt it is wel knowen / which folk ben they / &thorn;at consenteden to &yogh;our wilful|nesse / [2554] ffor trewely alle tho / &thorn;at counseileden &yogh;ow / to maken sodeyn werre / ne ben nat &yogh;oure frendes [2555] &para; lat us now considre which ben they / &thorn;at &yogh;e holde so gretly &yogh;oure frendes / as to &yogh;oure persone / [2556] for al be it so / &thorn;at &yogh;e be myghty and riche / certes &yogh;e ne ben but allone // [2557] ffor certes &yogh;e ne han no child / but a doughter / [2558] ne &yogh;e ne han bretheryn / ne Cosyns germayns / ne noon other ny kynrede / [2559] wherfore &thorn;at &yogh;oure enemys / for drede / shulde stynte to plede with &yogh;ow / or destroye &yogh;oure persone [2560] &para; &yogh;e knowen also / &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesses moten ben dispended in diuerse parties / [2561] &amp; whan &thorn;at euery wight / hath his part / they ne wolden taken / but litel reward to venge thy deth [2562] &para; But thyne enemys ben iij<SUP>e</SUP> / &amp; they han <MILESTONE N="169a" UNIT="folio">manye children / bretheryn / Cosyns / &amp; othere ny kynrede / [2563] &amp; though so were / &thorn;ou haddest slayn of hem/two or thre / &yogh;et dwellen &thorn;ere I-nowe / to wreken here deth / &amp; to slee thy persone [2564] &para; And though so be / &thorn;at &yogh;oure kynrede be more &amp; stedefast than 
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="448"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="227"> the kyn of &yogh;oure aduersarie / [2565] &yogh;et natheles / &yogh;oure kynrede / nys but a fer kynrede / they ben but litel sibbe to &yogh;ow [2566] &para; And the kyn of &yogh;oure enmys ben ny sibbe to hem / And certes as in &thorn;at / here condicion is bet &thorn;anne &yogh;oures [2567] &para; Thanne lat vs considre also / if &thorn;e counseillyng of hem / &thorn;at counseileden &yogh;ow / to taken sodeyn vengeaunce / wheither it acorde to reson / [2568] And certes &yogh;e knowe wel nay / [2569] ffor as by right &amp; reson &thorn;ere may no man taken vengeance on no wight / but the Iuge &thorn;at hath the Iurisdiccion of it / [2570] whan is it I-graunted him / to take thilke vengeance / hastily or at|temprely / as the lawe requyreth / [2571] And &yogh;et more ouer / of thilke word / that Tullius clepeth consentynge / [2572] &thorn;ou shalt considre / if thy myght &amp; thy powere may consente and suffise to thy wylfulnesse / &amp; to thy counseillours / [2573] And certes &thorn;ou maist wel seyn / &thorn;at nay / [2574] for sikerly / as for to speke proprely / we moun do no thyng / but oonly swich thyng / as we moun don rightfully / [2575] And certes / rightfully / ne mowe &yogh;e take no vengeance / as of &yogh;oure propre auctorite [2576] &para; Thanne mowe &yogh;e sen / &thorn;at &yogh;oure power ne consenteth nat / ne acordeth nat to &yogh;oure wilfulnesse [2577] Lat vs now examyne / the thridde poynt / &thorn;at Tullius clepeth Consequent [2578] &para; Thow shalt vnderstande / &thorn;at the vengeance &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest for to take / is the conse|quent / [2579] &amp; ther-of folweth a-nother vengeance / perile &amp; werre / &amp; o&thorn;ere damages / withoute noumbre / of which we ben nat war / as at this tyme [2580] &para; And as touchyng the ferthe poynt / &thorn;at Tullius clepeth engendrynge [2581] &thorn;ou shalt considre / &thorn;at this wrong / which &thorn;at is doon to the / is engendred / of the hate of thyne enemys / [2582] &amp; of the vengeance takyng / vp-on &thorn;at / wolde engendre a-nother vengeance &amp; muchel sorwe / &amp; wastynge of richesses / as I seide</P>
<P>[2583] &para; Now sire / as to &thorn;e poynt / &thorn;at Tullius clepeth causes / which &thorn;at is the laste poynt / [2584] &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="449"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="228"> shalt vnderstonde / <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in Dd. or Eg., or Hodson MSS.</NOTE> it hath certeyne causes / [2585] which &thorn;at men<NOTE PLACE="inter">clerkes</NOTE> clepen Oriens / and Efficiens / &amp; causa longinqua / &amp; causa propinqua / this is to seyn; the fer cause &amp; the ny cause / [2586] the fer cause / is / almyghty god / &thorn;at is cause of alle thynges / [2587] the ner cause / is thyne thre enemys / [2588] the cause accidental / was hate / [2589] the cause material / ben the ffyue woundes of thy doughter / [2590] the cause formal / is the manere of hire werkynge &thorn;at brou&yogh;ten laddres / &amp; clomben In at thy wyndowes / [2591] the cause fynal / was / for to slee thy doughter / it letted nat in as muche / as in hem was / [2592] But for to speke of the fer cause / as to what ende <MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio">they shuln come or what shal finaly bitide of hem in this cas ne can I nat deme / but by coniectynge &amp; by supposynge / [2593] ffor we shuln suppose / &thorn;at &thorn;ei shuln come to a wykked ende / [2594] by-cause &thorn;at &thorn;e book of Decrees seith&para;Selden or with gret peyne/ben causes I-brought to good ende / whan &thorn;ei ben badly bigonne</P>
<P>[2595] &para; Now sire if men wolde axen me / why &thorn;at god suffred men / to do &yogh;ow &thorn;is vilenye; Certes I can nat wel answere / as for no sothfastnesse / [2596] for the Apostle seith; &thorn;at &thorn;e sciences &amp; the Iugement&yogh; of oure lord god almyghty ben ful depe / [2597] &thorn;ere may no man comprehende ne serchen hem suffisauntly [2598] &para; Nathelees by certeyne presumpcions &amp; coniectynges I holde &amp; bileue / [2599] &thorn;at god which &thorn;at is ful of Iustice / &amp; of rightwysnesse hath suffred &thorn;is bitide / by Iuste cause resonable //</P>
<P>[2600] Thy name is Melibe / this is to seyn / a man &thorn;at drynketh hony / [2601] &thorn;ou hast dronke so muche hony of swete temporel richesses / &amp; delices &amp; honoures of this world / [2602] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art dronken / &amp; hast forgeten Ihesu crist &thorn;i creature / [2603] &thorn;ou ne hast nat don to him swich honour &amp; reuerence / as the oughte / [2604] ne &thorn;ou ne hast wel I-taken kepe / to 
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="450"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="229"> the wordes of Ouyde / &thorn;at seith [2605] vnder the hony<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota &amp; caue</NOTE> of the goodes of the body / is hid the venym &thorn;at sleeth the soule // [2606] And Salamon seith; If &thorn;ou hast founden hony ete of it / &thorn;at suffiseth; [2607] for if &thorn;ou ete of it / out of mesure / &thorn;ou shalt spewe &amp; be nedy &amp; poure / [2608] &amp; parauenture Crist hath the in despit / &amp; hath turned a-wey fro the his face &amp; hise Eres of misericorde / [2609] and also he hath suffred / &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ben punysshed / in the manere &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast I-trespasced [2610] &para; Thow hast don synne / ageyn oure lord Crist / [2611] ffor certes / the thre enemys of mankynde / &thorn;at is to seyn; &thorn;e flessh / the fend / &amp; the world / [2612] &thorn;ou hast suffred hem / entre / in-to thyn herte / wilfully / by the wyndowes of thy body / [2613] &amp; hast nat defended &thorn;i self / suffisauntly ageyns here assautes / &amp; here temptacions / so &thorn;at they han wounded thy soule / in fyue places / [2614] this is to seyn; the dedly synnes / &thorn;at ben entred in-to thyn herte / by thyne ffyue wyttes / [2615] And in &thorn;e same manere / oure lord crist hath wold &amp; suffred / &thorn;at thyne thre enemys / ben entred in-to thyn hous / by the wyndowes / [2616] &amp; han I-wounded thy doughtere in the forseid manere</P>
<P>[2617] &para; Certes quod Melibe / I se wel &thorn;at &yogh;e en|force &yogh;ow muchel / by wordes to ouercomen me in swich a manere / &thorn;at I shal nat venge me of myne enemys / [2618] shewynge me the perils &amp; the yueles &thorn;at myghten falle of &thorn;is vengeaunce // [2619] But who so wolde considere / in alle vengeaunces / the periles &amp; yueles / &thorn;at myghten sewe of vengeaunce takynge / [2620] a man wold neuere take vengeaunce / &amp; &thorn;at were harm / [2621] for by the venge|aunce takynge / ben the wykked men disseuered fro the goode men / [2622] And they &thorn;at han wil / to do wykked|nesse / restreynen here wikked purpos / whan they sen the punysshynge and the <MILESTONE N="170a" UNIT="folio">chastisynge of the trespassours</P>
<P>[2623] . . . . .
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="451"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="230"> . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in Dd. or Eg., or in any of the four Hodson MSS.</NOTE> [2625] &para; And &yogh;et seye I more / &thorn;at right as a singuler persone synneth / in takyng vengeaunce of ano&thorn;er man / [2626] right so synneth the Iuge / If he do no vengeaunce of hem &thorn;at it han disserued [2627] &para; ffor Senek seith; thus / &thorn;at maister he seith is god / &thorn;at proueth shrewes [2628] &para; and Cassidore seith A man dredeth to do outrages / whan he woot &amp; knoweth / &thorn;at it displeseth to the Iuges &amp; soueryns / [2629] And another seith; The<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> Iuge &thorn;at dredeth to do right / maketh men shrewes [2630] &para; and Seynt Poule &thorn;e Apostle seith in his epistle / whan he wryteth vn-to Romayns; That the Iuges beren nat the spere withouten cause / [2631] but &thorn;ei beren it / to punysshe the shrewes &amp; mysdoers / &amp; for to de|fende the goode men [2632] &para; If &yogh;e wyln thanne take venge|aunce of &yogh;oure enemys/&yogh;e shuln retourne or haue &yogh;oure recours/ to the Iuge &thorn;at hath the Iurisdiccion vp-on hem / [2633] and he shal punysshe hem / as the lawe axeth &amp; requyreth</P>
<P>[2634] &para; A quod Melibe; This vengeaunce liketh me no thyng / [2635] I bithenke me now &amp; take hede / how fortune hath norisshed me fro my childhode / &amp; hath holpen me to passe many a strong paas [2636] &para; Now wol I assayen hire trowynge / with goddes help / &thorn;at she shal helpe me / my shame for to venge</P>
<P>[2637] &para; Certes quod Prudence / if &yogh;e wol werke by my counseil &yogh;e shuln nat assaie fortune by no wey / [2638] ne &yogh;e ne shuln nat lene or bowe vn-to hire / after the word of Senek [2639] &para; ffor thynges &thorn;at ben folily doon / and tho &thorn;at ben doon in hope of fortune/shuln neuere come to good ende [2640] &para; And as the same Senek seith; The more cler / &amp; the more shynynge &thorn;at fortune is / the more brotel &amp; the sonner broke she is / [2641] trusteth nat in hire / for she nys nat stedefast ne stable / [2642] for whan &thorn;ou trowest to be moost syker &amp; seure of hire 
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="452"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="231"> helpe / she wol faile &amp; deceyue the [2643] &para; And where as &yogh;e seyn / &thorn;at fortune hath norisshed &yogh;ow / fro &yogh;owre childhod / [2644] I seye / in so muchel / shuln &yogh;e the lasse / truste in hire and in hire wyt [2645] &para; For Senek seith; what man &thorn;at is norisshed by fortune / she maketh<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> him a greet fool [2646] &para; Now thanne / syn &yogh;e desire / &amp; axe vengeaunce / &amp; the vengeaunce &thorn;at is don / after the lawe / &amp; bifore the Iuge / liketh &yogh;ow nat / [2647] And the vengeaunce &thorn;at is doon in hope of fortune / is peril|ous &amp; vncerteyn / [2648] thanne haue &yogh;e noon o&thorn;er remedie / but for to haue &yogh;oure recours vn-to the souereigne Iuge / &thorn;at vengeth alle vyleynyes &amp; wronges / [2649] &amp; he shal venge &yogh;ow / after &thorn;at him self witnesseth &para; where as he seith / [2650] leueth the vengeaunce to me / &amp; I shal do it /</P>
<P>[2651] Melibeus answerde / If I ne venge me nat of the vyleynye &thorn;at men han don to me / [2652] I sompne or warne hem / &thorn;at han doon to <MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio">me vyleynye / and alle othere / to do me a-nother vyleynye [2653] for it is wryten / If &thorn;ou take no vengeaunce / of an olde vileynye / &thorn;ou somp|nest &thorn;ine aduersaries / to do the a new vileynye / [2654] And also for my suffraunce / men wolden do me / so muche vileynye &thorn;at I myght neither bere it / ne sus|tene / [2655] And so shulde I ben put &amp; holden ouer lowe [2656] &para;ffor somme men seyn/In muchel suffrynge shuln manye thynges falle vn-to the / which &thorn;ou shalt nat mowe suffre</P>
<P>[2657] &para; Certes quod Prudence / I graunte &yogh;ow wel / &thorn;at ouer muchel suffraunce / is nat good / [2658] but &yogh;et ne folweth it nat &thorn;erof / &thorn;at euery persone / to whom men don vileynye / take of it vengeaunce / [2659] for &thorn;at aper|teneth &amp; longeth al oonly to the Iuges / ffor &thorn;ei shuln venge the vileynyes &amp; iniuries / [2660] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;o two auctoritees / &thorn;at &yogh;e han seid a-boue / ben oonly vnderstonden in the Iuges [2661] &para; ffor whan they suffren / ouer muchel the wronges and vileynyes to be doon / 
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="453"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="232"> withouten punysshynge / [2662] they sompne nat a man al oonly / for to do newe wronges / but &thorn;ei comaunden it [2663] &para; Also as a wys man seith / &thorn;at the Iuge / &thorn;at cor|recteth nat the synnere / comaundeth &amp; biddeth him / do synne [2664] &para; And &thorn;e Iuges &amp; souereynes myghten in here hand / so muche suffre of the shrewes &amp; mysdoeris / [2665] &thorn;at they shulden by swich suffraunce by proces of tyme / wexen of swich power &amp; myght / &thorn;at they shulde putte out the Iuges &amp; the souereyns / from here places / [2666] &amp; atte laste / maken hem lese here lordshippes</P>
<P>[2667] &para; But now / lat vs now putte / &thorn;at &yogh;e haue leue to venge &yogh;ow / [2668] I seye / &yogh;e be nat of myght &amp; power / as now / to venge &yogh;ow / [2669] ffor if &yogh;e wol maken comparison / vn-to the myght of &yogh;oure aduersaries &yogh;e shuln fynde in many thynges / &thorn;at I haue shewed &yogh;ow er this / &thorn;at here condicion / is bettre then &yogh;oures / [2670] And &thorn;erfore seye I / &thorn;at it is good as now / &thorn;at &yogh;e suffre / &amp; be pacient</P>
<P>[2671] &para; fforthermore &yogh;e knowen wel / &thorn;at after the comune sawe / it is a woodnesse / a man to stryue with a strengere / or a more myghty man than he is him self / [2672] And for to stryue with a man / of euene strengthe / &thorn;at is to seyn; with as stronge a man as he is / it is peril / [2673] &amp; for to stryue with a weykere man / it is folye / [2674] And &thorn;erfore shulde a man / fle stryuynge / as muchel as he myghte [2675] &para; ffor Salamon seith; It is a gret worship to a man / to kepe him from noyse &amp; stryf [2676] &para; And if it so happe / &thorn;at a man of grettere myght &amp; strengthe / than &thorn;ou art / do the greuaunce / [2677] studie and bisie the rather to stille the same greuaunce / than for to venge the [2678] &para; ffor Senek seith; &thorn;at he putteth him in a gret peril / &thorn;at stryueth with a grettere man / &thorn;an he is him self [2679] &para; And Caton seith; If a man of heigher estat or degree / or more my&yogh;ty <MILESTONE N="171a" UNIT="folio">than &thorn;ou / do the anoye or greuaunce; suffre him / [2680] for he &thorn;at oones hath greued the / 
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="454"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="233"> may another tyme releue the &amp; helpe / [2681] &yogh;et sette I kas / &yogh;e haue bothe myght &amp; licence / for to venge &yogh;ow / [2682] I seye / &thorn;at &thorn;ere be ful manye thynges / &thorn;at shuln restreyne &yogh;ow of vengeaunce takynge / [2683] &amp; make &yogh;ow for to enclyne to suffre / &amp; for to han pacience / in &thorn;e wronges / &thorn;at han ben doon to &yogh;ow [2684] &para; ffirst and forward / if &yogh;e wol considre &thorn;e defautes / &thorn;at ben in &yogh;oure owene persone / [2685] for which defautes / god hath suffred &yogh;ow haue &thorn;is tribulacion / as I haue seid &yogh;ow heere biforn [2686] &para; ffor the Poete seith / &thorn;at we oughten paciently / taken the tribu|lacions / &thorn;at comen to vs / whan &thorn;at we consideren / &amp; thynken &thorn;at we han desserued to haue hem [2687] &para; And Seynt Gregorie seith; &thorn;at whan a man considereth wel the noumbre / of hise defautes / &amp; of his synnes / [2688] &thorn;e peynes &amp; the tribulacions &thorn;at he suffreth / semen the lesse vn-to him / [2689] And in as muche as him thynk|eth hise synnes mor heuy &amp; greuous / [2690] in so muche / semeth his peyne / the lightere &amp; the esiere vn-to him [2691] &para; Also &yogh;e owen to enclyne / &amp; bowe &yogh;oure herte / to take the pacience of oure lord ihesu crist / as seith seynt Peter in hise epistles [2692] &para; Ihesu crist he seith hath suffred for vs / &amp; &yogh;euene ensaumple to euery man / to folwe &amp; sewe him [2693] for he dide neuere synne / ne neuere cam there / a vileyns word / out of his mouth / [2694] whan men cursed him / he cursed hem nought / And whan men betyn him / he manaced hem nought [2695] &para; Also gret pacience / which / seyntes &thorn;at ben in Paradys / han had in tribulacions / &thorn;at &thorn;ei han suffred / with-outen here desert or gilt / [2696] oughte muchel stire &yogh;ow to pacience [2697] &para; ffor&thorn;er|more &yogh;e shulde enforce &yogh;ow / to haue pacience / [2698] considerynge &thorn;at the tribulacions of this world / but litel while endure / &amp; soone passed ben / &amp; gon / [2699] &amp; the ioye / &thorn;at a man seketh to haue / by pacience in tribulacions / is perdurable / after &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="455"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="234"> Thapostle seith in his Epistle / [2700] The ioye of god he seith / is perdurable / &thorn;at is to seyn; euere lastynge [2701] &para; Also troweth &amp; bileueth stedfastly / &thorn;at he nys nat wel I-norisshed / ne wel I-taught/&thorn;at kan nat haue pacience / or wol nat receyue pacience [2702] &para; ffor Salamon seith; the doctrine &amp; wyt of a man / is knowen by<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> pacience [2703] &para; And in a-nother place he seith / &thorn;at he &thorn;at is pacient / gouerneth him bi gret prudence [2704] &para; And the same Salamon seith; the angry man &amp; wrathful / maketh noyses / And the pacient man / attempreth him &amp; stilleth; [2705] he seith also; It is more worth to be pacient / than for to be right strong [2706] &para; And he &thorn;at may haue the lordshipe / of his owne herte;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> is more to preise / than he &thorn;at by his force or strengthe / taketh grete Citees [2707] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith seynt Iame in his Epistle / that pacience / is a great vertu of perfeccion. [2708]</P>
<P>&para; Certes quod Melibe / I graunte &yogh;ow Dame Prudence / &thorn;at pacience is <MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio">a gret vertu of perfeccion / [2709] but euery man may nat haue / the perfeccion &thorn;at &yogh;e seken / [2710] ne I am nat of the noumbre / of the right per|fit men / [2711] for myn herte may neuere be in pees / vn-to the tyme / it be venged / [2712] And al be it so / &thorn;at it was gret perile to myne enemys / to do me a vileynye / in takynge vengeaunce vp-oon me / [2713] &yogh;et token &thorn;ei noon hede of the perile / but fulfilleden here wykked wyl &amp; here corage [2714] &para; And &thorn;erfore me thynketh / men oughten nat repreue me / though I putte me / in a litel perile / for to venge me / [2715] And though I do a gret excesse / &thorn;at is to seyn; &thorn;at I venge oon outrage by another.</P>
<P>[2716] &para; A quod Dame prudence / &yogh;e seyn &yogh;oure wil / and as &yogh;ow liketh / [2717] But in no cas of the world / a man shulde nat don outrage ne excesse / for to vengen him [2718] &para; ffor Cassidore seith; As yuele doth he / &thorn;at vengeth him by outrage / as he &thorn;at doth &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="456"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="235"> outrage / [2719] And &thorn;erfore &yogh;e shuln venge &yogh;ow / after the ordre of right / &thorn;at is to seyn; by the lawe / &amp; nat bi excesse ne by outrage [2720] &para; And also if &yogh;e wol venge &yogh;ow of the outrage of &yogh;oure aduersaries / in other manere than right comaundeth / &yogh;e synnen [2721] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Senek; &thorn;at a man shal neuere venge shrewednesse by shrewednesse / [2722] And if &yogh;e seye / &thorn;at right axeth / a man to defende violence / by violence / &amp; fightyng by fightyng [2723] &para; Certes &yogh;e seye soth / whan the defence is doon a-noon / with-outen interualle / or with-outen tariynge / or delay [2724] for to defende him / and nat for to venge / [2725] And it bihoueth / &thorn;at a man putte swich attemperaunce in his defence / [2726] &thorn;at men haue no cause ne matere / to repreue him &thorn;at defendeth him of excesse &amp; outrage / for elles were it a-geyn reson [2727] &para; Parde &yogh;e knowen wel / &thorn;at &yogh;e maken no deffence as now / for to deffende &yogh;ow / But for to venge &yogh;ow / [2728] And so sewith it / &thorn;at &yogh;e han no wyl to do &yogh;oure dede attemprely / [2729] And &thorn;erfore me thynketh / &thorn;at pacience is good &para; ffor Salamon seith; &thorn;at he that is nat pacient shal haue gret harm. [2730]</P>
<P>&para; Certes quod Melibe / I graunte &yogh;ow / &thorn;at whan a man is inpacient &amp; wrooth / of &thorn;at that toucheth him nat / &amp; that aperteneth nat vn-to him / though it harme him / it is no wonder; [2731] ffor the lawe seith; &thorn;at he is coupable / &thorn;at entremeteth or medleth with swich thyng / as aparteneth nat vn-to him [2732] &para; And Salamon seith; &thorn;at he that entremeteth of noise / or strif / of a-nother man / is like to him / &thorn;at taketh an hound by the erys / [2733] ffor right as he &thorn;at taketh a straunge hound by the erys / is other while biten / with the hound / [2734] right in the same wyse is it resoun / &thorn;at he haue harm / &thorn;at by his impacience / medleth him of the noise of a-nother man / where as it aparteneth nat vn-to him / [2735] But &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;at this dede / &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="457"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="236"> is to seyn; my grief &amp; my dissese toucheth me right ny [2736] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ough I be wroth and in|pacient / it is no merueille / [2737] &amp; sauynge &yogh;oure grace / I kan nat se &thorn;at it myght gretly harm me / though I took vengeaunce // [2738] ffor <MILESTONE N="172a" UNIT="folio">I am richere &amp; more myghty / than myne enemys ben / [2739] And wel knowen &yogh;e / &thorn;at by moneye / and by hauynge grete posses|siouns ben alle the thynges / of this world / gouerned [2740] &para; And Salamon seith; &thorn;at alle thynges obeyen to moneye.</P>
<P>[2741] &para; whan Prudence had herd hire housbonde auaunte him of his richesse &amp; of his moneye / despreys|yng the power of hise aduersaries / Spak &amp; seide in this wyse / [2742] Certes deere sire I graunte &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e ben riche &amp; myghty / [2743] and &thorn;at the richesses ben good to hem / that han wel I-geten hem / &amp; &thorn;at wel konne vsen hem [2744] &para; ffor right as the body of a man / may nat lyue with-outen soule / no moore may it lyue / withouten temporel goodes / [2745] &amp; by rich|esses may a man gete him grete frendes // [2746] and &thorn;erfore seith Pamphilles; I a natherdes doughter he seith be riche / she may chese of a thousand men / which she wol take to hire housbonde / [2747] for of a thousand men / oon wol nat forsaken hire ne refusen hire [2748] &para; And this Pamphilles seith also / If &thorn;ou be right happy / &thorn;at is to seyn; if &thorn;ou be right riche / &thorn;ou shalt fynden a gret noumbre of felawes &amp; frendes [2749] &para; And if thy fortune chaunge &thorn;at &thorn;ou wexe poore / fare<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> wel frendshipe &amp; felaweshipe // [2750] ffor &thorn;ou shalt be al allone / withouten any compaignye / but if it be the compaignye of poore folk [2751] &para; And &yogh;et seith this Pamphilles more-ouer; That they &thorn;at ben thralle &amp; bonde of lynage / shuln be mad worthy &amp; noble / by the richesses / [2752] &amp; right so as by richesses / &thorn;ere comen manye goodes / right so by pouerte / come there manye harmes &amp; yueles / [2753] for gret pouertee con|streyneth 
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="458"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="237"> a man to do many yueles [2754] &para; And &thorn;er|fore clepeth] Cassidore / pouertee / the moder of ruyne / [2755] &thorn;at is to seyn; the moder of ouerthrowyng or fallyng doun [2756] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Piers Alfonce; Oon of the gretteste aduersitees of this world / [2757] is / whan a freeman by kynde or of birthe / is constreyned by pouertee / to eten the almesse of hise enemy [2758] &para; And &thorn;e same seith Innocent / in oon of hise bookes he seith &thorn;at sorweful &amp; myshappy is the condicion of a poore beggere / [2759] for if he axe nat his mete / he dyeth for hungere / [2760] And if he axe / he dyeth for shame / &amp; algates necessite constreyneth him to aske [2761] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Salamon; &thorn;at bettre it is to dye than for to haue swich pouerte / [2762] And as the same Sala|mon seith; Bettre it is to dye of bitter deth / than for to lyuen in swich wyse / [2763] by theise resons &thorn;at I haue seid vn-to &yogh;ow / &amp; by manye othere resons &thorn;at I koude seye [2764] I graunte &yogh;ow / &thorn;at richesses ben goode to hem / &thorn;at geten hem wel / and to hem &thorn;at wel vsen tho richesses [2765] &para; And &thorn;erfore wol I shewe &yogh;ow / how &yogh;e shuln haue &yogh;ow / &amp; how &yogh;e shuln bere &yogh;ow / in gaderyng of &yogh;oure rychesses / &amp; in what manere &yogh;e shuln vsen hem.</P>
<P>[2766] &para; ffirst &yogh;e shuln geten hem / withouten gret desir / by good leyser / sekyngly and <MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio">nat ouer hastifly / [2767] for a man &thorn;at is to desiryng to gete richesses aboundeneth him first to thefte / &amp; to alle othere yueles [2768] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Salamon; he &thorn;at hasteth him to bisily to wexe riche / shal be noon Innocent [2769] &para; he seith also; &thorn;at the richesse &thorn;at hastily come&thorn; to<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> a man / sone &amp; lightly passeth &amp; gooth from a man / [2770] But &thorn;at richesse &thorn;at cometh litel &amp; litel / wexeth alwey &amp; multiplieth // [2771] And sire &yogh;e shullen gete richesses by &yogh;oure wyt &amp; by &yogh;oure trauaille vn-to &yogh;oure profit / [2772] &amp; that withouten wronge / or harm doynge to any other persone / [2773] for the lawe 
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="459"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="238"> seith / there maketh no man him self riche / if he do harm to a-nother wight / [2774] this is to seyn; that nature defendeth &amp; forbedeth by right / &thorn;at no man make him self riche / vn-to the harm of another persone / [2775] And Tullius seith; &thorn;at no sorwe / ne no drede of deth / ne no thyng &thorn;at may falle vn-to a man / [2776] is so muchel a-geyns nature as a man to encreese his owne profit / to harm of another man [2777] And though the grete men &amp; the myghty men geten richesses moore lightly / than &thorn;ou / [2778] &yogh;et shalt &thorn;ou nat be Idel ne slow / to do &thorn;i profit / for &thorn;ou shalt in alle wyse / flee ydelnesse [2779] &para; ffor Salamonseith; &thorn;at ydelnesse techeth a man / to do manye yueles [2780] &para; And the same Salamon seith; &thorn;at he that trauailleth &amp; bisieth him to tilien his land / shal ete breed / [2781] But he &thorn;at is ydel / &amp; casteth him to no bysinesse ne occupacion / shal falle in-to pouertee and dye for hunger / [2782] and he &thorn;at is ydel and slow / kan neuere fynde couenable tyme for to do his profit [2783] &para; ffor &thorn;ere is a versifiour seith; &thorn;at the ydel man excuseth him in wynter / by-cause of the grete cold / and in somer / by encheson of the hete [2784] &para; ffor &thorn;eise causes seith Caton; waketh &amp; enclyneth &yogh;ow nat / ouer muchel to slepe / for ouer muchel reste / norissheth &amp; causeth many vices [2785] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith seynt Ierome; Dooth somme goode dedes &thorn;atthe deuele which is &yogh;oure enemy / ne fynde &yogh;ow nat / vn-ocupied / [2786] for the deuele ne taketh nat lightly vn-to his werk|ynge / swich as he fynt ocupied in goode werkes</P>
<P>[2787] &para; Thanne thus / In getyng richesses / &yogh;e musten flee ydelnesse / [2788] And afterward / &yogh;e shuln vsen the richesses / which &yogh;e han geten / by &yogh;oure wit / &amp; by &yogh;oure trauaille [2789] in swich a manere / &thorn;at men holde &yogh;ow nat to skars / ne to sparynge / ne ful large / &thorn;at is to seyn; ouer large a spendere / [2790] ffor right as men blamen / an auaricious man by-cause of his scarsitee &amp; chyncherie / [2791] in the same wyse is he to blame 
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="460"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="239"> &thorn;at spendeth ouer largely [2792] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Caton; vse he seith thy richesse / &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast I-geten [2793] in swich a manere / &thorn;at men haue no matere ne cause to calle the / nei&thorn;er wrecche ne chynche / [2794] for it is a gret shame to a man / to haue a poore herte &amp; a riche purs [2795] he seith also / &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast I-geten / vse hem by mesure / that is to seyn; spende mesurably [2796] <MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio">for they that folily wasten / &amp; despenden the goodes &thorn;at &thorn;ei han [2797] whan they han no more propre of here owne / they shapen hem to take the goodes of another man / [2798] I seye thanne / that &yogh;e shuln flee auarice / [2799] vsynge &yogh;oure richesses in swich manere / &thorn;at men seyn nat / &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesses ben I-buried / [2800] but &thorn;at &yogh;e haue hem in &yogh;oure myght / and in &yogh;oure weldynge / [2801] ffor a wys man repreueth the auaricious man / &amp; seith thus in two vers [2802] &para; where-to &amp; why burieth a man hise goodes by his gret auarice / &amp; knoweth wel / &thorn;at nedes must he dye / [2803] ffor deth is the ende of euery man / as in this present lyf / [2804] And for what cause or encheson ioyneth he him / or knytteth he him so faste / vn-to hise goodes / [2805] that alle hise wyttes moun nat disseueren him / or departen him from hise goodes / [2806] And he knoweth wel / or oughte knowe / &thorn;at whan he is ded / he shal no thyng bere with him / out of &thorn;is world [2807] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Seynt Austyn; &thorn;at the Auaricious man is likned vn-to helle / [2808] &thorn;at &thorn;e moore it swolweth / the moore desir it hath to swolwe &amp; deuoure / [2809] And as wel as &yogh;e wolde eschue to be called an auaricious man or chynche / [2810] as wel shulde &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ow / and gouerne &yogh;ow in swich a wyse / &thorn;at men calle &yogh;ow ffoollarge [2811] &para; Therfore seith Tullius / the goodes of thyn hous / ne shulde nat ben hid ne kept so cloos / but that they myghte ben opened by pitee and debonairetee / [2812] &thorn;at is to seyn; to &yogh;eue hem part &thorn;at han gret nede / [2813] 
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="461"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="240"> ne thyne goodes shulden nat ben so open to be euery mannes goodes [2814] &para; Afterward in getyng of &yogh;oure richesses / and in vsynge of hem / &yogh;e shuln alwey haue thre thynges in &yogh;oure herte / [2815] &thorn;at is to seyn; oure lord god / Conscience / &amp; good name [2816] &para; ffirst &yogh;e shuln haue god in &yogh;oure herte / [2817] &amp; for no richesse &yogh;e shuln do no-thyng / which may in any manere displese god / &thorn;at is &yogh;oure creature &amp; makere [2818] &para; ffor after the word of Salamon; It is bettre to haue a litel good / with loue of god / [2819] than to haue muchel good / &amp; lese the loue of his lord god [2820] &para; And the prophete seith; &thorn;at bettre it is / to ben a good man / &amp; haue litel good &amp; tresor / [2821] than to be holden a shrewe / &amp; haue gret richesses [2822] &para; And &yogh;et I seye for&thorn;ermore / &thorn;at &yogh;e shulden alwey do &yogh;oure bysynesse / to gete &yogh;ow richesses / [2823] so &thorn;at &yogh;e gete hem with good conscience // [2824] And the Apostle seith; &thorn;at there nys thyng in this world of which we shulden haue so gret ioye / as whan oure conscience bereth vs good witnesse [2825] &para; And the wyse man seith; the substaunce of a man is ful good / whan synne is nat / in mannes conscience [2826] &para; Afterward in getynge of &yogh;oure richesses / and in vsynge of hem / [2827] &yogh;ow muste haue gret bisynesse / &amp; gret diligence / &thorn;at &yogh;oure good name / be alwey kept &amp; conserued // [2828] &para; ffor Sala|mon seith; &thorn;at bettre it is / &amp; more it auaileth a <MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio">man to haue a good name / than for to haue grete richesses [2829] &para; And &thorn;erfore he seith in another place; Do gret<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> diligence seith Salamon in kepyng of thy frend / &amp; of thy good name [2830] for it shal lengere abide with the / than any tresor / be it neuere so precious / [2831] And certes he shulde nat be called a gentil man &thorn;at after god &amp; good conscience alle thynges left / ne dooth his diligence &amp; bisynesse to kepen his good name [2832] &para; And Cassidore seith; &thorn;at is a signe of a gentil herte / whan a man loueth &amp; desireth / to haue a good name 
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="462"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="241"> [2833] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith Seint Austyn / that &thorn;ere ben two thynges / &thorn;at arn necessarie &amp; nedefulle [2834] &amp; &thorn;at is good conscience / &amp; good loos / [2835] &thorn;at is to seyn; good conscience to thyn owne persone inward / And good loos / for thy neighbore outward / [2836] And he &thorn;at him so muchel in his good conscience [2837] trosteth &thorn;at he displeseth &amp; setteth at nought his good name / or loos / &amp; rekketh nat / though he kepe nat his good name / nys but a cruel cherl</P>
<P>[2838] &para; Sire now haue I shewed &yogh;ow / how &yogh;e shulden do in getyng richesses / &amp; how &yogh;e shuln vsen hem / [2839] And I se wel &thorn;at for the trust / &thorn;at &yogh;e han in &yogh;oure richesses / &yogh;e wyln meeue werre &amp; bataille / [2840] I coun|seille &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e bigynne no bataille ne werre / in trust of &yogh;oure richesses / for they ne suffisen nought werres to mayn|tene [2841] &para; And &thorn;erfore seith a Philosophre; &thorn;at man &thorn;at desireth &amp; wol algates han werre / shal neuere haue suffisaunce / [2842] for the richere &thorn;at he is / &thorn;e grettere despences must he make / if he wol haue wor|ship &amp; victorie [2843] &para; And Salamon seith; &thorn;at the grettere richesses &thorn;at a man hath / the moo despendours he hath [2844] &para; And deere sire / al be it so / &thorn;at for &yogh;oure richesses / &yogh;e moun haue muchel folk / [2845] &yogh;et bihoueth it nat / ne it is nat good to bigynne werre / where as &yogh;e moun in othere manere / haue pees vn-to &yogh;oure profit / [2846] for the victorie of batailles / &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is world / lith nat in gret noumbre / or multitude of peeple / ne in the vertu of man / [2847] but in lith in the wil &amp; in the hand of oure lord god almyghty [2848] &para; And &thorn;erfore Iudas Machabeus / which was goddes knyght / [2849] whan he shulde fighte a-geyn his aduersarie &thorn;at hadde a gettere noumbre / &amp; a grettere mul|titude of folk &amp; strengere / than was the peeple of this Macha|bee / [2850] &yogh;et he reconforted his litel compaignye / &amp; seide right in this wyse [2851] &para; As lightly may oure lord god almyghty / &YOGH;eue victorie to fewe folk / 
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="463"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="242"> as to manye folk / [2852] for the victorie of a bataille / cometh nat by &thorn;e gret noumbre of peeple / [2853] but it cometh from oure lord god of heuene [2854] &para; And deere sire / for as muchel / as &thorn;er is no man certeyn / if it be worthy / &thorn;at god &yogh;eue him victorie . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in Dd. or in any of the</I> 4 <I>Hodson MSS.</I></NOTE> or nought // After &thorn;at Salamon seith; [2855] &thorn;erfore euery man shulde / gretly drede werres to bigynne / [2856] and by-cause &thorn;at in batailles fallen manye<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"> perils / [2857] and it happeth outher|while / &thorn;at as sone is the grete man slayn / as the litel man [2858] &para; And as it is I-wryten / in the secund book of kynges; the dedes of batailles ben auenturouse / and no thynge certeyne [2859] &para; for as lightly is oon hurt with a spere / as a-no&thorn;er [2860] And for &thorn;ere is gret peril in werre / &thorn;erfore shulde a man flee / and eschue werre / in as muchel / as a man may / goodly [2861] &para; ffor Salamon seith; he &thorn;at loueth peril / shal falle in perile /</P>
<P>[2862] &para; After &thorn;at Dame Prudence had spoken in this manere // Melibe answered and seide [2863] &para; I se wel Dame Prudence / that be &yogh;oure faire wordes / &amp; by &yogh;oure resons &thorn;at &yogh;e han shewed me / &thorn;at the werre liketh &yogh;ow no thyng [2864] / but I haue nat &yogh;et herd &yogh;our coun|seil / how I shal do in this nede</P>
<P>[2865] &para; Certes quod she / I counseile &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e acorde with &yogh;oure aduersaries / &amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e haue pees with hem // [2866] ffor seint Iame seith in hise Epistles; &thorn;at by concord and pees / &thorn;e smale richesses wexen grete / [2867] &amp; by discord and debate / the grete richesses fallen doun [2868] &para; And &yogh;e knowen wel / &thorn;at oon of the gretteste and moost souereyn thynges / &thorn;at is in this world / is vnyte and pees [2869] &para; And &thorn;erefore seide oure lord Ihesu Crist to hise Apostlees / in this wyse / [2870] wel happy &amp; blissed be they / &thorn;at louen &amp; purchasen pees / for they ben called / children of god [2871] &para; A quod Melibee / now se I wel / &thorn;at &yogh;e louen nat myn honour / ne my worshipe [2872] &YOGH;e knowen wel / &thorn;at myne 
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="464"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="243"> aduersaries / han bigonne this debat &amp; bryge / by here outrage [2873] &amp; &yogh;e se wel / &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne requeren / ne preye me nat of pees / ne they asken nat to be reconsiled / [2874] wol &yogh;e thanne &thorn;at I go &amp; meke me &amp; obeye me to hem / &amp; crie hem mercy; [2875] ffor sothe &thorn;at were nat my worshipe / [2876] ffor right as men seyn / &thorn;at ouer greet homlynesse / engendreth dispreisynge / so fareth it / by to greet humylitee / or mekenesse</P>
<P>[2877] &para; Thanne bygan Dame Prudence / to maken sem|blant of wratthe / &amp; seide / [2878] Certes sire / sauf &yogh;oure grace / I loue &yogh;oure honour / and &yogh;oure profit / as I do myn owene / &amp; euere haue doon / [2879] ne &yogh;e / ne noon other / seyn neuere the contrarie / [2880] And if I had seid / &thorn;at &yogh;e shulde han purchased the pees / &amp; the reconsiliacion / I ne hadde nat muchel mystake me / ne seid amys [2881] &para; ffor the wyse man seith; The dis|sencion bigynneth by another man / and the reconsilynge bigynneth by thy self [2882] &para; And the prophete seith; fflee shrewednesse / &amp; do goodnesse / [2883] seke pees &amp; folwe it / as muchel as in the is [2884] &para; &YOGH;et seie I nat / &thorn;at &yogh;e shuln rathere pursue to &yogh;oure aduersaries for pees / than they shuln to &yogh;ow / [2885] ffor I knowe wel / that &yogh;e ben so hard herted / &thorn;at &yogh;e wol do noo thyng for me [2886] &para; And Salamon seith; &thorn;at he &thorn;at hath ouer hard an herte / atte laste / he shal myshappe &amp; mystide //</P>
<P>[2887] whan Melibee had herd Dame Prudence / make semblaunt <MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio">of wrathe / he seide in thys wyse [2888] &para; Dame I preye &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e be nat displesed / of thynges &thorn;at I seye / [2889] for I knowe wel / &thorn;at I am angry &amp; wrooth / &amp; &thorn;at is no wonder / [2890] &amp; they &thorn;at ben wrothe / witen nat wel / what they doon / ne what they seyn [2891] &para; Therfore the prophete seith; troubled eyen / han noo cleer sighte; [2892] But seith &amp; counseileth me as &yogh;ow liketh / for I am redy to doo / right as &yogh;e wol desire / [2893] And if &yogh;e repreeue me of my folie / I am the more holden / to loue &yogh;ow &amp; to preise 
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="465"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="244"> &yogh;ow [2894] &para; ffor Salamon seith; &thorn;at he that repreueth him / &thorn;at doth folie / [2895] he shal fynde grettere grace / than he / &thorn;at deceyueth him by swete wordes</P>
<P>[2896] &para; Thanne seide Dame Prudence / I make no semblaunt of wrathe ne of angir / but for &yogh;oure grete profit [2897] &para; ffor Salamon seith; he is more worth / &thorn;at re|preueth or chideth a fool for his folie / shewynge him semblaunt of wrathe / [2898] than he &thorn;at supporteth him &amp; preiseth him / in his mysdoynge &amp; laugheth at his folie [2899] &para; And this same Salamon seith; afterward; &thorn;at by the sorweful visage of a man / &thorn;at is to seyn; by the sory &amp; heuy countenaunce of a man / [2900] the fool correcteth &amp; amendeth him self</P>
<P>[2901] &para; Thanne seide Melibee / I shal nat konne an|swere &yogh;ow / vn-to so manye faire resons / as &yogh;e putten to me &amp; shewen / [2902] Seith shortly &yogh;oure wil and &yogh;oure coun|seil / and I am al redy / to fulfille &amp; performe it /</P>
<P>[2903] Thanne Dame Prudence / discouered al hire wil to him / &amp; seide / [2904] I counseille &yogh;ow quod she a-bouen alle thynges / &thorn;at &yogh;e make pees bitwene god &amp; &yogh;ow / [2905] &amp; beth reconsiled vn-to him / &amp; to his grace / [2906] ffor as I haue seid &yogh;ow heere bifor&ntilde; / god hath suffred &yogh;ow / to haue this tribulacion &amp; dissese for &yogh;oure synnes / [2907] And if &yogh;e do as I seye &yogh;ow / god wol sende &yogh;oure aduersaries vn-to &yogh;ow / [2908] &amp; make hem falle at &yogh;oure feet / redy to do &yogh;oure wyl &amp; &yogh;oure com|aundement&yogh; [2909] &para; ffor Salamon seith; whan the con|dicion of man / is plesaunt &amp; likyng to god / [2910] he chaungeth the hertes of the mannes aduersaries / &amp; con|streyneth hem / to biseken him of pees &amp; of grace / [2911] I preye &yogh;ow late me speke with &yogh;oure aduersaries in pryue place / [2912] ffor they shuln nat knowe / &thorn;at it be of &yogh;oure wil / or &yogh;our assent / [2913] And thanne / whan I knowe here wil &amp; here entent / I may counseille &yogh;ow / the moore seurly.</P>
<P>[2914] &para; Dame quod Melibe / doth &yogh;oure wil &amp; 
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="466"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="245"> &yogh;oure likynge / [2915] for I putte me holly / in &yogh;oure disposicion and ordinaunce</P>
<P>[2916] &para; Thanne Dame Prudence / whan she sey / the good wil of hire housbonde / deliuered vn-to hire / &amp; tok auysin hire self / [2917] thynkynge how she myghte brynge this nede / vn-to good ende / [<I>so also in Eg.</I> 2726, <I>lf.</I> 195] [2918] And whan she sey hire tyme / she sente for &thorn;eise aduersaries / to come vn-to hire in-to a pryue place / [2919] &amp; shewed wysely vn-to hem the grete goodes &thorn;at comen of pees / [2920] &amp; the gret harmes and <MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio">perils / &thorn;at ben in werre / [2921] and seide to hem in goodly manere / how &thorn;at hem oughten haue gret re|pentaunce / [2922] of the iniuries and wronges &thorn;at they hadden doon to Melibe hire lord / &amp; vn-to hire &amp; to hire doughter</P>
<P>[2923] &para; And whan they herden / the goodly wordes of Dame Prudence / [2924] they weren so supprised and rauysshed &amp; hadden so gret ioye of hire / &thorn;at wonder was to telle [2925] &para; A lady quod they / &yogh;e han shewed vn-to vs / the blissynge of swetnesse / after the lawe of Dauid the prophete / [2926] for the reconsilynge which we be nat worthy to haue / in no manere / [2927] but we oughten requeren it / with gret contrition &amp; humilitee / [2928] &yogh;e of &yogh;oure grete goodnesse / haue presented vn|to vs [2929] &para; Now se we wel / &thorn;at the science &amp; the kon|nynge of Salamon is ful trewe / [2930] ffor he seith / &thorn;at swete wordes multiplien &amp; encressen frendes / and maken shrewes to be debonaire &amp; meke</P>
<P>[2931] &para; Certes quod &thorn;ei / we putten oure dede / and al oure matere &amp; cause / al holly in &yogh;oure good wyl / [2932] and ben redy to obeye / vn-to the speche / and comaunde|ment / of my lord Melibe / [2933] And &thorn;erfore / deere &amp; benygne lady / we preye &yogh;ow &amp; biseke &yogh;ow / as mekely as we konne &amp; moun / [2934] that it like vn-to &yogh;oure gret goodnesse / to fulfille in dede &yogh;oure good|ly wordes / [2935] ffor we consideren &amp; knowelichen / 
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="467"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="246"> &thorn;at we han offended / &amp; greuyd my lord Melibe / out of mesure / [2936] so ferforth / &thorn;at we ben nat of power / to maken his amendes / [2937] And &thorn;erfore we oblige vs / &amp; bynde vs &amp; our frendes / for to do all his wil &amp; hise comaundement&yogh; / [2938] but perauenture / he hath swich heuynesse / &amp; swich wrathe to vs-ward / by-cause of oure offence [2939] &thorn;at he wol enioyne vs swich a peyne / as we moun nat bere / ne sustene / [2940] And &thorn;erfore noble lady / we biseke / to &yogh;oure wommanly pitee / [2941] to taken swich a-vysement in this nede / &thorn;at we ne oure frendes / ben nat desherited &amp; destroyed thurgh oure folie</P>
<P>[2942] &para; Certes quod Prudence / it is an hard thyng and right perilous / [2943] &thorn;at a man putte him al outrely in the arbitracion &amp; Iuggement / &amp; in the myght &amp; powere of hise enemys // [2944] ffor Salamon seith; leeueth me / &amp; &yogh;eueth credence / to &thorn;at that I shal seyn / I seye quod he / &yogh;e peeple folk / &amp; gouernours of holy chirche / [2945] to thy sone / to thy wyf / to thy frend / ne to thy brother / [2946] ne &yogh;eue &thorn;ou neuere myght ne maistrie of &thorn;i body / whil &thorn;ou lyuest [2947] &para; Now sithen he defendeth / &thorn;at man shulde nat &yogh;eue / to his brother / ne to his frend / the myght of his body; [2948] by a strengere reson / he deffendeth and forbedeth a man / to &yogh;eue him self to his enemy / [2949] And nathe|lees I counseille &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e mystruste nat my lord / [2950] ffor I woot wel &amp; knowe verraily / &thorn;at he is debonaire &amp; meke / large / Curteys / [2951] &amp; no thyng desirous ne coueitous of good ne richesse / [2952] <MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio">ffor there nys no thyng in this world &thorn;at he desireth / saue oonly worshipe &amp; honour [2953] &para; ffor&thorn;ermore I knowe wel / &amp; am right sure / &thorn;at he shal no thyng do in this nede / withouten my counseil / [2954] and I shal so werken in this cause / &thorn;at by &thorn;e grace of oure lord god / &yogh;e shuln be reconsiled vn-to vs /</P>
<P>[2955] &para; Thanne seiden they with o vois; worshipful 
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="468"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="247"> lady / we putten vs / and oure goodes / al fully in &yogh;oure wyl / &amp; disposicion / [2956] &amp; ben redy to come what day &thorn;at it lyke / vn-to &yogh;oure noblesse / to lymyte vs / or assigne vs [2957] for to make oure obligacions and bond as strong as it liketh vn-to &yogh;oure goodnesse / [2958] &thorn;at we moun fulfille the wyl of &yogh;ow / &amp; of my lord Melibe</P>
<P>[2959] &para; Whan Dame Prudence had herd the an|sweres of theise men she bad hem go a-geyn priuely / [2960] and she retourned to hire lord Melibe / &amp; told him how she fond hise aduersaries ful of repentaunt / [2961] knowlechynge ful lowely here synnes &amp; trespas / and how they weren redy to suffren al peyne / [2962] requerynge &amp; preiynge him / of mercy &amp; pitee</P>
<P>[2963] &para; Thanne seide Melibe / he is wel worthy to haue pardoun &amp; for&yogh;efnesse of his synne / that excuseth nat his synne / [2964] but knowlecheth &amp; repenteth him / axynge indulgence // [2965] &para; ffor Senek seith; there is the remission &amp; for&yogh;efnesse / where as the confession is / [2966] ffor Confession is neyghbore to Innocence / [2967] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in this MS. or in any of the</I> 4 <I>Hodson MSS.</I></NOTE> And &thorn;erfore I assente / and conferme me to haue pees / [2968] but it is good / &thorn;at we do it nat with-outen thassent &amp; wil / of oure frendes</P>
<P>&para; [2969] Thanne was Prudence right glad &amp; ioyeful / &amp; seide / [2970] Certes sire quod she / &yogh;e han wel &amp; goodly answered; [2971] ffor ri&yogh;t as by the counseil / assent &amp; helpe of &yogh;oure frendes / &yogh;e han be stired to venge &yogh;ow / and make werre / [2972] Right so with|outen here counseil / shul &yogh;e nat a-corde &yogh;ow / ne haue pees with &yogh;oure aduersaries / [2973] ffor the lawe seith; &thorn;ere nys no thyng so good / by weye of kynde / as a thyng to ben vnbounde / by him &thorn;at it was I-bounde</P>
<P>[2974] &para; And &thorn;anne Dame Prudence with-outen delay or tariynge / sent a-noon hire messageres for hire kyn and for hire olde frendes / which &thorn;at were trewe and wyse [2975] 
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="469"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="248"> &amp; told hem by ordre in the presence of Melibe / al this matere as it is a-boue expressed &amp; declared / [2976] &amp; preyed hem / &thorn;at they wolde &yogh;eue here auys &amp; coun|seil / what were best to do in this nede [2977] &para; And whan Melibeus frendes / hadden taken here auys &amp; deliber|acion of the forseid matere / [2978] &amp; hadden examyned it / by gret bysynesse &amp; gret diligence; [2979] they &yogh;ouen ful counseil for to haue pees &amp; reste [2980] &amp; that Melibe shulde resseyue with good herte hise aduersaries / to for&yogh;ifnesse &amp; mercy</P>
<P>[2981] &para; And whan Dame Prudence had herd the assent of hire lord Melibe &amp; the counseil of hise frendes [2982] acord / with hire wyl &amp; hire entencion / [2983] she was wonderly glad in hire herte / and seide / [2984] <MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio">There is an olde prouerbe quod she / seith; &thorn;at the goodnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist do this day / do it [2985] and a-bide nat / ne delay it nat til to-morwe / [2986] And &thorn;erfore I counseille / &thorn;at &yogh;e sende &yogh;oure messageres / swich as ben discrete &amp; wyse / [2987] vn-to &yogh;oure aduersaries / tellynge hem on &yogh;oure bihalue / [2988] &thorn;at if they woln trete of pees &amp; of a-cord / [2989] &thorn;at they shape hem withouten delay or tariynge / to come vn-to vs / [2990] which thyng perfourmed was in dede // [2991] And whan theise trespassours &amp; repentynge folk of here folies / &thorn;at is to seyn; the aduersaries of Melibe / [2992] hadden herd what theise Messageres seiden vn-to hem / [2993] they weren right glad &amp; ioyeful / and answerden ful mekely &amp; benygnely / [2994] &yogh;eldynge graces and thankynges to here lord Melibe / &amp; to al his compaignye [2995] &amp; shopen hem withouten delay / to go with the Messagers &amp; obeye / to the comaundement of here lord Melibe /</P>
<P>[2996] And right a-noon &thorn;ei token here weye to the court of Melibe / [2997] &amp; token with hem somme of here trewe frendes / to make feith for hem / and for to ben here borwes [2998] &para; And whan they were come to 
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="470"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="249"> the presence of Melibe / he seide hem theise wordes [2999] &para; It stant thus quod Melibe / &amp; sooth it is / that &yogh;e [3000] causeles &amp; withouten skyle &amp; resoun / [3001] han doon grete Iniuries &amp; wronges to me and to my wyf Prudence / and to my doughter also / [3002] for &yogh;e han entred in-to myn hous by violence / [3003] and haue don swich outrage &thorn;at alle men knowen wel / that &yogh;e han deserued the deth / [3004] &amp; &thorn;erfore wol I knowe &amp; wite of &yogh;ow / [3005] wheither &yogh;e wol putte &thorn;e punysshynge &amp; chastisynge / &amp; the vengeaunce of this outrage in the wil of me &amp; of my wyf / or &yogh;e wol nat.</P>
<P>[3006] &para; Thanne the wysest of hem thre / answered for hem alle / and seide / // [3007] &para; Sire quod he / we knowen wel / &thorn;at we ben vnworthy / to come to the court of so gret a lord / &amp; so worthy as &yogh;e ben / [3008] ffor we han so gretly mystaken vs / &amp; han offendid &amp; a-gilt in swich a wyse ageyn &yogh;oure heye lordship / [3009] &thorn;at trewely we han deserued the deeth / [3010] But &yogh;et for the grete goodnesse &amp; debonairetee / &thorn;at al the world wytnesseth of &yogh;oure persone / [3011] we submitten vs to the excellence &amp; benygnytee of &yogh;oure gracious lordshipe / [3012] &amp; ben redy to obeye /to alle &yogh;oure comaundementes / [3013] bysekynge &yogh;ow / &thorn;at of &yogh;oure merciable pitee / &yogh;e wol considere oure grete repentaunce &amp; lowe submission / [3014] &amp; graunte vs for&yogh;euenesse of oure outrageous trespas &amp; offence / [3015] ffor wel we knowen / &thorn;at &yogh;oure liberal grace &amp; mercy / strecchen hem for-&thorn;ere in-to good|nesse / than doon oure outrageous giltes &amp; trespas in-to wykkednesse / [3016] al be it that cursedly &amp; damp|nablely / we han a-gilt a-geyn &yogh;oure heye lordshipe</P>
<P>[3017] &para; Thanne Melibe tok hem vp fro the ground ful benygnely [3018] &amp; receyued <MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio">here obligacions and here bondes / by here oothes vp-on here plegges &amp; borwes / [3019] and assigned hem a certeyn day / to retourne vn-to his court / [3020] for to accept &amp; receyue the sentence &amp; 
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="471"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="250"> Iugement / &thorn;at Melibe wolde comaunde to be doon on hem / by &thorn;e causes a-fore-seid / [3021] which thynges or|deyned / euery man retourned to his hous.</P>
<P>[3022] &para; And whan &thorn;at dame Prudence saw hire tyme / she freyned &amp; axed hire lord Melibe / [3023] what vengeaunce he thoughte to taken of hise aduersaries</P>
<P>[3024] &para; To which / Melibe answered and seide &para; Certes quod he / I thynke &amp; purpose me fully / [3025] to dis|herite hem / of al &thorn;at euere they han / &amp; for to putte hem in exile for euere</P>
<P>[3026] &para; Certes quod Dame Prudence / this were a cruel sentence / and muchel a-geyn reson / [3027] for &yogh;e ben riche I-now / and han no nede / of othere mennes good / [3028] &amp; &yogh;e myght lightly in this wyse / gete &yogh;ow a coueytous name / [3029] which is a vicious &thorn;ing &amp; oughte ben eschewed of euery good man / [3030] for after the sawe of the word of thapostle &para; Coueytise is rote of alle harmes [3031] and &thorn;erfore it were bettere for &yogh;ow / to lese muchel good of &yogh;oure owene / than for to take of here good in this manere / [3032] for bettere it is / to lese good with wor|ship / thanne it is / to wynne good with vyleynye &amp; shame / [3033] And euery man oughte to do his diligence &amp; his bysy|nesse to gete him a good name / [3034] &amp; &yogh;et shal he nat oonly / bisye him / in kepynge his good name / [3035] but he shal also enforcen him alwey to do som thyng / by which he may renouelle his good name / [3036] ffor it is wryten; &thorn;at &thorn;e olde good loos / or good name of a man / is sone goon &amp; passed / whan it is nat newed / ne re|nouelled [3037] &para; And as touchynge &thorn;at &yogh;e seyn / &yogh;e wol exile &yogh;oure aduersaries / [3038] &thorn;at thynketh me muchel a-geyn reson / &amp; out of mesure / [3039] con|sidered the power &thorn;at they han &yogh;euen &yogh;ow / vp-oon hem self [3040] &para; And it is wryten / &thorn;at he is worthy to leese his priuylege / &thorn;at mys-vseth the myght &amp; the power / &thorn;at is &yogh;eue him [3041] &para; And I sette cas / &yogh;e myghte enioyne hem &thorn;at peyne / by right &amp; by lawe / [3042] which I 
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="472"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="251"> trowe &yogh;e mowe nat do / [3043] I seye &yogh;e myghte nat putte it to execucion perauenture / [3044] and thanne were it likly to retourne to the werre / as it was biforn / [3045] and &thorn;erfore / if &yogh;e wole &thorn;at men do &yogh;ow obeis|aunce / &yogh;e muste deme more curteisly / [3046] this is to seyn; &yogh;e muste &yogh;eue more esy sentences &amp; Iuggement&yogh; [3047] &para; ffor it is wryten / &thorn;at he that most curteisly comaundeth / to him men muste obeyen [3048] &para; And &thorn;er|fore I preye &yogh;ow / &thorn;at in this necessitee &amp; in this nede / &yogh;e caste &yogh;ow to ouercome &yogh;oure herte [3049] &para; ffor Senek seith; that he &thorn;at ouercometh his herte / ouercometh twyes / [3050] And Tullius seith; &thorn;ere is no thyng so comendable in a gret lord / [3051] as whan he is debon|aire &amp; meke / and appeiseth him <MILESTONE N="177a" UNIT="folio">lightly / [3052] And I preye &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e wol for-bere now / to do vengeaunce [3053] in swich manere / &thorn;at &yogh;oure good name / may be kept and concerued / [3054] And &thorn;at men moun haue cause &amp; matere / to preise &yogh;ow of pitee &amp; of mercy [3055] / and that &yogh;e haue no cause / to repente &yogh;ow of thyng &thorn;at &yogh;e doon [3056] &para; ffor Senek seith; he ouercometh in al yuel manere/&thorn;at repenteth him nought of his victorie/[3057] wher|fore<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE> I preye &yogh;ow / lat mercy be in &yogh;oure herte / [3058] to the effect &amp; entente / that god al-myghty haue mercy on &yogh;ow / in his laste Iuggement / [3059] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in Dd. or the Hodson MSS.</NOTE> with|oute mercy shal be do to him / &thorn;at hath no mercy of a-nother wyght</P>
<P>[3060] &para; whan Melibe had herd / the grete skyles &amp; resons of Dame Prudence / &amp; hire wyse informacions and techynges / [3061] his herte gan enclyne to the wyl of his wyf / considerynge hire trewe entente / [3062] en|forced him a-noon &amp; assented fully to werken after hire counseil / [3063] &amp; thanked god / of whom procedeth al vertu / &amp; al goodnesse / &thorn;at him sente a wyf / of so gret discrecion [3064] &para; And whan the day cam / &thorn;at hise aduer|saries shulde appere in his presence / [3065] he spak vn|to 
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="473"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="252"> hem ful goodly / and seide in this wyse [3066] &para; Al be it so / &thorn;at of &yogh;oure pride and hey presumpcion and folye / &amp; of &yogh;oure neclygence / &amp; vnkunnynge [3067] &yogh;e haue mys-born &yogh;ow / &amp; trespaced vn-to me / [3068] &yogh;et for as muchel / as I se &amp; byholde &yogh;oure grete humylitee / [3069] &amp; that &yogh;e ben sory &amp; repentaunt of &yogh;oure giltes / [3070] it constreyneth me / to do &yogh;ow grace &amp; mercy / [3071] wherfore I receyue &yogh;ow in-to my grace / [3072] &amp; for&yogh;eue &yogh;ow outrely / alle the offences Iniuries and wronges &thorn;at &yogh;e haue doon a-geyn me &amp; myne / [3073] to this effect &amp; to this ende / &thorn;at god of hise endeles mercy / [3074] wole at the time of oure deyynge / for-&yogh;eue vs oure giltes / &thorn;at we han trespaced to him in this wrecched world / [3075] for doutelees / if we be sory and repentaunt of the synnes &amp; giltes which we han trespasced inne / in the sighte of oure lord god / [3076] he is so free &amp; so mercy|able / [3077] &thorn;at he wole for-&yogh;euen vs oure giltes / [3078] and bryngen vs to the blisse / that neuere hath ende; Amen;</P>
<TRAILER>Here is ended Chaucers tale of Melibe;</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="474">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="253">
<HEAD>&amp; bygynneth the Prologe of the Monkes tale;</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan ended was my tale / of Melibe</L>
<L N="3080">And of Prudence / &amp; hire benygnetee</L>
<L>Oure Host seide / as I am a feithful man</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at precious corpus / Madrian</L>
<L>I had leuere / than a barel ale</L>
<L N="3084">That goodleef my wyf / had herd this tale</L>
<L>She nys no-thyng / of swich pacience<MILESTONE N="177b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As was this Melibeus wyf / Prudence</L>
<L>By goddes bones / whan I bete myne knaues</L>
<L N="3088">She bryngeth me / the grete clobbed staues</L>
<L>And cryeth / slee the dogges euerychon</L>
<L>And breke hem bothe bak / &amp; euery bon</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at any neyghebore of myne</L>
<L N="3092">Wol nat in chirche / to my wyf enclyne</L>
<L>Or be so hardy / to hire to trespace</L>
<L>whan she cometh hom / she raumpeth in my face</L>
<L>And crieth fals coward / wreke thy wyf</L>
<L N="3096">By corpus bones / I wyl haue thy knyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou shalt haue my distaf / &amp; go spynne</L>
<L>ffro day to nyght / right thus she wol bigynne</L>
<L>Allas she seith / &thorn;at euere that I was shape</L>
<L N="3100">To wedde a mylk-soppe / or a coward ape</L>
<L>That wol ben ouer-ladde / with euery wyght</L>
<L>Thow darst nat stonde / by thy wyues right</L>
<L>This is my lif / but if that I wol fight</L>
<L N="3104">And out atte dore a-noon / I mot me dight</L>
<L>Or elles I am but lost / but if that I</L>
<L>Be like a wylde lyon / fool hardy</L>
<L>I wot wel / she wol do me slee / some day</L>
<L N="3108">Some neighebore / and thanne go my way</L>
<L>ffor I am perilous / with knyf in honde</L>
<L>Al be it / that I dar nat / hire withstonde
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="475"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="254"></L>
<L>ffor she is bygge in armes / be my feith</L>
<L N="3112">That shal he fynde / &thorn;at hire mysdooth or seith</L>
<L>But late vs passe a-wey / fro this matere</L>
<L>My lord the Monk / quod he / be mery of chere</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e shuln telle a tale / trewely</L>
<L N="3116">loo Rouchestre stant heere / fast by</L>
<L>Ride forth myn owne lord / breke nat our game</L>
<L>But by my trouthe / I knowe nat &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>whei&thorn;er shal I calle &yogh;ow / my lord Daun Iohn</L>
<L N="3120">Or Daun Thomas / or elles daun Albon</L>
<L>Of what hous be &yogh;e / by &yogh;oure fader kyn</L>
<L>I vow to god / &thorn;ou hast a ful fair skyn</L>
<L>It is a gentil pasture / there &thorn;ou goost</L>
<L N="3124">Thow art nat like a penaunt / or a goost</L>
<L>Vp-on my feith / &thorn;ou art som officer</L>
<L>Som worthy Sexteyn / or som Celerer</L>
<L>ffor by my fadres soule / as to my dome</L>
<L N="3128">&thorn;ou art a maister / whan &thorn;ou art at home</L>
<L>No poore Cloistrer / ne no nowys<MILESTONE N="178a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But a gouernour / wyly and wys</L>
<L>And there with al / of braunes &amp; of bones</L>
<L N="3132">A wel faryng persone / for the nones</L>
<L>I preye to god / &yogh;eue him confusion</L>
<L>That first the brought / vn-to Religion</L>
<L>Thow woldest han ben / a tredfoul a-right</L>
<L N="3136">hadestow as gret a leue / as &thorn;ou hast myght</L>
<L>To perfourme thy lust / in engendrure</L>
<L>Thow haddest bygeten / ful many a creature</L>
<L>Allas / why werest &thorn;ou / so wyde a cope</L>
<L N="3140">God &yogh;eue me sorwe / but and I were Pope</L>
<L>Nat oonly &thorn;ou / but euery myghty man</L>
<L>Though he were shore ful heye / vp-oon his pan</L>
<L>Shulde haue a wyf / for al the world is lorn</L>
<L N="3144">Religion hath take vp / al the corn</L>
<L>Of tredynge / &amp; we borel men ben shrympes</L>
<L>Of feble trees / there come wrecched ympes
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="476"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="255"></L>
<L>This maketh &thorn;at oure Eyres / ben so sklendre</L>
<L N="3148">And fieble / &thorn;at they moun nat wel engendre</L>
<L>This maketh &thorn;at oure wyues / woln assaie</L>
<L>Religious folk / for they moun bettre paie</L>
<L>Of Venus paiement&yogh; / than moun we</L>
<L N="3152">God wot / no lusshburgh / payen &yogh;e</L>
<L>But be nat wroth my lord / though &thorn;at I pleye</L>
<L>fful ofte in game / a sooth I haue herd seye</L>
<L>&para; This worthy Monke / toke al in pacience</L>
<L N="3156">And seide / I wol doon al my diligence</L>
<L>As fer as sovneth / in-to honestee</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ow a tale / or two or three</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ow list / to herken hiderward</L>
<L N="3160">I wyl &yogh;ow seyn / the lif of Seynt Edward</L>
<L>Or elles first / tragedies wel I telle</L>
<L>Of which I haue an .C. in my celle</L>
<L>Tragedy is to seyn / a certeyn storie</L>
<L N="3164">As olde bookes maken / memorie</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at stood / in gret prosperitee</L>
<L>And is I-fallen / out of heigh degree</L>
<L>In-to Miserie / and endeth wrecchedly</L>
<L N="3168">And they ben versified / comunly</L>
<L>Of sexe feet / which men clepen exametron</L>
<L>In prose eke / ben endited many oon</L>
<L>And eke in metre / in many a sondry wyse</L>
<L N="3172">loo this declaryng / ought I-now suffise</L>
<L>Now herkeneth / if &yogh;ow liketh for to heere<MILESTONE N="178b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But first I &yogh;ow byseke / in this matere</L>
<L>Though I be ordre / telle nat theise thynges</L>
<L N="3176">Be it of Popes, Emperours or kynges</L>
<L>After here ages / as men writen fynde</L>
<L>But telle hem some bifore / &amp; some bihynde</L>
<L>As it now cometh / vn-to my remembraunce</L>
<L N="3180">haue me excused / of myn ignoraunce</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Heere endeth &thorn;e prologe</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="477">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="256">
<HEAD>&amp; bigynneth &thorn;e Monkes tale / &thorn;at is titled de casibus virorum Illustrium; Chaucer.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iwol be-wayle / in manere of tragedie</L>
<L>The harm of hem / &thorn;at stoden in hey degree</L>
<L>And fellen so / &thorn;at &thorn;ere was no remedie</L>
<L N="3184">To brynge hem out / of here aduersitee</L>
<L>ffor certeyn / whan &thorn;at fortune list to flee</L>
<L>There may no man / the cours of hire with-holde</L>
<L>lat no man truste / on blynd prosperitee</L>
<L N="3188">Be war / by theise ensamples / trewe &amp; olde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Lucifer.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; At lucifer / though he an Aungel were<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Lucifer</NOTE></L>
<L>And nat a man / at him I wol bygynne</L>
<L>ffor though fortune may / non Aungel dere</L>
<L N="3192">ffrom heigh degree / &yogh;et fel he for his synne</L>
<L>Doun in-to helle / where as he &yogh;et is Inne</L>
<L>O lucifer brightest / of Aungelis alle</L>
<L>Now artow Sathanas / &thorn;at maist nat twynne</L>
<L N="3196">Out of miserie / in which &thorn;at &thorn;ou art falle</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Adam.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Loo Adam / in the feld of Damyssene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Adam</NOTE></L>
<L>with goddes owne fynger / wrought was he</L>
<L>And nat bigeten / of mannes sperme vnclene</L>
<L N="3200">And welte al Paradys / sauynge o tree</L>
<L>hadde neuere worldly man / so heigh degree</L>
<L>As Adam / til he for mysgouernaunce</L>
<L>was dryuen out / of his heye prosperitee</L>
<L N="3204">To laboure &amp; to helle / and to meschaunce
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000500.tif" N="478"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="257">
<HEAD>[Sampson.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Loo Sampson / which &thorn;at was / Anunciat<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sampson</NOTE></L>
<L>By the Aungel / longe / or his natyuyte</L>
<L>And was to god almyghty / consecrat</L>
<L N="3208">And stod in noblesse / whil he myght se</L>
<L>was neuere such a-nother / as was he</L>
<L>To speke of strengthe / &amp; ther-with hardynesse</L>
<L>But to hise wyues / told he his secree</L>
<L>Thurgh which he slow himself / for wrecchednesse<MILESTONE N="179a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sampson / this noble / almyghty champion</L>
<L>with-outen wepene / saue hise handes tweye</L>
<L>he slow / and al to-rent the leon</L>
<L N="3216">Toward his weddyng / walkyng by the weye</L>
<L>his fals wyf / coude him so plese and preye</L>
<L>Til she his counseille knew / and she vntrewe</L>
<L>vn-to hise foos / his counseille gan bywreye</L>
<L N="3220">And him forsoke / and toke a-nother newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thre hondred foxes / toke Sampson for Ire</L>
<L>And alle here tayles / he to-gidre bond</L>
<L>And sette the foxes tailles / alle on fire</L>
<L N="3224">ffor he on euery taille / had knyt a brond</L>
<L>And they brente alle the cornes / in &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>And alle here Olyuerys / &amp; vynes eke</L>
<L>A thousand men / he slow eke with his hond</L>
<L N="3228">And had no wepene / but an asses cheke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan they were slayn / so thursted him / &thorn;at he</L>
<L>was wel ney lorn / for which he gan to preye</L>
<L>That god wolde on his peyne / han som pitee</L>
<L N="3232">And sende him drynk / or elles most he deye</L>
<L>And of this Asses cheke / that was dreye</L>
<L>Out of a wang toth / sprang a-noon a welle</L>
<L>Of which he drank I-now / shortly to seye</L>
<L N="3236">Thus halp him god / as Iudicum can telle
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="479"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="258"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By verrey force / at Ga&yogh;an on a nyght</L>
<L>Maugree the Philistiens / of that Citee</L>
<L>The gates of the Toun / he hath vp plight</L>
<L N="3240">And oon his back / I-caried hem hath he</L>
<L>heigh on an hil / where as men myght hem se</L>
<L>O noble almyghty / Sampson lief and dere</L>
<L>had &thorn;ou nat tolde / to wommen thy secree</L>
<L N="3244">In al this world / ne hadde ben thy pere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Sampson / neuere / sither drank ne wyn</L>
<L>Ne on his hed cam rasour noon / ne shere</L>
<L>By precept / of the Messager / dyuyn</L>
<L N="3248">ffor alle hise strengthes / in hise heres were</L>
<L>And fully twenty wynter / &yogh;ere by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>he hadde of Israel / the gouernaunce</L>
<L>But sone shal he wepe / many a tere</L>
<L N="3252">ffor wommen shuln him brynge / to myschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; vn-to his lemman Dalida / he tolde</L>
<L>That in hise heeris / al his strengthe lay</L>
<L>And falsly vn-to his foomen / she him solde<MILESTONE N="179b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3256">And slepynge in hire barm / vp-oon a day</L>
<L>She made to clippe or shere / his heere a-way</L>
<L>And made hise foomen / al this craft espien</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at they him fond / in this array</L>
<L N="3260">They bounde him fast / &amp; putten out hise eyen</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But or his her was clipped / or I-shaue</L>
<L>There was no bond / with which men myght him bynde</L>
<L>But now is he in prison / in a caue</L>
<L N="3264">Where as they made him / atte querne grynde</L>
<L>O noble Sampson / strengest of mankynde</L>
<L>O whilom Iuge in glorie / and in richesse</L>
<L>Now maistow wepen / with thyne eyen blynde</L>
<L N="3268">Sithe &thorn;ou fro wele / art falle in wrecchednesse
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="480"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The ende of this caityf / was as I shal seye</L>
<L>his foomen maden a feste / vp-on a day</L>
<L>And maden him as here fool / bifore hem pleye</L>
<L N="3272">And this was in a temple / of gret array</L>
<L>But atte laste / he mad a foul affray</L>
<L>ffor he two pilers shoke / &amp; made hem falle</L>
<L>And doun fel temple &amp; al / and there it lay</L>
<L N="3276">And slow himself / &amp; eke his foomen alle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This is to seyn / the Princes euerychon</L>
<L>And eke thre thousand bodies / were there slayn</L>
<L>with fallyng of the gret temple / of ston</L>
<L N="3280">Of Sampson / now wol I no more sayn</L>
<L>Beth war by this ensample / old and playn</L>
<L>That no men telle here counseil / to here wyues</L>
<L>Of swich thyng / as they wolde han secree fayn</L>
<L N="3284">If &thorn;at it touche / here lymes / or here lyues</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Hercules.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of hercules / the Souereigne conquerour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Hercules</NOTE></L>
<L>Syngyn hise werkes laude / &amp; heigh renoun</L>
<L>ffor in his tyme / of strengthe he was the flour</L>
<L N="3288">he slow &amp; raft the skyn / fro the leoun</L>
<L>he of Centaures / leide the boost a-doun</L>
<L>he Arpies slow / the cruel briddes felle</L>
<L>he goldene Apples reft / of the dragoun</L>
<L N="3292">he drow out Cerberus the hound / of helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; he slow the cruel tyraunt / Busirus</L>
<L>And mad his hors / to frete him flessh &amp; bon</L>
<L>he slow the firy serpent / venimus</L>
<L N="3296">Of Achilois hornes two / he brak oon</L>
<L>And he slow Cakus / in a kaue of ston</L>
<L>he slow the Geaunt / Anthous the stronge</L>
<L>he slow the grisly Boor / and that a-noon</L>
<L>And bar the heuene / on his nekke long<MILESTONE N="180a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; id est diu</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="481"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="260"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; was neuere wight / sithe &thorn;at the world bigan</L>
<L>That slow so manye monstres / as dide he</L>
<L>Thurgh-out this wyde world / his name ran</L>
<L N="3304">what for his strengthe / &amp; for his heigh bounte</L>
<L>And euery rewme / went he for to se</L>
<L>he was so stronge / &thorn;at no man myght him lette</L>
<L>At bothe the worldles endes / seith Trophee<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ille vates chalde|orum tropheus.</NOTE></L>
<L>In stide of boundes / he a piler sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A lemman hadde / this noble champion</L>
<L>That hight Dyanira / as fressh as May</L>
<L>And as theise Clerkes / maken mencion</L>
<L N="3312">She hath him sent a shert / fressh and gay</L>
<L>Allas this sherte / allas &amp; weyleway</L>
<L>Envenymed was / so sotilly with-alle</L>
<L>That or &thorn;at he had wered it / half a day</L>
<L N="3316">It made his flessh / al from his bones falle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But nathelees / some clerkes hire excusen</L>
<L>By oon &thorn;at hight nessus / that it maked</L>
<L>Be as be may / I wol hire nought accusen</L>
<L N="3320">But oon his bak / the shert he wered al naked</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his flessh / was for the venym blaked</L>
<L>And whan he sey / noon other remedye</L>
<L>In hote coles / he hath him seluen raked</L>
<L N="3324">ffor with no venym / deigned him to dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus starf / this worthy myghty Hercules</L>
<L>loo / who may troste / on fortune any throwe</L>
<L>ffor him &thorn;at folweth / al this world of prees</L>
<L N="3328">Or he be war / is oft I-leid ful lowe</L>
<L>fful wys is he / that can him seluen knowe</L>
<L>Beth war / for whan &thorn;at fortune list to glose</L>
<L>Thanne wayteth she / hire man to ouerthrowe</L>
<L N="3332">By suche a wey / as he wolde leest suppose
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000504.tif" N="482"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="261">
<HEAD>[Nebuchadnezzar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The myghty trone / the precious tresor<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nabugodonosor</NOTE></L>
<L>The gloriouse ceptre / and real maiestee</L>
<L>That hadde the kyng / Nabugodonosor</L>
<L N="3336">with tonge vnethe / may descryued be</L>
<L>he twies wan Ierusalem / the Citee</L>
<L>The vesselles of the temple / he with him ladde</L>
<L>At Babiloyne / was his souereyne see</L>
<L N="3340">In which his glorie / and his delit he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The fairest children / of the blood real</L>
<L>Of Israel / he let do gelde a-noon</L>
<L>And maked eche of hem / to ben his thral<MILESTONE N="180b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3344">A-monges othere / Danyel was oon</L>
<L>That was the wysest child / of euerychon</L>
<L>ffor he the dremes / of the kyng expouned</L>
<L>where as in Chadeie / clerk ne was &thorn;ere noon</L>
<L N="3348">That wist to what fyn / hise dremes souned</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This proude kyng / let make a statue of gold</L>
<L>Sexti cubites long / &amp; seuene in brede</L>
<L>To which ymage / he bothe &yogh;ong and old</L>
<L N="3352">Comaunded to loute / and haue in drede</L>
<L>Or in a furneys / ful of flaumbes rede</L>
<L>he shal be brent / &thorn;at wolde nought obeye</L>
<L>But neuere wolde assent / to that dede</L>
<L N="3356">Danyel / ne his &yogh;onge felawes tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This kyng of kynges / proud was &amp; elat</L>
<L>he wende that god / &thorn;at sit in mageste</L>
<L>Ne myght him nat byreue / of his estat</L>
<L N="3360">But sodeynly / he loost his dignetee</L>
<L>And like a beest / him semed for to be</L>
<L>And ete hey as an oxe / &amp; lay there oute</L>
<L>In reyn with wylde beestes / walked he</L>
<L N="3364">Til certeyne tyme / was I-come a-boute
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="483"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="262"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And like an Egles fetheres / wex his heres</L>
<L>His nayles lyke / a briddes clawes were</L>
<L>Til god relesed him / a certeyne &yogh;eres</L>
<L N="3368">And &yogh;af him wyt / &amp; thanne with many a tere</L>
<L>he thanked god / &amp; euere his lyf in fere</L>
<L>was he / to don amys / or more trespace</L>
<L>And til &thorn;at tyme / he leyd was oon his bere</L>
<L N="3372">he knew &thorn;at god / was ful of myght &amp; grace</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Belshazzar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his sone / which &thorn;at hight / Balthasar<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Balthasar</NOTE></L>
<L>That helde the regne / after his fadres day</L>
<L>he by his fader / coude nought by war</L>
<L N="3376">ffor proud he was of herte / &amp; of array</L>
<L>And eke an ydolastre / was he ay</L>
<L>his heigh estat / assured him in pride</L>
<L>But fortune kest him doun / &amp; &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L N="3380">And sodeynly his regne / gan dyuyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A feste he made / vn-to his lordes alle</L>
<L>vppon a tyme / &amp; made hem blithe be</L>
<L>And thanne his officers / gan he calle</L>
<L N="3384">Goth bryngeth forth / the vesseles quod he</L>
<L>which &thorn;at my fader / in his prosperitee</L>
<L>Out of the temple of Ierusalem / biraft</L>
<L>And to oure heighe goddes / thanke we<MILESTONE N="181a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3388">Of honour &thorn;at oure eldres / with vs laft</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His wyf / his lordes / &amp; hise concubynes</L>
<L>Ay dronken / while here appetites laste</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;eise noble vesseles / sondry wynes</L>
<L N="3392">And oon a wal / this kyng his eyen caste</L>
<L>And sey an hand / armlees / &thorn;at wroot ful faste</L>
<L>ffor fere of which / he quoke &amp; siked sore</L>
<L>This hand &thorn;at Balthasar / so sore a-gaste</L>
<L N="3396">wroot / mane techel phares / &amp; no more
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="484"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="263"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In al &thorn;at lond / Magicien was noon</L>
<L>That coude expoune / what &thorn;is lettre mente</L>
<L>But Danyel / expouned it a-noon</L>
<L N="3400">And seide kyng / god to thy fader sente</L>
<L>Glorie &amp; honour / regne / tresor / Rente</L>
<L>And he was proud / &amp; nothyng god ne dradde</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore / god / gret wreche vp-oon him sente</L>
<L N="3404">And him bireft / the regne that he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He was out cast / of mannes compaignye</L>
<L>with Asses / was his habitacion</L>
<L>And ete hey as a beest / in wete &amp; drye</L>
<L N="3408">Til &thorn;at he knew by grace / &amp; by reson</L>
<L>That god of heuene / hath domynacion</L>
<L>Ouer euery regne / and euery creature</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne had god / of him compassion</L>
<L N="3412">And him restored his regne / &amp; his figure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Eke &thorn;ou &thorn;at art his sone / art proud also</L>
<L>And knowest alle &thorn;eise thynges / verrely</L>
<L>And art rebel to god / and art his foo</L>
<L N="3416">Thow drank eke of hise vessels / boldely</L>
<L>Thy wyfe eke / and &thorn;ine wenches synfully</L>
<L>Dronke of the same vesselles / sondry wynes</L>
<L>And heriest false goddes / cursedly</L>
<L N="3420">Therfore to the / I-shapen / ful gret peyne is</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This hand was sent fro god / &thorn;at oon the wal</L>
<L>wroot / Mane thechel phares / truste me</L>
<L>Thy regne is don / &thorn;ou weyest nought at al</L>
<L N="3424">Dyuyded is thy regne / and it shal be</L>
<L>To Medes and Perses / I-&yogh;euen quod he</L>
<L>And thilke same nyght / this kyng was slawe</L>
<L>And Darius occupieth his degree</L>
<L N="3428">Though he &thorn;er-to had / nei&thorn;er right ne lawe
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="485"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lordynges ensample / her-by moun &yogh;e take</L>
<L>how &thorn;at in lordship / is no sykernesse</L>
<L>ffor whan fortune / wil a man forsake<MILESTONE N="181b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3432">She bereth a-wey his regne / &amp; his richesse</L>
<L>And eke hise frendes / bothe more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>ffor what man &thorn;at hath frendes / thurgh fortune</L>
<L>Mishap / wyl mak hem enemys / I gesse</L>
<L N="3436">This prouerbe is ful soth / &amp; ful comune</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Zenobia.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Cenobia / of Palymerie Quene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cenobia</NOTE></L>
<L>As wryten Persiens / in here noblesse</L>
<L>So worthy was in armes / &amp; so kene</L>
<L N="3440">That no wight passed hire / in hardynesse</L>
<L>Ne in lynage / ne in other gentillesse</L>
<L>Of kynges blod of Perce / is she descended</L>
<L>I sey nat / &thorn;at she had / moost fairestnesse</L>
<L N="3444">But of hire shap / she myght nat ben amended</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffrom hire childhode / I fynde &thorn;at she fledde</L>
<L>Office of wommen / and to wode she went</L>
<L>And many a wylde hertes blood / she shedde</L>
<L N="3448">With arwes brode / &thorn;at she to hem sente</L>
<L>She was so swift / &thorn;at she a-noon hem hente</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at she was eldre / she wolde kille</L>
<L>Leones / lepardes / and Beres al-to-rente</L>
<L N="3452">And in hire armes / welde hem at hire wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; She durste / wilde Bestes dennes / seke</L>
<L>And rennen in the Mountaignes / al the nyght</L>
<L>And slepe vnder the Bussh / &amp; she coude eke</L>
<L N="3456">wrastlen by verrey force / and verry myght</L>
<L>with any &yogh;onge man / were he neuere so wyght</L>
<L>There myght no thyng / in hire armes stonde</L>
<L>She kept hire maydenhode / from euery wight</L>
<L N="3460">To no man deigned hire / for to be bonde
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="486"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="265"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But atte laste / hire frendes han hire maried</L>
<L>To Onedake / a Prince of that contree</L>
<L>Al were it so / &thorn;at she hem longe taried</L>
<L N="3464">And &yogh;e shuln vnderstonde / how that he</L>
<L>hadde suche fantasies / as hadde she</L>
<L>But nathelees / whan they were knytte in fere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; id <I>est</I> simul</NOTE></L>
<L>They lyued in ioye / and in felicitee</L>
<L N="3468">ffor ech of hem had other / lief &amp; dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Saue oo thyng / &thorn;at she wolde neuere assent</L>
<L>By no wey / &thorn;at he shulde by hire lye</L>
<L>But oones / for it was hire pleyn entent</L>
<L N="3472">To haue a child / the world to multiplie</L>
<L>And also sone / as &thorn;at she myght espie</L>
<L>That she was nat with childe / with &thorn;at dede</L>
<L>Thanne wold she suffre him / done his fantasie<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3476">Eft sone / and nat but ones / out of drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And if she were with childe / at thilke kast</L>
<L>No more shulde he pleyen / thilke game</L>
<L>Til fully fourty dayes / weren past</L>
<L N="3480">Thanne wolde she ones suffre him / do the same</L>
<L>Al were this Onedake / wylde or tame</L>
<L>he gat no more of hire / for thus she seide</L>
<L>It was to wyues / leccherie and shame</L>
<L N="3484">In other cas / if that men with hem pleide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Two sons / by this Onedak / had she</L>
<L>The which she kept in vertu / and lettrure</L>
<L>But now / vn-to oure tale / turne we</L>
<L N="3488">I sey / so worshipful a creature</L>
<L>And wys ther-with / &amp; large with mesure</L>
<L>So penyble in the werre / &amp; curteis eke</L>
<L>Ne more labour myght / in werre endure</L>
<L N="3492">Was none / though al this world men shulde seke
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="487"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="266"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; hire riche aray / ne myght nat be tolde</L>
<L>As wel in vessel / as in hire clothynge</L>
<L>She was al clad / in perry / and in golde</L>
<L N="3496">And eke she left nought / for non huntynge</L>
<L>To haue of sondry tonges / ful knowynge</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at she leiser hadde / &amp; for to entende</L>
<L>To lerne bookes / was al hire likynge</L>
<L N="3500">how she in vertu / myght hire lyf despende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And shortly / of this storie / for to trete</L>
<L>So doughty was hire housbond / &amp; eke she</L>
<L>That they conquered / many regnes grete</L>
<L N="3504">In the orient / with many a fair Citee</L>
<L>Appertenaunt / vn-to the Magestee</L>
<L>Of Rome / &amp; with strong hond / held hem ful faste</L>
<L>Ne neuere myght here foomen / don hem flee</L>
<L N="3508">Ay / whil that Onedakes dayes / laste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Here batailles / who so list hem for to rede</L>
<L>Ageyn Sapor the kyng / &amp; othere moo</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at al this processe / fel in dede</L>
<L N="3512">why she conquered / &amp; what title &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>And after of hire myschef / &amp; hire woo</L>
<L>How &thorn;at she was byseged / and I-take</L>
<L>lat him / vn-to my Maister / Petrak go</L>
<L N="3516">That wryt I-now / of this / I vndertake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan Onedake was ded / she myghtily<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The Regnes helde / &amp; with hire propre honde</L>
<L>Ageyns hire foos / she faught so cruelly</L>
<L N="3520">That there nas kyng / ne Prince / in al &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>That he nas glad / if he &thorn;at grace fond</L>
<L>That she ne wolde / vp-on his land verreye</L>
<L>with hire they made / alliaunce / by bonde</L>
<L N="3524">To ben in pees / and lete hire ride &amp; pleye
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="488"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="267"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Emperour of Rome / Claudyus</L>
<L>Ne him biforn / the Romayn Galien</L>
<L>Ne dursten neuere / ben so corageous</L>
<L N="3528">Ne noon Ermyn / ne noon Egipcien</L>
<L>Ne Surrien / ne non Arrabien</L>
<L>with-Inne the feldes / that durst with hire fight</L>
<L>leest &thorn;at she wolde hem / with hire handes slen</L>
<L N="3532">Or with hire meyne / putten hem to flight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In kynges habite / wente hire sones two</L>
<L>As Eyres / of here fadres Regnes alle</L>
<L>And Heremanno and Thymalao</L>
<L N="3536">here names were / as Persiens hem calle</L>
<L>But ay fortune hath / in hire hony / galle</L>
<L>This myghty Quene / may no while endure</L>
<L>ffortune / out of hire regne / mad hire falle</L>
<L N="3540">To wrecchednesse / and to mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Aurelian / whan that the gouernance</L>
<L>Of Rome / come in-to handes tweye</L>
<L>he shope vp-on this Quene / to do vengeaunce</L>
<L N="3544">And with hise legions / he toke his weye</L>
<L>Toward Cenobie / &amp; shortly for to seye</L>
<L>he mad hire flee / and atte laste hire hente</L>
<L>And fettred hire / and eke hire children tweye</L>
<L N="3548">And wan the lond / &amp; home to Rome he wente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Amonges othere thynges / &thorn;at he wan</L>
<L>hire Char / that was / with gold wrought / &amp; perre</L>
<L>This gret Romayn / this Aurelian</L>
<L N="3552">hath with him ladde / for &thorn;at men shulde it se</L>
<L>Biforn his Triumphe / walketh she</L>
<L>with gilt cheynes / on hire nekke hangynge</L>
<L>Corovned was she / as after hire degree</L>
<L N="3556">And ful of Perre / charged hire clothynge
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="489"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="268"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas fortune / she that whilom was</L>
<L>Dredful to kynges / and to Emperoures</L>
<L>Now gaureth al the peeple / on hire / allas</L>
<L N="3560">And she &thorn;at helmed was / in stark stoures</L>
<L>And by force / wan Tovnes stronge / and Toures<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Shal on hire hed now / were a vitrymyte</L>
<L>And she &thorn;at bar the Ceptre / ful of floures</L>
<L N="3564">Shal bere a distaf / hire cost for to quyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">[In the MS. lines 3653-3956 come here.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter the Cruel, of Spain.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[In the MS. lines 3565 to 3652 come after line 3956.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 186, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O noble / o worthy Petre / glorie of spayne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petro</NOTE></L>
<L>whom fortune helde / so heigh in mageste</L>
<L>wel oughten men / thy pytous deth compleyne</L>
<L N="3568">Out of thy lond / thy brother mad the flee</L>
<L>And after at a Sege / by sotiltee</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">a line blank in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>where as he / with his owen hand slow the</L>
<L N="3572">Succedyng in thy regne / &amp; in thy rente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The felde of snow / with the Egle of blak &thorn;ere-Inne</L>
<L>kaught with the lyme rod / coloured as the glede</L>
<L>he breweth this cursednesse / &amp; al this synne</L>
<L N="3576">The wykked nest / was wirker of this nede</L>
<L>Nought Charles / Olyuer / &thorn;at toke ay hede</L>
<L>Of trouthe &amp; honour / but of Armorike</L>
<L>Genylon / Olyuer / corrupt for mede</L>
<L N="3580">Brought this worthy knyght / in swich a brike</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter of Cyprus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O worthy Petro / kyng of Cipre also<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Petro</NOTE></L>
<L>That Alisaundre wan / by heigh maistrie</L>
<L>fful many an hethen / wroughtestow ful woo</L>
<L N="3584">Of which thyne owne lieges / hadden envye</L>
<L>And for no thyng / but for thy Chyualrie</L>
<L>They in thy bed / han slayn the by the morwe</L>
<L>Thus kan fortune / hire whel gouerne &amp; gye</L>
<L N="3588">And out of ioye / brynge men to sorwe
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000512.tif" N="490"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="269">
<HEAD>[Bernabo Visconti, of Milan.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of Melan / gret Barnabo / viscounte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Barnabo</NOTE></L>
<L>God of delit / and skourge of lumbardie</L>
<L>Why shulde I nought / thyn Infortune Acompte</L>
<L N="3592">Sithe in estat / &thorn;ou clombe were so heighe</L>
<L>Thy brothers sone / &thorn;at was thy double allye</L>
<L>ffor he thy nevew was / &amp; sone in lawe</L>
<L>with-Inne his prison / made the to dye</L>
<L N="3596">But why / ne how not I / &thorn;at &thorn;ou were slawe</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Ugolino, Count of Pisa.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of the Erl Hugelyn / of Pi&yogh;e the langour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Hugelyn</NOTE></L>
<L>There may no tonge tellen / for pitee</L>
<L>But litel out of Pi&yogh;e / stant a Tour</L>
<L N="3600">In which Tour / in prison put was he</L>
<L>And with him ben / hise litel children three</L>
<L>The eldest skarsely / fyue &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>Allas fortune / it was gret crueltee</L>
<L N="3604">swich Briddes / for to putte / in swich a cage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Dampned was he / to dye in &thorn;at prison</L>
<L>ffor Roger / which &thorn;at Busshop was / of Pi&yogh;e</L>
<L>had on him mad / a fals suggestion</L>
<L N="3608">Thurgh which the peeple / gan vp-oon him rise</L>
<L>And putten him to prison / in swich wyse<MILESTONE N="187a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd / &amp; mete &amp; drynk he hadde</L>
<L>So smal / that wel vnethe / it may suffise</L>
<L N="3612">And ther-with-al / it was ful poore &amp; badde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And oon a day bifel / that in that houre</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at his mete / wont was to be brought</L>
<L>The Gayler shette the dores / of the Tour</L>
<L N="3616">he herd it wel / but he spak right nought</L>
<L>And in his herte / a-noon &thorn;ere fel a thought</L>
<L>That they for honger / wolde don him dyen</L>
<L>Allas quod he / allas &thorn;at I was wrought</L>
<L N="3620">There-with the teres / fellen from hise eyen
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="491"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="270"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his &yogh;onge sone / &thorn;at thre &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>vn-to him seide / fader / fader / why do &yogh;e wepe</L>
<L>whan wyl the gailler / bryngen oure potage</L>
<L N="3624">Is &thorn;ere no mussel bred / that &yogh;e do kepe</L>
<L>I am so hungry / that I may nat slepe</L>
<L>Now wolde god / &thorn;at I myght slepen euere</L>
<L>Thanne shulde nought hunger / in my wombe crepe</L>
<L N="3628">There is no thyng but bred / &thorn;at me were leuere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus day by day / this child bygan to crie</L>
<L>Til in his his fadres barm / a-doun it lay</L>
<L>And seide / fare wel fader / I mot dye</L>
<L N="3632">And kist his fader / &amp; dyed the same day</L>
<L>And whan the wooful fader / ded it say</L>
<L>ffor woo / hise armes two / he gan to byte</L>
<L>And seide allas fortune / and weylaway</L>
<L N="3636">Thy false whel / my woo al may I wyte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hise children wend / &thorn;at it for hunger was</L>
<L>That he hise armes gnow / &amp; nat for woo</L>
<L>And seiden fader / do nat so allas</L>
<L N="3640">But rathere ete the flessh / vp-oon vs two</L>
<L>Oure flessh &thorn;ou &yogh;af vs / take oure flessh vs froo</L>
<L>And ete I-now / right thus / &thorn;ei to him seide</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at / with-Inne a day or two</L>
<L N="3644">The leide hem in his lappe a-doun / &amp; deide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; him-self dispeired eke / for hunger starf</L>
<L>Thus ended is / this myghty Erl of Pise</L>
<L>ffrom heigh estat / fortune a-way him karf</L>
<L N="3648">Of this tragedye / it ought I-now suffise</L>
<L>who so wol heere it / in a lengere wyse</L>
<L>Redeth the grete Poete / of ytaille</L>
<L>That hight Daunt / for he can it al deuyse</L>
<L N="3652">ffro poynt to poynt / nat oo word wil he faille<NOTE PLACE="foot">[In the MS. lines 3957, etc., follow here.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000514.tif" N="492"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="271">
<HEAD>[Nero.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[In the MS. lines 3653 to 3956 follow after line 3564.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al-though tha[t] Nero / were vicious<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Nerone</NOTE></L>
<L>As any fend / &thorn;at lith ful lowe a-doun</L>
<L>&YOGH;et he / as telleth vs / Swetoneus</L>
<L N="3656">This wilde world / had in subieccion</L>
<L>Both Est and West / North &amp; semptrion</L>
<L>Of Rubies saphires / &amp; of Perles white</L>
<L>were alle hise clothes breided / vp &amp; doun</L>
<L N="3660">ffor he in gemmes / gretly gan delite</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; More delicat / more pompous of array</L>
<L>More proud / was neuere Emperour / than he</L>
<L>That ilke cloth / &thorn;at he had wered oo day</L>
<L N="3664">After &thorn;at tyme / he nolde it neuere see</L>
<L>Nettes of gold thred / had he gret plentee</L>
<L>To fisshe in Tybre / whan him liste pleye</L>
<L>hise lustes were as lawe / in his degree</L>
<L N="3668">ffor fortune as his frend / him wolde obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; he Rome Brende / for his delicasie</L>
<L>The senatours he slew / vp-on a day</L>
<L>To here how &thorn;at men / wolde wepe &amp; crye</L>
<L N="3672">And slow his brother / &amp; by his suster lay</L>
<L>his Moder mad he / in pitous array</L>
<L>ffor he hire wombe slitte / to be-holde</L>
<L>where he conceyued was / so weylaway</L>
<L N="3676">That he so litel / of his moder tolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No tere / ou&yogh;t of his eyen / for &thorn;at sighte</L>
<L>Ne com / but seide / a fair womman was she</L>
<L>Gret wonder is / how &thorn;at he coude or myghte</L>
<L N="3680">Be domesman / of hire dede beaute</L>
<L>The wyn to bryngen him / comaunded he</L>
<L>And drank a-noon / non o&thorn;er woo he made</L>
<L>whan myght is ioyned / vn-to crueltee<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="3684">Allas to depe / wol the venym wade
<PB REF="00000515.tif" N="493"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &yogh;outhe / a maister / had this Emperour</L>
<L>To teche him lettrure / and curteisie</L>
<L>ffor of moralitee / he was the flour</L>
<L N="3688">As in his tyme / but if bookes lye</L>
<L>And whil this maister / had of him maistrie</L>
<L>he maked him so konnynge / &amp; so souple</L>
<L>That longe tyme it was / &thorn;at or tyrannye</L>
<L N="3692">Or any vice durste / in him vncouple</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Seneka / of which that I deuyse<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By-cause Nero hadde of him / swich drede</L>
<L>ffor he fro vices / wolde him ay chastise</L>
<L N="3696">Discretly as by word / and nat be dede</L>
<L>Sire wolde he seyn / an Emperour mot nede</L>
<L>Be vertuous / and hate tirannye</L>
<L>ffor which / he in a bath / made him to blede</L>
<L N="3700">On bothe hise armes / til he muste dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Nero had eke / of a Custema&umacr;nce</L>
<L>In &yogh;outhe / a-geyns his maister / for to ryse</L>
<L>which afterward / him &thorn;oughte a gret greuaunce</L>
<L N="3704">Therfore he made him dyen / in this wyse</L>
<L>But nathelees / this Seneka / this wyse</L>
<L>Ches in a bathe / to dye in this manere</L>
<L>Rathere than han / a-nother turmentrie</L>
<L N="3708">And thus hath Nero / slayn / his maister dere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now fel it so / that fortune list no lengere</L>
<L>The heye pride / of Nero to cherice</L>
<L>ffor though &thorn;at he was strong / &yogh;et was she strengere</L>
<L N="3712">She thoughte thus / by god I am to nyce</L>
<L>To sette a man / that is fulfilled of vice</L>
<L>In hey degree / and Emperour him calle</L>
<L>By god / out of his Sete / I wol him trice</L>
<L N="3716">whan he leest weneth / sonest shal he falle
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="494"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The peeple roos vp-on him / on a nyght</L>
<L>ffor his defaute / and whan he it espied</L>
<L>Out at his doores / a-noon he hath him dight</L>
<L N="3720">Allone / and there he wende / han ben allied</L>
<L>he knokked faste / and ay the more he cried</L>
<L>The fastere shette they / here doores alle</L>
<L>Tho wiste he wel / he hadde him self mys-gyed</L>
<L N="3724">And went his wey / no lengere durst he calle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The peeple criede / and rombled vp &amp; doun</L>
<L>That with hise Eres / herd he how they seide</L>
<L>Where is this fals tyraunt / this Neron</L>
<L N="3728">ffor fere almost / out of his wyt he breide</L>
<L>And to hise goddes / pitously he preyde</L>
<L>ffor socour / but it myght nought betide</L>
<L>ffor drede of this / him &thorn;ought &thorn;at he deyde</L>
<L N="3732">And ran in-to a Gardyne / him to hide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And in this Gardyne / fond he cherles tweye</L>
<L>That setyn by a fir / gret and red</L>
<L>And to theise cherles / he gan to preye</L>
<L N="3736">To slen him / &amp; to girden of his hed</L>
<L>That to his body / whan &thorn;at he were ded</L>
<L>were no despite I-don / for his deffame<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>him self he slow / he coude no bettre red</L>
<L N="3740">Of which / fortune lough / &amp; hadde a game</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Holofernes.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; was neuere capitaigne / vnder a kyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Oliferno</NOTE></L>
<L>That Regnes moo / putte in subieccioun</L>
<L>Ne strengere was in feld / of alle thyng</L>
<L N="3744">As in his tyme / ne gretter of renoun</L>
<L>Ne more pompous / in heigh presumpcion</L>
<L>Than Olyferne / which fortune ay kiste</L>
<L>So lykerously / &amp; ladde him vp &amp; doun</L>
<L N="3748">Til that his hed was of / or that he wiste
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="495"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nat oonly &thorn;at this world / had him in awe</L>
<L>ffor lesynge of richesse / or libertee</L>
<L>But made euery man / reneye his lawe</L>
<L N="3752">Nabugodonosor / was god / seide he</L>
<L>Noon other god / shulde adhoured be</L>
<L>Ageyns this hest / no wyght dar trespace</L>
<L>Saue in Bethulya / a strong Citee<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Et fecerunt filii Israell secundum quod constituerat eis sacerdos domi|ni Eliachim;</NOTE></L>
<L>where Eliachym / a Preest was / of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But take kepe of the deth / of Oliferne</L>
<L>A-mydde his oost / he dronke lay a nyght</L>
<L>with-Inne his tent / large as is a berne</L>
<L N="3760">And &yogh;et for al his pompe / &amp; al his myght</L>
<L>Iudith a womman / as he lay vp-right</L>
<L>Slepynge / his hed of smote / &amp; from his tente</L>
<L>fful pryuyly she stal / from euery wyght</L>
<L N="3764">And with his hed / vn-to hire toun she wente</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Antiochus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; what nedeth it / of king Anthiocus<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Anthioco illustri</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle / his heygh / real mageste</L>
<L>his heigh pride / his werkes venimus</L>
<L N="3768">ffor swich a-nother was &thorn;ere noon / as he</L>
<L>Rede which that he was / in Machabe</L>
<L>And rede the proude / that he seide</L>
<L>And why he fel / fro heigh prosperite</L>
<L N="3772">And in an hil / how wrecchedly he deyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffortune him hadde / enhaunced so in pride</L>
<L>That verreyly / he wende he myghte atteyne</L>
<L>Vn-to the sterres / vp-on euery syde</L>
<L N="3776">And in balaunce weyghen / ech mounteigne</L>
<L>And alle the floodes / of the see / restreyne</L>
<L>And goddes peeple / had he moost in hate</L>
<L>Hem wolde he sleen / in turment and in peyne</L>
<L N="3780">wenyng &thorn;at god ne myghte / his pride abate
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="496"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="275"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And for &thorn;at Nichanor / and Thimothe</L>
<L>with Iewes were / venquysshed myghtily<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vn-to the Iewes / swich an hate had he</L>
<L N="3784">That he bad / Greithe his Char / ful hastily</L>
<L>And swor and seide / ful dispitously</L>
<L>Vn-to Ierusalem / he wolde eft sone</L>
<L>To wreke his Ire on hit / ful crewelly</L>
<L N="3788">But of his purpos / he was lette ful sone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; God for his manace / him so sore smote</L>
<L>With invisible wounde / ay incurable</L>
<L>That in hise guttes / karf it so &amp; bote</L>
<L N="3792">That hise peynes / weren inportable</L>
<L>And certeynly the wrecche / was vnresonnable</L>
<L>ffor many a mannes guttes / did he peyne</L>
<L>But from his purpos cursed / and dampnable</L>
<L N="3796">ffor al his smert / he wolde him nat restreyne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But bad a-noon / apparailen his oost</L>
<L>And sodeynly / or he was of it war</L>
<L>God daunted al his pride / and al his boost</L>
<L N="3800">ffor he sore fil / out of his Char</L>
<L>That it hise lymes / &amp; his skin to-tar<NOTE PLACE="marg">.id est lacerauit.</NOTE></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he neither / myght go ne ryde</L>
<L>But in a Char / men a-boute him bar</L>
<L N="3804">Al forbrused / bothe bak and syde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The wreche of god / him smote so cruelly</L>
<L>That thurgh his body / wykked wormes crepte</L>
<L>And ther with al / he stank so horribly</L>
<L N="3808">That noone of alle his meyne / &thorn;at him kepte</L>
<L>Wheither so he woke / or elles slepte</L>
<L>Ne myght nought the stynk / of him / endure</L>
<L>In this myschief / he wayled and eke wepte</L>
<L N="3812">And knew god / lord / of euery creature
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="497"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To al his oost / &amp; to him self also</L>
<L>fful wlatsom was the stynk / of his careyne</L>
<L>No man ne myght him bere / to ne froo</L>
<L N="3816">And in this stynk / &amp; this orrible peyne</L>
<L>he starf ful wrecchedly / in a Mounteigne</L>
<L>Thus hath this robbour / &amp; this homycide</L>
<L>That many a man / made / to wepe &amp; pleyne</L>
<L N="3820">Swich gerdoun / as bilongeth vn-to pride</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Alexander the Great.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The storie of Alexandre / is so comune<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Alex|andro.</NOTE></L>
<L>That euery wyght / &thorn;at hath discrecion</L>
<L>hath herd somwhat / or al / of his fortune</L>
<L N="3824">This wyde world / as in conclusion</L>
<L>he wan by strengthe / or for his heigh renoun</L>
<L>They were glad / for pees / vn-to him sende</L>
<L>The pride of man and beest / he leide a-doun<MILESTONE N="185a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3828">where so he come / vn-to the worldles ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Comparison / myght neuere &yogh;et be maked</L>
<L>Bitwix him / and another Conquerour</L>
<L>ffor al this world / for drede of him hath quaked</L>
<L N="3832">he of knyghthode / and of fredome flour</L>
<L>ffortune him maked / the Eyr of hire honour</L>
<L>Saue wyn &amp; wommen / no thyng myght a-swage</L>
<L>his heigh entent / in armes and labour</L>
<L N="3836">So was he ful / of leonyn corage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; what prys were it to him / though I &yogh;ow tolde</L>
<L>Of Darius / and an hundred thousand moo</L>
<L>Of kynges / Princes / Dukes / Erles bolde</L>
<L N="3840">which he conquered / &amp; brought hem in-to woo</L>
<L>I seye / as fer / as man may ride or go</L>
<L>The world was his / what shulde I more deuyse</L>
<L>ffor though I wryte / or told &yogh;ow euere moo</L>
<L N="3844">Of his knyghthode / it might nat suffise
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="498"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; xij &yogh;er he regned / as seith Machabe</L>
<L>Philippus sone / of Macedoyne he was</L>
<L>That first was kyng / in Grece / the Contre</L>
<L N="3848">O worthy gentil Alisandre / allas</L>
<L>That euere shulde fallen / swich a kas</L>
<L>Empoysenned / of thyne owen folk / &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>thy Sys fortune / hath turned in-to as</L>
<L N="3852">And for the / ne wep she neuere / a teere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; who shal me &yogh;eue teres / to compleyne</L>
<L>The deth of gentillesse / &amp; of fraunchise</L>
<L>That al this world welded / in his demeyne</L>
<L N="3856">And &yogh;et him thoughte / it myghte nat suffise</L>
<L>So ful was his corage / of hey emprise</L>
<L>Allas who shal me helpe / to endyte</L>
<L>ffalse fortune / &amp; poyson to despise</L>
<L N="3860">The which two / of al this woo / I wyte</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Julius C&aelig;sar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By wysdom / manhed / and by gret labour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Iulio Cesare</NOTE></L>
<L>ffram humble bedde / to real magestee</L>
<L>vp ros he / Iulius / the Conquerour</L>
<L N="3864">That wan al thoccident / by lond and see</L>
<L>By strengthe of hond / or elles by tretee</L>
<L>And vn-to Rome / made hem tributarie</L>
<L>And sithe of Rome / the Emperour was he</L>
<L N="3868">Til &thorn;at fortune / wex his aduersarie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O myghty Cesar / that in Thessalie</L>
<L>Ageyns Pompeus / fader thyn in lawe<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That of the Orient / had al the Chyualrie</L>
<L N="3872">As fer as &thorn;at the day / bigynneth dawe</L>
<L>Thow thurgh thy knyghthode / hast hem take &amp; slawe</L>
<L>Saue fewe folk / that with Pompeus fledde</L>
<L>Thurgh which &thorn;ou puttest / al thorient in awe</L>
<L N="3876">Thanke fortune / that so wel the spedde
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="499"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But now a litel while / I wyl bywayle</L>
<L>This Pompeus / this noble gouernour</L>
<L>Of Rome / which &thorn;at fley at this bataille</L>
<L N="3880">I seye / oon of his men / a fals traitour</L>
<L>his hed of smot / to wynnen him fauour</L>
<L>Of Iulius / and him the hed he brought</L>
<L>Allas Pompeie / of thorient Conquerour</L>
<L N="3884">That fortune / vn-to swich a fyn / the brought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To Rome a-geyn / repaireth Iulius</L>
<L>with his triumphe / lauriat ful heye</L>
<L>But on a tyme / Brutus Cassius</L>
<L N="3888">That euere hadde / of his hey estat / envye</L>
<L>fful priuyly / hath made / Conspiracie</L>
<L>Ageyns this Iulius / in sotile wyse</L>
<L>And cast the place / in which he shulde deye</L>
<L N="3892">with boydekyns / as I shal &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Iulius / to the capitolie wente</L>
<L>vp-on a day / as he was wont to gon</L>
<L>And in the Capitolie / a-noon him hente</L>
<L N="3896">This false Brutus / &amp; hise othere foon</L>
<L>And stryked him / with Boydekyns / a-noon</L>
<L>with many a wounde / &amp; thus they lete him lye</L>
<L>But neuere grunt he / at no stroke / but oon</L>
<L N="3900">Or elles at two / but if his storie lye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So manly was this Iulius / of herte</L>
<L>And so wel loued / estatly honeste</L>
<L>That though hise dedly woundes / so sore smerte</L>
<L N="3904">his mantel ouer hise hipes / caste he</L>
<L>ffor no man shulde sen / his pryuete</L>
<L>And as he lay of deyinge / in a traunce</L>
<L>And wist verreily / that ded was he</L>
<L N="3908">Of honeste / &yogh;at had he / remembraunce
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="500"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucan to the / this storie I recomende</L>
<L>And to Sweton / and to valerius also</L>
<L>That of the storie / wryten word and ende</L>
<L N="3912">how &thorn;at theise grete / Conquerours two</L>
<L>ffortune was first frend / and sithe a foo<MILESTONE N="186a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No man ne truste / vp-oon hire fauour longe</L>
<L>But haue hire in a-wayte / for euer mo</L>
<L N="3916">wytnesse on alle / theise Conquerours stronge</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Cresus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This riche Cresus / whilom kyng of lyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cresus</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whiche / Cresus Cirus / sore him drawe</L>
<L>&YOGH;et was he kaught / a-myddes al his pride</L>
<L N="3920">And to be brent / men to the fyr him ladde</L>
<L>But such a reyn / down fro the walken shadde</L>
<L>That it slow the fyr / &amp; made to him escape</L>
<L>But to be war / no grace &yogh;et he hadde</L>
<L N="3924">Til fortune / on the galwes / made him gape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan he eskaped was / he gan nat stynte</L>
<L>ffor to begynne / a newe werre a-geyn</L>
<L>he wende wel / for &thorn;at fortune him sente</L>
<L N="3928">Swich hap / &thorn;at he eskaped thurgh the reyn</L>
<L>That of his foos / he myghte nat be slayn</L>
<L>And eke a sweuene / vp-oon a nyght he mette</L>
<L>Of which he was so proud / &amp; eke so fayn</L>
<L N="3932">That in vengeaunce / he al his herte sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vp-oon a tree he was / as &thorn;at him thoughte</L>
<L>where Iupiter him wessh / bothe bak &amp; syde</L>
<L>And Phebus eke / a fair towayl him broughte</L>
<L N="3936">To drye him with / &amp; her-for wex his pride</L>
<L>And to his doughter / &thorn;at stod him beside</L>
<L>which &thorn;at he knew / in hey science habounde</L>
<L>he bad hire telle him / what it signyfiede</L>
<L N="3940">And she his drem / bygan right thus expounde
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="501"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The tree quod she / the galwes is to mene</L>
<L>And Iuppiter bitokeneth / Snow &amp; reyn</L>
<L>And Phebus / with his towayle so clene</L>
<L N="3944">Tho ben the Sonnes stremes / for to seyne</L>
<L>Thow shalt an-hanged be / fader certeyne</L>
<L>Reyn shal the wasshe / &amp; sonne shal the drye</L>
<L>Thus warned him ful plat / &amp; ful pleyne</L>
<L N="3948">his doughter / which &thorn;at called was / Phanye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An-hanged was Cresus / the proude kyng</L>
<L>His real trone / myght him nought a-vaille</L>
<L>Tragedi es / noon other maner thyng</L>
<L N="3952">Ne can in syngynge / crie ne bywaille</L>
<L>But for &thorn;at fortune / alday wol assaille</L>
<L>with vnwar strok / the Regnes &thorn;at ben proude</L>
<L N="3955">ffor whan men trosten hire / than wyl she faille</L>
<L>And keuere hire bright face / with a cloude<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[In the MS. lines 3565 to 3652 follow here.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endeth the Monkes Tale / de casibus virorum Illustrium<NOTE PLACE="foot">[This colophon and lines 3957, etc., come after line 3652 in the MS. at the foot of page 1 of leaf 187.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="502">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="281">
<HEAD>Here bigynneth the Prologe of the Nonnes Prest /<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HOo quod the knyght / good sire no more of this</L>
<L>That &yogh;e han seid / is right I-now I-wys</L>
<L>And mochel more / for litel heuynesse</L>
<L N="3960">Is right I-now / for mechil folk I gesse</L>
<L>I seye for me / it is a gret dissese</L>
<L>where as men han ben / in gret welthe &amp; ese</L>
<L>To heren of here sodeyn fal / allas</L>
<L N="3964">And the contrarie is ioye / &amp; gret solas</L>
<L>As whan a man hath ben / in poure estat</L>
<L>And clymbeth vp / and wexeth fortunat</L>
<L>And there abydeth / in prosperitee</L>
<L N="3968">Swich thyng is gladsom / as it thynketh me</L>
<L>And of swich thyng / were goodly for to telle</L>
<L>&yogh;a quod oure hoost / by seynt Poules belle</L>
<L>&yogh;e seye right soth / this Monke he clappeth loude</L>
<L N="3972">he spak how fortune / couered was with a cloude</L>
<L>I not neuere what / and als of a tragedie</L>
<L>Right now &yogh;e herde / and parde no remedie</L>
<L>Is it / for to be-wayllen / ne compleyne</L>
<L N="3976">That<NOTE PLACE="inter">id quod</NOTE> &thorn;at is don / and als it is a peyne</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han seide / to heere of heuynesse</L>
<L>Sire Monke no more of this / so god &yogh;ow blisse</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure tale a-noyeth / al this compaignye</L>
<L N="3980">Swich thyng is nat worth / a boterflye</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere-Inne is ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS. cher]</NOTE> / no disporte ne game</L>
<L>wherfore sire Monke / o daun Piers by thy name</L>
<L>I preye &yogh;ow hertily / telle vs som-what elles</L>
<L N="3984">ffor sikerly / nere clynkyng of &yogh;oure belles
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="503"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="282"></L>
<L>That oon &yogh;oure bridel hange / oon euery syde</L>
<L>By heuene kyng / &thorn;at for vs alle dyde</L>
<L>I shulde er this / haue fallen doun for slepe</L>
<L N="3988">Al-though the slough / had neuere ben so depe</L>
<L>Thanne had &yogh;oure tale / al ben tolde in veyn</L>
<L>ffor certeynly / as &thorn;at theise Clerkes seyn</L>
<L>where as a man / may haue noon audience</L>
<L N="3992">Nat helpeth it / to tellen his sentence</L>
<L>And wel I woot / the substaunce is in me</L>
<L>If any thyng / shal wel reported be</L>
<L>Sire seye somwhat / of huntyng I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L N="3996">&para; Nay quod this Monke / I haue no lust to pleye</L>
<L>Now lat a-nother telle / as I haue tolde</L>
<L>Thanne spak oure hoost / with rude speche &amp; bolde</L>
<L>And seide vn-to the Nonnes preest / a-noon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Dd. 4. 24 <I>leaf</I> 188 <I>gone</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L>[Com nere &thorn;ou preest/ com hider &thorn;ou sir Iohn<NOTE PLACE="marg">Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf</I>  209</NOTE></L>
<L N="4001">Tell vs soch thyng/ as may our hertes glade</L>
<L>Be blythe / &thorn;ough &thorn;ou ride / vp-on a Iade /</L>
<L>What &thorn;ough thyn hors / be both foule and lene</L>
<L N="4004">Yf he woll serue the rek nat a bene/.</L>
<L>loke that thyn hert be mery euermoo/</L>
<L>Yis sir koth he / yis hoost so mot I goo/</L>
<L>But I be mery / I-wis I woll be blamed</L>
<L N="4008">And right anoon his tale he hath attamed</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seid / vn-to vs euerychone</L>
<L>This swete preest/ this godely man sir Iohn</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endeth the prologe of &thorn;e Nonnes preest/</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="504">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="283">
<HEAD>and begynneth his tale of &thorn;e Cok and &thorn;e Hen<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eg. 2726, <I>on leaf</I> 209</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Apoure widowe / somdele stope in age /</L>
<L N="4012">was whilom dwellyng in a narow cotage</L>
