<L>which signyfied / he shulde an-hanged be</L>
<L>&para; lo heere Andremacha / Ectoris wyf</L>
<L N="4332">That day &thorn;at Ector / shulde lese his lif</L>
<L>She dreemed / on the same nyght byforn</L>
<L>how &thorn;at the lyf of Ector / shulde be lorn</L>
<L>If thilke day he went / in-to bataille</L>
<L N="4336">She warned him / but it myght nat a-vaille</L>
<L>he went for to fight / nathelees</L>
<L>But he was slayn a-noon of Achilles</L>
<L N="4339">But thilke tale / is al to long to telle</L>
<L>And eke it is ny day / I may nat dwelle<MILESTONE N="192a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Shortly I seye / as for conclusion</L>
<L>That I shal han / of this auisioun</L>
<L>Aduersitee / and I seye forthermoore</L>
<L N="4344">That I ne telle / of laxatyues no store</L>
<L>ffor they ben venemous / I woot it wel</L>
<L>I hem deffye / I loue hem neuere a del</L>
<L>&para; Now late vs speke of myrthe / &amp; sthynte al this</L>
<L N="4348">Madame Partelote / so haue I blis</L>
<L>Of oo thyng / god hath sent me / large grace</L>
<L>ffor whan I se the beaute / of &yogh;oure face</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben so scarlet reed / a-boute &yogh;oure eyen</L>
<L N="4352">It maketh al my drede / for to dyen</L>
<L>[For as siker / as In principio<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf 213, bk. Not in</I>  Dd. 4. 24.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Mulier est Hominis confusio</L>
<L>Madame &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;is latyn is</L>
<L N="4356">womman is all my Ioye / and blis]</L>
<L>And whan I fele a-nyght / &yogh;oure softe syde</L>
<L>Al be it / that I may nat / on &yogh;ow ryde</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at oure perche / is maad so narwe allas</L>
<L N="4360">I am so ful of ioye / and of solas</L>
<L>That I deffye / bothe sweuene and dreem</L>
<L>And with that word / he fley doun fro the beem</L>
<L>ffor it was day / and eke his hennes alle</L>
<L N="4364">And with a chukke / he gan hem for to calle
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="514"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="293"></L>
<L>ffor he had founde a corn / lay in the &yogh;erd</L>
<L>Real he was / he was no more a-ferd</L>
<L>he fethered Pertelote / twenty tyme</L>
<L N="4368">And tradde hire eke / as oft / er it was prime</L>
<L>he loketh as it were / a grym leoun</L>
<L>And on his toos / he rometh vp &amp; doun</L>
<L>him deyned nat to sette / his foot to grounde</L>
<L N="4372">And chukketh / whan he hath / a corn I-founde</L>
<L>And to him rennen thanne / his wyues alle</L>
<L>Thus real / as a prince is / in his halle</L>
<L>leue I this Chaunteclere / in his pasture</L>
<L N="4376">And after wol I telle / his auenture</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;at the monthe / in which the world bygan<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota</NOTE></L>
<L>That highte Marche / whan god first maked man</L>
<L N="4379">was complet / and I-passed were also</L>
<L>Syn March bygan / thretty dayes &amp; two<NOTE PLACE="marg">id <I>est</I> secundo die</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Maii</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifel that Chauntecler / in al his pride</L>
<L>his wyues seuene / walking him beside</L>
<L>Caste vp his eyen / to the bright Sonne</L>
<L N="4384">That in the signe of Taurus / hadde ronne</L>
<L>Twenty degrees and oon / and somwhat more</L>
<L>he knew by kynde / and by noon o&thorn;er loore</L>
<L>That it was prime / and krew with blisful steuene<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4388">The sonne he seide / is clomben vp on heuene</L>
<L>ffourty<NOTE PLACE="inter">id est .xl</NOTE> degrees and oon / and more I-wys</L>
<L>Madame Pertelote / my worldlis blys</L>
<L>herkeneth theise blisful bryddes / how they synge</L>
<L N="4392">And se the fresshe floures / how they sprynge</L>
<L>fful is myn herte / of reuel and solas</L>
<L>But sodeynly him fel / a sorweful caas</L>
<L>ffor euere the lattere ende / of ioye / is woo<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota Salamon</NOTE></L>
<L N="4396">God woot &thorn;at worldly ioye / is sone a-go</L>
<L>And if a Rethor / coude faire endite</L>
<L>he in a cronycle saufly / myght it wryte</L>
<L>As for a souereyn / notabilitee</L>
<L N="4400">Now euery wys man / lat him herkne me
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="515"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="294"></L>
<L>This storie is also trewe / I vndertake</L>
<L>As is the book / of launcelot de lake</L>
<L>That wommen holde / in ful gret reuerence</L>
<L N="4404">Now wol I turne ageyn / to my sentence</L>
<L>&para; A Colfox ful of sly iniquytee</L>
<L>That in the groue had woned / &yogh;eres three</L>
<L>By hey ymaginacion / fore-cast</L>
<L N="4408">The same nyght / thurgh-out the hegges brast</L>
<L>In-to the &yogh;erd / there Chaunteclere the faire</L>
<L>was wont / and eke his wyues to repaire</L>
<L>And in a bed of wortes / stille he lay</L>
<L N="4412">Til it was passed / vnderne of the day</L>
<L>waytyng his tyme / on Chauntecleer to falle</L>
<L>As gladly doon / theise homycides alle</L>
<L>That in a-wayt liggen / to murdre men</L>
<L N="4416">O false mordrour / liggyng in thy den</L>
<L>O new scaryot / newe Gaenyloir</L>
<L>ffals dissimilour / o greek Synoir</L>
<L>That broughtest Troye / al vttirly to sorwe</L>
<L N="4420">O Chaunteclere / accursed be the morwe</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou in-to &thorn;at &yogh;erd / flaugh / fro the beemes</L>
<L>Thow were ful wel I-warned / by thy dreemes</L>
<L>That thilke day / was perilous to thee</L>
<L N="4424">But what &thorn;at god for-woot / mot nedes bee</L>
<L>After the opynyoun / of certeyn clerkes</L>
<L>wytnesse oon him / &thorn;at any parfyt Clerk is</L>
<L>That in Scole / is gret altricacioun</L>
<L N="4428">In this matere / and gret disputisioun</L>
<L>And hath ben / of an hundred thousand men</L>
<L>But I ne kan nat / bulte it to the bren<MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As can the holy Doctour / Augustyn</L>
<L N="4432">Or Boyce / or the Bysshop Bradwardyn</L>
<L>wheither &thorn;at goddis worthy / fore-wetyng</L>
<L>Streyneth me needly / for to doon a thyng</L>
<L>Needly / clepe I / symple necessitee</L>
<L N="4436">Or ellis if free chois / be grauntid me
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="516"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="295"></L>
<L>To doo &thorn;at same thyng / or do it nought</L>
<L>Though god forn-woot it / or &thorn;at it was wrought</L>
<L>Or if his wityng / streyneth neuere a del</L>
<L N="4440">But by necessite / condicionel</L>
<L>I wole nat han to done / of swich matere</L>
<L>My tale is of the Cok / as &yogh;e may heere</L>
<L>That took his counseil / of his wyf / with sorwe</L>
<L N="4444">To walken in the &yogh;erd / vp-oon &thorn;at morwe</L>
<L>That he had mette &thorn;at dreem / &thorn;at I &yogh;ow tolde</L>
<L>Wommens counseils / ben ful often colde</L>
<L>Wommannes counseil / brought vs first to woo</L>
<L N="4448">And made Adam / fro Paradys to goo</L>
<L>There as he was ful merie / &amp; wel at ese</L>
<L>But for I not to whom / it myght displese</L>
<L>If I counseil of wommen / wolde blame</L>
<L N="4452">Passe ouer / for I seide it in my game</L>
<L>Rede auctoures / ther they trete of swich matere</L>
<L>And what they seyn of wommen / &yogh;e moun heere</L>
<L>Theise ben the Cokkes wordes / &amp; nat myne</L>
<L N="4456">I kan noon harm / on no womman deuyne</L>
<L>&para; ffaire in the sond / to bathe myrily</L>
<L>lith Pertelote / and hire sustres by</L>
<L>Ageyne the sonne / and Chauntecler so free</L>
<L N="4460">Sang meriere / than the Mermayde in the see</L>
<L>ffor Phisiologus / seith sikirly</L>
<L>how &thorn;at they syngen wel / and merily</L>
<L>&para; And so bifel / as &thorn;at he cast his eye</L>
<L N="4464">A-mong the wortes / on a boterflye</L>
<L>he was war of this fox / &thorn;at lay ful lowe</L>
<L>No thyng / ne liste him thanne / for to crowe</L>
<L>But cried a-noon / Kok / Cok / &amp; vp he stirte</L>
<L N="4468">As man &thorn;at was affraied / in his herte</L>
<L>ffor naturely / a beest desireth flee</L>
<L>ffrom his contrarie / if &thorn;at he may it se</L>
<L>Though he neuere erst / had seen it / with his eye</L>
<L N="4472">This Chauntecleer / whan he gan him espye
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="517"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="296"></L>
<L>He wolde han fled / but that the fox a-noon<MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seide / gentil sire allas / whider wol &yogh;e goon</L>
<L>Be &yogh;e affrayed of me / that am &yogh;oure freend</L>
<L N="4476">Now certes / I were worse than a feend</L>
<L>If I to &yogh;ow wolde harm / or vylanye</L>
<L>I nam nat come / &yogh;oure counseil for to espie</L>
<L>But trewely the cause / of my comyng</L>
<L N="4480">was oonly for to herken / how &thorn;at &yogh;e syng</L>
<L>ffor trewely &yogh;e han / as merie a steuene</L>
<L>As any Aungel hath / &thorn;at is in heuene</L>
<L>Ther-with &yogh;e han in Musyke / more felynge</L>
<L N="4484">Than had Boice / or any &thorn;at can synge</L>
<L>My lord &yogh;oure fader / god his soule blisse</L>
<L>And eke &yogh;oure moder / of hire gentillesse</L>
<L>han in myn hous I-ben / to my gret ese</L>
<L N="4488">And certes sire / ful fayn wolde I &yogh;ow plese</L>
<L>But for men speke of syngynge / I wol seye</L>
<L>So mote I brouke wel / myne eyen tweye</L>
<L>Saue &yogh;e / I ne herd neuere / man so synge</L>
<L N="4492">As dede &yogh;oure fader / in the morwenynge</L>
<L>Certes it was of herte / al that he song</L>
<L>And for to make his voys / the more strong</L>
<L>he wolde so peyne him / &thorn;at with bothe hise eyen</L>
<L N="4496">he muste wynke / so loude he wolde cryen</L>
<L>And stonden on his tippton / ther-with-al</L>
<L>And strecche forth his nekke / long &amp; smal</L>
<L>And eke he was / of swich discrecioun</L>
<L N="4500">That &thorn;ere nas noman / in no regioun</L>
<L>That him in song or wysdam / myghte passe</L>
<L>I haue wel red / in Daun Burnel the Asse</L>
<L>Among his vers / how &thorn;at &thorn;ere was a Cok</L>
<L N="4504">That for a Preestes sone / &yogh;af him a knok</L>
<L>Vp-on his leg / whil he was &yogh;ong &amp; nyce</L>
<L>He made him for to lese / his benefice</L>
<L>But certyn &thorn;ere is / no comparisoun</L>
<L N="4508">Betwix the wysdom / &amp; discrecioun
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="518"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="297"></L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure fader / and of his subtilitee</L>
<L>Now syngeth sire / for seynt Charitee</L>
<L>&para; lat se / kan &yogh;e &yogh;oure fader countrefete</L>
<L N="4512">This Chauntecler / his wenges gan to bete</L>
<L>As man &thorn;at coude / his treson nat espie</L>
<L>So was he rauysshed / with his flaterie</L>
<L>Allas &yogh;e lordes / many a fals flaterour</L>
<L N="4516">Is in &yogh;our court / and many a losengeour<MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That plesen &yogh;ow wel more / be my feith</L>
<L>Than he that soothfastnesse / vn-to &yogh;ow seith</L>
<L>Redeth Ecclesiast / of flaterie</L>
<L N="4520">Beth war &yogh;e lordes / of here trecherie</L>
<L>&para; This Chauntecler stod hye / vp-oon his toos</L>
<L>Strecchynge his nekke / &amp; held hise eyen cloos</L>
<L>And gan to crowe loude / for the nones</L>
<L N="4524">And daun Russel the fox / stirt vp at ones</L>
<L>And by the gargat / hente Chauntecler</L>
<L>And on his bak / vn-to the wode him beer</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;et ne was &thorn;ere no man / &thorn;at him sewid</L>
<L N="4528">O destynee / &thorn;at may nat ben eschewed</L>
<L>Allas that Chauntecler / fley fro the beemes</L>
<L>Allas his wyf / ne roughte nat / of dreemes</L>
<L>And on a friday / fel al this meschaunce</L>
<L N="4532">&para; O venus / &thorn;at art goddesse of plesaunce</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at thyn seruaunt / was this Chauntecleer</L>
<L>And in thy seruyce / dyd al his power</L>
<L>More for delyt / than world to multiplie</L>
<L N="4536">Why woltow suffre him / on thy day to dye</L>
<L>&para; O Gaufreed / deere Maister souereyn</L>
<L>That whan thy worthy kyng / Richard was slayn</L>
<L>with shot compleynedest / his deeth so sore</L>
<L N="4540">why ne had I now / thy science &amp; thy lore</L>
<L>The friday for to chide / as deden &yogh;e</L>
<L>ffor on a friday soothly / slayn was he</L>
<L>Than wolde I shewe how / &thorn;at I coude pleyne</L>
<L N="4544">ffor Chauntecleres drede / &amp; for his peyne
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="519"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="298"></L>
<L>Certes swich cry / ne lamentacion</L>
<L>was neuere of ladies mad / whan ylion</L>
<L>was wonne / &amp; Pirrus with his streite swerd</L>
<L N="4548">whan he had hente / kyng Priamus by the berd</L>
<L>And slayn him / as seith vs Eneydes</L>
<L>As maden alle the hennes / in the cloos</L>
<L>whan they had seyn / of Chauntecleer the sighte</L>
<L N="4552">But souereynly / Dame Pertelote shrighte</L>
<L>fful loudere / than dede / hasdrubales wyf</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at hire housbonde / hadde I-lost his lyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;at the Romaynes / hadden brent Cartage</L>
<L N="4556">She was so ful of turment / and of rage</L>
<L>That wilfully / in-to the fyr she stirte</L>
<L>And brent hire seluen / with a stedfast herte</L>
<L>&para; O wooful hennes / right so cryden &yogh;e<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4560">As whan &thorn;at Nero / brente the Citee</L>
<L>Of Rome / criden Senatoures wyues</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at here housbondes / losten alle here lyues</L>
<L>with-outen gilt / this Nero hath hem slayn</L>
<L N="4564">&para; Now wol I turne / vn-to my tale a-geyn</L>
<L>The sely wydewe / and eke hire doughtren two</L>
<L>herden theise hennes crie / and maken woo</L>
<L>And out at the dores / stirten they a-noon</L>
<L N="4568">And seye the fox / to-ward the groue goon</L>
<L>And bar vp-on his bak / the Cok a-way</L>
<L>And criden out harrowe / &amp; weylaway</L>
<L>ha ha the fox / and after him they ran</L>
<L N="4572">And eke with staues / many a-nother man</L>
<L>Ran Colle oure dogge / and Talbot &amp; gerland</L>
<L>And Malkyn with a distaf / in hire hand</L>
<L>Ran kow and kalf / and eke the verray hogges</L>
<L N="4576">So feered for the berkyng / of the dogges</L>
<L>And showtyng of the men / and wommen eke</L>
<L>They ronne so / hem thought here hertes breke</L>
<L>They &yogh;elleden as fendes / don in helle</L>
<L N="4580">The Dokes criden / as men wolde hem quelle
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="520"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="299"></L>
<L>The Gees for fere / flowen ouer the trees</L>
<L>Out of the hyue / kom the swarme of bees</L>
<L>So hidous was the noise / A benedicitee</L>
<L N="4584">Certes he Iakke straw / &amp; his meyne</L>
<L>Ne maden neuere shoutes / half so shille</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at they wolden / any flemmyng kylle</L>
<L>As thilke day was maad / vp-on the fox</L>
<L N="4588">Of Bras they broughten beemes / &amp; of Box</L>
<L>Of horn / of Boon / in which they blew &amp; pouped</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-with-al / they shrykeden &amp; they houped</L>
<L>It semed / as that heuene shulde falle</L>
<L N="4592">Now goode men I prey &yogh;ow / herkeneth alle</L>
<L>lo how fortune / turneth sodeynly</L>
<L>The hope &amp; pride eke / of hire enemy</L>
<L>This Cok &thorn;at lay / vp-oon the foxes bak</L>
<L N="4596">In al his drede / vn-to the fox he spak</L>
<L>And seide sire / if I were as &yogh;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;et wolde I seyn / as wys god helpe me</L>
<L>Turneth a-geyn / &yogh;e proude Cherles alle</L>
<L N="4600">A verrey pestilence / vp-oon &yogh;ow falle</L>
<L>Now I am comen vn-to the wodes syde</L>
<L>Maugree &yogh;oure hed / the Cook shal heere abide</L>
<L>I wol him ete in feith / and that a-noon</L>
<L N="4604">The fox answered / in feith it shal be doon<MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And as he spak &thorn;at word / al sodeynly</L>
<L>The Cok brak from his mouth / delyuerly</L>
<L>And hye vp-on a tree / he flaw a-noon</L>
<L N="4608">And whan the fox saw / &thorn;at the Cok was gon</L>
<L>Allas quod he / o chaunteclere allas</L>
<L>I haue to &yogh;ow quod he / I-don trespas</L>
<L>In as meche / as I maked &yogh;ow afferd</L>
<L N="4612">whan I &yogh;ow hente / &amp; brought in-to this &yogh;erd</L>
<L>But sithe I dede it / in no wykke entente</L>
<L>Come doun / &amp; I shal telle &yogh;ow what I mente</L>
<L>I shal sey soth to &yogh;ow / god helpe me so</L>
<L N="4616">Nay / thanne quod he / I shrewe vs bothe two
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="521"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="300"></L>
<L>And first I shrewe my self / bothe blode &amp; bones</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou begile me / oftere than ones</L>
<L>Thow shalt no more / thurgh thy flaterie</L>
<L N="4620">Do me to synge / &amp; wynke with myn eye</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at wynketh / whan he shulde see</L>
<L>Al wilfully / god lat him neuere thee</L>
<L>Nay quod the fox / but god &yogh;eue him meschaunce</L>
<L N="4624">That is so vndiscret / of gouernaunce</L>
<L>That iangleth / whan he shulde holde his pees</L>
<L>lo which it is / for to be rechelees</L>
<L>And necligent / and troste on flaterie</L>
<L N="4628">But &yogh;e &thorn;at holden this tale / of folie</L>
<L>As of a fox / or of a Cok / or hen</L>
<L>Taketh the moralitee / goode men</L>
<L>ffor seynt Poule seith / &thorn;at al &thorn;at wryten is</L>
<L N="4632">To oure doctrine / it is I-wryte I-wys</L>
<L>Taketh the fruyt / &amp; lat the chaf be stille</L>
<L>Now goode god / if &thorn;at it be thy wylle</L>
<L>As seith my lord / so make vs alle goode men<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Kantuar'</NOTE></L>
<L N="4636">An brynge vs to his blisse / Amen
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000544.tif" N="522"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="301">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire Nonnes Preest / oure hoost seide a-noon</L>
<L>I-blissed be thy breche / &amp; euery ston</L>
<L>This was a murie tale / of Chauntecleer</L>
<L N="4640">But by my trouthe / if &thorn;ou were seculer</L>
<L>Thow woldest ben a tredfoul / a-right</L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;ou haue corage / as &thorn;ou hast myght</L>
<L>The were nede of hennes / as I wene</L>
<L N="4644">&yogh;a / moo than seuen tymes / seuentene</L>
<L>Se which braunes / hath this gentil Preest<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So gret a nekke / &amp; swich a large breest</L>
<L>he loketh as a Sperhauke / with hise eyen</L>
<L N="4648">him nedeth nat / his colour for to dyghen</L>
<L>with brasile / ne with greyn of Portyngale</L>
<L>Now sire / faire falle &yogh;ow / for &yogh;oure tale</L>
<L>And after that / he with ful merie chere</L>
<L N="4652">Seide vn-to a nother / as &yogh;e shuln heere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Heere endeth the Tale of the Nonnes Preest /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="G" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="523">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="527">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>G.</B> FRAGMENT VIII.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE SECOND NUN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE PROEM.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>&amp; bigynneth the Secund Nonnes Tale of Seynt Cecile / with-oute a Prologe;<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 195, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">THe ministre / and the Norice vn-to vices</L>
<L>which &thorn;at men clepen / in Englissh / ydelnesse</L>
<L>That porter at the gate is / of delices</L>
<L>To eschuen / &amp; by hire contrarie / hire oppresse</L>
<L N="5">That is to seyn / by leueful bysinesse</L>
<L>Wel oughte we / to don al oure entente</L>
<L N="7">leest &thorn;at the fend / thurgh ydelnesse vs hente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">&para; ffor he &thorn;at with his thousand cordes / slye</L>
<L>Continuely vs wayteth / to biclappe</L>
<L>whan he may man / in ydelnesse espie</L>
<L>he can so lightly / cacche him in his trappe</L>
<L N="12">Til &thorn;at a man be hent / right by the lappe</L>
<L>he nys nat war / the fend hath him in honde</L>
<L N="14">wel oughte vs werche / &amp; ydelnesse with-stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">&para; And though men dradden / neuere for to dye</L>
<L>&YOGH;et se men wel / by res&omacr;n doutelees<MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That ydelnesse is roten / slogardrye</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;ere neuere cometh / no good ne encrees</L>
<L N="19">And syn that slouthe / hire holdeth in a lees</L>
<L>Oonly for to slepe / and ete and drynke</L>
<L N="21">And to deuouren / al &thorn;at othere swynke
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="524"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="528"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">&para; And for to putte vs / from swich ydelnesse</L>
<L>That cause is / of so gret confusion</L>
<L>I haue heere doon / my feithful bysynesse</L>
<L>After the legende / in translacion</L>
<L N="26">Right of thy glorious lyf / and passion</L>
<L>Thow with thy gerland / wrought of Rose &amp; lilie</L>
<L N="28">The mene I / mayde &amp; martir / seynt Cecilie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou that flour / of virgines art alle<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Inuocacio ad Mariam</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at Bernard / list so wel to wryte</L>
<L>To the / at my bygynnyng / I first calle</L>
<L>Thow confort of vs wrecches / do me endite</L>
<L N="33">Thy maydenes deth / &thorn;at wan thurgh hire merite</L>
<L>The eternal lyf / and ouer the fend victorie</L>
<L N="35">As man may after reden / in hire storie</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">&para; Thow mayde &amp; moder / doughter of thy sone</L>
<L>Thow welle of mercy / synful soules cure</L>
<L>In whom / &thorn;at god of bountee / chees to wone</L>
<L>Thow humble &amp; heygh / ouer euery creature</L>
<L N="40">Thow nobledest so ferforth / oure nature</L>
<L>That no disdeyn / the makere hadde of kynde</L>
<L N="42">his sone in blood &amp; flessh / to clothe &amp; wynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">&para; with-Inne the cloistre blisful / of thy sydes</L>
<L>Took mannes shap / the eternal loue &amp; pees</L>
<L>That of the Tryne compas / lord and gyde is</L>
<L>whom erthe and see / &amp; heuene / out of relees</L>
<L N="47">Ay heryen / and &thorn;ou virgine wemmelees</L>
<L>Baar of thy body / &amp; dwelledest mayde pure</L>
<L N="49">The creatour / of euery creature
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="525"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">&para; Assembled is / in the magnificence</L>
<L>with mercy / goodnesse / &amp; swich pitee</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou &thorn;at art the Sonne / of excellence</L>
<L>Nat oonly helpest hem / &thorn;at preyen the</L>
<L N="54">But ofte tyme / of thy benignytee</L>
<L>fful freely / er that men / thyn helpe byseche</L>
<L N="56">Thow goost biforn / and art here lyues leche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">&para; Now helpe / &thorn;ou meke &amp; blisful / faire mayde</L>
<L>Me flemed wrecche / in this desert of galle<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thynke on the womman Cananee / that seide</L>
<L>That whelpes eten / somme / of the crommes alle</L>
<L N="61">That from hire lordes table / ben I-falle</L>
<L>And though that I / vnworthy / sone of Eue</L>
<L N="63">Be synful / &yogh;et accepte my byleue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">&para; And for &thorn;at feith / is deth / with-outen werkes</L>
<L>So for to werkyn / &yogh;eue me wyt &amp; space</L>
<L>That I be quyt from thens / &thorn;at moost derk is</L>
<L>O &thorn;ou that art so fair / and ful of grace</L>
<L N="68">Be myn aduocate / in that heigh place</L>
<L>There as with-outen ende / is songe Osanne</L>
<L N="70">Thow Cristes moder / doughter deere of Anne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">&para; And of thy light / my soule in prison lighte</L>
<L>That troubled is / by the cogitacion</L>
<L>Of my body / and also by the wighte</L>
<L>Of erthely lust / and fals affeccion</L>
<L N="75">O hauene of refuyt / o sauacion</L>
<L>Of hem / &thorn;at ben in sorwe / &amp; in distresse</L>
<L N="77">Now helpe / for to my werke / I wol me dresse
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="526"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&para; &YOGH;et preye I &yogh;ow / that reden that I wryte</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eue me / that I do no diligence</L>
<L>This ilke storie / subtilly to endite</L>
<L>ffor bothe haue I / the wordes &amp; sentence</L>
<L N="82">Of him / that at the seyntes reuerence</L>
<L>The storie wrot / and folwen hire legende</L>
<L N="84">And preye &yogh;ow / &thorn;at &yogh;e wole my werk amende</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) [THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<L>&para; ffirst wolde I &yogh;ow / the name of Seynt Cecelie<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Interpretacio nominis Cecilie quam ponit frater Iacobus Ianuensis in legenda aurea;</NOTE></L>
<L>Expoune / as men moun in hire storie se</L>
<L>It is to seyn on englissh / heuenes lilie</L>
<L>ffor pure chastnesse / of virginite</L>
<L N="89">Or for she whitnesse hadde / of honestee</L>
<L>And grene of conscience / and of good fame</L>
<L N="91">The swote sauour / lilie was hire name</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">&para; Or Cecile is to sayn / the weye to blynde</L>
<L>ffor she ensaumple was / by good techynge</L>
<L>Or ellis Cecile / as I wretyn fynde</L>
<L>Is ioyned / by a maner / conioynynge</L>
<L N="96">Of heuene and lia / and here in figurynge</L>
<L>The heuene is set / for thought of holynesse</L>
<L N="98">And lia / for hire lastynge bysinesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">&para; Cecile / may eke be seid / in this manere</L>
<L>wantyng of blyndnesse / for hire grete light</L>
<L>Of sapience / and for hire thewes clere<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or ellis lo / this maydenes name bright</L>
<L N="103">Of heuene and leos / cometh / for which by right</L>
<L>Men myghte hire wel / the heuene of peeple calle</L>
<L N="105">Ensample of good / and wyse werkes alle
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="527"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">&para; ffor leos peeple / in englissh is to seye</L>
<L>And right as men moun / in the heuene se</L>
<L>The Sonne &amp; Moone / and sterres euery weye</L>
<L>Right so / men goostly / in this mayden free</L>
<L N="110">Seyen of feith / the magnanymytee</L>
<L>And eke the clernesse / hol of sapience</L>
<L N="112">And sondry werkes / brighte of excellence</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">&para; And right so / as theise philosophres wryte</L>
<L>That heuene is swift / &amp; round / &amp; eke brennynge</L>
<L>Right so was faire Cecile / the white</L>
<L>fful swift &amp; bysy / euere in good werkynge</L>
<L N="117">And round and hool / in good perseuerynge</L>
<L>And brennyng euere / in Charite ful brighte</L>
<L N="119">Now haue I &yogh;ow declared / what she highte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; This mayden bright / Cecile / as hire lif seith<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Gregorius in regis|tro libro 10 / ad Eulogium patriar|cham scribit Iudi|camus preterea / quia grauem hic interpretum diffi|cultatem patimur dum enim non sunt qui sensum de sen|su exprimant set transferre semper verborum proprie|tatem velunt / om|nem dictorum sen|sum confundunt &amp;c'.</NOTE></L>
<L>was come of Romayns / &amp; of noble kynde</L>
<L>And from hire Cradel / vp-fostred in the feith</L>
<L>Of Crist / and bar his gospel in hire mynde</L>
<L N="124">She neuer cessed / as I wryten fynde</L>
<L>Of hire preyere / and god to loue &amp; drede</L>
<L N="126">Bysekynge him to kepe / hire maydenhede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">&para; And whan this mayden shulde / vn-to a man</L>
<L>I-wedded be / that was ful &yogh;onge of age</L>
<L>which &thorn;at I-cleped was / valerian</L>
<L>And day was comen / of hire mariage</L>
<L N="131">She ful deuout and humble / in hire corage</L>
<L>vnder hire robe of gold / &thorn;at sat ful faire</L>
<L N="133">had next hire flessh / I-clad hire in an hayre
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="528"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">&para; And whil &thorn;at the Orgenes / maden melodye</L>
<L>To god allone / in hire herte thus song she</L>
<L>O lord my soule / and eke my body gye</L>
<L>vnwemmed / lest &thorn;at I confounded be</L>
<L N="138">And for his loue / &thorn;at deyde vp-on the tree</L>
<L>Euery secunde / &amp; thridde day she faste</L>
<L N="140">Ay biddyng / in hire orisouns ful faste</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">&para; The nyght cam / &amp; to bedde must she goon</L>
<L>with hire housbonde / as ofte is the manere</L>
<L>And pryuely / to him / she seide a-noon</L>
<L>O swete / and wel biloued / spouse deere<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="145">There is a counseil / &amp; &yogh;e wolde it heere</L>
<L>which &thorn;at right fayn / I wolde vn-to &yogh;ow seye</L>
<L N="147">So that &yogh;e swere / &yogh;e shuln it nat biwreye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">&para; Valerian gan faste / vn-to hire swere</L>
<L>That for no caas / ne thyng &thorn;at myghte be</L>
<L>He shulde neuere moo / bywreyen hire</L>
<L>And thanne at erst / to him seide she</L>
<L N="152">I haue an Aungel / which &thorn;at loueth me</L>
<L>That with gret loue / where so I wake or slepe</L>
<L N="154">Is redy ay / my body for to kepe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">&para; And if that he may felen / out of drede</L>
<L>That &yogh;e me touche / or loue in vileynye</L>
<L>he right a-non / wol sleen &yogh;ow with the dede</L>
<L>And in &yogh;oure &yogh;outhe / thus &yogh;e shulden dye</L>
<L N="159">And if that &yogh;e / in clene loue me gye</L>
<L>He wol &yogh;ow loue as me / for &yogh;oure clennesse</L>
<L N="161">And shewe to &yogh;ow his ioye / &amp; his brightnesse
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="529"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">&para; This valerian / corrected as god wolde</L>
<L>Answerde ageyn / if I shal trosten the</L>
<L>lat me that Aungel seen / &amp; him biholde</L>
<L>And if that it / a verray Aungel be</L>
<L N="166">Than wol I doon / as &thorn;ou hast preyed me</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou loue / a-nother man forsothe</L>
<L N="168">Right with this swerd / than wol I slee &yogh;ow bothe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">&para; Cecile answerde a-noon / right in this wyse</L>
<L>If that &yogh;ow list / the Aungel shuln &yogh;e se</L>
<L>So that &yogh;e trowe on Crist / &amp; &yogh;ow bapti&yogh;e</L>
<L>Goth forth / to via apia / quod she</L>
<L N="173">That fro this toun / ne stant but myles three</L>
<L>And to the pouere folkes / &thorn;at there dwellen</L>
<L N="175">Sey hem right / as that I shall &yogh;ow tellen</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">&para; Tolle hem that I Cecile / &yogh;ow to hem sent</L>
<L>To shewen &yogh;ow / the goode vrban the olde</L>
<L>ffor secree nedes / and for good entente</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &yogh;e / seynt vrban han biholde</L>
<L N="180">Telle him tho wordes / which I to &yogh;ow tolde</L>
<L>And whan that he / hath purged &yogh;ow fro synne</L>
<L N="182">Than shuln &yogh;e sen &thorn;at Aungel / er we twynne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">&para; This valerian / is to the place goon</L>
<L>And right as he was taught / by hys lernynge</L>
<L>he fond this holy vrban / a-noon</L>
<L>A-mong the seyntes buriels / lotynge<NOTE PLACE="inter">id <I>est</I> latitantem</NOTE></L>
<L N="187">And he a-noon / with-outen tariynge</L>
<L>Dide his message / and whan that he it tolde<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="189">vrban for ioye / his handes gan vp holde
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="530"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">&para; The teeres from his eyen / leet he falle</L>
<L>Almyghty lord / o Ihesu Crist quod he</L>
<L>Sowere of chast counseil / hierde of vs alle</L>
<L>The fruyt of thilke seed / of Chastitee</L>
<L N="194">That &thorn;ou hast sowe in Cecile / take to the</L>
<L>lo lyke a bisy bee / with-oute gyle</L>
<L N="196">The seruyth ay / thyn owen thral Cecile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">&para; ffor thilke spouse / that she tok but now</L>
<L>fful lyke a fiers leon / she sendith heere</L>
<L>As meke / as euere was any lamb to &yogh;ow</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word / a-noon there gan appere</L>
<L N="201">An olde man / clad in white clothes clere</L>
<L>That hadde a book / with lettre of gold in honde</L>
<L N="203">And gan biforn Valerian / to stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">&para; Valerian as ded / fel doun for drede</L>
<L>whan he him say / &amp; he vp hente him tho</L>
<L>And oon his book / right thus he gan to rede</L>
<L>O lord / of o feith / o god / with-oute moo</L>
<L N="208">O cristendom / and fader of alle also</L>
<L>Abouen alle / &amp; ouer alle / euery where</L>
<L N="210">Theise wordes / alle with gold / I-wretyn were</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">&para; whan this was red / than seide this olde man</L>
<L>leeuest &thorn;ou this thyng or no / sey &yogh;a or nay</L>
<L>I leue alle thyng / quod valerian</L>
<L>ffor sother thyng than this / I dar wel say</L>
<L N="215">vnder the heuene / no wyght thynke may</L>
<L>Tho vanysshed this olde man / he nyste where</L>
<L N="217">And Pope vrban / him cristened right there
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="531"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">&para; Valerian goth hoom / and fynt Cicilie</L>
<L>with-Inne his Chaumbre with an Aungel stond</L>
<L>This Aungel hadde of Roses / and of lilie</L>
<L>Corounes two / the which he bar in honde</L>
<L N="222">And first to Cecile / as I vnderstonde</L>
<L>he &yogh;af that oon / and after gan he take</L>
<L N="224">That other / to valerian hire make</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">&para; with body clene / and with vnwemmed thought</L>
<L>kepeth ay wel / theise corones quod he</L>
<L>ffro Paradys to &yogh;ow / haue I hem brought</L>
<L>Ne neuere moo / ne shuln they roten be</L>
<L N="229">Ne lese here swote sauour / trusteth me</L>
<L>Ne neuere wyght / shal sen hem with his eye<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="231">But he be chaast / and hate vylenye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">&para; And thow valerian / for thow so sone</L>
<L>Assentedest / to good counseil also</L>
<L>Sey what the list / &amp; &thorn;ou shalt han thy boone</L>
<L>I haue a brother / quod valerian tho</L>
<L N="236">That in this world / I loue no man so</L>
<L>I preye &yogh;ow / &thorn;at my brother may haue grace</L>
<L N="238">To knowe the trouth / as I do in this place</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">&para; The Aungel seide / god liketh thy requeste</L>
<L>And bothe with the palme / of martirdoom</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shuln come / vn-to his blisful reste</L>
<L>And with that word / Tiburce his brother coom</L>
<L N="243">And whan that he / the sauour vndernoom</L>
<L>which that the Rooses / &amp; the lilies caste</L>
<L N="245">with-Inne his herte / he gan to wondre faste
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="532"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="536"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">&para; And seide I wondre / this tyme of the &yogh;ere</L>
<L>whennes that swote sauour / cometh so</L>
<L>Of Rose and lilies / that I smelle heere</L>
<L>ffor though I hadde hem / in myn hondes two</L>
<L N="250">The sauour myghte in me / no deppere goo</L>
<L>The swete smel / &thorn;at in myn herte I fynde</L>
<L N="252">hath chaunged me / al in a-nother kynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">&para; Valerian seide / two corounes han we</L>
<L>Snow white / &amp; Rose reed / &thorn;at shynen clere</L>
<L>which &thorn;at thyne eyen / han no myght to se</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ou smellest hem / thurgh my preyere</L>
<L N="257">So shaltow sen hem / leue brother deere</L>
<L>If it so be / &thorn;ou wolt with-outen slouthe</L>
<L N="259">Byleeue aright / &amp; knowen verray trouthe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">&para; Tiburce answerde / seist &thorn;ou this to me</L>
<L>In soothnesse / or in dreem / I herkne this</L>
<L>In dremes quod valerian / haue we be</L>
<L>Vn-to this tyme / brother myn I-wys</L>
<L N="264">But now at erst / in trouthe / oure dwellyng is</L>
<L>how wostow this quod Tiburce / in what wyse</L>
<L N="266">Quod valerian / that shal I the deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">&para; The Aungel of god / hath me the trouthe I-taught</L>
<L>which &thorn;ou shalt seen / if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt reneye</L>
<L>The ydoles and be clene / and ellis naught</L>
<L>And of the myracle / of theise corones tweye</L>
<L N="271">Seynt Ambrose / in his preface list to seye</L>
<L>Solempnely / this noble doctour deere</L>
<L N="273">Commendeth it / and seith in this manere<MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="533"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">&para; The palme of martirdom / for to receyue</L>
<L>Seynt Cecile / fulfild of goddes &yogh;ifte</L>
<L>The world and eke hire chaumbre / gan she weyue</L>
<L>wytnesse Tiburces / and Cecilies shrifte</L>
<L N="278">To which / god of his bountee wolde shifte</L>
<L>Corones two / of floures wel smellynge</L>
<L N="280">And made his Aungel / hem the corones brynge</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">&para; The mayde hath brought hem / to blisse a-boue</L>
<L>The world hath wist / what it is worth certeyn</L>
<L>Deuocion of Chastitee / to loue</L>
<L>Tho shewed him Cecile / al open &amp; pleyn</L>
<L N="285">That alle ydoles / nys but a thyng in veyn</L>
<L>ffor they ben doumbe / &amp; &thorn;er-to they ben deeue</L>
<L N="287">And charged him / his ydoles for to leeue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">&para; who so &thorn;at troweth nat this / a beest he is</L>
<L>Quod tho Tiburce / if that I shal nat lye</L>
<L>And she gan kisse his breest / that herde this</L>
<L>And was ful glad / he coude trouthe espye</L>
<L N="292">This day / I take the / for myn allye</L>
<L>Seide this blisful / faire mayde deere</L>
<L N="294">And after &thorn;at she seide / as &yogh;e moun heere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">&para; lo / right so / as the loue of Crist / quod she</L>
<L>Made me thy brothers wyf / right in that wyse</L>
<L>A-noon for myn allye / heere take I the</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt / thyne ydoles despise</L>
<L N="299">Go with thy brother now / and the baptise</L>
<L>And make the clene / so &thorn;at &thorn;ou nowe byholde</L>
<L N="301">The Aungels face / of which thy brother tolde
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="534"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">&para; Tiburce answerde / and seide Brother deere</L>
<L>ffirst telle me / whider &thorn;at I shal / &amp; to what man</L>
<L>To whom quod he / come forth with right good cheere</L>
<L>I wol the lede / vn-to the Pope vrban</L>
<L N="306">To vrban / Brother myn valerian</L>
<L>Quod tho Tiburce / woltow me thider lede</L>
<L N="308">Me thynketh / that it were a wonder dede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">&para; Ne menestow nat vrban / quod he thoo</L>
<L>That is so ofte dampned / to be ded</L>
<L>And woneth in halkes / alwey to and froo</L>
<L>And dar nat oones / putte forth his hed</L>
<L N="313">Men shulde him brennen / in a fyr so red</L>
<L>If he were founde / or &thorn;at men myght him spie</L>
<L N="315">And we also / to bere him compaignye<MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">&para; And whil we sekyn / thilke diuinitee</L>
<L>That is I-hid / in heuene pryuely</L>
<L>Algate I-brent in this world / shuln we be</L>
<L>To whom Cecile answerde / boldely</L>
<L N="320">Men myghten dredyn wel / and skylfully</L>
<L>Thys lyf to lese / my owne deere brother</L>
<L N="322">If this were lyuyng oonly / &amp; noon other</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">&para; But there is better lyf / in other place</L>
<L>That neuere shal be lost / ne drede the nought</L>
<L>which goddes sone / vs tolde / thurgh his grace</L>
<L>That fadres sone / hath alle thynges wrought</L>
<L N="327">And al &thorn;at wrought is / with a skilful thought</L>
<L>The goost &thorn;at fro the fader / gan procede</L>
<L N="329">hath sowled hem / with-outen any drede
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="535"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="539"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L N="330">&para; By word &amp; by myracle / he goddes sone</L>
<L>Whan he was in this world / declared heere</L>
<L>That &thorn;ere was other lyf / &thorn;ere man may wone</L>
<L N="333">To whom answerde Tiburce / o suster deere</L>
<L>Ne seydestow right now / in this manere</L>
<L>There nas but o god / lord in soothfastnesse</L>
<L N="336">And now of three / how maistow bere wytnesse</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L N="337">&para; That shal I telle quod she / er I go</L>
<L>Right as a man / hath sapiences three</L>
<L>Memorie / engyn / and Intellect also</L>
<L N="340">So in oo beyng / of diuinitee</L>
<L>Thre persones / may there / right wel be</L>
<L>Tho gan she him / ful bisily to preche</L>
<L N="343">Of Cristes sone / and of his peynes teche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">&para; And manye poyntes / of his passion</L>
<L>how goddes sone / in this world was withholde</L>
<L>To doon mankynde / playn remyssion</L>
<L N="347">That was I-bounde / in synne / &amp; cares colde</L>
<L>Al this thyng / she vn-to Tiburce tolde</L>
<L>And after this Tiburce in good entente</L>
<L N="350">With valerian / to Pope vrban he wente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That thanked god / &amp; with glad herte &amp; light<NOTE PLACE="marg">qui sanctus vrbanus</NOTE></L>
<L>he cristned him / and mad him in that place</L>
<L>Parfyt in his lernynge / goddes knyght</L>
<L N="354">And after this / Tiburce gat swich grace</L>
<L>That euery day / he sey in tyme and space</L>
<L>The Aungel of god / and euery maner boone</L>
<L N="357">That he god axed / it was sped ful soone
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="536"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L>&para; It wer ful hard / by ordre for to seyn<MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[Leaves 200 and 201 are transposed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>how manye wondres / Ihesus for hem wroughte</L>
<L>But at the laste / to tellen short and pleyn</L>
<L N="361">The sergeaunte&yogh; of the Toun of Rome / hem soughte</L>
<L>And hem / biforn Almache the prefect / broughte</L>
<L>which hem opposed / and knew al here entente</L>
<L N="364">And to the ymage / of Iubiter / hem sente</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="365">&para; And seide / who so wol nought do sacrifise</L>
<L>Swap of his hed / this is myn sentence heere</L>
<L>A-noon theise martirs / that I &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
<L N="368">Oon Maximus / that was an officere</L>
<L>Of the prefectes / and his cornyculere</L>
<L>hem hente / &amp; whan he forth / the seyntes ladde</L>
<L N="371">him self he wep / for pitee &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="372">&para; Whan Maximus had herd / the seyntes loore</L>
<L>he gat him / of the Turmentours leue</L>
<L>And hadde hem to his hous / with-oute more</L>
<L N="375">And with here prechyng / er &thorn;at it were eue</L>
<L>They gonnen fro turmentours / to reue</L>
<L>And fro Maxime / and fro his folk echone</L>
<L N="378">The fals feith / to trowe in god allone</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L N="379">&para; Cecile cam / whan it was woxen nyght</L>
<L>With Preestes / &thorn;at hem cristened alle I-feere</L>
<L>And afterward / whan day was woxen light</L>
<L N="382">Cecile him seide / with a ful stedfast cheere</L>
<L>Now Cristes owne knyghtes / leeue &amp; deere</L>
<L>Cast al a-wey / the werkes of derknesse</L>
<L N="385">And armeth &yogh;ow in armes of brightnesse
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="537"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="541"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&para; &YOGH;e han forsothe / I-don a gret bataille</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure cours is don / &yogh;oure feith haue &yogh;e conserued</L>
<L>Goth to the corone of lyf / &thorn;at may nat faile</L>
<L N="389">The rightful Iuge / which that &yogh;e han serued</L>
<L>Shal &yogh;eue it &yogh;ow / as &yogh;e han it deserued</L>
<L>And whan this thyng / was seid / as I deuyse</L>
<L N="392">Men ledde hem forth / to don the sacrifise</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L N="393">&para; But whan they weren / to the place brought</L>
<L>To tellen shortly / the conclusioun</L>
<L>They nolde encence / ne sacrifise right nought</L>
<L N="396">But on here knees / they setten hem a-doun</L>
<L>With humble herte / and sad deuocion</L>
<L>And losten bothe here heuedes / in the place</L>
<L N="399">here soules wenten / to the kyng of grace</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L>&para; This Maximus / that sey this thyng betide<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with pitous teeres / tolde it a-noon right</L>
<L>That he here soules saw / to heuene glide</L>
<L N="403">with Aungeles / ful of cleernesse / and of light</L>
<L>And with his word / conuerted many a wyght</L>
<L>ffor which / Almachius / dide him so to-bete</L>
<L N="406">with whippe of leed / til he his lyf gan lete</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L N="407">&para; Cecile him took / and buried him a-noon</L>
<L>By Tiburce / and Valerian softly</L>
<L>With-Inne hire buriynge place / vnder the stoon</L>
<L N="410">And after this / Almachius hastily</L>
<L>Bad hise Mynystres / fecchen openly</L>
<L>Cecile / so &thorn;at she myghte in his presence</L>
<L N="413">Doon sacrifise / and Iubiter encence
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="538"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="414">&para; But they conuerted / at hire wyse loore</L>
<L>Wepten ful sore / and &yogh;auen ful credence</L>
<L>vn-to hire word / and cryden moore &amp; moore</L>
<L N="417">Crist goddes sone / with-outen difference</L>
<L>Is verray god / this is al oure sentence</L>
<L>That hath so good a seruaunt / him to serue</L>
<L N="420">This / with o vois / we trowen / though we sterue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="421">&para; Almachius / that herde of this doynge</L>
<L>Bad fecchen Cecile / &thorn;at he myghte hire se</L>
<L>And alderfurst lo / this was his axynge</L>
<L N="424">What maner womman / artow quod he</L>
<L>I am a gentil womman / born / quod she</L>
<L>I axe the quod he / though it the greeue</L>
<L N="427">Of thy religion / and of thy byleue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="428">&para; Why thanne bygan / &yogh;oure question folily</L>
<L>Quod she / &thorn;at woldest two answeres conclude</L>
<L>In oo demaunde / &yogh;e axed lewedly</L>
<L N="431">Almache answerde / vn-to &thorn;at similitude</L>
<L>Of whennes cometh / thyn answeryng so rude</L>
<L>Of whennes quod she / whan &thorn;at she was freyned</L>
<L N="434">Of Conscience / and of good feith vnfeyned</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="435">&para; Almachius seide / ne takestow noon heede</L>
<L>Of my power / and she answerde him this</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure myght quod she / ful litel is to drede</L>
<L N="438">ffor euery mortal mannes power / nys</L>
<L>But like a bladdre / ful of wynd I-wys</L>
<L>ffor with a nedles poynt / whan it is blowe</L>
<L N="441">May al the boost of it / be leid ful lowe
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="539"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="442">&para; fful wrongfully / bygonne &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>And &yogh;et in wrong / is al thy perseueraunce<MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[Leaves 200 and 201 are transposed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wostow nat how / oure myghty Princes free</L>
<L N="445">Ben thus comaunded / and mad ordinaunce</L>
<L>That euery cristene wyght / shal han penaunce</L>
<L>But if that he / his cristendom with-seye</L>
<L N="448">And goon al quyt / if he wol it reneye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&para; &YOGH;oure princes erren / as &yogh;oure nobleye dooth</L>
<L>Quod tho Cecile / and with a wood sentence</L>
<L>&YOGH;e make vs gilty / and is nat sooth</L>
<L N="452">ffor &yogh;e &thorn;at knowen wel / oure Innocence</L>
<L>ffor as muche / as we doon a reuerence</L>
<L>To crist / and for we bere a cristene name</L>
<L N="455">&YOGH;e put on vs a cryme / and eke a blame</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="456">&para; But we &thorn;at knowen / thilke name so</L>
<L>ffor vertuous / we moun it nought with-seye</L>
<L>Almache answerde / chees on of theise twoo</L>
<L N="459">Do sacrifise / or cristendom reneye</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou mowe now / escapen by that weye</L>
<L>At which / this holy blisful / faire mayde</L>
<L N="462">Gan for to laughe / and to the Iuge she seide</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="463">&para; O Iuge confus / in thy nycetee</L>
<L>Woltow / &thorn;at I reneye / Innocence</L>
<L>To maken me / a wykked wight / quod she</L>
<L N="466">lo he dissimuleth here / in audience</L>
<L>He stareth and wodeth / in his aduertence</L>
<L>To whom Almachius seide / vnsely wrecche</L>
<L N="469">Ne wostow nat / how fer my myght may strecche
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="540"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="544"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L N="470">&para; Han nought oure myghty princes / to me &yogh;euen</L>
<L>&YOGH;a / bothe power / and auctoritee</L>
<L>To maken folk / to dyen or to lyuen</L>
<L N="473">Why spekestow so proudly / thanne to me</L>
<L>I speke nought / but stedfastly quod she</L>
<L>Nat proudly / for I seye as for my syde</L>
<L N="476">We haten dedly / thilke vice of pride</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="477">&para; And if &thorn;ou drede nought / a soth for to heere</L>
<L>Thanne wol I shewe / al openly by right</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou hast mad / a ful gret lesyng heere</L>
<L N="480">Thow seist / thyne princes / han the &yogh;euen myght</L>
<L>Bothe for to sleen / and for to quyken a wight</L>
<L>Thow &thorn;at ne maist / but oonly lyf byreue</L>
<L N="483">Thow hast noon other power / ne no leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L N="484">&para; But &thorn;ou maist seyn / thyne princes han the maked</L>
<L>Ministre of deth / for if thow speke of moo<MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thow liest / for thy power is ful naked</L>
<L N="487">Do wey thyn boldenesse / seide Almachius tho</L>
<L>And do sacrifise to our goddes / er &thorn;ou go</L>
<L>I recche nat what wrong / &thorn;at thow me profre</L>
<L N="490">ffor I can suffre it / as a Philosophre</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="491">&para; But thilke wronges / may I nat endure</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou spekest / of oure goddes heere quod he</L>
<L>Cecile answerde / o nyce creature</L>
<L N="494">Thow seidest no word / syn &thorn;ou spake to me</L>
<L>That I ne knew there-with / thy nycetee</L>
<L>And that &thorn;ou were / in euery maner wyse</L>
<L N="497">A lewed officere / a veyn Iustise
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="541"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="545"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L>&para; There lakketh no thyng / to thyne vttere eyen<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; exteriori|bus oculis</NOTE></L>
<L>That &thorn;ou nart blynd / for &thorn;ing &thorn;at we sen alle</L>
<L>That is a ston / &thorn;at men moun wel espien</L>
<L N="501">That ilke a ston / a god &thorn;ou wolt it calle</L>
<L>I rede the / lat thyn hond / vp-on it falle</L>
<L>And taste it wel / &amp; ston &thorn;ou shalt it fynde</L>
<L N="504">Syn &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest nat / with thyne eyen blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="505">&para; It is a shame / that the peeple shal</L>
<L>So scornen the / and laughe at thyn folie</L>
<L>ffor comunly / men woot it wel ouer al</L>
<L N="508">That myghty god is / in his heuenes hye</L>
<L>And theise ymages / wel &thorn;ou maist espie</L>
<L>To the / ne to hem self / moun nat profite</L>
<L N="511">ffor in effect / they be nat worth a myte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="512">&para; Theise and swich othere / seide she</L>
<L>And he wex wroth / &amp; bad men shulde hire lede</L>
<L>hoom til hire hous / and in hire hous quod he</L>
<L N="515">Brenne hire / right in a bathe / with flaumbes rede</L>
<L>And as he bad / right so was done the dede</L>
<L>ffor in a bathe / they gonne hire faste shetten</L>
<L N="518">And nyght and day / gret fyr they vnder betten</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="519">&para; The longe nyght / and eke a day also</L>
<L>ffor al the fyr / and eke the bathes hete</L>
<L>She sat al cold / and feled no woo</L>
<L N="522">It made hire nat / a drope for to swete</L>
<L>But in that bath / hire lif she muste lete</L>
<L>ffor he Almachius / with a ful wykke entente</L>
<L N="525">To slen hire in the bath / his sonde sente
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="542"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="526">&para; Thre strokes in the nekke / he smot hire tho</L>
<L>The turmentour / but for no maner chaunce<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he myght nat smyte / al hire nekke a two</L>
<L N="529">And for &thorn;ere was that tyme / an ordinaunce</L>
<L>That no man / shulde do man / swich penaunce</L>
<L>The ferthe strok to smyten / soft or soore</L>
<L N="532">This turmentour / ne durste do no more</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L N="533">&para; But half ded / with hire nekke I-koruen there</L>
<L>he lefte hire lye / and on his wey is went</L>
<L>The cristene folk / which &thorn;at a-boute hire were</L>
<L N="536">with shetes / han the blod ful faire I-hent</L>
<L>Three dayes lyued she / in this turment</L>
<L>And neuere cessed / hem the feith to teche</L>
<L N="539">That she had fostred / hem / she gan to preche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">&para; And hem she &yogh;af / hire meebles &amp; hire thyng</L>
<L>And to the Pope vrban / bytok hem tho</L>
<L>And seide / I axed this of heuene kyng</L>
<L N="543">To haue respit / three dayes and no moo</L>
<L>To recomende to &yogh;ow / er that I go</L>
<L>Theise soules lo / and that I myght do werche</L>
<L N="546">heere of myn hous / perpetuelly a chirche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="547">&para; Seynt vrban / with hise dekenes priuely</L>
<L>The body fette / and buryed it by nyghte</L>
<L>A-mong hise othere seyntes / honestly</L>
<L N="550">hire hous / the Chirche of seynt Cecile highte</L>
<L>Seynt vrban halwed it / as he wel myghte</L>
<L>In which / in-to this day / in noble wyse</L>
<L N="553">Men don to Crist / and to his seynt seruyse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Amen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Heere endeth the Secund Nonnes tale;</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="543">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="547">
<HEAD>&amp; bigynneth the Prologe of the Chanouns &yogh;eman;</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan that told was / the lyf of seynt Cecile</L>
<L>Er we had riden fully / fyue myle</L>
<L>At Boughton vnder blee / vs gan a-take</L>
<L N="557">A man / &thorn;at clothed was / in clothes blake</L>
<L>And vndernethe he wered / a surplys</L>
<L>his hakeney / which &thorn;at was / al pomely grys</L>
<L>So swat / that it wonder was to se</L>
<L N="561">It semed / as he had pryked / myles three</L>
<L N="564">Aboute the peyntrel / stod the fome ful hye</L>
<L N="565">he was of fome / al flekked as a Pye</L>
<L N="562">The hakeneye eke / &thorn;at his &yogh;eman rod vp-oon<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="563">So swatte / that vnethe myght it gon</L>
<L N="566">A male tweyfold / vp-on his croper lay</L>
<L N="567">It semed that he caried / litel array</L>
<L>Al light for somer / rod this worthy man</L>
<L N="569">And in myn herte / to wondre I began</L>
<L>What that he was / til that I vnderstode</L>
<L>how &thorn;at his cloke / was sowed to his hode</L>
<L>ffor which / whan I had longe a-vysed me</L>
<L N="573">I demed him som Chanoun / for to be</L>
<L>his hat heng at his bak / doun by a lace</L>
<L>ffor he had riden more / than trot or pace</L>
<L>he had ay / priked / lyke as he were wood</L>
<L N="577">A clote leef he hadde / vnder his hood</L>
<L>ffor swete / and for to kepe / his hed from hete</L>
<L>But it was ioye / for to sen him swete</L>
<L>his forhe[de] dropped / as a stillatorie</L>
<L N="581">were ful of plaunteyn / and of peritorie
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="544"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="548"></L>
<L N="582">And whan &thorn;at he was come / he gan to crie</L>
<L>God saue quod he / this ioly compaignye</L>
<L>ffast haue I pryked quod he / for &yogh;oure sake</L>
<L N="585">By cause / that I wolde / &yogh;ow a-take</L>
<L>To ryden in the same / myrie compaignye</L>
<L>his &yogh;eman was eke / ful of curteisie</L>
<L>And seide sir[s]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a hole in the MS.]</NOTE> / now in the morwe tyde</L>
<L N="589">Out of &yogh;oure hostelrie / I saw &yogh;ow ride</L>
<L>And warned heere my lord / &amp; my souerayn</L>
<L>which that to riden with &yogh;ow / is ful fayn</L>
<L>ffor his disport / he loueth daliaunce</L>
<L>&para; ffrend for thy warnynge / god &yogh;eue the good chaunce</L>
<L>Thanne seide oure hoost / for certeyn it wolde seme</L>
<L>Thy lord were wys / and so I may wel deme</L>
<L>he is ful iocunde / also dar I leye</L>
<L N="597">Can he ought telle / a mery tale or tweye</L>
<L>with which he glade may / this compaignye</L>
<L>who sire my lord / &yogh;a &yogh;a with-outen lye</L>
<L>he can of myrthe / and eke of iolytee</L>
<L N="601">Nat but I-now / also sire trusteth me</L>
<L>And &yogh;e him knew / as wel as do I</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wolde wondre / how wel and craftily</L>
<L>he coude werke / and that in sondry wyse</L>
<L N="605">He hath take on him / many a gret emprise<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>which were ful hard / for any &thorn;at is heere</L>
<L>To brynge a-boute / but they of him it lere</L>
<L>As homly as he ryt / a-monges &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="609">If &yogh;e him knewe / it wolde be for &yogh;oure prow</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wolde nat forgon / his acqueyntaunce</L>
<L>ffor mechel good / I dar leye in balaunce</L>
<L>Al that I haue / in my possession</L>
<L N="613">he is a man / of heigh discresion</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ow wel / he is a passyng man</L>
<L>wel quod oure hoost / I preye the telle me than</L>
<L>Is he a Clerk or noon / telle what he is</L>
<L N="617">Nay / he is grettere than a Clerk / I-wys
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="545"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="549"></L>
<L>Seide this &yogh;eman / and in wordes fewe</L>
<L>Hoost of his craft / som-what I wol &yogh;ow shewe</L>
<L>I seye my lord can / suche sotiltee</L>
<L N="621">But al his craft / &yogh;e moun nat wyte of me</L>
<L>And som-what helpe I &yogh;et / to his werkyng</L>
<L>That al this grounde / on which we ben ridyng</L>
<L>Til that we come / to Caunterbury Toun</L>
<L N="625">he coude al clene / turnen vp so doun</L>
<L>And paue it al of siluer / and of golde</L>
<L>And whan this &yogh;eman / had this tale I-tolde</L>
<L>Vn-to oure host / he seide benedicite</L>
<L N="629">This thyng / is wonder merueillous / to me</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at thy lord / is of so heigh prudence</L>
<L>By cause of which / men shulde him reuerence</L>
<L>That of his worship / reweth he so lite</L>
<L N="633">his ouer sloppe / nys nought worth a myte</L>
<L>As in effect / to him / so mot I go</L>
<L>It is al baudy / and tore also</L>
<L>Why is thy lord so sluttissh / I the preye</L>
<L N="637">And is of power / bettre cloth to beye</L>
<L>If that his dede / acorded with thy speche</L>
<L>Telle me that / and I the biseche</L>
<L>&para; Why quod this &yogh;eman / wher-to aske &yogh;e me</L>
<L N="641">God helpe me so / for he shal neuere the</L>
<L>But I wol nat a-vowe / that I seye</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore kepe it secree / I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L>he is to wys in feith / as I bileue</L>
<L N="645">That &thorn;at is ouer doon / It wol nat preue<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Omne quod est nimium &amp;c'</NOTE></L>
<L>A-right / as Clerkes seyn / it is a vyce</L>
<L>werfore in that / I holde him lewed and nice<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor whan a man hath / ouer gret a wit</L>
<L N="649">fful ofte him happeth to mys-vsen it</L>
<L>So doth my lord / and that me greueth sore</L>
<L>God it amende / I can sey no more</L>
<L>&para; Ther-of no fors / good &yogh;eman / quod oure hoost</L>
<L N="653">Syn of the conynge of thy lord &thorn;ou woost
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="546"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="550"></L>
<L>Telle how he doth / I preye the hertly</L>
<L>Syn that he is / so crafty / and so sly</L>
<L>Where dwelle &yogh;e / if it to telle be</L>
<L N="657">In the subarbes of a Toun / quod he</L>
<L>lurkynge in hernes / and in lanes blynde</L>
<L>Where as theise robbours / &amp; theise theues by kynde</L>
<L>holden here pryue / ferful residence</L>
<L N="661">As they that durn nat shewen / here presence</L>
<L>So faren we / if I shal seye the sothe</L>
<L>&YOGH;et quod oure hoost / lat me talke to the</L>
<L>Why artow so discoloured / of thy face</L>
<L N="665">Peter quod he / god &yogh;eue it harde grace</L>
<L>I am so vsed / in the fir to blowe</L>
<L>That it hath chaunged / my colour I trowe</L>
<L>I nam nat wont / in no myrour to prye</L>
<L N="669">But swynke sore / and lerne multiplie</L>
<L>we blundren euere / and pouren in the fyre</L>
<L>And for al that / we faille of oure desire</L>
<L>ffor euere we lakke / oure conclusion</L>
<L N="673">To mechel folk / we don illusion</L>
<L>And borwe gold / be it a pound or two</L>
<L>Or ten or twelue / and manye sommes moo</L>
<L>And maken hem wenen / atte leest weye</L>
<L N="677">That of a pound / we coude make tweye</L>
<L>&YOGH;et is it fals / and ay we han good hope</L>
<L>It for to doon / and after it we grope</L>
<L>But that science / is so fer vs biforn</L>
<L N="681">We moun nat / al-though we hadden sworn</L>
<L>It ouer take / it slit a-wey so faste</L>
<L>It wol vs make beggers / atte laste</L>
<L>Whil this &yogh;eman was thus / in this talkyng</L>
<L N="685">This Chanoun drow him nere / &amp; herd al thyng</L>
<L>Which this &yogh;eman spak / for suspecion</L>
<L>Of mennes speche / euere hadde this Chanon</L>
<L>ffor Caton seith / that he that gilty is</L>
<L N="689">Demeth al thyng / be spoke of him I-wys<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="547"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="551"></L>
<L>That was the cause / he gan so ney him drawe</L>
<L>To his &yogh;eman / to herken al his sawe</L>
<L>And thus he seide / vn-to his &yogh;eman thoo</L>
<L N="693">holde &thorn;ou thy pees / &amp; speke no wordes moo</L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;ou do / thow shalt it dere a-bye</L>
<L>Thow sclaundrest me heere / in this companye</L>
<L>And eke discouerest / &thorn;at &thorn;ou shuldest hide</L>
<L N="697">&YOGH;a quod oure hoost / telle on what so betide</L>
<L>Of al his thretenynge / rekke nat a myte</L>
<L>In feith quod he / no more I do but lyte</L>
<L>And whan this Chanon saw / it wolde nat be</L>
<L N="701">But his &yogh;eman / wolde telle / his pryuete</L>
<L>he fledde a-wey / for verrey sorwe &amp; shame</L>
<L>A quod the &yogh;eman / heere shal rise a game</L>
<L>Al that I can / a-noon I wol &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L N="705">Syn he is gon / the foule fend him quelle</L>
<L>ffor neuere heere-after / wyl I with him mete</L>
<L>ffor peny ne for pound / I &yogh;ow byhete</L>
<L>he &thorn;at me brought first / vn-to that game</L>
<L N="709">Er that he dye / sorwe haue he &amp; shame</L>
<L>ffor it is ernest to me / be my feith</L>
<L>[So shall he fynd forsoth &thorn;at it assayeth.<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="226a">]<NOTE PLACE="marg">"deficit versus" Dd.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;et for al my smert / &amp; al my grief</L>
<L N="713">ffor al my sorwe / labour / &amp; meschief</L>
<L>I coude neuer leue it / in no wyse</L>
<L>Nowe wolde god my wyt / myght suffise</L>
<L>To tellen al / &thorn;at longeth to that art</L>
<L N="717">And nathelees / &yogh;ow wil I tellen part</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at my lord is gon / I wyl nat spare</L>
<L>Swich thyng as that I knowe / I wil declare</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Heere endeth the prologe of the Chanons &YOGH;eman /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="548">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="552">
<HEAD>[THE PREAMBLE.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>and bygynneth his tale of Multiplicacion;</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With this Chanon / I dwelt haue seuene &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="721">And of his science / am I neuere the nere</L>
<L>Al that I had / I haue lost ther-by</L>
<L>And god wot / so han many moo than I</L>
<L>There I was wont / to be right fressh and gay</L>
<L N="725">Of clothynge / and of othere good array</L>
<L>Now may I were / an hose / vp-on myn hed</L>
<L>And where my colour was / bothe fressh &amp; red</L>
<L>Now is it wan / and of a leden hewe<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="729">Who so it vseth / sore shal he rewe</L>
<L>And of my swynk / &yogh;et blered is myn eye</L>
<L>lo which a vauntage is / to multiplie</L>
<L>That slydyng science / hath me mad so bare</L>
<L N="733">That I haue no good / where so euere I fare</L>
<L>And &yogh;et I am endetted so / ther-by</L>
<L>Of gold / that I haue borwed / trewely</L>
<L>That whil I lyue / I shal it quyte neuere</L>
<L N="737">lat euery man / be war by me / for euere</L>
<L>What maner man / &thorn;at casteth him ther-to</L>
<L>If he continue / I holde his thrift I-do</L>
<L>ffor so helpe me god / &thorn;er-by shal he nat wynne</L>
<L N="741">But empte his purs / &amp; make his wittes thynne</L>
<L>And whan he thurgh his madnesse / &amp; folye</L>
<L>hath loost his owne good / thurgh Iupartie</L>
<L>Thanne he exciteth / othere folk ther-to</L>
<L N="745">To lese here good / as he him self hath do</L>
<L>ffor vn-to shrewes / ioye it is and ese</L>
<L>To haue here felawes / in peyne &amp; dissese
<PB REF="00000571.tif" N="549"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="553"></L>
<L>Thus was I ones lerned / of a Clerk</L>
<L N="749">Of that / no charge / I wil speke of oure werk</L>
<L>&para; Whan we ben there / as we shuln excersise</L>
<L>Oure eluyssh craft / we semen wonder wyse</L>
<L>Oure termes ben so clergeal / and queynte</L>
<L N="753">I blowe the fyr / til that myn hert feynte</L>
<L>What shulde I telle / eche proporcion</L>
<L>Of thynges / which that we / werche vp-on</L>
<L>As on fyue / or sexe vnces / may wel be</L>
<L N="757">Of siluer / or sum other quantitee</L>
<L>And bisie me / to telle &yogh;ow the names</L>
<L>Of Orpement / brent bones / Iron squames</L>
<L>That in-to poudre / grounden be ful smal</L>
<L N="761">And in an erthene pot / how put is al</L>
<L>And salt I-put In / and also papere</L>
<L>Biforn these poudres / &thorn;at I speke of heere</L>
<L>And wel I-couered / with a laumpe of glas</L>
<L N="765">And meche other thyng / which &thorn;at &thorn;ere was</L>
<L>As of the pot / and glasses enlutynge</L>
<L>That of the eyr / myght passe out no thynge</L>
<L>And of the esy fyr / and smert also</L>
<L N="769">which &thorn;at was made / &amp; of the care and woo</L>
<L>That we hadde / in oure maters sublymyng</L>
<L>And in amalgamyng / and calcenyng<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of quyk siluer / I-cleped Mercurie crude</L>
<L N="773">ffor alle oure sleightes / we can nat conclude</L>
<L>Oure Orpement / and sublimed Mercurie</L>
<L>Oure grounden litarge eke / on the porfurie</L>
<L>And eche of theise / vnces a certeyne</L>
<L N="777">Nat helpeth vs / oure labour is in veyne</L>
<L>Ne eke oure spirites / ascencion</L>
<L>Ne oure maters / &thorn;at lyn al fix a-doun</L>
<L>Moun in oure werkynge / no thyng vs a-vaille</L>
<L N="781">ffor loost is al oure labour / &amp; trauaille</L>
<L>And al the cost / a twenty deuel weye</L>
<L>Is loost also / which we vp-on it leye
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="550"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="554"></L>
<L>There is also / ful many a-nother thyng</L>
<L N="785">That is vn-to oure craft / appertenyng</L>
<L>Though I be ordre / hem nat reherce can</L>
<L>By cause that I am / a lewed man</L>
<L>&YOGH;et wole I telle hem / as they come to mynde</L>
<L N="789">Though I ne can nat / sette hem in here kynde</L>
<L>As Bole Armonyak / verdegres / Boras</L>
<L>And sundry vesselles / mad of erthe &amp; glas</L>
<L>Oure Vrinales / and oure descensories</L>
<L N="793">Violes / croslet&yogh; / and sublimatories</L>
<L>Cucurbit&yogh; / and alambikes eke</L>
<L>And othere suche / dere I-now a-leke</L>
<L>Nat nedeth it / for to reherce hem alle</L>
<L N="797">Watres rubifyng / and Booles galle</L>
<L>Arsenyk / salarmonyak / and Brymston</L>
<L>And Erbes coude I telle eke / many oon</L>
<L>As Egremoyne / Valerian / and lymarie</L>
<L N="801">And othere swich / if &thorn;at me list tarie</L>
<L>Oure laumpes brenne / bothe nyght &amp; day</L>
<L>To brynge a-boute oure purpos / if we may</L>
<L>Oure fourneys eke of calcinacion</L>
<L N="805">And of watres / albificacion</L>
<L>Vnslekked lym / Chalk / and gleir of an ey</L>
<L>Poudres diuerse / asshes / donge / pisse / &amp; cley</L>
<L>Sered pottes / salpetir vitriole</L>
<L N="809">And diuerse fyres made / of wode &amp; cole</L>
<L>Sal tartre / Alkaly / and salt preparat</L>
<L>And combust matiers / and coagulat</L>
<L>Cley / mad with hors &amp; mannes her / &amp; oyle</L>
<L N="813">Of Tartre / Alumglas / Berm / wort / and Argule</L>
<L>Rysalger / and oure matiers embityng<MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And eke of oure matiers / encorporyng</L>
<L>And of oure siluer / citrynacion</L>
<L N="817">And of cementynge / and fermentacion</L>
<L>Oure Ingottes / testes / &amp; manye moo</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ow telle / as was me taught also
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="551"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="555"></L>
<L>The foure spirite&yogh; / &amp; the bodies seuene</L>
<L N="821">By ordre / as ofte I herd my lord nemene</L>
<L>The first spirit / quyk siluer called is</L>
<L>The secund Orpement / the thridde I-wys</L>
<L>Sal Armonyak / and the ferthe Bremston</L>
<L N="825">The bodyes seuene eke / lo hem heere a-noon</L>
<L>Sol / gold is / and Luna siluer we threpe</L>
<L>Mars Iren / Mercurie quyksiluer we clepe</L>
<L>Saturnus led / and Iuppiter is Tyn</L>
<L N="829">And venus Coper / by my fader kyn</L>
<L>This cursed craft / who so wil excersise</L>
<L>He shal no good haue / &thorn;at him may suffise</L>
<L>ffor al the good / he spendeth there-a-boute</L>
<L N="833">he lese shal / ther-of haue I no doute</L>
<L>who so &thorn;at listeth outren / his folie</L>
<L>lat him come forth / and lerne multiplie</L>
<L>And euery man / &thorn;at hath ought in his cofre</L>
<L N="837">lat him appiere / and wexe a Philosophre</L>
<L>Ascauns that craft / is so light to lere</L>
<L>Nay nay god wot / al be he Monke or frere</L>
<L>Preest or Chanon / or any other wyght</L>
<L N="841">Though he sitte at his book / bothe day &amp; nyght /</L>
<L>In lernynge / of this eluyssh / nyce lore</L>
<L>Al is in veyn / and perde mechel more</L>
<L>To lerne a lewed man / this subtilitee</L>
<L N="845">ffy / spek nat ther-of / for it wil nat be</L>
<L>And cone he letterure / or cone he noon</L>
<L>As in effect / he shal fynde it al oon</L>
<L>ffor bothe two / by my sauacion</L>
<L N="849">Concluden / in multiplicacion</L>
<L>I-like wel / whan they han al I-do</L>
<L>This is to seyn / they faillen bothe two</L>
<L>&YOGH;et forgat I / to make rehersail</L>
<L N="853">Of watres Corosif / and of lymail</L>
<L>And of bodies / mollificacion</L>
<L>And also / of here induracion<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>The rest of</I> <B>Dd. 4. 24</B> <I>is gone.</I>]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="552"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="556"></L>
<L>[Oyles ablucions / and metall fusible<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eg. 2726, <I>on leaf</I>228</NOTE></L>
<L N="857">To telle all/ wold passe ony byble</L>
<L>That ougher is / wherfore as for &thorn;e best</L>
<L>Of all thise names / now woll I me rest</L>
<L>ffor as I trowe / I haue yow told ynough</L>
<L N="861">To reise a feend / all loke he neuer so rough</L>
<L>A nay let be / the Philizophres stone</L>
<L>Elixer cleped / we sechen fast ecchone</L>
<L>ffor hade we hym / &thorn;an were we seker ynow</L>
<L N="865">But vn-to god of heuen I make a vow</L>
<L>ffor all our craft/ whan we haue all do</L>
<L>And all our sleight/ he woll nat com vs to</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hath ymade vs spenden mochell gode<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="228b"></L>
<L N="869">ffor sorow of which / all-most we wexen wode</L>
<L>But that gode hope / krepeth in our hert</L>
<L>Supposing euere / &thorn;ough we sore smert</L>
<L>To be releued / by hym afterwarde</L>
<L N="873">Soch supposyng / and hope is sharpe and harde</L>
<L>I warne you wele / it is to sechen euere</L>
<L>That futer tens / hath made men disceuere</L>
<L>In trust there-of / from all that euer &thorn;ey hadde</L>
<L N="877">Yitte of &thorn;at art/ &thorn;ey can nat wexen sadde</L>
<L>ffor vn-to hem / it is / a bitter sweete</L>
<L>So semeth it / for ne hade &thorn;ey but a shete</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;ey myght / wrape hem in at nyght</L>
<L N="881">And a brat / to walk in / by day-light</L>
<L>They wold hem sell / and spenden on &thorn;is craft</L>
<L>They con nat stynt/ tyll no thyng be laft</L>
<L>And euermore / where &thorn;at euere they goon</L>
<L N="885">Men mow hem knowe / by smell of brymstoon</L>
<L>ffor all the world / &thorn;ey stynken as &thorn;e goot</L>
<L>Her sauour is so / rammyssh and so hoot</L>
<L>That though a man / a myle from hem be</L>
<L N="889">The savour woll enfecte hem / trusteth me</L>
<L>As thus by smell / and thredebare array</L>
<L>Yf that men lust / this folk they knowen may
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="553"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="557"></L>
<L>And yf a man / woll aske hem priuely</L>
<L N="893">Why they ben clothed so vnthriftely</L>
<L>They right anoon woll rownen in his ere</L>
<L>And seyn / yf &thorn;ey espied were</L>
<L>Men wold hem slee / by-cause of her science</L>
<L N="897">lo thus this folk/ betrayen Innocence</L>
<L>Passe ouere this / I go my tale vn-too</L>
<L>On that our pot/ be on the fire ydoo</L>
<L>Of metals / with a certeyn quantitee</L>
<L N="901">My lorde hem tempreth / and no man but he</L>
<L>Now he is goon I dare sey boldely</L>
<L>ffor as men seyn / he can do craftely</L>
<L>Algate I wote wele / he hath soch a name</L>
<L N="905">and yitte full oft he renneth in a blame</L>
<L>And wote ye how / full oft it happeth so</L>
<L>The pot to-breketh / and fare-wele all is goo /</L>
<L>Thise metals ben / of so grete violence<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="229a"></L>
<L N="909">Our walles mow nat make hem resistence</L>
<L>But yf they weren wrought of lyme and stoon</L>
<L>They percen so / and thurgh the wall &thorn;ey goon</L>
<L>And som of hem / synk in-to the ground</L>
<L N="913">Thus han we lost / by tymes / many a pound</L>
<L>And som arn skatered / all the flore about/</L>
<L>Som lepe in-to the roof / withouten dout/</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at the fende / nat in our sight hym shewe</L>
<L N="917">I trowe he with vs be / that ylk shrewe</L>
<L>In hell / where he lorde is and syre</L>
<L>Nys ther more woo / ne more rancour / ne Ire</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at our pot / is broke / as I haue seid</L>
<L N="921">Euery man chitte / and halt hym evill appayed</L>
<L>Som seyn / it was long on the fire makyng</L>
<L>Som seiden nay / it was on the blowyng</L>
<L>Than was I ferde / for that was myn office</L>
<L N="925">Strawe koth the thirde / ye be leude and nyce</L>
<L>It was nat tempred / as it was wont to be</L>
<L>Nay koth the feerth stynt/ and herken me
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="554"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="558"></L>
<L>By cause / our fire was nat made of beche</L>
<L N="929">That is the cause / and none other syth eche</L>
<L>I can nat tell / where-on it was long</L>
<L>But wele I wote grete stryf / is vs among</L>
<L>What koth my lord / there nys no more to doon</L>
<L N="933">Of thise perels / I woll be ware eft-soon</L>
<L>I am right seker / &thorn;at &thorn;e pot war crased</L>
<L>Be as be may / be ye no thing amased</L>
<L>As vsage is / let swepe &thorn;e flore as swythe</L>
<L N="937">Pluk vp your hertes / and beth glad and blythe</L>
<L>The mullok/ on an hepe / ysweped was</L>
<L>And on the flore yeast/ a Canvas</L>
<L>And all this mullok/ in a seue I-throwe</L>
<L N="941">And syfted and ypiked / many a throwe</L>
<L>Parde koth one / somwhat of our metall</L>
<L>Yitte is ther here / &thorn;ough &thorn;at we han nat all</L>
<L>and though this thyng / myshapped haue as now</L>
<L N="945">Another tyme / it may be wele ynow</L>
<L>Vs most put our gode / in auenture</L>
<L>A Merchaunt parde / may nat ay endure /</L>
<L>Trusteth wele me / in his prosperitee<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="229b"></L>
<L N="949">Som tyme his gode / is drowned in the see</L>
<L>And som tyme / comth it sauf vn-to the lond</L>
<L>Pees koth my lord / &thorn;e next tyme I woll fond</L>
<L>To bryng our Craft/ all in another plite</L>
<L N="953">And but I doo / let me han the wyte</L>
<L>There was defaute / in somwhat/ wele I wote</L>
<L>Another seid / the fire was to hote</L>
<L>But be it hote or cold / I dare sey this</L>
<L N="957">That we concluden euermore amys</L>
<L>We faill of that / which &thorn;at we wold haue</L>
<L>And in our madnes / euermore we raue</L>
<L>And whan we ben / togiders euerychoon</L>
<L N="961">Euery man semeth / a Salamon</L>
<L>But euery thyng which &thorn;at shyneth as &thorn;e goold</L>
<L>Nys nat goold / as I haue herd toold
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="555"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="559"></L>
<L>Ne euery appull / &thorn;at is faire at yie</L>
<L N="965">Ne is nat gode / what so we clap or crye</L>
<L>Ryght so lo / fareth it amonges vs</L>
<L>He &thorn;at semeth the wisest/ by Ihesus</L>
<L>Is most fool / whan it comth to &thorn;e preef</L>
<L N="969">And he &thorn;at semeth truest/ is a theef/</L>
<L>That shull ye knowe / or &thorn;at I from you wende</L>
<L>Be that I of my tale / haue made an ende<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="556">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="560">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[There was a Chanon of religion</L>
<L N="973">Amonges vs / wold infect all a toun</L>
<L>Though it as grete were / as was Nynyvee</L>
<L>Rome Alisaundre Troye / and other thre</L>
<L>His sleightes / and his infinyte falsnesse</L>
<L N="977">There coude no man writen / as I gesse</L>
<L>Though that he lyve myght a thousand yere</L>
<L>In all this world of falshede / nas his pere</L>
<L>ffor in his termes / he so woll hym wynde</L>
<L N="981">And speke his wordes / in so slye a kynde</L>
<L>Whan he common shall / with ony wyght</L>
<L>That he woll make doten / anoon ryght</L>
<L>But it a feend be / as hym-seluen is</L>
<L N="985">ffull many a man / hath he begiled or this</L>
<L>And woll / yf &thorn;at he lyve may a while</L>
<L>And yitte men ride and goon / full many a myle /</L>
<L>Hym for to seke / and haue his aqweyntaunce<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="230a"></L>
<L N="989">Nat knowyng of his fals gouernaunce</L>
<L>And yf ye lyst / to yeve me audience</L>
<L>I woll it tell here / in your presence</L>
<L>But worshipfull Chanons religious</L>
<L N="993">Ne demeth nat / &thorn;at I sklaundre your hous</L>
<L>all-though that my tale / of a chanon be</L>
<L>Of euery ordre som shrewe is pardee</L>
<L>And god forbede / &thorn;at all a companye</L>
<L N="997">Shold folow a singler mannes folye</L>
<L>To sclaundre you / is no thing myn intent/</L>
<L>But to correcten / &thorn;at is mys yment
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="557"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="561"></L>
<L>This tale / was nat onely / told for yow</L>
<L N="1001">But eke for other moo / yee wote wele how</L>
<L>That among cristes Apostles .xij.</L>
<L>There was no traytour / but Iudas hym selue</L>
<L>Than why shold / &thorn;e remenaunt han a blame</L>
<L N="1005">That giltles were / by you sey I &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Saue onely this / yf ye woll herken me</L>
<L>Yf ony Iudas / in your Couent be</L>
<L>Remeveth hym be tymes I yow rede</L>
<L N="1009">Yf shame or loos / may causen ony drede</L>
<L>And be no thyng/ dysplesed I you prey</L>
<L>But in this caas / herkeneth wat I shall sey</L>
<L>In london was a preest / annielere</L>
<L N="1013">That there-in dwelled had / many a yere</L>
<L>Which was so plesaunt/ and so seruysable</L>
<L>vn-to the wyf where / as he was at &thorn;e table</L>
<L>That she wold suffre hym / no thing for to pay</L>
<L N="1017">ffor borde ne clothyng went he neuer so gay</L>
<L>And spendyng siluer / hade he right ynow</L>
<L>There-of no force / I woll procede as now</L>
<L>And tell forth my tale of the Chanon</L>
<L N="1021">That brought this preest/ to confusion</L>
<L>This fals Chanon / cam vp-on a day</L>
<L>vn-to the prestes Chambre where he lay</L>
<L>Bysechyng hym / to lene hym a certein</L>
<L N="1025">Of gold / and he wold qwyte it hym ayein</L>
<L>leene me a mark / but dayes thre</L>
<L>And at my day / I woll it qwyten thee /</L>
<L>And yf so be / &thorn;ou fynde me fals<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="230b"></L>
<L N="1029">Another day / hang me by the hals</L>
<L>The preest hym toke / a mark/ and that as swythe</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Chanon hym thanked often sythe</L>
<L>And toke his leve / and went forth his weye</L>
<L N="1033">And at &thorn;e iij.<SUP>de</SUP> day / brought his moneye</L>
<L>And to this preest/ he toke this gold agein</L>
<L>Where-of this preest/ was wonder glad and feyn
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="558"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="562"></L>
<L>Certes koth he / no thing noyeth me</L>
<L N="1037">To lene a man a noble / or .ij. or .iij.</L>
<L>Or what thyng/ were in my possession</L>
<L>Whan he so trewe is / of condicion</L>
<L>That in no wise / he breke woll his day</L>
<L N="1041">To soch a man / I can neuere sey nay</L>
<L>What koth this Chanon shold I be vntrewe</L>
<L>Nay that were thyng/ yfall/ all of newe</L>
<L>Treuth is a thyng/ that I woll euere kepe /</L>
<L N="1045">In-to that day / in which &thorn;at I shall krepe</L>
<L>In-to my grave / and elles god forbede</L>
<L>Byleueth this / as seker as your crede</L>
<L>God thank I. and in gode tyme be it seid</L>
<L N="1049">That there was neuer man yitte euyll appayed</L>
<L>ffor gold ne siluer / &thorn;at he to me lent</L>
<L>Ne neuere falshede / in myn hert I-ment</L>
<L>And sir koth he / now of my pryvytee</L>
<L N="1053">Sen ye so godely / han ben vn-to me</L>
<L>And kythed to me / so grete gentillesse/</L>
<L>Som-what / to quyte with your kyndenesse</L>
<L>I woll yow shewe / yf &thorn;at yow list lere</L>
<L N="1057">I woll yow teche pleynly the manere</L>
<L>How I can werken / in philisophie</L>
<L>Taketh gode hede / ye shull wele seen at yie</L>
<L>That I woll don a maistrie or I goo</L>
<L N="1061">ya koth &thorn;e prest / yee sir and woll ye soo</L>
<L>Marie there-of I pray yow hertly</L>
<L>at your commaundement sir truely</L>
<L>koth &thorn;e Chanon / and elles god forbede</L>
<L N="1065">Lo how &thorn;is &thorn;eef cowde his seruice bede</L>
<L>ffull soth it is / &thorn;at soch profred seruice</L>
<L>Stynketh / as witnessen &thorn;ise old wise</L>
<L>And that full sone / I woll it vercifie<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="231a"></L>
<L N="1069">In this Chanon / rote of all trecherie</L>
<L>That euermore delite hath / and gladnesse</L>
<L>Soch fendly thoughtes / in his hert empresse
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="559"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="563"></L>
<L>How Cristes peple / he may to myschief bryng</L>
<L N="1073">God kepe vs from his fals dissimulyng</L>
<L>Nat wist this preest / with whom &thorn;at he delt</L>
<L>Ne of his harme commyng / he no thyng felt</L>
<L>O sely preest/ o sely Innocent/</L>
<L N="1077">With Couetise anoon / &thorn;ou shalt be blent/</L>
<L>O graceles / full blynd is thy conseyt/</L>
<L>No thyng / ne art &thorn;ou ware of the disceyt/</L>
<L>Which that this fox / yschapen hath to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1081">His wily wrenches / &thorn;ou ne maist nat flee</L>
<L>Wherfore to go / to the conclusion</L>
<L>That referreth to thy confusion</L>
<L>Vnhappy man / anone I woll me hye</L>
<L N="1085">To tell thyn vnwitte / and thy folye</L>
<L>and eke &thorn;e falsnesse of &thorn;at other wrecche</L>
<L>As ferforth / as that my connyng / woll strecche</L>
<L>This Chanon / was my lord ye wold wene</L>
<L N="1089">Sir hoost/ in feith / and by &thorn;e hevenes quene</L>
<L>It was another Chanon / and nat he</L>
<L>That can an hundred fold more subteltee</L>
<L>He &thorn;at hath betrayed folkes many tyme</L>
<L N="1093">Of his falsnesse it dulleth me to ryme</L>
<L>Ever whan that I speke of his falshede</L>
<L>ffor shame of hym my chekes / wexen rede</L>
<L>Algates they begynne for to glowe</L>
<L N="1097">ffor redness / haue I. noon / right wele I knowe</L>
<L>In my visage / for fumes diuerse</L>
<L>Of metals / which ye han herd me reherce</L>
<L>Consumed and wasted han my rednesse</L>
<L N="1101">Now take hede / of this Chanons cursednesse</L>
<L>Sir koth the Chanon / let your man goon</L>
<L>ffor qwyk-siluer / &thorn;at we it hade anoon</L>
<L>And let hym bryng ounces / ij. or .iij.</L>
<L N="1105">And whan he comth as fast shull ye see</L>
<L>A wonder thyng / which ye sawe neuere or this</L>
<L>Sir koth the preest/ it shall be don ywis
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="560"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="564"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He bade his seruaunt / fecch hym this thyng/<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="231b"></L>
<L N="1109">And he all redy was / at his biddyng/</L>
<L>And went hym forth / and cam anon ayein</L>
<L>With his qwyk-sylver shortly for to seyn</L>
<L>And toke thise ounces. thre / to the Chanon</L>
<L N="1113">And he hem leid faire and well adoun</L>
<L>And bade the seruaunt/ coles for to bryng/</L>
<L>That he anoon myght / go to his werkyng/</L>
<L>The coles right anoon weren yfette</L>
<L N="1117">And this Chanon toke out/ a Crosselette</L>
<L>Of his bosom / and shewed it to &thorn;e preest/</L>
<L>This Instrument / koth he which &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest</L>
<L>Take in thyn honde / and put thy self/ &thorn;ere-in</L>
<L N="1121">Of this qwyk-siluere an ounce / and there begyn</L>
<L>In &thorn;e name of Crist / to wex a Phili&yogh;ophre</L>
<L>There ben full fewe / which &thorn;at I wold profre</L>
<L>To shewe hym thus moch/ of my science</L>
<L N="1125">ffor ye shull se here / by experience</L>
<L>That this qwyk-syluer / I shall now mortefye /</L>
<L>Right in your sight anoon withouten lye</L>
<L>And make it as gode siluer / and as fyne</L>
<L N="1129">As &thorn;ere is ony / in your purs and myne</L>
<L>Or elles where / and make it mallable</L>
<L>And elles holdeth me fals / and vnable</L>
<L>Amonges folk / for euere to appiere</L>
<L N="1133">I haue a poudre here / &thorn;at cost me dere</L>
<L>Shall make all gode / for it is cause of all</L>
<L>My kunnyng / which I to you shewe shall</L>
<L>voyde your man / and let hym be there out/</L>
<L N="1137">and shette &thorn;e dore / whiles we ben about/</L>
<L>Our pryvitee / &thorn;at no man vs espie</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;at we werk/ in &thorn;is Philosophie</L>
<L>all as he bad fulfilled was in dede</L>
<L N="1141">This ylk seruaunt/ anon right/ out yede</L>
<L>And his maister shette &thorn;e dore anoon</L>
<L>And to her labour spedely they goon
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="561"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="565"></L>
<L>This preest/ at &thorn;is cursed chanons biddyng</L>
<L N="1145">vpon &thorn;e fire / anon set this thyng</L>
<L>And blewe &thorn;e fire / and besied hym full fast/</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Chanon / in-to the Crosselet cast/</L>
<L>A poudre / note I where-of / it was<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="232a"></L>
<L N="1149">Ymade / outher of chalk / outher of glas</L>
<L>Or som-what elles / was nat worth a flie</L>
<L>To blynd with the preest / and bad hym hie</L>
<L>The coles for to couchen all aboue</L>
<L N="1153">The Crosselet/ for in tokenyng &amp; the loue</L>
<L>koth this Chanon / &thorn;yn owen handes two</L>
<L>Shull werche all thyng/ &thorn;at shall here be do /</L>
<L>Graunt mercy koth the preest/ and was full glad</L>
<L N="1157">And couched cole / as &thorn;at &thorn;e chanon bad</L>
<L>And while he besy was / this sely wrecche</L>
<L>This fals Chanon / &thorn;e foule fende hym fecche</L>
<L>Out of his bosom / toke a bechen cole</L>
<L N="1161">In which full subtelly / was made an hole</L>
<L>And there-in put was/ of siluere lemaill</L>
<L>An ounce / and stopped was withouten faill</L>
<L>This hole with wexe to kepe &thorn;e lemaill in</L>
<L N="1165">And vnderstondeth / &thorn;at &thorn;is fals gyn</L>
<L>was nat made there / but it was made byfore</L>
<L>And other thynges / that I shall tell more</L>
<L>Here-afterward / which &thorn;at he/with hym brought</L>
<L N="1169">Or he cam there / hym to begile he thought/</L>
<L>And so he did or &thorn;at &thorn;ey were atwynne</L>
<L>Tyll &thorn;at he hade / terued hym / coude he nat blyn</L>
<L>It dulleth me / whan &thorn;at I of hym speke</L>
<L N="1173">Of his falshede / fayn wold I me wreke</L>
<L>Yf I wist how / but he is here and there</L>
<L>He is so variaunt/ he abytte nowhere</L>
<L>But taketh hede / now sirs / for goddes love</L>
<L N="1177">He toke his cole / of which I spake above</L>
<L>And in his hande / he bare it priuelye</L>
<L>And whiles &thorn;e preest / couched beselye
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="562"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="566"></L>
<L>The coles / as I told you / or this</L>
<L N="1181">This Chanon seid frend / ye don amys</L>
<L>This is nat couched / as it ought to be</L>
<L>But sone I shall amenden it/ koth he</L>
<L>Now let me medle there-with / but a while</L>
<L N="1185">ffor of yow haue I pitee / by seint Gyle</L>
<L>Ye ben right hote / I se wele how ye swete</L>
<L>Haue here a cloth / and wipe awey &thorn;e wete</L>
<L>And whiles that the preest/ wyped his face<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="232b"></L>
<L N="1189">This Chanon toke his cole / with sory grace</L>
<L>And leid it aboue / vp-on &thorn;e mydward</L>
<L>vp-on the Crosselet/ and blew wele afterward</L>
<L>Tyll that &thorn;e coles / gan fast brenne</L>
<L N="1193">Now yeve vs drynk/ koth &thorn;e Chanon thenne</L>
<L>As swythe / all shall be wele I vndertake</L>
<L>Sitte we doun / and let vs mery make</L>
<L>And whan that this Chanons / bechen cole</L>
<L N="1197">was brent/ all &thorn;e lemaill/ out of &thorn;e hole</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e Croselet / fell anoon adoun</L>
<L>And so it most nedes be / by resoun</L>
<L>Sen it so even aboue / it couched was</L>
<L N="1201">But there-of wist &thorn;e preest/ no-thyng allas /</L>
<L>He demed all coles eliche gode</L>
<L>ffor of &thorn;at sleight/ he no-thing vnderstode</L>
<L>And whan this / Alcamistre sawe his tyme</L>
<L N="1205">Rise vp koth he sir preest/ and sit by me</L>
<L>And for I wote wele Ingot/ haue we noon</L>
<L>Goth forth/ walketh / and bryng vs a chalk stoon</L>
<L>ffor I woll make / of &thorn;e same shappe</L>
<L N="1209">That is an yngot / yf I may haue happe</L>
<L>And bryngeth eke with you / a bolle or a pan</L>
<L>ffull of water / and ye shull see wele &thorn;an</L>
<L>How &thorn;at our besynesse / shall thryve or preeve</L>
<L N="1213">And yitte for ye shull haue no mysbyleve</L>
<L>Ne wrong conceyt of me in your absence</L>
<L>I ne woll nat bene out/ of your presence
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="563"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="567"></L>
<L>But go with you and com with yow ayein</L>
<L N="1217">The Chambre dore / shortly for to seyn</L>
<L>They opened and shette / and went her weye</L>
<L>And forth with hem &thorn;ey carieden &thorn;e keye /</L>
<L>And commen ayein without delay</L>
<L N="1221">What shold I tarien / all &thorn;e long day</L>
<L>He toke the chalk / and shope it in &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Of an Ingot/ as I shall yow devise</L>
<L>I sey he toke out of his owen sleve</L>
<L N="1225">A teyne of siluer euyll mot he cheve</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at ne was / but an vnce of weight/</L>
<L>And taketh hede now of his cursed sleight/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He shoope his Ingotte / in lenth / and in brede<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="233a"></L>
<L N="1229">Of this teyne / without ony drede</L>
<L>So sliely &thorn;at the preest/ it nat espied</L>
<L>And in his sleve ayein / he gan it hied</L>
<L>And from the fire / he toke vp his matere</L>
<L N="1233">And in &thorn;e Ingot put/ it with mery chere</L>
<L>And in the watery vessell / he it cast/</L>
<L>Whan that hym lyst/ and bade &thorn;e preest as fast/</L>
<L>What there is / put in thyn hande and groope</L>
<L N="1237">Thow fynd shalt there / silver as I hoope</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>He put his hand in / and toke vp a teyne</L>
<L N="1241">Of silver fyn / and glad / in euery veyne</L>
<L>Was this preest/ whan he sawe it was so</L>
<L>Goddes blessyng/ and his moders also</L>
<L>And all halowes / haue ye sir Chanon</L>
<L N="1245">Seid this preest/ and I her malison</L>
<L>But and ye vouchesauf / to techen me</L>
<L>This noble craft/ and this subteltee</L>
<L>I woll be your / in all &thorn;at euer I may</L>
<L N="1249">Koth the Chanon / yitte woll I make assay</L>
<L>The secund tyme / &thorn;at ye mow taken hede</L>
<L>And ben expert/ of this / and in your nede
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="564"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="568"></L>
<L>Another day assay / in myn absence</L>
<L N="1253">This disciplyne / and &thorn;is crafty science</L>
<L>let take another ounce / koth he tho</L>
<L>Of qwyk-siluere / with-out wordes mo</L>
<L>And do there-with / as ye haue don or this</L>
<L N="1257">with &thorn;at other / which &thorn;at now siluer is</L>
<L>This preest hym besieth in all &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>To don as &thorn;is Chanon / this cursed man</L>
<L>Commaunded hym / and fast blew the fire</L>
<L N="1261">ffor to com to theffect / of his desire</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Chanon / right in &thorn;e mene while</L>
<L>All redy was / this preest/ efte to begyle</L>
<L>And for a a countenaunce / in his hande he bare</L>
<L N="1265">An holowen styk / take kepe and beware</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ende of which / an once and no more</L>
<L>Of siluer lemaill / put was / as byfore</L>
<L>Was in his cole / and stopped with wex wele</L>
<L N="1269">ffor to kepe in his lemaill euery dele.</L>
<L>And while this preest/ was in his besynesse<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="233b"></L>
<L>This Chanon with his styk/ gan hym dresse /</L>
<L>To hym anon / and his poudre cast in /</L>
<L N="1273">As he dyd ere / &thorn;e devyll out of his skyn</L>
<L>Hym terne / I pray to god for his falshede</L>
<L>ffor he was fals / in euery thyng/ and dede</L>
<L>And with his styk/ aboue &thorn;e Crosselet/</L>
<L N="1277">That was ordeyned / with &thorn;at fals get/</L>
<L>He stered the coles / till relent gan</L>
<L>The wexe ayeinst the fire / as euery man</L>
<L>But it a fole be / wote wele &thorn;at it mot nede</L>
<L N="1281">And all &thorn;at in the styk/ was out yede</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Crosselette hastely fell/</L>
<L>Now gode sirs / what woll ye bet &thorn;an well</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;is preest/ was &thorn;us begiled ayein</L>
<L N="1285">Supposyng nat but trouth / &thorn;e soth to seyn</L>
<L>He was so glad / &thorn;at I can nat expresse</L>
<L>In no manere / his merth/ and his gladnesse
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="565"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="569"></L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Chanon / he profred eftsone</L>
<L N="1289">Body and gode / ya koth &thorn;e Chanon sone</L>
<L>Though I pore be / crafty &thorn;ou shalt me fynd</L>
<L>I warne the yitte / is there more behynd</L>
<L>Is there ony Coper / here-in seid he</L>
<L N="1293">Ye koth the preest/ I trowe well there be</L>
<L>Elles go by vs som / and &thorn;at as swythe</L>
<L>Now sir go &thorn;y wey / and hie the blythe</L>
<L>He went his way / and with the coper cam</L>
<L N="1297">And &thorn;is Chanon it / in his handes nam</L>
<L>And of that Coper weyed out but an ounce</L>
<L>all to symple is my tung/ to pronounce</L>
<L>As mynystre of my wit / &thorn;e doublenesse</L>
<L N="1301">Of this Chanon / rote of all cursednesse</L>
<L>He semed frendly to hem / &thorn;at knewe hym nought/</L>
<L>But he was fendly / both in hert and thought/</L>
<L>It werieth me / to tell of his falnesse</L>
<L N="1305">And natheles yitte woll I it expresse</L>
<L>To thentent/ that men mow be ware there-by</L>
<L>And for noon other cause truely</L>
<L>He put the ounce of Coper in &thorn;e Crosselet/</L>
<L N="1309">And on the fire / as swythe he hath it set/</L>
<L>And cast in poudre / and made the preest to blowe/<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="234a"></L>
<L>And in his werkyng/ for he stowped lowe</L>
<L>As he did ere / and all nas but a Iape</L>
<L N="1313">Right as hym list/ the preest/ he made his ape</L>
<L>And afterward in &thorn;e Ingotte / he it cast/</L>
<L>And in the pan / put it at the last/</L>
<L>With the water / and in he put his owen hand.</L>
<L N="1317">And in his sleue / as ye byforehand</L>
<L>Herd me tell / hade a siluer teyne</L>
<L>He slyely toke it out/ &thorn;is cursed hyne</L>
<L>vnwetyng this prest/ of his fals craft/</L>
<L N="1321">And in &thorn;e pannes botom / he hath it laft/</L>
<L>And in the water / rombled to and froo</L>
<L>And wondir priuely toke vp also
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="566"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="570"></L>
<L>The Coper Teyne / nat knowyng &thorn;is preest/</L>
<L N="1325">And hid it / and hym hent by the brest/</L>
<L>And to hym spake / and thus seid in his game</L>
<L>Stoupeth adoun / by god ye be to blame</L>
<L>Helpeth me now / as I did yow whilere</L>
<L N="1329">Put in your hande / and loke what is there</L>
<L>This preest/ toke vp &thorn;is siluer teyne anoon</L>
<L>And than seid the Chanon let vs goon</L>
<L>With thise iij. teynes / which &thorn;at we han wrought/</L>
<L N="1333">To som goldsmyth / and wete yf they ben ought/</L>
<L>ffor by my feith / I nold / for myn hode</L>
<L>But yf &thorn;at &thorn;ey were siluer fyn and gode</L>
<L>And &thorn;at as swythe / preued shall it be</L>
<L N="1337">Vn-to &thorn;e goldsmyth with thise teynes .iij.</L>
<L>They went/ and put thise teynes in assay</L>
<L>To fire and hamer / myght no man sey nay</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;ey weren / as hem ought to be</L>
<L N="1341">This sotted preest/ whoo was gladder &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Was neuer bird gladder / ayeinst the day</L>
<L>Ne nyghtyngale / in the seson of May</L>
<L>Was neuer noon / &thorn;at list bet to syng</L>
<L N="1345">Ne lady lustier / in karolyng</L>
<L>Or for to speke of loue / and wommanhede</L>
<L>Ne knyght in armes / don a doughty dede</L>
<L>To stonde in grace / of his lady dere</L>
<L N="1349">Than hade this preest/ &thorn;is sory craft to lere /</L>
<L>And to this Chanon / thus he spake and seid.<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="234b"></L>
<L>ffor the loue of god / that for vs all deid.</L>
<L>And as I may deserue it vn-to yow</L>
<L N="1353">What shall this resceit cost/ telleth now</L>
<L>By our lady koth this Chanon it is dere</L>
<L>I warn yow wele / for save I and a frere</L>
<L>In Engelond / there can no man it make</L>
<L N="1357">No force koth he / now sir for goddes sake</L>
<L>what shall I paye / telleth me I pray</L>
<L>I-wys koth he / it is full dere I say
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="567"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="571"></L>
<L>Sir at a worde / yf &thorn;at the list it haue</L>
<L N="1361">ye shull paye .xl. li. so god me save</L>
<L>And ner the frenshippe / &thorn;at ye did or this</L>
<L>To me ye shold paye more ywys</L>
<L>This prest / &thorn;e som of .xl. li. anoon</L>
<L N="1365">Of nobles fette / and toke hem euerychoon</L>
<L>To this Chanon / for this ylk resceyt/</L>
<L>All his werkyng/ nas but fraude and disceyt/</L>
<L>Sir preest he seid / I kepe haue no loos</L>
<L N="1369">Of my Craft/ for I wold/ it kept were cloos</L>
<L>And as ye loue me / kepeth it secree</L>
<L>ffor and men knewe / all my subteltee</L>
<L>By god &thorn;ey wold haue so grete envye</L>
<L N="1373">To me / by cause of my philosophie</L>
<L>I shold be dede / there were noon other weye</L>
<L>God it forbede koth &thorn;e preest / what ye seye</L>
<L>yitte hade I leuer spenden / all &thorn;e gode</L>
<L N="1377">Which &thorn;at I haue / and elles were I wode /</L>
<L>Than that ye shold fall / in soch myschief</L>
<L>ffor your gode will / sir haue ye right gode preef</L>
<L>koth the Chanon / and fare well graunt mercy</L>
<L N="1381">He went his wey / and neuere &thorn;e preest hym sye</L>
<L>After &thorn;at day / and whan &thorn;at &thorn;is preest shoold.</L>
<L>Maken assay at soch tyme / as he wold.</L>
<L>Of this resceit fare wele / it wold nat be</L>
<L N="1385">Lo thus beiaped and begiled was he</L>
<L>Thus maketh he / his Introduccion</L>
<L>To bryng folk/ to her destruccion</L>
<L>Considereth sirs / how &thorn;at in ecch astate</L>
<L N="1389">Bitwene men and gold there is debate/</L>
<L>So ferforth/ so that vnneth is there noon<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="235a"></L>
<L>This multeplying blynt so many oon</L>
<L>That in gode feyth / I trowe &thorn;at it be</L>
<L N="1393">The cause grettest/ of soch skarstee</L>
<L>As men reccorde / many mo than I.</L>
<L>Philisophres speken so mystely
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="568"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="572"></L>
<L>In this Craft/ &thorn;at men han now a dayes</L>
<L N="1397">They mow wele chittren / as &thorn;at doon Iayes</L>
<L>And in her termes sette her lust and peyne</L>
<L>But to her purpoos / shull &thorn;ey neuere atteyne</L>
<L>A man may lightly lerne / yf he haue ought/</L>
<L N="1401">To multiplye / and bryng his gode to nought/</L>
<L>Lo soch a lucre it is / in this lusty game</L>
<L>A mans merth / it woll turne vn-to grame</L>
<L>And empten also / grete and hevy purses</L>
<L N="1405">And maken folk / for to purchacen curses</L>
<L>Of hem that han her gode / &thorn;ere-to ylent/</L>
<L>ffy for shame / &thorn;ey &thorn;at han be brent</L>
<L>Allas can &thorn;ey nat flee / &thorn;e fires hete</L>
<L N="1409">Ye &thorn;at it vse / I rede ye it lete</L>
<L>lest ye lese all/ for bet &thorn;an neuere / is late</L>
<L>Neuer to thryve / were to long a date</L>
<L>Though ye proll ay / ye shull it neuere fynde</L>
<L N="1413">Ye ben as bold as is bayard the blynde</L>
<L>That blundreth forth / and perell casteth noon</L>
<L>He is as bold to renne ayeinst a stoon</L>
<L>As for to go beside / in the hie weye</L>
<L N="1417">So faren ye that multiplie I seye</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;at your yien kon nat seen aright/</L>
<L>loke &thorn;at your mynd / lak nat his sight/</L>
<L>ffor though ye loke neuere so brode and stare</L>
<L N="1421">Ye shull no thyng wyn / on &thorn;at chaffare</L>
<L>But wasten all &thorn;at ye mow rappe and renne</L>
<L>withdrawe the fyre / lest it to fast brenne</L>
<L>Medleth no more with &thorn;at arte I mene</L>
<L N="1425">ffor yf ye do / your thryft is goon full clene</L>
<L>And right as swythe / I woll yow tellen here</L>
<L>What that the Philisophres seyn in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Lo thus seith Arnold of the newe toun</L>
<L N="1429">As his Rosarie / maketh mension</L>
<L>He seyth right thus without ony lye<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="235b"></L>
<L>There may no man Mercurie mortefye
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="569"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="573"></L>
<L>But it be with his brothers knowleccheyng/</L>
<L N="1433">How &thorn;at he / which that first seid this thyng/</L>
<L>Of philisophres / fader was Hermes</L>
<L>He seith how that the Dragon doutles</L>
<L>Ne dyeth nat/ but yf that he be slayn</L>
<L N="1437">with his brother / and &thorn;at is for to seyn</L>
<L>By the dragon Mercurie / and noon other</L>
<L>He vnderstode / and brymstone by his brother</L>
<L>That out of Sol and luna / were ydrawe</L>
<L N="1441">And therfore seid he / take hede to my sawe</L>
<L>Let no man besy hym / &thorn;is arte for to seche</L>
<L>But yf that / &thorn;e entencion and speche/</L>
<L>Of Philisophres / vnderstonde can</L>
<L N="1445">And yf he do / he is / a lewde man</L>
<L>ffor this science / and this cunnyng koth he</L>
<L>Is of the secree / of secretes pardee</L>
<L>Also &thorn;ere was a disciple of Plato</L>
<L N="1449">That on a tyme / seid his maister to</L>
<L>As his boke senior woll bere witnesse</L>
<L>And this was his demaund/ in sothfastnesse</L>
<L>Tell me &thorn;e name of &thorn;e priue stoon</L>
<L N="1453">And Plato answerd vn-to hym anoon</L>
<L>Take a stone / that Tytanus men name</L>
<L>Which is that koth he / magnasia is &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Seid plato / ya sir / and is it thus</L>
<L N="1457">This is ignotum per ignocius</L>
<L>What is magnasia / gode sir I you prey</L>
<L>Is it a water / &thorn;at is made I sey</L>
<L>Of elymentes .iiij. koth plato</L>
<L N="1461">Tell me &thorn;e rote gode sir koth he &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of that water / yf it be your will /</L>
<L>Nay nay koth Plato / certeyn &thorn;at I nyll</L>
<L>The philisophres sworn were euerychoon</L>
<L N="1465">That &thorn;ey shold discouere it in-to noon</L>
<L>Ne in no boke it write in no manere</L>
<L>ffor vn-to crist/ it is so leef and dere
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="570"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="574"></L>
<L>That he woll nat/ &thorn;at it discouered be</L>
<L N="1469">But where it lyketh / to his deytee /</L>
<L>Men for to espire / and eke for to defende<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="236a"></L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at hym lyketh / lo this is the ende</L>
<L>Than conclude I thus / sen &thorn;at god of heven</L>
<L N="1473">Ne woll nat &thorn;at philisophres neven</L>
<L>How that a man / shall com vn-to this stone</L>
<L>I rede vs for &thorn;e best/ let it gone</L>
<L>ffor who so maketh god his aduersarie</L>
<L N="1477">As for to werk ony thyng in contrarie</L>
<L>Of his will/ neuer shall he thryue</L>
<L>Though he multeplye terme of his lyve</L>
<L>And there appoynt/ for ended is my tale</L>
<L N="1481">God send euery true man bote of his bale /</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit fabula seruientis Canonici</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="H" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="571">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="576">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>H.</B> FRAGMENT IX.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE MANCIPLE'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>et incipit prologus Mancipuly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf</I> 236</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wot ye nat where / &thorn;ere stant a litle toun</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at cleped is / bob vp and doun</L>
<L>Vnder the blee / in Caunterbury weye</L>
<L N="4">There gan our hoost / for to iape and pleye</L>
<L>And seid sires what don is in the myre</L>
<L>There is no man for prayer ne for hyre</L>
<L>That woll awake / our felawes arn behynde</L>
<L N="8">A theef myght full lightly robbe and bynde</L>
<L>Se how he nappeth / see for goddes bones</L>
<L>That he woll fall from his hors at ones</L>
<L>Is &thorn;at a coke of london / with meschaunce</L>
<L N="12">Do hym com forth/ he knoweth his penaunce</L>
<L>ffor he shall tell a tale by my fay</L>
<L>all-&thorn;ough it be nat worth a botell hay</L>
<L>Awake &thorn;ou koke sit vp / god yeue &thorn;e sorow</L>
<L N="16">What ayleth the to slepe by &thorn;e morow</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou had fleen all nyght or art &thorn;ou dronk/</L>
<L>Or haast &thorn;ou with som quene / all nyght yswonk/</L>
<L>So that &thorn;ou maist nat / hold vp &thorn;yn hede</L>
<L N="20">This Cook &thorn;at was pale and no &thorn;ing rede</L>
<L>Seid to our hoost/ as god my soule blesse</L>
<L>As there is fall on me / soch heuynesse</L>
<L>Note I nat why / but me were leuer slepe<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="236b"></L>
<L N="24">Than the best galon wyn / &thorn;at is in chepe
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="572"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="577"></L>
<L>Well koth &thorn;e maunciple / yf I may do ese</L>
<L>To the Sir Cook/ and no wight displese</L>
<L>Which that here rideth / in this company</L>
<L N="28">And our hoost wold of his curtesy</L>
<L>I wold as now excuse &thorn;e of &thorn;y tale</L>
<L>ffor in gode feith/ &thorn;y visage is full pale</L>
<L>Thyn yien dasen eke / as me thynketh</L>
<L N="32">And wele I wote / thy breeth full foule stynketh</L>
<L>That sheweth wele / &thorn;ou art nat wele disposed</L>
<L>Of me certeyn &thorn;ou shalt nat/ be glosed.</L>
<L>See how he yaneth / see &thorn;is drunken wight/</L>
<L N="36">As though he wold swalow vs anoon ryght/</L>
<L>Hold cloos &thorn;y mouth/ for thy fader kyn</L>
<L>The deuell of hell / set his fote there-in</L>
<L>Thy cursed breth / effecte woll vs all/</L>
<L N="40">ffy stynkyng Swyn / foule mot &thorn;e fall/</L>
<L>A taketh hede sirs / of this lusty man</L>
<L>Now swete sir / woll ye iust at &thorn;e fan</L>
<L>There-to me thynketh/ ye ben right wele yshape</L>
<L N="44">I trowe ye drunk haan / wyn of ape</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is whan men pleye with a strawe</L>
<L>And with his speche / &thorn;e Cooke wax angrye and wrawe</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e maunciple gan to nodde fast/</L>
<L N="48">ffor lak of speche / and doun &thorn;e hors hym cast/</L>
<L>where as he lay / tyll &thorn;at hym men vptoke</L>
<L>This was a faire Chyuache of a Cooke</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at he hade nat/ hold hym by his ladle</L>
<L N="52">And or &thorn;at he ayein were / in his sadle</L>
<L>There was grete shovyng to and froo</L>
<L>To lyft hym vp / and moch care and woo</L>
<L>So vnweldy / was &thorn;is sory palled goost/</L>
<L N="56">And to &thorn;e Maunciple / &thorn;an spake our hoost/</L>
<L>By cause that drynk hath dominacion</L>
<L>vp-on this man / by my savacion</L>
<L>I trowe he leudly / tell woll his tale</L>
<L N="60">ffor were it wyn / or strong musty ale
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="573"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="578"></L>
<L>That he drank/ he speketh in his nose</L>
<L>He snuffeth fast/ and eke he hath the pose</L>
<L>He hath also to do more than ynough<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="237a"></L>
<L N="64">To kepe hym / in his sadle out of &thorn;e slough</L>
<L>And yf he fall from his caple eft sone</L>
<L>Than shull we all han ynough to done</L>
<L>In lyftyng vp / his hevy drunken cors /</L>
<L N="68">Tell on thy tale / of hym make I no fors</L>
<L>But yitte Maunciple / in feith &thorn;ou art to nyce</L>
<L>Thus openly / to repreve hym / of his vyce</L>
<L>Another day / he woll perauenture</L>
<L N="72">Reclayme the / and bryng &thorn;e to lure</L>
<L>I mene / he speke woll / of smale thynges/</L>
<L>And for to pynchen / at thy rekenynges</L>
<L>That were nat honest / yf it cam to preef</L>
<L N="76">koth &thorn;e Maunciple / &thorn;at were a grete myschief</L>
<L>So myght he lyghtly / bryng me in &thorn;e snare</L>
<L>Yitte hade me leuer / pay for &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>which &thorn;at he rytte on / &thorn;an he shold with me stryue</L>
<L N="80">I woll nat wratth hym / as mot I thryue</L>
<L>That / &thorn;at I spake / I seid it in my bourde</L>
<L>And wete ye what/ I have here in my gourde</L>
<L>A draught of wyn / it is / of a ripe grape</L>
<L N="84">And right anoon / ye shull se a gode iape</L>
<L>This Coke shall drynk/ &thorn;ere-of yf I may</L>
<L>vp peyne of deth / he woll nat sey me nay</L>
<L>And certenly to tell as it was</L>
<L N="88">Of this vessell / &thorn;e Cooke / drank fast allas</L>
<L>what nedeth it / he drank ynough byforn</L>
<L>And whan he hade pouped / in his horn</L>
<L>To the Maunciple / he toke &thorn;e gourde agayn</L>
<L N="92">And of that draught / &thorn;e Cook was wonder fayn</L>
<L>And thanked hym / in soch wise as he coude</L>
<L>Than gan our hoost / to laugh wonder loude</L>
<L>And seid I se wele / it is necessarie</L>
<L N="96">Where &thorn;at we goo / gode drynk with vs to carie
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="574"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="579"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at woll turne rancour and disese</L>
<L>To accorde and loue / and many a rancour pese</L>
<L>O &thorn;ou Bacus / blessed be thy name</L>
<L N="100">That so canst turne / ernest in-to game</L>
<L>Worshipe and thank be / vn-to thy deitee</L>
<L>Of that mater ye gete no more for me</L>
<L>Tell on thy tale Maunciplie I the prey<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="237b"></L>
<L N="104">Wele sir koth he / now herken what I sey</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit prologus Mancipij</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="575">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="580">
<HEAD>et Incipit fabula sua de la Crowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf</I>237, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHan Phebus was dwellyng in erth adoun</L>
<L>As old bokes maken mensyoun</L>
<L>He was &thorn;e most/ lusty bachelere</L>
<L N="108">In all this world / and eke &thorn;e best Archiere</L>
<L>He slough anoon &thorn;e serpent Phiton as he lay</L>
<L>Slepyng ayeinst &thorn;e son / vp-on a mery day</L>
<L>And many another noble / worthy dede</L>
<L N="112">He with his bowe wrought / as men mow rede</L>
<L>Pleyen he coude / on euery mynstralsye</L>
<L>And syngen &thorn;at it was a melodye</L>
<L>To heren of his clere voice the soun</L>
<L N="116">Certes the kyng of Thebes Amphyoun</L>
<L>That with his syngyng walled &thorn;at Citee</L>
<L>Coude neuere syngen half so wele as hee</L>
<L>There-to he was / the semeliest man</L>
<L N="120">Thas is or was / sen &thorn;at &thorn;e world began</L>
<L>What nedeth it / his fetures to discryve</L>
<L>ffor in this world / was noon so faire on lyve</L>
<L>He was there-with fulfilled of gentillesse</L>
<L N="124">Of honour / and of perfite worthynesse</L>
<L>This Phebus / that was flour of bachelrye</L>
<L>As wele in fredom / as in Chiualrye</L>
<L>ffor his desport/ in signe of victorie</L>
<L N="128">O Phiton / so as telleth vs &thorn;e storie</L>
<L>Was wont to bere in his hande a bowe</L>
<L>Now hade &thorn;at Phebus in his hous a crowe</L>
<L>Which in a cage / he fustred many a day</L>
<L N="132">And taught it speke / as &thorn;at men teche a Iay
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="576"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="581"></L>
<L>White was this Crowe / as is a snowe-white swan</L>
<L>And countrefete &thorn;e speche of euery man</L>
<L>He coude / whan he shold tell a tale</L>
<L N="136">There-with in all &thorn;is werld / no nyghtyngale</L>
<L>Ne cowde by an hundred thousand dele<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="238a"></L>
<L>Syngen so wonder merely and wele</L>
<L>Now had this Phebus / in his hous a wyf/</L>
<L N="140">Which that he loved more than his lyf/</L>
<L>And nyght and day / dyd ever his diligence</L>
<L>Hir for to plese / and doon hir reuerence</L>
<L>Save onely / yf the soth / that I shall seyn</L>
<L N="144">Ielous he was / and wold haue kept hir feyn</L>
<L>ffor hym were loth byiaped / for to be</L>
<L>And so is euery wight / in soch degree</L>
<L>But all for nought / for it availeth nought/</L>
<L N="148">A gode wyf / &thorn;at is clene / of werk and thought/</L>
<L>Shold nat be kept / in noon awaite certein</L>
<L>And truely / the labour is in veyn</L>
<L>To kepe a shrewe for it woll nat be.</L>
<L N="152">This hold I. for a verray nycetee</L>
<L>To spille labour / for to kepe wyves</L>
<L>Thus writen old clerkes in her lyves</L>
<L>But now to purpos / as I first began</L>
<L N="156">This worthy Phebus / doth all &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>To plese hir / wenyng &thorn;at soch plesaunce</L>
<L>And for his manhode / and his gouernaunce</L>
<L>That no man shold / haue put hym from his grace</L>
<L N="160">But god it wote / there may no man embrace</L>
<L>As to destreyne / a thyng/ which &thorn;at nature</L>
<L>Hath naturelly / sette in a creature</L>
<L>Take ony bird / and put it in a kage</L>
<L N="164">And do all thyn intent / and &thorn;y corage</L>
<L>To fustre it tenderly / with mete and drynk/</L>
<L>Of all deyntees / &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst bethynk/</L>
<L>And kepe it as clenly / as &thorn;ou may</L>
<L N="168">All-though his cage of gold be neuere so gay
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="577"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="582"></L>
<L>Yitte hade this bird by .xx. thousand fold</L>
<L>leuer in a fforest/ &thorn;at is rude and cold</L>
<L>Goo ete wormes / and soch wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="172">ffor euere &thorn;is bird woll don his besynesse</L>
<L>To escape out of his cage yf &thorn;at he may</L>
<L>His libertee / this bird desireth ay</L>
<L>Let take a Cat / and fostre hym well with mylk/</L>
<L N="176">And tendre flessh / and make his couche of sylk/</L>
<L>And let hym seen a mous / go by the wall /<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="238b"></L>
<L>Anoon he weyueth mylk/ and flessh and all</L>
<L>And euery deyntee / that is in that hous</L>
<L N="180">Soch apetyte hath he / to ete the mous</L>
<L>lo here hath lust/ his dominacion</L>
<L>And appetite / flemeth discrecion</L>
<L>A she wolf hath also / a velens kynd</L>
<L N="184">The lewdest wolf/ &thorn;at she may fynd</L>
<L>Or leest of reputacion / &thorn;at woll she take</L>
<L>In tyme whan &thorn;at hir list to han a make</L>
<L>All thise ensaumples / speke I. by thise men</L>
<L N="188">That ben vntrewe / but no thyng by wommen</L>
<L>ffor men han euere / a likerous appetite</L>
<L>On lower thyng / to perfourme her delite</L>
<L>Than on her wyfes / ben &thorn;ey neuere so feire</L>
<L N="192">Ne neuere so true / ne so deboneire</L>
<L>fflessh is so newe fangell/ with meschaunce</L>
<L>That we ne con / in no thyng haue plesaunce</L>
<L>That sowneth in-to vertue ony while</L>
<L N="196">This Phebus / which &thorn;at &thorn;ough vp-on no gyle</L>
<L>Disceyued was / for all his iolytee</L>
<L>ffor vnder hym / another hade she</L>
<L>A man of litle reputacion</L>
<L N="200">Nat worth to Phebus in comparison</L>
<L>The more harme is / it happeth often so</L>
<L>Of which there comth / mochell harme and woo</L>
<L>And so byfell / whan Phebus was absent/</L>
<L N="204">His wyf anoon / hath for hir lemman sent/
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="578"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="583"></L>
<L>Hir lemman sertes / &thorn;is is a knavyssh speche</L>
<L>fforyeue it mee / and &thorn;at I you beseche</L>
<L>The wise Platoo / seith as ye mow rede</L>
<L N="208">The worde mot/ nede accorde with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Yf men shull proprely / tell a thyng/</L>
<L>The worde mot Cosyn be / to &thorn;e werkyng/</L>
<L>I am a boystous man / right thus sey .I.</L>
<L N="212">There nys / noon other difference / truly</L>
<L>Bitwene a wyf/ &thorn;at is of hye degree</L>
<L>Yf of hir body / dishonest she bee</L>
<L>And a pouere wenche other &thorn;an this/</L>
<L N="216">Yf so be &thorn;e werken both amys/</L>
<L>But that the gentile / in estate aboue<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="239a"></L>
<L>She shall be cleped his lady / as in love</L>
<L>And for that other is a poure womman</L>
<L N="220">She shall be cleped his wenche / or his lemman</L>
<L>And god it wote / myn owen dere brother</L>
<L>Men leyn &thorn;at one / as lowe / as lith &thorn;at other</L>
<L>Right so bitwene / a titeles tyraunt/</L>
<L N="224">And an outlawe / or a theef erraunt/</L>
<L>The same I sey / there is no difference</L>
<L>To Alisaundre / told was this sentence</L>
<L>That for the tyraunt/ is of gretter myght</L>
<L N="228">By force of meynee / for to slee doun ryght/</L>
<L>And bren hous and home / and make all pleyn</L>
<L>Lo therefore is he cleped a Capiteyn</L>
<L>And for the Outlawe hath / but small meynee</L>
<L N="232">And may nat do / so grete an harme as hee</L>
<L>Ne bryng a cuntree / to so grete myschief/</L>
<L>Men clepe hym an outlawe / or a theef/</L>
<L>But for I am a man / nat Textuele</L>
<L N="236">I woll nat tell of textes neuer a dele</L>
<L>I woll go to my tale / as I began</L>
<L>Whan phebus wyf / hade sent for hir lemman</L>
<L>And they wroughten / all her lust volage</L>
<L N="240">The white crowe / &thorn;at hyng ay in &thorn;e kage
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="579"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="584"></L>
<L>Byheld her werk/ and seid neuer a word</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at home was com / Phebus &thorn;e lord.</L>
<L>The crowe sang Cukkow Cukkow Cukkow</L>
<L N="244">What bird koth Phebus / what song syngest &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Ne were &thorn;ou wont so merely / to syng</L>
<L>That to my hert it was a reioysyng</L>
<L>To here &thorn;y voice / allas what song is this /</L>
<L N="248">By god koth he I syng nat amys</L>
<L>Phebus koth he / for all &thorn;y worthynesse</L>
<L>ffor all &thorn;y beautee / and &thorn;y gentillesse</L>
<L>ffor all &thorn;y song / and all &thorn;y mynstralcye</L>
<L N="252">ffor all &thorn;y waytyng / blered is thyn yie</L>
<L>With one of litle reputacion</L>
<L>Nat worth to the in comparison</L>
<L>The mountaunce of a gnatte so mot I thryve</L>
<L N="256">ffor on thy bedde / &thorn;y wyf I sawe hym swyve /</L>
<L>What woll ye more / &thorn;e crowe anoon hym told<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="239b"></L>
<L>By sadde tokenes / and by wordes bold</L>
<L>How &thorn;at his wyf / hade don hir leccherie</L>
<L N="260">Hym to grete shame / and to grete velanye</L>
<L>And told hym eft / he saw it with his yien</L>
<L>This Phebus / gan a-way-ward for to wrien</L>
<L>And thought his sorowfull hert brast a two</L>
<L N="264">His bowe he bent/ and sette there in a floo</L>
<L>And in his Ire / his wyf / &thorn;an hath he slayn</L>
<L>This is theffect / there is no more to sayn</L>
<L>ffor sorow of which / he brake his mynstralsye</L>
<L N="268">Both harpe and leute / gytern and sautrye</L>
<L>And eke he brake his arowes / and his bowe /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;us spake he to the Crowe</L>
<L>Traytour koth he / with tung of Scorpion</L>
<L N="272">Thow hast me brought / to my confusion</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at I was wrought / why nere I dede</L>
<L>O dere wyf / gemme / of lustihede</L>
<L>That were to me so sad / and eke so trewe</L>
<L N="276">Now lyst / &thorn;ou dede / with face pale of hewe
<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="580"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="585"></L>
<L>ffull giltles / &thorn;at durst I swere y-wis /</L>
<L>O racle hond to don so foule a mys</L>
<L>O trouble witte / o Ire reccheles</L>
<L N="280">That vnavised / smytest gyltles</L>
<L>O wan-trust / full of fals suspecion</L>
<L>Where was thy witte / and &thorn;y discrecon</L>
<L>O euery man be ware of rakelnesse</L>
<L N="284">Ne trowe no thing / without strong witnesse</L>
<L>Smyte nat so sone / or &thorn;at ye weten why</L>
<L>But beeth avised / well and soberly</L>
<L>Or ye don / ony execucion</L>
<L N="288">Vp-on your Ire / for suspecion</L>
<L>Allas a thousand folk han / for racle Ire</L>
<L>ffully fordone or brought hem in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Allas for sorow / I woll my self slee</L>
<L N="292">And to the Crowe / o fals theef seid he</L>
<L>I woll &thorn;e qwyte anoon / &thorn;y fals tale</L>
<L>Thow song whilom like a nyghtyngale</L>
<L>Now shalt &thorn;ou fals theef &thorn;y song forgone</L>
<L N="296">And eke thy white fethers euerychone /</L>
<L>Ne neuer in all thy lyf / ne shalt &thorn;ou speke /<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="240a"></L>
<L>Thus shull men / on a traytour ben a-wreke</L>
<L>Thow and &thorn;yn of-spryng / ever shull be blake</L>
<L N="300">Ne neuer swete noise / shull ye make</L>
<L>But euer crie ayeinst / tempest and reyn</L>
<L>In tokenyng / &thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e / my wyf is sleyn</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Crowe he stirt / and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="304">And pulled his white fethers of euerychoon</L>
<L>And made hym blak/ and reft hym all his song</L>
<L>And eke his speche / and out at the dore hym slong</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e devill / which I hym betake</L>
<L N="308">And for this caas / ben all crowes blake /</L>
<L>Lordynges by this ensaumple I you preye</L>
<L>Beth ware and taketh kepe / what &thorn;at ye seye</L>
<L>Ne telleth never no man / in all your lyf/</L>
<L N="312">How &thorn;at another man / hath dyght his wyf /
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="581"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="586"></L>
<L>He woll you hate / mortally certeyn</L>
<L>Daun Salamon / as wise clerkes seyn</L>
<L>Techeth a man / to kepe his tung well/</L>
<L N="316">But as I seid I am nat textewell /</L>
<L>But natheles / &thorn;us taught my dame</L>
<L>My son thynk/ on &thorn;e crowe/ a goddes name/</L>
<L>My son kepe wele thy tung/ and kepe thy frende</L>
<L N="320">A wykked tung/ is wers &thorn;an a feende</L>
<L>My son from a fend / men mow hem blesse</L>
<L>My son / god of his endlees godenesse</L>
<L>Walleth a tung with teeth / and lyppes eke</L>
<L N="324">ffor a man shold hym avise / what he speke</L>
<L>My son full oft/ for to moch speche</L>
<L>Hath many a man ben spylt/ as clerkes teche</L>
<L>But for litle speche / avisely</L>
<L N="328">Is no man shent/ to speke generally</L>
<L>My son &thorn;y tung/ sholdest &thorn;ou restreyne</L>
<L>at all tymes / but whan &thorn;ou dost &thorn;y peyne</L>
<L>To speke of god / in honour and prayere</L>
<L N="332">The first vertue son yf &thorn;ou wolt lere</L>
<L>Is to restreyne / and kepe wele &thorn;y tung</L>
<L>Thus lerne children / whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey be yong/</L>
<L>My sone of mochell spekyng evill avised</L>
<L N="336">There lesse spekyng hade / ynough suffised.</L>
<L>Comth moch harme / thus was me told and taught/<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="240b"></L>
<L>In mochell speche / synne ne wanteth nat/</L>
<L>Wost &thorn;ou nat/ where-of a racle tung serueth</L>
<L N="340">Right as a swerd for-kytteth / and kerueth/</L>
<L>An arme a two / my dere son right so</L>
<L>A tung kytteth / frendship all a two</L>
<L>A iangeler is to god abhomynable</L>
<L N="344">Rede Salamon / so wise and honourable</L>
<L>Rede Dauid in his psalmes / rede Senek</L>
<L>My son speke nat/ but with thyn hede &thorn;ou bek/</L>
<L>Dissimule as &thorn;ou were deef/ yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou here</L>
<L N="348">A iangeler speke / of parlious matere
<PB REF="00000604.tif" N="582"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="587"></L>
<L>The flemmyng seith/ and lerne it/ yf the lest/</L>
<L>That litle ianglyng causeth moch rest/</L>
<L>My son / yf &thorn;ou no wykked word hast seid</L>
<L N="352">The dare nat drede / for to be bewreid</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at hath mysseyde / I dare wele seyn</L>
<L>He may by no waye / clepe his worde ageyn</L>
<L>Thyng &thorn;at is seid / is seid / and forth it goth</L>
<L N="356">Though hym repent/ or be him leef or loth</L>
<L>He is his thrall / to whom &thorn;at he hath seid</L>
<L>A tale/ of which/ he is now evill appayed</L>
<L>My son be ware / and be noon auctor newe</L>
<L N="360">Of tidynges whether &thorn;ey be fals or trewe</L>
<L>Where-so &thorn;ou com / amonges hie or lowe</L>
<L N="362">Kepe well &thorn;y tung/ and thynk vpon &thorn;e crowe/.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit fabula Mancipij de la Crowe</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="I" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="583">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="589">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>I.</B> FRAGMENT X.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE BLANK-PARSON LINK.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[This is really a link between some unwritten Tale and the Parson's. It has been made into the Manciple-Parson Link (or Yeoman-Parson by the Christ-Church MS) by Chaucer's copiers, though not meant for it.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="prologue">
<HEAD>&amp; Incipit prologus Rectoris fabule<NOTE PLACE="marg">Egerton 2726, <I>on leaf</I>240, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By that &thorn;e Maunciple / hade his tale ended.</L>
<L>The son from &thorn;e South lyne/ was discended.</L>
<L>So lowe that he nas nat/ to my sight/</L>
<L N="4">Degrees .ix. / and .xx<SUP>ty</SUP> of hight/</L>
<L>x. of &thorn;e Clok / it was tho as I gesse</L>
<L>ffor .xj. fote / and litle more/ or lesse</L>
<L>My shadow was / at thilk tyme as there</L>
<L N="8">Of soch fete / as my length parted were</L>
<L>In .vj fete equall / of proporcion<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="241a"></L>
<L>There-with the mones exaltacion</L>
<L>I mene libra / all-wey gan ascende</L>
<L N="12">As we were entryng/ at a thorpes ende</L>
<L>ffor which our hoost/ as he was wont to gye</L>
<L>As in this caas / our ioly company</L>
<L>Seid in this wise / lordynges euerychone</L>
<L N="16">Now lakketh vs no tales moo &thorn;an one</L>
<L>ffulfilled is my sentence / and my decree</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;at we han herde in ecch degree</L>
<L>All-most fulfilled is / all myn ordenaunce</L>
<L N="20">I pray to god / so yeue hym right gode chaunce</L>
<L>That telleth/ this tale to vs lustely</L>
<L>Sir preest koth he / art &thorn;ou a vicary</L>
<L>Or art &thorn;ow parson / sey soth be thy fey</L>
<L N="24">Be what &thorn;ou be / ne breke &thorn;ou nat our pley
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="584"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="590"></L>
<L>ffor euery man saue &thorn;ou / hath told his tale</L>
<L>Vnbokle and shewe vs / what is in &thorn;y male</L>
<L>ffor truely me thynketh / by &thorn;y chere</L>
<L N="28">Thow sholdest knytte vp wele a grete matere</L>
<L>Tell vs a fable anon / for goddes bones</L>
<L>This parson answerd / all at ones</L>
<L>Thow getest/ fable noon ytold for me</L>
<L N="32">ffor Poule &thorn;at writeth vn-to Tymothe</L>
<L>Repreven hem / &thorn;at weyven sothfastnesse</L>
<L>And tellen fables / and soch wrecchednesse</L>
<L>Why shold I sowe draf/ out of my fyst/</L>
<L N="36">Whan I may sowe whete / yf &thorn;at me lyst/</L>
<L>ffor which I sey / &thorn;at yf &thorn;ou list to here</L>
<L>Moralitee/ and vertuous matere</L>
<L>And &thorn;an / that ye woll yeue me audience</L>
<L N="40">I woll fayn / at cristes reuerence</L>
<L>Do yow plesaunce leefull/ as I can</L>
<L>But trusteth wele / I am a sothern man</L>
<L>I can nat geest/ rom / ram / ruf by lettre</L>
<L N="44">Ne god wote / ryme hold I but litle better</L>
<L>And therfore yf &thorn;ou list/ I woll nat glose</L>
<L>I woll yow tell a mery tale in prose</L>
<L>To knytte vp all &thorn;is feest/ and make an ende</L>
<L N="48">And Ihesu for his grace / witte me sende/.</L>
<L>To shewe yow / &thorn;e weye in this viage<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="241b"></L>
<L>Of thylk perfyte glorious pilgrymage</L>
<L>That hight Ierusalem celestiall/</L>
<L N="52">And yf ye vouchesauf/ anoon I shall/</L>
<L>Begynne vp-on my tale / for which I prey</L>
<L>Tell your avice / I can no better sey</L>
<L>But natheles / this meditacion</L>
<L N="56">I put it ay / vnder correccion</L>
<L>Of clerkes / for I am nat textuell/</L>
<L>I take but &thorn;e sentence / trusteth well</L>
<L>Therefore I make / a protestacion</L>
<L N="60">That I woll stond / to correccion
<PB REF="00000607.tif" N="585"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="591"></L>
<L>Vp-on this worde / we han assented sone</L>
<L>ffor as vs semed / it was to done</L>
<L>To enden / in som vertuous sentence</L>
<L N="64">And for to yeve hym / space / and audience</L>
<L>And bad our hoost/ he shold to hym sey</L>
<L>That all we / to tell his tale hym prey</L>
<L>Our hoost/ hade &thorn;e wordes / for vs all</L>
<L N="68">Sir prest koth he / now faire yow byfall</L>
<L>Sey what yow list/ and we woll gladly here</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at worde / he seid in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Telleth koth he your meditacon</L>
<L N="72">But hasteth yow / &thorn;e son / woll adoun</L>
<L>Beth fructuous / and &thorn;at in litle space</L>
<L N="74">And to do wele/ god send yow his grace</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Hic desinit prologus Rectoris/</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000608.tif" N="586">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="593">
<HEAD>et incipit fabula SuA.<NOTE PLACE="head">[There are no paragraph-breaks in the MS, but Tyrwhitt's are kept in the print for convenience sake.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>[75]</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="242a">Our swete lord of heven / that no man woll peryssh/ but woll &thorn;at &thorn;ey com all to the knowlecche of hym / and to the blisfull lyf that is perdurable / [76] Amonesteth vs / by the prophete Ieremye / and seith in this wise / [77] Stondeth vp-on the weyes / and seeth / and axeth of old pathes / that is to seye of old sentences / which is the gode weye / [78] and walketh in that weye / and ye shull fynde / refresshyng for your soules &amp;c / [79] Many ben the weyes espirituels / that leden folk / to our lord Ihesu Crist / and to &thorn;e reigne of glorie / [80] of which weyes / there is a full noble weye / and a couenable which may nat fayle / to man / ne to womman &thorn;at &thorn;urgh synne hath mysgone / from the right weye / of Ierusalem celestiall / [81] And this weye is cleped Penitence / of which man/ shold gladly herken / and enqweren / with all his hert/ [82] to weten what is Pen|itence / and whennes it is cleped Penitence / and in how many maners / ben &thorn;e accions of werkynges of Penitence [83] and how many spices there ben of penitence / and which thynges appertenen / and byhoven to Penitence/ and which thynges distourben Penitence /
<PB REF="00000609.tif" N="587"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="594"></P>
<P>[84] Seint Ambrose seith / that Penitence is / the pleynyng of a man / for the gylt/ that he hath done / and no more to do / ony thyng for which hym ought to pleyn / [85] And som doctour seith / Penitence is the wayment|yng of a man / &thorn;at soroweth for his synne / and pyneth hym self/ for he hath mysdoon / [86] Penitence / with certein circumstaunces / is verray repentaunce of a man / that halt hym / self in sorow / and other peyne for his gyltes / [87] and for he shall be verray penitent/ he shall first bewail the synnes that he hath doo / and stedfastly purposen / in his hert/ to haue shryft/ of mouth / and to don satisfaccion / [88] and neuer to do thyng for which hym ought more bewayle / or to compleyn / and to con|tynue in gode werkes / or elles his repentaunce may nat / availl/ [89] ffor as seyth Seint Isidre / he is a Iaper and a gabber/ and no verray repentant/ &thorn;at eft sone doth thyng/ for which hym ought repent/ [90] wepyng/ and nat for to stynt to synne / may nat availl/ [91] But natheles / men shull hope / &thorn;at euery tyme / that man falleth/ be it neuer so oft / that he may arise / &thorn;urgh peni|tence / yf he haue grace / but certenly / it is grete doute / [92] for as seith Gregorie / vnneth ariseth he out of synne / &thorn;at is charged with the charge of evill vsage / [93] and therfore repentyng folk/ &thorn;at stynt for to synne / and forlete synne / or synne forlete hem / holy chirche halt hem seker of her savacon / [94] And he &thorn;at synneth / and verrely repenteth hym / in his last day/ holy chirche / yitte hopeth his savacon / by &thorn;e grete mercy of our lord Ihesu Crist/ for his repentaunce / but take the seker weye/</P>
<P>[95] and now seth / I haue declared yow / what thyng is penitence / now shull ye vnderstonde / &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben .iij. accions of Penitence / [96] The first is / that a man be baptised / after that he hath synned. [97] Seint<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="242b"> Austyn seith / but he be penitent / for his old synfull lyf/ he may nat begynne the newe 
<PB REF="00000610.tif" N="588"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="595"> clene lyf/ [98] ffor certes yf he be baptised with-outen penitence of his old gylt/ he resceyueth the mark/ of baptisme / but nat &thorn;e grace / ne the remyssions of his synnes / till he haue verray repentaunce / [99] Another defaute is this / &thorn;at men doon dedely synne / after that they han resceyued baptisme / [100] The .iij<SUP>de</SUP> defaute is this/ that men fallen/ in venyall synnes/ after her baptisme from day to day / [101] There-of seith Austyn / &thorn;at Penitence of gode and humble folk/ is the penitence of euery day /</P>
<P>[102] The spices of Penitence ben .iij. / that one of hem is solempne / another commune / and the thirde is pryvee / [103] thylk penaunce &thorn;at is so|lempne / is in ij. maners / as to be put out/ of holy chirche / for slaughter of children / and soch / maner thyng/ [104] Another thyng is / whan man hath synned openly / of which synne / &thorn;e fame is openly spoken / in &thorn;e cuntree and than holy chirche by Iuge|ment distreyneth hym / for to don open penaunce / [105] Commune penaunce is &thorn;at prestes enIoynen men / in certein caas as for to go perauenture / naked in pilgrymages / or bare-fote / [106] Pryvee penaunce is thylk/ that men doon / all day for pryve synnes / of which we shryue vs priuelye and resceyve pryvee penaunce /</P>
<P>[107] Now shalt &thorn;ou vnderstond what is behovely / and necessarie to verray perfite penitence / and &thorn;is stant on .iij. thynges / [108] Contricion of hert/ Con|fession of mouth / and Satisfaccion / [109] ffor which seith Seint Iohn Crisostomus / Penitence distreyneth man / to accepte / benignely euery peyne / &thorn;at hym is enIoyned / with contricion of hert/ and shryft of mouth/ with satis|faccion / and in werkyng of all maner humylitee/ [110] and this is fruytfull penitence/ Ayeinst/ .iij. thynges/ in which we wrath our lord Ihesu Crist / [111] &thorn;is is to sey / by delite in thynkyng/ by rechelesnesse in spekyng/ by wykked synfull werkyng/ [112] And ayeinst thise 
<PB REF="00000611.tif" N="589"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="596"> wykkyd gyltes/is Penitence &thorn;at may be lykkened vn-to a tree/</P>
<P>[113] &thorn;e rote of this tree / is contricion / &thorn;at hideth hym in the hert // of hym / &thorn;at is verray repentaunt/ right as &thorn;e rote of a tree / hydeth hym in the erthe. [114] Of the rote of Contricion / spryngeth a stake / that bereth braunches and leves of Confession / and fruyt of Satisfaccion / [115] ffor which Crist seith in his gospell/ doth digne fruyt/ of Penitence/for by this fruytmow men vnderstonde/and knowe this tree / and nat by the rote &thorn;at is hydde in &thorn;e hert / of man/ ne by &thorn;e braunches / ne the leves / of confession / [116] and &thorn;erfore our lord Ihesu Crist seith thus / by the fruyt of hem ye shull knowe hem [117] Of this rote eke spryngeth / a seede of grace the which is moder of sekirnesse / and in this sede / is egre and hote [118] &thorn;e grace of this sede / spryngeth of god / &thorn;urgh re|membraunce on &thorn;e day of dome / and on &thorn;e peynes of hell / [119] Of this mater seyth / Salamon that in the drede of god / man forlete[t]h his synne [120] The hete of &thorn;is seede / is &thorn;e love of god / and &thorn;e desiryng/ of &thorn;e Ioye perdurable [121] <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="243a">This hete draweth the hert of a man to god / and doth hym hate his synne / [122] for sothely / there is no thing/ &thorn;at savoureth so wele to a child / as the mylk of his Norice/ne no thing is to hym more abhom|ynable / than thilk mylk / whan it is medled with other mete/ [123] Ryght so &thorn;e synfull man &thorn;at loueth his synne / hym semeth &thorn;at it is most swete to hym / of ony thyng/ [124] but from &thorn;at tyme / &thorn;at he loueth sadly / our lord Ihesu Crist/ and desireth the lyf perdurable / there nys to hym / no thyng more abhomynable / [125] ffor / sothly the lawe of god / is the love of god / ffor which Dauid &thorn;e prophete seith I haue loved thy lawe / and hated wykkednesse /and hate /he &thorn;at loveth god/kepeth his lawe/ and his/ worde/[126] This tree sawe &thorn;e prophete Danyell in sperit/ vp-on the avision/ of Nabogodonosor/ whan he coun|ceilled / hym to do penitence / [127] Penaunce is the tree of lyf to hem &thorn;at it resceyven/ and he &thorn;at holdeth hym / 
<PB REF="00000612.tif" N="590"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="597"> in verrey Penitence / is blissed after the sentence / of Salamon</P>
<P>[128] In this Penitence and contricion / man shall vn|derstonde / .iiij. thynges &thorn;at is to sey / what is contricion / and which ben &thorn;e causes / &thorn;at meven a man to con|tricion / and how he shall be contrite / and what con|tricion availeth to the soule / [129] Than is it thus / &thorn;at contricion / is &thorn;e verray sorow / &thorn;at a man resceyueth in his hert / for his synnes / with sad purpoos / to shryve hym and to do penaunce / and neuer more to do synne / [130] and &thorn;is sorow shall ben in this maner / as seith Seint Bernard / it shall be hevy and grevous and full sharpe and poynant/ in hert/ [131] ffirst for man hath agylt his lord and his creatour / And more sharpe and poynant/ for he hath agilt his fader celestiall / [132] And yitte more sharpe and poynant/ for he hath wratthed and agilt/ ayeinst hym / that bought hym / &thorn;at with his precious blode hath deliuered vs / from &thorn;e bondes of synne / and from &thorn;e crueltee of the devill/ and from &thorn;e peynes of hell/</P>
<P>[133] The causes that oughten meve a man to con|tricion / ben .vj. ffirst a man shall remembre hym/ of his synnes / [134] but loke he / that thylk remem|braunce / ne be to hym no delite / by no weye / but grete shame and sorow / for his gylt / ffor Iob seith / synfull / men doon werkes / worthy of confusion / [135] and therfore seith Ezechie I woll remembre me all the yeres of my lyf / in bitternesse / of myn hert / [136] And our lord seith / in the Appocalypes / Remembre yow from whens / &thorn;at ye ben falle / for byfore that tyme / that ye synned / ye weren the children of god / . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [137] but for your synne / ye ben wexen thrall and foull / and menbres of the feend / hate of aungels / sclaundre of holy chirche/ and fode of &thorn;e fals serpent/ perpetuell mater of the fire of hell/ [138] And yitte more foule and abhom|ynable for ye trespasen so oft tyme/ as doth &thorn;e hound / &thorn;at retourneth to ete his spewyng/ [139] and yitte 
<PB REF="00000613.tif" N="591"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="598"> be ye fouler ffor your long contynuyng in syn and your synfull vsage / for which ye ben roten in your synne / as a beste in his dung/ [140] Soch maner of thoughtes / maketh man have shame of his <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="243b">Syn/ and no delite / As god seith / by the prophete Ezechiel [141] ye shull remembre yow / of your weyes / and they shull displese yow / Sothely synnes / ben the weyes / that leden folk to hell/</P>
<P>[142] The secunde cause / that ought make a man to haue disdeyne of synne / is this / That as seyth Seint Petir / who-so &thorn;at doth synne / is thrall of synne / and synne putteth a man / in grete thraldom [143] And ther|fore seith the prophete Ezechiel / I went sorowfull in dysdeyn of my self / and certes wele ought a man haue disdeyn of synne / and withdrawe hym from that thraldom / and velanye / [144] And loo what seith Senek / in this mater / he seith thus / &thorn;ough I wost/ &thorn;at neyther god ne man / ne shold neuer knowe it / yitte wold I have disdeyn for to do synne / [145] And &thorn;e same Seneca seith / Also &thorn;at I am born to gretter thyng than to bee thrall to my body / or than/ for to maken of my body a thrall/ [146] Ne a fouler thrall / may no man/ ne womman/ maken of his body / &thorn;an for to yeve his body to synne / [147] all were it &thorn;e foulest/ cherle / or the foulest womman / that lyueth and leest of value / yitte is he &thorn;an more foule / and more in seruitute / [148] euere from &thorn;e hier degree / &thorn;at man falleth / the more is he thrall/ and more to god vile / and to &thorn;e world abhom|ynable / [149] O god wele ought man haue disdeyn / of synne seth &thorn;at &thorn;urgh synne / &thorn;ere as he was free / now is he maked bonde / [150] And therfore seith seint Austeyn / yf &thorn;ow have disdeyn of thy seruaunt yf he agylt/ or synne/ have &thorn;ou &thorn;an disdeyn/ &thorn;at &thorn;ou sholdest do synne [151] take reward of thy value / &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne be / to foule to thy self / [152] Allas wele oughten they than haue disdeyn / to be 
<PB REF="00000614.tif" N="592"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="599"> seruauntes and thralles to synne / and sore ben a-shamed of hem self/ [153] &thorn;at god of his endles godenes / hath sette hem in hie astate / or yeve hem witte / strength of body / heale / beaute / prosperitee / [154] and bought hem from &thorn;e deth / with his hert blode / that they so vnkyndely ayenst his gentillesse / quyten hym so veleynsly / to the slaughter of her owen soules / [155] O gode god ye wommen &thorn;at ben of so grete beautee / remembreth yow / of the proverbe of Salamon he saith [156] lykkeneth a faire womman &thorn;at is foule of hir body / lyke to a ryng of gold / &thorn;at were in the groyne / of a sowe [157] right so / as a sow wroteth in euery ordur so wroteth she hir beautee / in styngyng synne /</P>
<P>[158] The thirde cause / that ought meue a man / to contricion / is drede of the daye of Dome / and of the horrible peynes of hell / [159] for as seith Seint Ierom / At euery tyme / that we remembreth / of the day of dome I qwake / [160] for whan I ete or drynk/ or what so &thorn;at I do / euer semeth me / &thorn;at &thorn;e trumpe sowneth in myn ere / [161] Rise ye vp that ben dede and comth to the iugement/ [162] O gode god mochell ought a man / to drede soch a Iugement/ there as we shull ben all / As Seint Poule seith byfore the sete of our lord Ihesu Crist / [163] where as he shall make a generall/ <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="244a">Con|gregacion / where as no man may be / absent / [164] for certes / ther ne availeth noon essoyen / ne excusacon / [165] and nat onely / that our defautes / shull be iuged / but eke that all our werkes / shull openly ben knowe / [166] And as seith Seint Bernard / there ne shall no pledyng availl/ ne sleight/ we shull yeve rekenyng/ of euery ydell worde / [167] there shull we han a iuge / that may nat be disceyved / ne corrupt/ and therfore certes all our thoughtes be discouered as to hym / ne for prayer ne for mede / he shall nat be corrupt/ [168] And therfore seith Salamon / the wrath of god / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000615.tif" N="593"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="600"> ne woll nat spare no wight/ for prayer ne for yifte / and therfore / at the day of dome / there nys noon hope to escape/ [169] wherfore as seith / seint Anselme / full grete angwyssh shull the synfull folk have / at that tyme / [170] there shall &thorn;e stierne and wroth Iuge / sitte above / and vnder hym / the horrible pitte of hell open to de|stroye hym / &thorn;at mot be-knowe his synnes / which synnes openly ben shewed byfore god / and byfore euery creature / [171] and in &thorn;e left side / mo devels &thorn;an hert may bethynk/ for to harye and drawe / &thorn;e synfull soules / to the peyne of hell/ [172] and with|in &thorn;e hertes of folk/ shall be &thorn;e bityng conscience and without forth/ shall/ be the world all brennyng/ [173] whider shall the wrecched synfull man flee than / to hide hym / certes he may nat hide hym / he most com forth / and shewe hym / [174] ffor certes as seith Seint Ierom The erthe shall cast hym out of hym / and the see also / And the heyre also / &thorn;at shall be full of thunder clappes / and lightenynges [175] Now soth-ly / who-so woll remembre of thise thynges / I gesse &thorn;at his synne shall turne hym / in no delite / but to grete sorow / fer drede of &thorn;e peyne of hell / [176] And ther|fore seith Iob / to god / suffre lord / that I may a while bewaile and wepe / or that I go / without retournyng to &thorn;e derk lond / couered with the derknesse of deth / [177] to &thorn;e lond of mysease / and of derknesse / where as is the shadow of deth / where as there is noon ordre ne ordenaunce / but grisly drede / &thorn;at euere shall last / [178] Lo here mow ye see / &thorn;at Iob prayed respite a while / to bewepe and waile his trespas ffor sothly a day of / respite / is better &thorn;an all the tresour of &thorn;is world. [179] and for-asmoch / as a man may acquyte hym self/ byfore god / by penitence / in this world and nat by tresour / therfore shold he pray to god / to yeve hym respite a while to bywepe and wayle his trespaces [180] ffor certes the sorow that a man myght/ make from the begynnyng 
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="594"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="601"> of the world / nys nat but a litle thyng/ at regarde / of the sorow / of hell [181] the cause why / that Iob clepeth hell / the lond of derknesse / [182] vnderstondeth &thorn;at he clepeth it lond or erthe / for it is stable / and neuer shall/ faill/ derknesse / for he that is in hell / hath defaute of light materiall / [183] ffor certes the derk light/ that shall / com out of the fire / that euer shall brenne / shall turne hym all to peyn / that is in hell/ for it showeth <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="244b">Hym to the horrible devels &thorn;at hym turmenten [184] couered with &thorn;e derknesse of deth / that is to sey / that he / that is in hell/ shall have defaute of the sight of god / for certes the sight of god / is the lyf perdurable [185] the derk nesse of deth / ben the synnes / that the wrecched man hath don / which &thorn;at distourben hym / to se the face of god / Right as a derk cloude / bitwene vs and &thorn;e son / [186] lond of mysease / by cause that there ben .iij. maners of defautes ayeinst .iij. thynges / that folk of this world han / in this present lyf/ that is to sey / honoures / delices / and ricchesses / [187] Ayeinst honour haue they in hell/ shame and confusion / [188] for wele ye wote / that men clepen honour / the reuerence &thorn;at man doth to man / but in hell is noon Honour ne reuerence / ffor certes no more reuerence / shall be don there to a kyng &thorn;an to a knaue / [189] ffor which god seith / by &thorn;e prophete Ieremye / &thorn;e folk &thorn;at men despisen / shull ben in despyte / [190] Honour is eke cleped grete lord|shipe There shall no wight serue other / but of harme and turnement/ Honour is eke cleped grete dignitee and hy|nesse / but in hell they shull ben all fortroden of deuels / [191] as god seith the horrible deuels / shull goon and com vpon the hedes of dampned folk/ and this is / for-asmoch/ as the hyer that they were / in this present lyf/ the more shull &thorn;ey ben abated and defouled in hell / [192] Ayeinst the richesse of this world / shull they haue mysease of pouertee / and this pouertee shall be in .iiij. thynges / [193] In defaute of tresour / of which that 
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="595"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="602"> Dauid seith / the Riche folk/ that embraceden and oneden all her hert/ to tresour of this world / shullen slepe / in the slepyng of deth / and no thyng shull they fynden in her hondes / of all her tresour / [194] And more-ouere the mysease of hell/ shall be in defaute of mete and drynk/ [195] ffor thus seith our lord by Moises / &thorn;ey shull ben wasted with hunger / and the birdes of hell / shull devoure hem with bitter deth / and the gall of the dragon / shall ben her drynk / and &thorn;e venym of the dragon her morsels / [196] and ferther-ouere / her mysese / shall be in defaute of clothyng/ for they shull be naked in body / as of clothyng save &thorn;e fire / in which they brenne / and other fylthes / [197] and naked shull they ben of soule / and of all maner vertues which that is / &thorn;e clothyng of &thorn;e soule where ben &thorn;an the gaye Robes / and &thorn;e soft shetes / and &thorn;e smale shertes / [198] lo what seith god of heven / by &thorn;e prophete Ysaie &thorn;at vnder hem shull ben strawed mothes and her couertours / shull ben of wormes of hell/ [199] and ferther-ouer her mysease / shall be in defaute of frendes / for he is nat pore &thorn;at hath gode frendes / but &thorn;ere is no frende [200] ffor neyther god / ne no creature / shall ben frende to hem / And euerycch of hem / shall hate other with dedely hate / [201] The sonnes and &thorn;e doughtren shull rebellen / ayeinst fader and moder / and kynrede ayeinst kynrede and chiden and despisen / euerycch of hem other / both day and nyght/ <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="245a">As god seith by the prophete Michias / [202] And the lovyng children / &thorn;at whilom loued so flesshly euerycch other / wolden euerycch of hem eten other / yf they myght/ [203] for how shold &thorn;ey loven hem to-geder / in &thorn;e peyne of hell/ whan &thorn;ey haten euerycch other / in &thorn;e prosperitee of this lyf / [204] ffor trust wele / her flesshly loue / was dedely hate / as seith the prophete Dauid / who-so loveth wykked|nesse / hateth his soule / [205] and whoso hateth his owen soule / certes he may love noon other wyght/ 
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="596"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="603"> in no maner / [206] And therfore / in hell / is no solace ne no frendshipe / but euer the more / the flesshly kynredes / &thorn;at ben in hell/ the more cursynges &thorn;e more chid|ynges / and the more dedely hate &thorn;ere is / among hem / [207] and ferther ouer / &thorn;ey shull haue defaute of all maner delices / ffor certes delices / ben after the appetites / of the .v. wittes / as sight / heryng Smellyng/ Savour|yng/ and touchyng/ [208] but in hell / her sight shall be full of derknesse / and of smoke / and her yien full of teres / and her heeryng full of waymentyng/ and gnastyng of teeth / As seith Ihesu Crist/ [209] her nose|thirles shull ben full of styngyng stenche / And as seith Ysaie &thorn;e prophete her savouryng / shall be full of bitter gall/ [210] and touchyng/ of all her body ycouered with fire / &thorn;at neuer shall qwenche / and with wormes &thorn;at neuer shall dyen / as god seith / by the mouth of Ysaie / [211] and for asmoch/ as &thorn;ey shull nat wene / &thorn;at &thorn;ey mow dyen for peyne / and by her deth flee from peyne / &thorn;at mow &thorn;ey vnderstonde / in &thorn;e worde of Iob / &thorn;at seith / there is &thorn;e shadow of deth / [212] Certes a shadow / hath &thorn;e lyknes of the thyng/ of which it is shadowed . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [213] right so fareth the peyne of hell / it is lyke deth / for the horrible Angwyssh / and why / for it peyneth hem ever as though men shuld dyen anoon / but certes they shull nat dye / [214] ffor as seith seint Gregorie / to wrecched kaytyfs / shall be deth without deth / and ende without ende / and defaute without faylyng/ [215] ffor her deth shall all-weye lyven / and her ende shall euermore begynne / and her defaute / shall nat fayle / [216] And therfore seith Seint Iohn the Euaungelist &thorn;ey shull folow deth / and &thorn;ey shull nat fynde hym / and they shull desire to deye / and deth shall flee from hem [217] / And eke Iob seith / that in hell is noon ordre / of rewle/ [218] and all-be-it so / &thorn;at god hath create all thynges in right ordre / and no thyng with|out 
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="597"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="604"> ordre but all thinges ben ordeyned and nom|bred / yitte natheles &thorn;ey that ben dampned / ben no thing in ordre / ne holden noon ordre / [219] ffor &thorn;e erthe ne shall bere hem / no fruyt / [220] ffor as &thorn;e prophete Dauid seith / god shall destroye the fruyt of the erthe / as from hem / ne water ne shall yeve hem no moistre / ne the eyre no refresshyng/ ne fire no light/ [221] ffor as seith seint Basilie / the brennyng/ of the fire of this werld shall god yeve in-to hell to hem &thorn;at ben dampned / [222] but &thorn;e light/ and &thorn;e clerenesse shall be yoven in|to heven / to his children / Right as the gode man yeveth <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="245b">fflessh to his children / and bones to his houndes / [223] And for &thorn;ey shull haue none hope to escape / seith Seint Iob / atte last / &thorn;at &thorn;ere horrour / and grisly drede dwell without ende / [224] horrour is all-wey drede of harme &thorn;at is to com / and &thorn;is drede shall euer dwell in the hertes of hem / &thorn;at ben dampned and therfore han &thorn;ey lorn / . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> for .vij. causes [225] ffirst for god / &thorn;at is her iuge shall be without mercy to hem / and &thorn;ey mow nat plese hym / ne noon of his halowes / ne &thorn;ey ne mow yeve no thyng for her raunsom / [226] ne &thorn;ey haue no voice to speke to hym / ne &thorn;ey may nat flee from peyne / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [227] And &thorn;erfore seith Salamon / &thorn;e wykked man deyeth / and whan he is dede / he shall have no hope to escape from peyne / [228] who-so than wold wele vn|derstonde / &thorn;e peynes / and bethynk hym wele / &thorn;at he hath deserued &thorn;ylk peynes / for hys synnes / certes he shold haue more talent/ to syghen and to wepe / &thorn;an for to syng and to pleye / [229] ffor as seith &thorn;e same Salamon who so &thorn;at hade &thorn;e science to knowe &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at ben stablysshed and ordeyned for synne / he wold make sorow [230] thilk science / as seith Seint Austyn make&thorn; a man to wayment/ in his hert/</P>
<P>[231] The ferth poynt &thorn;at ought make a man / 
<PB REF="00000620.tif" N="598"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="605"> haue contricion / is &thorn;e sorowfull remembraunce of the gode / &thorn;at he hath left to don here in erthe / and eke &thorn;e gode &thorn;at he hath lorne / [232] sothely &thorn;e gode werkes / &thorn;at he hath left / eyther &thorn;ey ben the gode werkes / &thorn;at he wrought/ or he fell in-to dedely synne or els &thorn;e gode werkes / &thorn;at he wrought/ while he laye in synne / [233] sothly &thorn;e gode werkes / &thorn;at he dyd byfore / &thorn;at he fell in synne / ben all mortefied and astoned and dulled / by the oft synnyng/ [234] That o&thorn;ere gode werkes / &thorn;at he wrought while he lay in synne / &thorn;ey ben vttrely dede / as to lyf perdurable in heuen / [235] Than thilk gode werkes &thorn;at ben mortefied / by oft synnyng/ which gode werkes he did whiles he was in charitee / ne mow neuer qwyk ayein / without verrey penitence [236] And &thorn;erfore seith god / by &thorn;e mouth of Ezechiell / &thorn;at yf &thorn;e rightfull man re|turne ayein / from his rightwosnesse / and werk wykked|nesse / shall he lyve [237] nay / for all &thorn;e gode werkes &thorn;at he hath wrought/ ne shull neuere ben in remembraunce / for he shall deye in his synne / [238] And vp-on &thorn;at chapitre seith Seint Gregorie thus / &thorn;at we shull vnder|stonde this principally [239] &thorn;at whan we doon<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>MS. repeats:</I> principally / &thorn;at whan we don]</NOTE> dedely synne / it is for nought / &thorn;an for to reherce / or drawe in-to memorie &thorn;e gode werkes &thorn;at we han wrought/ byfore/ [240] for certes in &thorn;e werkyng of &thorn;e dedely synne / &thorn;ere is no trust/ to no gode werk/ &thorn;at we haue doon byforne/ &thorn;at is to seye / as for to haue &thorn;er-by &thorn;e lyf per|durable / in heven / [241] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> whan we haue contricion / [242] but sothely &thorn;e gode werkes &thorn;at men doon while &thorn;ey ben in dedely synne / for as moch as &thorn;ey were doon in dedely synne &thorn;ey mow neuer qwyk <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="246a">Ayein / [243] for certes thyng &thorn;at neuere had lyf/ may neuer qwykken And natheles all be it so / &thorn;ey ne availlen nat/ to haue &thorn;e lyf perdurable yitte availlen 
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="599"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="606"> they to abregge / &thorn;e peyne of hell / or elles to gete temperall richesse [244] or elles &thorn;at god woll the rather enlumyne and light the hert / of the synfull man / to / haue repentaunce / [245] and eke &thorn;ey availen for to vse a man to do gode werkes / &thorn;at &thorn;e fende haue &thorn;e lesse power of his soule / [246] And thus the curteys lord Ihesu crist / ne woll &thorn;at no gode werk be lost/ for in som what/ it shall availl / [247] But for as|moch / as &thorn;e gode werkes &thorn;at men doon / while &thorn;ey ben in gode lyf ben all mortefied by synne folowyng/ And eke seith &thorn;at all &thorn;e gode werkes / &thorn;at men don while &thorn;ey ben in dedely synne / ben all vtterly dede / as for to haue the lyf perdurable / [248] wele may &thorn;at man/ &thorn;at no gode werk ne doth / syng &thorn;e newe fressh song/ Iay tout perdu mon temps / &amp; mon labour / [249] ffor certes synne byreveth a man both godenes of nature / and eke &thorn;e godenesse of grace / [250] for sothly the grace of &thorn;e holy goost fareth lyke fire / &thorn;at may nat be ydle ffor fire fayleth anoon as it forleteth his werk|yng/ and right so grace faileth anoon / as it forleteth his werkyng/ [251] than leseth &thorn;e synfull man &thorn;e godenes of glorie &thorn;at onely is behight to gode men / &thorn;at labouren and werken / [252] wele may he be sory than / &thorn;at oweth all his lyf to god / as long as he hath lyved and eke as long as he shall lyve / &thorn;at no godenes ne hath to paye with his dette/ to god / to whom he oweth all his lyf / [253] for trust wele he shall yeue accountes / as seith Seint Barnard of all &thorn;e godes &thorn;at han be yoven hym in &thorn;is present lyf/ and how he hath hem dispended [254] nat so moch &thorn;at &thorn;ere shall nat perissh and here/ of his hede ne a moment of an houre / ne shall nat peryssh/ of his tyme &thorn;at he ne shall yeue of it a rekenyng/</P>
<P>[255] The .v<SUP>te</SUP>. thyng &thorn;at ought meve a man to contricion is remembraunce of &thorn;e passion &thorn;at our lord Ihesu Crist suffred for our synnes / [256] ffor as seith seint Bernard while &thorn;at I lyve / I shall haue remem|braunce/ 
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="600"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="607"> of &thorn;e travailes &thorn;at our lord Ihesu Crist suffred in prechyng / [257] his werynesse in trauaillyng his tempt|aciouns whan he fasted / his long wakynges / whan he prayed / his teres whan he wept/ for pitee of / gode peple / [258] &thorn;e wo and the shame / And &thorn;e filth &thorn;at men seiden to hym / of &thorn;e foule spettyng/ &thorn;at men spette in his face / of the buffettes &thorn;at men yave hym / of the foule mowes and of the foule re|preves &thorn;at men to hym seyden / [259] of the nayles / with which he was nayled to the crosse / and of all &thorn;e remenaunt of his passion &thorn;at he suffred for oure synnes / and no thyng for his gylt/ [260] And ye shull vnder|stonde that in man is euery maner of ordre or ordenaunce turned<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="246b"> Vp-so-doun / [261] for it is soth / &thorn;at god and reson / and sensualitee / and &thorn;e body of a man / ben ordeyned / &thorn;at euerycch of thise .iiij. thynges shold haue lordshipe ouer &thorn;at other / [262] as thus god shold haue lordshipe ouere reson / and reson ouere sensualitee / and sensualitee ouer &thorn;e body of man / [263] But sothly whan man synneth/ all &thorn;is ordre or ordynaunce is turned vp-so-doun / [264] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;an for asmoch as reson of man ne woll nat be subiette ne obeisant to god / &thorn;at is his lord by right / &thorn;er|fore leseth it &thorn;e lordshipe &thorn;at it shold haue ouer sensualite / and eke ouer &thorn;e body of man / [265] and why for sensualite rebelleth ayeinst reson / and by &thorn;at weye leseth reson &thorn;e lordshipe ouer sensualitee / and ouere &thorn;e body / [266] for right as reson is rebell to god / right so is both sensualitee rebell to reson / and to &thorn;e body also / [267] And certes this dysordinaunce and this rebellion / Our lord Ihesu Crist abought vp-on his precious body full dere / And herkeneth in which wise / [268] ffor-asmoch / &thorn;an as reson is rebell to god &thorn;er|fore is man worthy to haue sorow and to be dede / [269] This suffred our lord Ihesu Crist for man / after &thorn;at he hade be betrayed of his disciple / and distreyned and 
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="601"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="608"> bound so that his blode brast out / at euery naill of his hondes / as seith Seint Austyn / [270] and ferther-ouer / for-asmoch as reson of man / ne woll nat daunte his sensu|alitee whan it may / therfore is man worthy to haue shame / And &thorn;is suffred our lord Ihesu Crist for man / whan &thorn;ey spette in his visage / [271] And ferther ouere for-as|moch &thorn;an / as &thorn;e kaytyf body of man / is rebell both to reson and to sensualitee / Therfore is it worthy the deth / [272] And &thorn;is suffred our lord Ihesu Crist/ for man vpon &thorn;e crosse / where as there was no parte of his body free / without grete peyne and bitter passion / [273] and all this suffred Ihesu Crist/ &thorn;at neuer forfayted . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> to mochell am I peyned for &thorn;e thynges that I neuer disserued / and to moch defouled for shenshippe &thorn;at man is worthy to haue / [274] And ther|fore may the synfull man wele sey / as seith Seint Bernard / accursed be the bitternesse of my synne / for which &thorn;ere most be suffred so moche bitternesse / [275] ffor certes after the diuers discordaunces / of our wikkednesses / was &thorn;e passion of Ihesu Crist ordeyned in diuers thynges [276] as thus / Certes synfull mannes soule is betrayed of the devill/ by Couetise of temperall prosperitee/ and scorn|ed by disceyte whan he cheseth flesshly delices / and yitte it is turmented by Inpacience / of aduersitee / and by espyte / by seruage / and subieccion of synne / and at &thorn;e last it is slayn fynally / [277] for this disordinaunce of synfull man was Ihesu Crist betrayed / and after &thorn;at was he bounde / &thorn;at cam for to vnbynde vs of synne / and of peyne / [278] than was he bescorned &thorn;at onely shold be honoured in all thynges / and of all thynges / [279] &thorn;an <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="247a">Was his Visage / &thorn;at ought to be desired to be seen / of all mankynde in which visage / Aungels desire to loke / veleynsly bespette / [280] &thorn;an was he scourged / &thorn;at no thing hade agylt/ and finally &thorn;an was he crucefied and slayn / [281] than was accompliced &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="602"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="609"> worde of Ysaye / he was wounded for our mysdedes / and defouled by our felonyes [282] Now seth &thorn;at Ihesu Crist toke vp-on hymself / &thorn;e peyne of all our wykkednesse / mochell ought synfull man wepe and bewaile / &thorn;at for his synnes / goddes son of heven / shold all this peyne endure / [283] The .vj.<SUP>te</SUP> thyng &thorn;at ought meve a man to contricion / is the hope of thre thynges / &thorn;at is to seye fforyevenesse of synne / and &thorn;e yifte of grace / wele for to do / and the glorie of heuen / with which god shall gwerdon man for his gode dedes [284] and for-asmoch / as Ihesu crist yeveth vs / thise yiftes / of his largenesse and for his soueraigne bountee / therfore is he cleped Ihesus Nazarenus rex Iudeorum [285] Ihesus is to sey Savyour or sav|acion / of whom men shull hope to haue foryevenesse / of synnes / which &thorn;at is proprely sauacion of synnes [286] And therfore seid &thorn;e Aungell to Ioseph/ thow shall klepe hyis name Ihesus / &thorn;at / shall saven his peple of her synnes / [287] And here-of seith Seint Petir &thorn;ere is noon other name vnder heven / &thorn;at is youen to ony man / by which a man may be saued but onely Ihesus / [288] Nazarenus is asmoch for to sey / as florisshyng / in which a man shall hope / &thorn;at he &thorn;at yeveth hym remyssion / of synnes / shall yeve hym eke grace well to doo for in &thorn;e flour is hope of fruyt/ in tyme commyng/ and in foryeuenesse of synne / hope of grace / well to do / [289] I was at &thorn;e dore of &thorn;yn hert/ seith Ihesus / and cleped for to entre / he &thorn;at openeth to me shall haue foryevenesse of synne / [290] I woll entre In-to him by my grace / and soupe with hym by the gode werkes / &thorn;at he shall do / which werkes ben &thorn;e fode of god / and he shall soupe with me / by &thorn;e grete ioye / &thorn;at I shall yeue hym / [291] &thorn;us shall man hope for his werkes of penaunce / &thorn;at god shall yeve hym his reigne as he byhoteth hym in his gospell/</P>
<P>[292] Now shall man vnderstonde / in which 
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="603"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="610"> maner shall be his contricion / I sey &thorn;at it shall be vnmesurable and totall / &thorn;is is to sey a man shall be verray repentaunt/ for all his synnes / &thorn;at he hath doon / in delite of his thought/ for delite is full parlious / [293] ffor there ben two maner of consentynges / &thorn;at one of hem is cleped consentyng of affeccion / whan a man is meved to do synne / and than delyteth hym longe for to thynk on &thorn;at synne / [294] and his reson apperceyueth it wele / &thorn;at it is synne ayeinst &thorn;e lawe of god / And yitte his reson / refreyneth nat his foule delite / or talent/ &thorn;ough he se wele / apertely / &thorn;at it is ayeinst &thorn;e reuerence of god all-though his reson / ne consent nat to do &thorn;at synne in dede / [295] yit/ seyn som doctours / &thorn;at soch delite &thorn;at dwelleth long it is <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="247b">Full parlious / all-be-it neuer so lite / [296] And also a man shold sorow namely for all &thorn;at euer he hath desired / ayeinst the lawe of god / with perfite consentyng of his reson / for there-of is no doute / &thorn;at it is dedely synne in consentyng/ [297] ffor certes there is no dedely synne / &thorn;at it is ferst in mannes thought/ and after &thorn;at in his delite/ and so forth in-to consentyng / and in-to dede / [298] wherfore I sey &thorn;at many men / ne repent hem neuer of soch &thorn;oughtes and delites ne neuer shryven hym of it / but onely of &thorn;e dede / of grete synnes outward. [299] wherfore I seye / &thorn;at soch wykked delites / and wykked thoughtes ben subtell begylers / of hem &thorn;at shull be dampned / [300] More-ouer man ought to sorowen / for his wykked wordes / as wele as his wykked dedes / for certes the repentaunce of a singuler synne / and nat repentant of all his other synnes / or els repent hym of all his other synnes / and nat of a synguler synne / may nat availl [301] ffor certes god all-myghty is all gode / and &thorn;erfore / eyther he foryeueth all / or els right nought/ [302] And here-of Seith seint Austyn I wote certeinlye / [303] &thorn;at god is enemye to euery synner / and how &thorn;an / he &thorn;at obserueth oo synne / shall he haue foryevenesse of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="604"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="611"> remenaunt/ of his other synnes / nay / [304] And ferther|ouer contricion shold be wonder sorowfull / and ang|wyssious / And &thorn;erfore yeveth hym god pleinly his mercy / And &thorn;erfore whan my soule was angwyssious within me / I hade remembraunce of god / &thorn;at my prayer myght com to hym / [305] ffertherouere contricion most be contynuell / and &thorn;at man haue sted|fast purpoos to shryve hym / and for to amend hym / of his lyf/ [306] ffor sothely while contricion lasteth / man may ever haue hope of foryevenesse / of &thorn;is comth hate of synne / &thorn;at destroyeth synne / both in hym self and eke in other folk/ at his power [307] ffor which seith Dauid / ye &thorn;at louen god / hateth wykkednesse / for trusteth wele / to loue god is for to loue &thorn;at he loveth/ and hate &thorn;at he hateth /</P>
<P>[308] The last &thorn;yng &thorn;at men shull vnderstonde in contricion is this / whereof avayleth contricion I sey &thorn;at som tyme contricion deliuereth man from synne [309] of which &thorn;at Dauid seith / I sey koth Dauid / &thorn;at is to sey I purposed me fermely to shryve me / and &thorn;ow lord relesedest my synne / [310] And right so as contricion avayleth nat/ without sad purpoos of shryft/ yf a man haue oportunitee right so / litle worth is shrift/ or satisfaccon without contricion [311] And more-ouer contricion destroyeth / &thorn;e prison of hell / and maketh weyke and feble / all the strengthes of &thorn;e devill/ and restoreth &thorn;e yiftes of &thorn;e holy goost/ and of all gode vertues / [312] and it clenseth &thorn;e soule of synne / and deliuereth &thorn;e soule from &thorn;e peyne of hell and from the companye of the devill/ and from &thorn;e seruage of synne / and restoreth it to all godes espirituels / and to &thorn;e companye and <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="248a">Comunion of holy chirche / [313] And ferther ouer it maketh hym / &thorn;at whilom was son of Ire / to be son of grace / and all thise thynges / ben preued by holy writte/ [314] And therfore he &thorn;at woll sette his intent/ to thise &thorn;ynges / he were full 
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="605"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="612"> wise / for sothely / he ne shold nat than / in all his lyf / haue corage to synne / but yeue his body / and all his hert to &thorn;e seruice of Ihesu Crist/ and &thorn;ere-of do hym homage / [315] ffor sothely our swete lord Ihesu Crist hath spared vs / so debonairlye / in our folies / &thorn;at yf he ne hade pitee of mannes soule / a sory song we myght all synge</P>
<TRAILER>Explicit prima pars Penitencle</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Et sequitur secunda pars eiusdem</HEAD>
<P>[316]</P>
<P>THe Secunde partie of Penitence is Confession / &thorn;at is signe of Contricion / [317] Now shull ye vnderstonde what is confession and whether it aught nedes be doon / or noon / and which &thorn;inges ben couenable to verray confession /</P>
<P>[318] ffirst shalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde / &thorn;at confession is verray shewyng of synnes to &thorn;e preest/ [319] &thorn;is is to sey verray / for he most confessen hym of all the condicions / &thorn;at longen to his syn as ferforth as he can / [320] all mot be seid / and no thyng excused ne hidde ne forwrapped And nought avaunt the of &thorn;y gode werkes / [321] And ferther ouer it is necessarie to vnder|stonde / Whens &thorn;at synnes spryngen and how &thorn;ey encrecen / And which &thorn;ey ben /</P>
<P>[322] Of &thorn;e spryngyng of synnes seith Seint Poule / in &thorn;is wise / &thorn;at right as by a man / synne entred first in-to &thorn;is world / and &thorn;urgh &thorn;at synne deth / right so &thorn;ylk deth entred in-to all men &thorn;at synnedden / [323] And &thorn;is man was Adam. by whom synne entred in-to this world / Whan he brake &thorn;e commaundementes of god [324] And &thorn;erfore he &thorn;at was so myghty &thorn;at he shold nat haue deyed bycam soch one / &thorn;at he most nedes deye / whether he wold or noon / and all his progenye in &thorn;is world / &thorn;at in &thorn;at man synned / [325] loke in &thorn;e state of Innocence / Whan Adam and Eve 
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="606"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="613"> naked weren in Paradys / and no thing ne hadden shame / of her nakednesse / [326] how &thorn;at &thorn;e serpent &thorn;at was moost wilye of all other bestes &thorn;at god hade make / seid to &thorn;e womman why commaunded god to you / &thorn;at ye shuld nat ete of euery tree in paradys / [327] The womman answerd of &thorn;e fruyt koth she of &thorn;e trees of Paradys / we feden vs but sothely of the fruyt of the tree / &thorn;at is in &thorn;e myddle of Paradys / god forbad vs for to ete / ne nat touchen it / lest perauenture we sholden dye / [328] The serpent seid to &thorn;e womman nay nay / ye shull nat deye of deth / forsoth god wote / &thorn;at what <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="248b">Day &thorn;at ye eten there-of / your yien shull open / and ye shull seen / and ben as goddes / knowyng gode and harme / [329] &thorn;e womman &thorn;an sawe / &thorn;at &thorn;e tree was gode to fedyng / and faire to &thorn;e yie / and delectable to sight/ she toke of the fruyt of &thorn;e tree / and ete it/ and yaue to hir housbond / and he ete / and anon &thorn;e yien of hem both opened / [330] and whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey knewe &thorn;at &thorn;ey were naked / &thorn;ey sewed of fyke leues / a maner of breches / to hide her membres [331] There mow ye see / &thorn;at dedely synne hath first suggestion of the fend / as sheweth here by &thorn;e adder / and afterward &thorn;e delite of the flessh / as sheweth here by Eve / and after &thorn;at &thorn;e consentyng of reson as sheweth here by Adam / [332] for trusteth wele / &thorn;ough so were / &thorn;at he tempted Eve / &thorn;at is to sey / &thorn;e flessh / and &thorn;e flessh hade delite in &thorn;e beaute of &thorn;e fruyt dyffended / yitte certes tyll &thorn;at reson / &thorn;at is to seye Adam con|sented to the etyng of &thorn;e fruyt/ yitte stode &thorn;ey in the state of Innocence / [333] Of that / Adam toke we thilk synne originall/ for of hym flesshly dissended be we all/ and engendred of vyle / and corrupt mater / [334] and whan &thorn;e soule is put in our body / right anon is con|tract originall synne / and &thorn;at / &thorn;at was erst / but onely peyne of concupicence / is afterward both peyne and synne [335] And &thorn;erfor be we all born sones of 
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="607"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="614"> wratth and of dampnacion / perdurable / yf it nere baptisme / &thorn;at we resceyuen / which benymmeth vs &thorn;e culpe / but for|soth &thorn;e peyne dwelleth with vs / as to temptacion / which peyne hyght concupiscence / [336] <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> whan it is wrongfully vsed disposed or ordeyned in man / yt maketh hym coueyte by coueytice of flessh / flesshly synne by sight of his yien / as to erthely thynges / and eke couetise of hyenesse / by pride of hert/</P>
<P>[337] Now as to speke of &thorn;e first couetice / &thorn;at is concupicence / after &thorn;e lawe of our membres &thorn;at were lawfully ymaked and by rightfull Iuge|ment of god / [338] I sey for-asmoch as man is nat obeisant to god / &thorn;at is his gode lord &thorn;erfore is the flessh to hym disobeisant/ &thorn;urgh concupiscence / which yitte is cleped Norisshyng of synne / . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [339] therfore all &thorn;e while &thorn;at a man hath in hym &thorn;e peyne of concupiscence / It is impossible / but he be tempted som tyme / and meved in his flessh to synne / [340] and &thorn;is thyng may nat faill as long as he lyveth/ it may wele wexe feble / and faill by vertue of baptysme / and by &thorn;e grace of god / &thorn;urgh Penitence / [341] but fully shall it neuer quenche / &thorn;at he ne shall som|tyme / be meued in hym self/ but yf he were refreyned by sekenesse or malifice or sorcerie or cold drynkes / [342] ffor lo what seith Seint Poule / &thorn;e flessh coueyteth ayeinst &thorn;e sperit/ and the sperit ayeinst &thorn;e flessh / &thorn;ey ben so contrarie / <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;at a man may nat all-wey do as he wold / [343] The same seint Poule seith / after his grete penaunce in water and in londe / in water by nyght / and by day in grete peryll/ and in grete peyne / In londe in famyn and thirst / and cold and clothlees / and ones stoned all-moost to &thorn;e deth / [344] yitte seid I. allas I caytif man / who shall <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="249a">Deliuere me from the prison of my kaytif body / [345] And seint Ierom seith/ whan he long tyme hade wonned in desert/ where as he hade no companye / but of wild bestes / where as he ne hadde 
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="608"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="615"> no mete / but herbes / and water to his drynk/ ne no bed but the naked erthe / for which his flessh was blak / as an Ethiopien for hete / and nye destroyed for cold / [346] yitte seid he / &thorn;at &thorn;e brennyng of lecherie boyled in all his body / [347] wherfore I wote wele sekerly / &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben disceyued &thorn;at seyen / &thorn;at they be nat tempted in her body [348] witnesse of Seint Iame &thorn;e Apostle / &thorn;at seith / &thorn;at euery wight is tempted in his owen con|cupyscence / &thorn;at is to sey / &thorn;at euerycch of vs hath mater and occasion / to be tempted of &thorn;e norisshyng of synne / &thorn;at is in his body [349] And therfore seith Seint Iohn &thorn;e Euaungelist / yf &thorn;at we sey / &thorn;at we be without synne we disceyue our self and trouth is nat in vs /</P>
<P>[350] Now shull ye vnderstonde / in what maner synne wexeth or encreseth in a man / The first thyng is / &thorn;e norisshyng of synne of which I spake biforn / thilk flesshly concupiscence / [351] And after &thorn;at &thorn;e suggestion of the devill / &thorn;at is to sey / &thorn;e devels bely / with which he bloweth in a man &thorn;e fire of flesshly concupiscence [352] and after that / A man be|&thorn;ynketh hym / whether he woll do or noo &thorn;at &thorn;yng/ to which he is tempted / [353] and &thorn;an yf &thorn;at a man withstonde and weyue / &thorn;e first entisynges of his flessh and of &thorn;e fend &thorn;an is it no synne / And yf so be &thorn;at he do nat so / &thorn;an feleth he anon a flame of delite / [354] and &thorn;an is it gode to be ware and kepe hym wele / or elles he woll fall anon / in-to consentyng of synne / and &thorn;an woll he do it yf he haue tyme and place [355] And of &thorn;is mater seith Moises by &thorn;e devyll in this maner / the fende seith I woll chace and pursue man / by wyk suggestion / and I woll hent hym / by &thorn;e mevyng or steryng of synne / and I woll parte my prayes or my praye by de|liberacon / and my lust shall be accomplised in delite / I woll drawe my swerde in consentyng [356] for certes right as a swerd departed a thyng in two peces / Right 
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="609"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="616"> so / consentyng departeth god from man / and &thorn;an woll I slee hym with myn hond in dede of synne / thus seith the fende [357] ffor certes &thorn;an is a man all dede in soule and &thorn;us is synne accompliced by delite and consentyng / and &thorn;an is &thorn;e synne cleped actuell /</P>
<P>[358] fforsoth synne is in two maners either it is veniall or dedely synne / sothely whan man loveth ony creature / more &thorn;an Ihesu Crist our Creatour &thorn;an is it dedely synne / And veniall synne is yf man loue Ihesu Crist lesse &thorn;an hym ought/ [359] fforsoth &thorn;e dede of &thorn;is synne is full perlious / for it amenuseth &thorn;e love &thorn;at men shold haue to god more and more [360] And therfore yf a man charge hym self / with many soch veniall synnes / certes but yf so be / &thorn;at he sone or som|tyme discharge him of hem by shryft of mouth/ &thorn;ey mow full lightly amenuse in hym / all &thorn;e love &thorn;at he hath to Ihesu Crist/ [361] And in this wise skyppeth veniall / in-to dedely synne ffor certes the more &thorn;at a man chargeth his soule with veniall synnes <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="249b">The more is he enclyned to fall in dedely synne / [362] And therfore let vs nat be necligent to descharge vs of veniall synnes / for &thorn;e prouerbe seith &thorn;at many smale maken a grete / [363] And herken this ensaumple / A grete wawe of &thorn;e see comth somtyme with so grete a violence &thorn;at it drencheth the shippe And &thorn;e same harme doth somtyme &thorn;e smale dropes of water/ &thorn;at entren &thorn;urgh a litle crevice / in-to &thorn;e thurrok/ and in &thorn;e botom of the shippe / yf men be so necligent/ &thorn;at men ne discharge bem nat by tyme [364] And therfore all-&thorn;ough &thorn;ere be a difference bitwene thise two causes of drenchyng / all-gates &thorn;e shippe is dreynt/ [365] Right so fareth it som tyme of dedely synne / and of Anoyous veniall synnes / whan they multeplie in a man so gretely / &thorn;at &thorn;ylk worldly thynges / &thorn;at he loueth / &thorn;urgh which he synneth venially / is as grete in his hert/ as &thorn;e loue of god or more / [366] 
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="610"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="617"> And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e loue of euery thyng &thorn;at is nat byset in god/ ne doon principally for goddes sake / all-&thorn;ough &thorn;at a man love it lesse &thorn;an god / yitte is it veniall synne / [367] And dedely synne is whan &thorn;e love of ony thyng weyeth in &thorn;e hert of man / as moch as &thorn;e love of god / or more [368] Dedely synne / as seith seint Austyn / is whan a man turneth his hert from god / which &thorn;at is verray souerayn bountee &thorn;at may nat chaunge / and yeveth his hert to thyng &thorn;at may chaunge and flytte / [369] and certes &thorn;at is euery &thorn;yng save god of heuen / fforsoth is &thorn;at yf a man yeve his loue / which &thorn;at he oweth all to god / with all his hert vn-to a creature / Certes as moch of his love / as he yeueth to thylk creature / so moch he byreveth from god / [370] And &thorn;er|fore doth he synne / for he &thorn;at is dettour to god / ne yeldeth nat to god all his dette / &thorn;at is to sey all &thorn;e love of his hert /</P>
<P>[371] Now seth man vnderstondeth generally / which is veniall synne / &thorn;an is it couenable / to tellen specially of synnes which &thorn;at many a man perauenture / ne demeth hem nat synnes / ne shryueth hem nat of the same thynges / And yitte natheles / &thorn;ey ben synnes / [372] sothly as thise clerkes writen / &thorn;is is to sey / &thorn;at at euery tyme &thorn;at man eteth or drynketh / more than suffyseth to &thorn;e sustenaunce of his body / in certein he doth synne / [373] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> Eke whan he herkeneth nat be|nyngnely the compleynt of the pore [374] Eke whan he is in hele of body / and woll nat fast whan o&thorn;er folk fast/ without cause resonable / Eke whan he slepeth more &thorn;an nedeth or whan he comth by thilk encheson to late to chirche / or to other werkes of charitee // [375] Eke whan he vseth his wyf without soueraigne desire of engendrure to the honour of god or for thentent / to yeld to his wyf &thorn;e dette of his body / [376] / Eke whan he woll nat visite &thorn;e seke / and &thorn;e prisoner yf he may 
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="611"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="618"> Eke yf he loue wyf or child or other worldly thyng more &thorn;an reson requyreth / Eke yf he flater or blaundyse / more than hym ought/ for ony necessitee / [377] Eke yf he amenuse or withdrawe the almesse of &thorn;e pore / Eke yf he apparayleth his mete more deliciously &thorn;an nede is/ or ete to hastely by <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="250a">Likerous|nesse / [378] Eke yf he tale Vanitees at chirche / or at goddes seruice / or &thorn;at he be a talker of ydell wordes / of foly or of velanye / for he shall yeld accountes &thorn;ere-of at &thorn;e daye of dome [379] Eke whan he byheteth or assureth to do &thorn;ynges / &thorn;at he may nat perfourme / Eke whan &thorn;at he by sleightes or folye / myseseth or scorneth his neighbour / [380] Eke whan he hath ony wykked suspession of thyng / whan he woteth of it no soth|fastnesse / [381] Thise synnes and mo without nombre / ben synnes / As seith seint Austyn /</P>
<P>[382] Now shull men vnderstonde &thorn;at all-be-it so / &thorn;at noon erthely man may eschew all veniall synnes yitte may he refreyne hym / by the brennyng loue / &thorn;at he hath to our lord Ihesu Crist / and by prayer and confession / and other gode werkes / so &thorn;at it shall but litle greve / [383] ffor as seith Seint Austyn / yf a man love god in soch a maner &thorn;at all &thorn;at euer he doth / is in &thorn;e love of god / or for the loue of god / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [384] loke how moch &thorn;at a drope of water &thorn;at falleth in a furneys full of fire / annoyeth and greveth So moch anoyeth a veniall synne / vn-to a man &thorn;at is perfite in &thorn;e love of Ihesu Crist/ [385] Men mow also refreyne veniall synne / by resceyvyng worthely &thorn;e precious body of Ihesu Crist/ [386] by resceyuyng eke of holy water / and almesse dede / by generall confession / of confiteor at Masse and at Complyn / and by blessynges of bisshopes / and of Prestes and of other gode werkes ./.
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000634.tif" N="612"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="619">
<HEAD>Sequitur de Septem peccatis mortalibus &amp; eorum dependenciis circumstanciis &amp; speciebus</HEAD>
<P>[387]</P>
<P>NOW is it byhouely thyng to tell which ben dedely synnes that is to sey Cheveteyns for-asmoch as &thorn;ey renne in oo lees but in diuers maners / Now ben they cleped Chefteynes for-asmoch as &thorn;ey ben chief / and spryngen of all other synnes / [388] Of &thorn;e rotes of thise .vij. synnes / than is Pride &thorn;e generall rote of all harmes for of &thorn;is rote spryngen certein braunches / as Ire Envye Accidie or Slouth Auarice or Couetise to common vnderstondyng Glotonye / and lecherie / [389] And euerycch of thise thynges / and synneshath his braunches and his twygges as shall be declared in her chapitres folowyng / <NOTE PLACE="inter">no break in the MS.</NOTE></P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[The Twigs of Pride.]</HEAD>
<P>[390] And &thorn;ough so be &thorn;at no man can vttrely tell / &thorn;e nombre of twigges / and of the harmes &thorn;at commen of pride yitte woll I shewe a partie of hem / as ye shull vnderstonde [391] There is Inobedyence / Auauntyng/ Ypocrisie / Despite / Arrogaunce / Inprudence / Swellyng of hert / Insolence / Elacion / Inpacience / Stryf / Contumasye / Presumpcion / Inreuerence / Vayneglorie / and many another twyg / &thorn;at I can nat declare / [392] Ino|bedient is he / &thorn;at disobeyeth for despite / to &thorn;e commaunde|mentes <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="250b">Of god / and to his soueraignes / and to his gostely fader [393] Auauntour is he &thorn;at bosteth of the harme or of the bountee that he hath don / [394] Ypocrisie / he is an Ypocrite &thorn;at hideth to showe hym soch as he is / and sheweth hym / soch as he nought is / [395] Dispytous is he / &thorn;at hath disdeyne / of his neighbore / &thorn;at is to sey of his even cristen / or hath despite to doon / &thorn;at hym yight to do / [396] Arrogant is he &thorn;at thynketh / &thorn;at he hath thilk bountees in hym &thorn;at he hath nat/ or 
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="613"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="620"> weneth &thorn;at he shold have hem / by his desertes / or elles he demeth / &thorn;at he be / &thorn;at he is nat/ [397] In|prudent is he / &thorn;at for his pride / hath no shame of his synnes / [398] Swellyng of hert is / whan man reioyseth hym of harme / &thorn;at he hath doon / [399] Inso|lent is he &thorn;at despiseth in his Iugement all other folk/ as to regarde of his value / and of his connyng and of his spekyng/ and of his heryng [400] Elacion is whan he ne may neither suffre to haue maister ne felawe / [401] Inpacient is he &thorn;at woll nat be ytaught/ ne vnder|nom of his vice / and by stryf werieth truth / wetynglye / and defendeth his folye / [402] Contumax is he / &thorn;at &thorn;urgh his Indignacion / is ayeinst euerycch auctoritee / or power of hem / &thorn;at ben his soueraignes / [403] Pre|sumpcion is whan a man vndertaketh an emprise/ &thorn;at hym ought nat to do / or els &thorn;at he may nat do / and &thorn;is is calld surquydre / Inreuerence is whan men doon nat honour / &thorn;ere as hem ought to do / and wayten to be reuerenced [404] Pertinacie is / whan man diffendeth his folie / and trusteth to moch to his owen witte / [405] Vaynglorie / is for to haue pompe and delite / in &thorn;is temporell hyenesse / and glorifie hem in this worldly astate / [406] Ianglyng is whan men speken to moch byfore folk/ and clappen as a myll/ and taken no kepe what &thorn;ey seyen.</P>
<P>[407] And yitte is there a pryve spice of Pride / &thorn;at wayteth first for to be salowed / or he wold salow / all be he lesse worthy &thorn;an &thorn;at o&thorn;er is peraventur And eke he waiteth or desireth to sitte or elles to go above hym in &thorn;e weye or kysse pax / or ben ensensed or gon to offryng byfore his neighbour [408] and semblable thynges ayeinst his duete perauenture / but he &thorn;at hath his hert / and his intent in soch a proude desire / to be magnyfied and honoured byfore &thorn;e peple</P>
<P>[409] Now ben there two maners of Pride / &thorn;at one of hem is within the hert of man / and &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="614"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="621"> o&thorn;er is without / [410] of which sothly &thorn;ise for|seid thynges / and mo &thorn;an I haue seid ben apperteynent to Pride / &thorn;at is in &thorn;e hert of man And &thorn;e other spices of pride ben without / [411] but natheles &thorn;at one of thise spices of pride is signe of &thorn;at other Right as &thorn;e gay levesell / at the Taverne is signe of &thorn;e wyne / &thorn;at is in &thorn;e seler / [412] and &thorn;is is in many thynges / As in speche and countenaunce and in outrageous array of clothyng/ [413] ffor certes yf &thorn;ere hadde be no syn in clothyng/ crist wold nat so sone / haue noted and spoke of &thorn;e clothyng of &thorn;e riche man in &thorn;e gospell / [414] And as seith Seint Gregorie / &thorn;at precious clothyng is coul|pable for the derth of it / and for his softnesse <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="251a">And for his straungenesse and disgesynesse / and for the super|fluytee or for &thorn;e inordinate scantnesse of it/ [415] Allas may man nat see / as in our dayes / &thorn;e synfull costlewe array of clothyng/ and namely in to moch superfluytee / or els in to disordinate scantnesse/</P>
<P>[416] As to &thorn;e first synne / in superfluite of clothyng/ which &thorn;at maketh it so dere / to harme of the peple [417] nat onely &thorn;e cost of enbrowdyng the desgise of endentyng or barryng oundyng palyng wyndyng or bendyng and semblable wast of cloth in vanytee / [418] But &thorn;ere is also &thorn;e costlewe furryng in her gownes so moch pounsonyng of chisell to make holes / and so moch daggyng of sheres / [419] forth-with &thorn;e superfluytee in length of &thorn;e forseid gownes trayl|yng in the dung / and in the myre / on hors and eke on fote / as wele of man as of womman / &thorn;at all thilk traillyng is verrey wasted consumed threde|bare and roten with dunge / rather &thorn;an it yeven to the poure to grete damage of &thorn;e forseid poure folk/ [420] And &thorn;at in sondrye wise / &thorn;is is to sey / &thorn;at &thorn;e more that cloth is wasted &thorn;e more mot it cost to &thorn;e peple for scarsenesse [421] And ferther ouer yf so be &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden yeve soch pounsoned and 
<PB REF="00000637.tif" N="615"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="622"> dagged clothyng / to &thorn;e poure folk it nys nat conuenient to were for her astate / ne sufficiant to bote her necessitee / to kepe hem from the dystemperaunce of the firmament / [422] On &thorn;at other side to speke of &thorn;e orible and disord|inate scantnesse / of clothyng/ As ben thise cutted sloppes / and hanselyns / &thorn;at &thorn;urgh her shortnesse &thorn;ey kever nat the shamefull membres of man / to wykked intent/ [423] Allas som of hem shewen &thorn;e boce of her shappe and &thorn;e orrible swollen membres / &thorn;at semeth like &thorn;e maladye of Hirnya / in &thorn;e wrappyng of her hoses / [424] and eke the buttokkes of hem faren as it were &thorn;e hynder part of a shee ape / in the full of the mone / [425] And moreouer &thorn;e wrecched swollen membres / &thorn;at &thorn;ey shewe &thorn;urgh disgysyng and departyng of her hosen in white &amp; rede semeth &thorn;at half her priue shame|full membres weren flayn / [426] And yf so be &thorn;at &thorn;ey depart her hoses in other colours / as is white and blewe / or white and blak / or blak and rede / and so forth / [427] &thorn;an semeth it / as by variaunce of colours / &thorn;at half the partie of her pryvee membres / ben corrupt/ by the fire of Seint Antony or by Cancre / or other soch meschaunce / [428] Of the hynder part of her buttokkes it is full horrible for to see / ffor certes in &thorn;at partie of her body / &thorn;ere as &thorn;ey purgen her stynkyng ordre / [429] &thorn;at foule partie shewe they / to &thorn;e peple proudely in despite of honestee / which honestee / &thorn;at Ihesu Crist and his frendes obserued to shewe in her lyve / [430] Now as of &thorn;e array outrageous of wommen god wote &thorn;at &thorn;ough &thorn;e visages of som of hem seme full chaste and debonaire / yitte notifie &thorn;ey in her array of atyre / likerousnesse and pride [431] I sey nat / &thorn;at dishonestee in clothyng of man or womman is vncouen|able but certes &thorn;e superfluytee / and disordinate scantnesse . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> is reprevable/ [432] Also &thorn;e synne of hournement or of apparaill/ is in thynges &thorn;at appertenen to ridyng/ <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="251b">As in to many delycate horses / &thorn;at ben holden 
<PB REF="00000638.tif" N="616"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="623"> for delite / &thorn;at ben so faire fat and costlewe / [433] And also by many a vicious knave / &thorn;at is sustened by cause of hem / In to curious harneys / as in sadles / in Cropers / Paytrels / and bridles / couered with precious clothyng/ and riche barres and plates of gold and of siluer / [434] for which god seith by Zakarye &thorn;e prophete / I woll confounde &thorn;e riders of soch horses / [435] Thise folk taken litle rewarde / of &thorn;e ridyng of goddes son of heuen and of his harneys . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> but &thorn;e pore clothes of his disciples / Ne we rede nat &thorn;at euer he rode on other beest / [436] I speke this for &thorn;e synne of superfluytee / and nat for resonable honestee whan reson requyreth it/ [437] And ferther-ouer certes Pride is gretely notified / in holdyng of grete meyne / whan &thorn;ey ben of litle profite / . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [438] and namely whan &thorn;at meyne is felonous and damage|ous to &thorn;e peple / by hardynesse of hie lordshippe or by wey of offices / [439] for certes soch lordes sellen &thorn;an / her lordshippes to &thorn;e devill of hell/ whan they sustene &thorn;e wykkednesse of her meynee / [440] Or elles whan thise folk of lowe degree as thilk &thorn;at holden hostillers / sustenaunt the theft of her Ostillers / and &thorn;at is in maner of deceytes / [441] Thilk maner of folk ben &thorn;e flies &thorn;at folowen &thorn;e hony / or elles &thorn;e houndes &thorn;at folowen &thorn;e careyn soch forseid folk stranglen spiritually her lordshippes [442] for which &thorn;us seith Dauid &thorn;e prophete wykked Deth mot com vp thilk lordshipes / and god yeve &thorn;at &thorn;ey mow discende in-to hell/ all doun / for in her houses ben iniquytees / and shrewednesse / and nat god of heuen / [443] and certes but yf &thorn;ey don amende|ment/ Right as god yaaf his beneson to kyng Pharao by &thorn;e seruice of Iacob / and to laban by the seruice of Ioseph / right so god woll yeve his malison / to soch lordshipes as sustene &thorn;e wykkednesse of her seruauntes / but they 
<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="617"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="624"> com to amendement/ [444] Pride of the table appereth eke full ofte / for certes riche men ben cleped to festes / and poure folk ben pntte aweye / and rebuked [445] Also in excesse of diuers metes and drinkes and namely soch maner bakemetes and dysshmetes brennyng of wild fire and peynted and castelled with paper / and semblable wast/ So &thorn;at it is Abbucion for to thynk/ [446] And eke in to grete preciousnesse of vessell and curiositee of mynstralcie / by which a man is stered &thorn;e more to delices of luxurie / [447] yf so be he sette his hert &thorn;e lasse vp-on / our lord Ihesu Crist/ certein it is a synne / And certeinly the delices myght ben so grete in this caas / &thorn;at man myght lightly fall by hem in-to dedely synne / [448] And whan &thorn;ey surden by frealtee vnavised of malice ymagened avised and forcast/ or elles of vsage / ben dedely synnes / it is no doute / [449] And whan &thorn;ey surden by frealtee vn|avised sodenly withdrawe ayein / all be &thorn;ey greuous synnes / I gesse that they ben nat dedely / [450] Now myght men axe where-of &thorn;at Pride surdeth and spryngeth And I sey somtyme it spryngeth of &thorn;e godes of nature / And somtyme of &thorn;e godes of fortune <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="252a">And somtyme of the godes of grace / [451] Certes the godes of Nature . . . . .[452] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> ben hele of body / As strength / delyvernesse / beautee / Gentries / ffraunchise [453] Godes of nature of the soule ben / gode witte / Sharpe vnderstondyng / subtle engyne / vertue naturell/ gode memorie / [454] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [455] Godes of grace ben / Science / pouere to suffre Spirituall trauaill / benignitee / vertuous contemplacion / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and semblab &thorn;ynge [456] Of which forseid godes / certes it is a full grete folie / a man to pride him in ony of hem all / [457] 
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="618"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="625"> Now as for to speke of godes of nature / god wote &thorn;at somtyme we haue in nature as moch to our Damage as to our profite / [458] As for to speke of hele of body / certes it passeth full lightly / and eke it is full oft / encheson of sekenesse / of our soule / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;e body is hole / the more we ben in peraill to fall / [459] Eke for to Pride hym in his strength of body / it is an hie folye ffor certes the flessh coueiteth ayeinst the sperit / And ay the more strong &thorn;at &thorn;e flessh is / &thorn;e sorier may &thorn;e soule be / [460] And ouere all &thorn;is / strength of body and worldly hardynesse causeth full oft many a man to perill and myschaunce / [461] Eke for to Pride him of his gentrie / is a full grete folye / for oft tyme the gentrie of his body begynneth the gentrie of the soule / and eke we ben all of o fader and of o moder and all we ben of oo nature / roten and corrupte / both riche and poure [462] fforsoth oo maner gentrie is for to preise / &thorn;at apparaileth a mannes corage with vertues and moralitees/ and maketh hym cristes child [463] ffor trust wele &thorn;at ouer what man / &thorn;at synne hath maistrie / he is a verray cherll to synne /</P>
<P>[464] Now ben &thorn;ere generall signes of gentilnesse / as eschewyng of vice and ribawdrie / and seruage of synne / in worde / in werk / and countenaunce [465] and vsyng vertue / curtesye / and clennesse / and to be liberall / &thorn;at is to sey large by mesure / for thilk &thorn;at passeth mesure / is folie and synne [466] Another is to remembre hym of bountee / &thorn;at he of other folk hath resceyued [467] Another is to be benigne to his gode subiettes wherfore seith Senek / &thorn;ere is no thing more conuenable / to a man of hie astate / &thorn;an debonairtee and pitee / [468] And therfore thise flies / that men clepen Bees / whan &thorn;ey make her kyng/ &thorn;ey chesen one &thorn;at hath no prikke / where-with he may styng [469] 
<PB REF="00000641.tif" N="619"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="626"> Another a man to haue a noble hert and a diligent/ to atteyne to hie vertuous thynges / [470] Now certes a man to pride hym in the godes of grace is eke an outrageous folye / for thilk yiftes of grace / &thorn;at shold haue turned hym to godenesse / and to medicyne / turneth hym to venym / and to confusion As seith Seint Gregorie / [471] Certes also who so prideth hym in &thorn;e godes of fortune / he is a grete fool / for somtyme / is a man a grete lord by &thorn;e morow &thorn;at is a caytyf and a wrecche or it be nyght/ [472] And somtyme &thorn;e richesse of a man is cause of his deth / Somtyme &thorn;e delices of a man is cause of greuous maladye / &thorn;urgh which he dieth/ [473] Certes &thorn;e commendacon of &thorn;e peple is oft full fals and full brotle/ for to trust / This daye &thorn;ey preise / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="252b">To-morow they blame / [474] God wote / desire to haue commendacion eke of &thorn;e peple hath caused deth/ to many a besy man / [475] Now seth &thorn;at so is / &thorn;at ye haue vnderstonde / what is Pride / and which ben the Spices of it/ and whan Pride sourdeth and spryngeth.;.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic tractus Superbie desinit / &amp; remedium eiusdem Hic Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[476]</P>
<P>Now shull ye vnderstonde which is &thorn;e Remedye ayeinst &thorn;e synne of pride / and &thorn;at is humylitee / or mekenesse / [477] &thorn;at is a vertue &thorn;urgh which a man hath verrey knowlecche of hym-self/ and holdeth him|self no pris ne deyntee / as in regarde of his dissertes consideryng euer his frealtee / [478] Now ben there .iij. maners of humylitee / as humylitee in hert/ Another humylitee in his mouth / the thirde in his werkes / [479] the humylitee in hert / is in .iiij. maners / &thorn;at one is / whan a man holdeth hym-self as nought worthy by-fore god of heven / Another is whan he despiseth 
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="620"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="627"> noon other man / [480] the thirde is / whan he ne rekketh nat / &thorn;ough men hold hym nought worth / the ferthe is / when he is nat sory of his humyliacion [481] And &thorn;e humilitee of mouth is in .iiij. thynges / In attempre speche / and in humblesse of speche / and whan he beknoweth with his / owen mouth / &thorn;at he is soch as hym thynketh / &thorn;at he is in hert / Another is whan he preiseth the bountce of another man / and no thyng &thorn;ere-of amenuseth [482] humylitee Eke in werkes is / in iiij. maners / &thorn;e first is whan he putteth other men byfore / &thorn;e secund is to chese the lowest place ouerall / &thorn;e iij<SUP>de</SUP>. is to assent gladly to gode counseill / [483] the ferthe is to stonde gladly to &thorn;e awarde of his soueraignes / or of hym / &thorn;at is in hier degree / certein &thorn;is is a grete werk of humylitee.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic desinit Remedium Superbie / &amp; tractus Incipit hic Inuidie/.</HEAD>
<P>[484]</P>
<P>After Pride I woll speke of the foule synne of Envye which that is as by the worde of &thorn;e Philisophre Sorow of other Mannes prosperitee And after the worde of Seint Austyn it is sorow of o&thorn;ere mennes wele / and Ioye of other mennes harme / [485] This foule synne is platly ayeinst the holy goost / yit natheles / ffor-asmoch as bounte perteneth proprely to &thorn;e holy goost / and Envye comth proprely of malice &thorn;er|fore it is proprely ayeinst the bountee of the holy goost / [486] Now hath malice .ij. spices / &thorn;at is to sey hardynesse of hert / in wikkednesse / or els &thorn;e flessh of man is so blynd &thorn;at he considereth nat / &thorn;at he is in synne / or rekketh nat &thorn;at he is in synne / which is &thorn;e hardnesse of &thorn;e deuell / [487] That other spice of malice is whan &thorn;at a man werryeth trouth / and eke whan &thorn;at he wote <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="253a">That it is trouth / and eke whan &thorn;at he werrieth &thorn;e grace / &thorn;at god hath yeve to his 
<PB REF="00000643.tif" N="621"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="628"> neighbour / and all this is by Envye / [488] Certes &thorn;an is Envye &thorn;e werst synne &thorn;at is / for sothely all other synnes / ben somtyme onely ayeinst o speciall vertue / [489] But certes Envye is ayeinst all vertues / and ayeinst all godenesse / for it is sorie / of all &thorn;e bountees of his neighbour / and in &thorn;is maner it is diuers from all other synnes / [490] ffor wele vnneth is &thorn;ere ony synne &thorn;at it ne hath som delite in it self / save onely Envye / &thorn;at euere hath in it self / angwyssh and sorow / [491] The spices of Envye ben thise / &thorn;ere is first sorow / of other mannes godenesse and of his pros|peritee / and prosperite is kyndly mater of ioye / Than is Envye a synne ayeinst kynde / [492] The secunde spice of Envie / is ioye of other mannes harme / and &thorn;at is proprely like to the devill / &thorn;at euere reioyseth hym / of mannes harme / [493] Of thise .ij. spices comth bakbytyng / And this synne of bakbityng or detraccion / hath certeyn spices as &thorn;us Som man prayseth / by a wykked intent / [494] for he maketh all-weye a wykked knotte / at &thorn;e last ende . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;at is digne of more blame / &thorn;an worth is all the preisyng / [495] The secunde spice is / &thorn;at yf a man be gode / or doth or seith a thyng to gode intent / the bakbiter woll turne all thilk godenesse vp so doun / to his shrewed intent / [496] The thirde is to amenuse &thorn;e bounte of his neigh|bore [497] The ferthe spice of bakbityng is &thorn;is / &thorn;at yf men speke godenesse of a man<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>MS. wrongly inserts, from the next line</I>, in dispreysyng of hym]</NOTE> &thorn;an woll &thorn;e bakbiter sey / Parfaye yitte soch a man is bet &thorn;an he / in dispreisyng of hym / &thorn;at men praise / [498] The fyfte spice is &thorn;is for to consent gladly / and herken gladly to &thorn;e harme / &thorn;at men speke of o&thorn;ere folk / This synne is full grete / and ay encreceth / after &thorn;e wykked intent of &thorn;e bakbyter / [499] After bakbytyng comth grucchyng or murmuracion / and som tyme it spryngeth of Inpacience / ayeinst god / and somtyme ayeinst man / 
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="622"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="629"> [500] Ayeinst god is it / whan a man gruccheth / ayeinst peyne of hell or ayeinst pouertee / or losse of catell / or ayeinst Reyn / or tempeste / or elles gruccheth &thorn;at shrewes han prosperitee / or elles &thorn;at gode men han ad|uersitee / [501] And all thise thynges / shold men suffre paciently / ffor &thorn;ey com by the rightfull Iugement and ordynaunce of god / [502] Somtyme comth grucchyng of Auarice / as Iudas grucched ayeinst the Magdaleyn / whan she anoynted the hede of our lord Ihesu Crist / with hir precious oynement / [503] this manere murmur is soch / as whan man gruccheth / of godenes / &thorn;at hym self doth or &thorn;at other folk don of her owen catell / [504] Somtyme comth murmur of Pride / as whan Symon the Pharisee / grucched ayeinst &thorn;e Magdaleyne whan she approched to Ihesu Crist / and wept at his fete for hir synnes [505] And somtyme it sourdeth of Envye / whan men discoueren a mannes harme / &thorn;at was priue / and bereth hym on honde thyng &thorn;at is fals / [506] Murmur is eke oft amonges seruauntes / &thorn;at grucchen whan her soueraignes bidden hem to do thynges leefull / [507] And for-asmoch as &thorn;ey <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="253b">Dare nat openly / withsey the commaundementes of her soueraignes / yitte woll &thorn;ey seyen harme and grucche and murmur priuelye / ffor verray despite [508] which wordes men clepen the devels pater noster / &thorn;ough so be / &thorn;at &thorn;e devyll ne hade neuer pater noster / but &thorn;at lewed folk yeven it soch a name / [509] somtyme it / comth of Ire or pryve hate / &thorn;at norissheth Rancour in hert / as afterward I shall declare / [510] Than comth eke bitternesse in hert / &thorn;urgh which bitternesse euery gode dede of his neighbour / semeth to hym bitter and vnsauerye / [511] Than comth discorde and vnbyndeth all maner of frenshippe / Than comth scornyng of . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> his neigh|bour / all do he neuere so wele / [512] &thorn;an comth accusyng / as whan man seketh occasion to anoyen his 
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="623"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="630"> neighbour which &thorn;at is like the Craft of the devell / &thorn;at wayteth both nyght and day to accuse vs all/ [513] Than comth malignytee / &thorn;urgh which a man anoyeth his neighbour priuelye yf he may / [514] and yf he ne may / all-gate his wykked will ne shall nat want/ as for to brenne his hous priuelye / or enpoysen / or slee his bestes / and semblable thynges./.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Inuidie tractus desinit / &amp; Remedium inde hic Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[515]</P>
<P>Now woll I speke / of &thorn;e remedye ayeinst this foule synne of Envie / first is the love of god principall/ and lovyng of his Neighbore as hym self / for sothly &thorn;at one may nat be without &thorn;at o&thorn;er [516] and trust wele / &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of thy neighbour / &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde the name of thy brother ffor certes all we han oo fader flesshly and oo moder / &thorn;at is to sey Adam and Eve / and eke oo fader spirituell / and &thorn;at is god of heuen [517] Thy neighbour art &thorn;ou hold to love / and will all godenes And &thorn;erfore seith god / love thy neighbour as &thorn;y self / &thorn;at is to sey to savacon both of lyf and soule / [518] And more-ouer &thorn;ou shalt love hym in worde and in benygne amonestyng/ and chastizyng/ and comforte hym in his anoyes / and praye for hym with all thyn hert / [519] And in dede &thorn;ou shalt love hym in soch wise / &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt do to hym in charitee / as &thorn;ou woldest / &thorn;at it were don to thyn owen persone / [520] and therfore &thorn;ou ne shalt do to hym no damage in wykked wordes / ne harme in his body / ne in his catell ne in his soule / by entisyng of wikked ensaumple / [521] &thorn;ou ne shalt nat desire his wyf/ ne noon of his thynges / vnderstonde eke &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of neighbour is com|prehended his enemy [522] Certes man shall love his enemye by the commaundement of god / And sothely thy frend shalt &thorn;ou love in god [523] I sey thyn enemy for goddes sake / by his commaunde|ment 
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="624"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="631"> / for yf it were reson / &thorn;at man shold hate his enemye / forsoth god nold nat resceyve vs to his love / &thorn;at ben his enemyes [524] Ayeinst .iij. maner of wronges / &thorn;at his enemye doth to hym / he shall do thre thynges as &thorn;us / [525] Ayeinst hate/ <NOTE PLACE="foot">[<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="254a">: Ayeinst hate <I>repeated</I>.]</NOTE>and rancour of Hert / he shall love hym in Hert/ Ayeinst chidyng and wykked wordes / he shall praye for his enemye/ Ayeinst &thorn;e wykked dede of his enemye / he shall don hym bountee/ 526] ffor Crist seith loveth your enemyes and prayeth for hem &thorn;at speke you harme / and eke for hem / &thorn;at you chasen and pursuen / and doth bountee to hem / &thorn;at you haten / lo thus commaundeth vs our lord Ihesu Crist to do to our enemyes / [527] fforsoth Nature dryveth vs to love our frendes / and parfeye our enemyes han more nede to love / &thorn;an our frendes / and &thorn;ey &thorn;at more nede han / certes to hem shollen men do gode|nesse / [528] and certes in thilk dede / have we remem|braunce of the love of Ihesu Crist / that deyed for his enemyes / [529] And in-asmoch as thilk loue / is &thorn;e more greuous to perfourme / So moch is the more grete the merite And &thorn;erfore the lovyng of our enemye hath confounded the venym of &thorn;e devyll [530] for right as &thorn;e devill / is discomfited by humylitee / right so is he wounded to the deth/ by love of our Enemye / [531] Certes &thorn;an is loue the medecyn that casteth out the venym of Envye from mannes hert/ [532] &thorn;e spices of this pace shull be more largely declared in her chapitres folowyng./.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Remedium Inuidie desinit &amp; tractus Ire Incipit /.</HEAD>
<P>[533]</P>
<P>After Envye woll I descryve &thorn;e synne of Ire for sothly who-so &thorn;at hath Envye vp-on his neighbour / anone he woll comunely fynde hym a mater of wrath / in worde or in dede / ayeinst hym / to whom he hath envye [534] And as wele comth Ire of Pride / 
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="625"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="632"> as of Envye ffor sothly / he &thorn;at is proude or envyous / is lightly wroth /</P>
<P>[535] this synne of Ire After the discryvyng of Seint Austyn / is wikked will to be avenged by worde or by dede [536] Ire after the Philisophre is the feruent blode of a man yqwyked in his hert/ &thorn;urgh which he wold harme to hym &thorn;at he hateth/ [537] ffor certes the hert of man by eschawfyng and mevyng of his blode wexeth so trouble / &thorn;at he is out of all Iugement of reson / [538] But ye shull vnderstonde/ &thorn;at Ire is in two maners / &thorn;at one of hem is gode / and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is wykked / [539] The gode Ire is / by ielousye of godenesse / &thorn;urgh which a man is wroth / with wikkednesse / and ayeinst wykkednesse And &thorn;er|fore seith a wise man / &thorn;at Ire is bet &thorn;an pley / [540] this Ire is with Debonairtee and it is wroth with|out bitternesse / nat wroth ayeinst the man / but wroth with &thorn;e mysdede / of the man / as seith the prophete David Irascimini &amp; nolite peccare / [541] Now vnderstondeth &thorn;at wikked Ire is in two maners &thorn;at is to sey soden Ire / or hasty Ire / without avisement/ and consentyng of reson [542] The menyng and &thorn;e sence of this / is / &thorn;at &thorn;e reson of a man ne con|sent nat / to thilk soden Ire / and than is it venyall / [543] Another Ire is full wykked &thorn;at comth of ffelonye / of hert avised and cast byforn <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="254b">With Wykked will to do Vengeaunce / and there-to his reson consenteth / and sothly this is dedely synne [544] This Ire is so dis|plesaunt to god &thorn;at it troubleth his hous / and chaseth the holy goost/ out of mannes soule and wasteth and de|stroyeth / the liknesse of god that is to sey / the vertue that is in mannes soule [545] and putteth in hym the lyk|nesse of the devyll/ and benymmeth the man from god / that is his rightfull lord / [546] This Ire is a full grete plesaunce to &thorn;e devill / for it is the devels fourneis / &thorn;at is enchaufed with the fire of hell / [547] ffor certes 
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="626"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="633"> right so / as fire is most myghty to destroye all erthelye thynges / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [548] loke how that fire of smale gledes / &thorn;at ben almost dede vnder asshen wollen qwyk ayein whan they be touched with brymstone / Right so woll Ire euermore qwyk ayein whan it is touched by the pride &thorn;at is couered in mannes hert/ [549] ffor certes fire ne may nat com out of nothing/but yf it were first naturely in the same thyng/ as fire is drawen out of flyntes with steell / [550] And right so as Pride is oft tyme mater of Ire / right so is rancour norice and keper of Ire [551] There is a maner tree / as seith Seint Isidre / &thorn;at whan men maken fire of that tre / and couere the coles of it with asshen / sothely the fire of it woll lasten all a yere or more/ [552] and right so fareth it / of Rancour whan it is ones conceyued in the hertes of som men / certein it woll last perauenture from o Ester day vn-till another Ester day and more / [553] but certes thilk man is full fer from the mercy of god all &thorn;at while /</P>
<P>[554] In &thorn;is forseid devels fourneys &thorn;ere forgen thre Shrewes / Pride &thorn;at ay bloweth and encreseth the fire by chidyng and wikked wordes / [555] Than stant Envye and holt &thorn;e hote Iren vpon the hert of man with a peire of long tonges / of long Rancour / [556] And than stant / the Syn of Contwmelie or Stryf / and cheste and batereth and forgeth by veleyns reprevynges / [557] Certes this cursed synne anoyeth both in the man hymself and eke to his neighbour / for sothly all-most / all the harme &thorn;at ony man doth / to his neighbour cometh of wratth / [558] for certes outrageous wratth / doth all &thorn;at euer the devill hym commaundeth for he ne spareth neither Crist / ne his swete moder / [559] and in his out|rageous angre and Ire / allas allas / full many oon / at &thorn;at tyme / feleth in his hert full wikkedly / 
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="627"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="634"> both of Crist / and eke of all his halowes / [560] Is nat &thorn;is a cursed vice / yis certes / allas it benymmeth from man his witte / and his reson and all his debonair lyf / spirituell/ &thorn;at shold kepen his soule / [561] Certes it benymmeth eke goddes due lordshippe / and &thorn;at is mannes soule / and the love of his neighbores / it stryueth eke all day ayeinst trouth / it reveth hym &thorn;e quyete of his hert / and subuerteth his soule /</P>
<P>[562] Of Ire commen stynkyng engendrures ffirst hate / &thorn;at is old wratth / Discorde / &thorn;urgh which a man forsaketh his old frende / full longe / [563] and than comth Werr and euery manere Wrong &thorn;at man doth / to his neighbour / in body or in catell / [564] Of this cursed synne of Ire / comth manslaughter And vnderstonde <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="255a">Wele &thorn;at Homycide is manslaughter in diuers Wise / Som manere of homicide is spirituell / and som is bodely [565] Spirituell manslaughter is in .vj. thynges / first by hate / as seint Iohn seith / he &thorn;at hateth his brother / is an homicide / [566] Homycide is eke by bakbityng/ of which bakbiters seith Salamon &thorn;at &thorn;ey han two swerdes / with which they sleen her neighbores ffor sothly / as wykked is to benym hym his gode name as his lyf / [567] Homycide is eke in yevyng of wikked counseill by fraude / as for to yeve counseill to areyse wrongfull custumes and taliages [568] Of which seith Sala|mon / lyon roryng / and bere hungrie / ben like to &thorn;e cruell lordshippes in which holdyng or abreggyng of the shepe / of the hire / or of the wages of seruauntes / or els in vsure / or in with-drawyng of the almesse of pore folk/ [569] ffor which the wise man seith / ffedeth hym that all-most deyeth for hunger / ffor sothly / but yf &thorn;ou fede him &thorn;ou sleest hym / and all thise ben dedely synnes / [570] Bodely manslaughter is whan &thorn;ou sleest hym with thy tung / in other maner / as whan &thorn;ou commaundest to slee a man / or yevest hym counceill to slee a 
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="628"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="635"> man / [571] Manslaughter in dede is in .iiij. maners / &thorn;at one is by lawe / right as a Iustice dampneth hym &thorn;at is coulpable to the deth / but let the Iustice be ware / &thorn;at he do it rightfully/ and &thorn;at he do it nat for delite to spill blode but for kepyng of rightwo|nesse [572] Another homicide is don for necessitee/ as whan a man sleeth another in his diffendant/ and &thorn;at he ne may escape non o&thorn;er wise from his owen deth/ [573] But certainlye yf he may escape with|out slaughter of his aduersarie and sleeth hym / he doth synne / and he shall bere penaunce as for dedely synne / [574] Eke yf a man / by caas or auenture shete an arow or cast a stone with which he sleeth a man he is an homycide / [575] Eke yf a womman by necligence ouerlie hir child in hir slepyng / it is homycide and dedely synne/ [576] Eke whan man distourbeth con|cepcion of a child and maketh a womman eyther bareyn by drynkyng of venemouse herbes &thorn;urgh which she may nat conceyue/ or sleeth a child by drynkes or els putteth certen materiall thynges in hir secre places / to slee the child [577] or els doth vnkyndely synne / by which man or womman shedeth her nature in maner or in place / &thorn;ere as a child may nat be con|ceyued / or els and yf a womman haue conceyued and hurte hir self / and sleeth the child / yitte is it homicide / [578] what sey we eke / of wommen &thorn;at mordren her children / ffor drede of worldly shame/ certes it is an horrible homicide/ [579] Homycide is eke / yf a man ap|proche to a womman by desire of lecherie / &thorn;urgh which &thorn;e child is perisshed / or elles smyt a womman wetyngly / &thorn;urgh which she leseth her childe All &thorn;ise ben homy|cides/ and horrible dedely synnes / [580] Yitte comth ther of Ire many no synnes / as wele in worde as in thought / and in dede / as he &thorn;at arretteth / vp-on god or blameth god of &thorn;ing/ of which he is him <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="255b">Self gilty or despiseth god / and all his halowes / as don thise cursed hasardours / 
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="629"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="636"> in diuers cuntrees / [581] This cursed synne doon &thorn;ey whan &thorn;ey felen in her hert full wikkedly of god and his halowes [582] Also whan &thorn;ey treten vnreuerently &thorn;e sacrament of the auter/ &thorn;at synne is so grete/ &thorn;at vnneth it may be relesed / but that the mercy of god passeth all his werkes / it is so grete / and he so benigne / [583] Than comth of Ire / Attrye angre / whan a man is sharply amonested in his shrifte / to for|lete synne/ [584] &thorn;an woll he be angry and answere hokerly and angrelye / or defende or excuse his synne / by vnstedfastnesse of his flessh / or els he did it / for to hold companye with his felawes / or elles he seith / the fend enticed hym / [585] or els he did it / for his youth / or els his complexion is so corageous / &thorn;at he ne may nat forbere or els it is destenye as he seith/ vn-to a certein age / or els he seith it comth hym of his gentillesse of his Auncetres / and semblable thynges / [586] All &thorn;ise maner of folk / so wrappen hem in her synnes / &thorn;at &thorn;ey ne woll deliuere hem self/ ffor sothly no wight/ &thorn;at excuseth hym wilfully of his synne / may nat be deliuered of his synne / till &thorn;at he mekely beknowe his synne [587] After this than comth sweryng/ &thorn;at is expresse ayeinst the commaundement of god / and &thorn;is befalleth oft of angre and of Ire / [588] God seith &thorn;ou shalt nat take / the name of thy lord god / in veyne / or in Idle / Also our lord Ihesu Crist seith / by the worde of Seint Mathewe / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [589] ne woll &thorn;ou nat swere in all maner / neither by heven / for it is goddes Trone / ne by erthe / for it is &thorn;e benche of his fete / ne by Ierusalem / for it is the Citee of a grete kyng/ ne by thyn hede / for &thorn;ou maist nat make an here white ne blak/ [590] But seith by your word. ye ye / nay nay / and what &thorn;at is more is of evill / &thorn;us seith Crist/ [591] ffor Cristes sake / ne swereth nat so synfully in dysmembryng of Crist/ by soule / 
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="630"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="637"> hert/ bones and body / for certes it semeth / that ye thynk &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed Iewes / ne dismembred nat ynough / &thorn;e precious persone of Crist/ but ye dismembre hym more [592] And yf so be &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe com|pell yow to swere / &thorn;an shull ye rewle you / after the lawe of god / in your sweryng / As seith Ieremye / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;ou shalt kepe .iij. condicions/ &thorn;ou shalt swere in trouth / in dome / and in rightwosnesse [593] this is to sey &thorn;ou shalt swere soth / for euery lesyng is ayeinst Crist / for Crist is verray trouth / and &thorn;ynk wele this / &thorn;at euery grete swerer nat compelled lawefully to swere / &thorn;e wound shall nat departe from his hous / while he vseth soch sweryng/ [594] Thow shalt swere eke in dome. whan &thorn;ou art constreyned by the domes|man / to witnesse the trouth [595] Eke &thorn;ou shalt nat swere for envye / ne for fauour / ne for mede but for rightwosnesse / for declaracon of it/ to &thorn;e worshippe of god / and helpyng of thyn even cristen / [596] And &thorn;erfore euery man / &thorn;at taketh goddes name in Idle / or falsly forswereth with his mouth / or els taketh on him <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="256a">The name of Crist to be called a Cristen man / and lyveth ayeinst cristes lyvyng/ and his techyng/ All they taken goddes name in ydle / [597] loke eke what seith Seint Petir Actuum 4<SUP>o</SUP> / Non est aliud nomen sub celo &amp;c / There is non other name seith Seint Petir / vnder heuen / to men / in which &thorn;ey mow be saved / &thorn;at is to sey / but in the name of Ihesu Crist / [598] Take kepe eke / how &thorn;at / &thorn;e precious name of Ihesu Crist / as seith Seint Poule / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> In &thorn;e name of Ihesu / euery knee of hevenly creatures / or erthely / or of hell / shold bowe / ffor it is so hye / and so worshipfull/ &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed fend in hell/ shold tremble for to here it named / [599] &thorn;an semeth it / &thorn;at men &thorn;at sweren so horriblye / by his 
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="631"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="638"> blessed name / &thorn;at they despise it more boldely / &thorn;an dyd the cursed Iewes / or elles the devill &thorn;at trembleth / whan he hereth his name /</P>
<P>[600] Now certes seth &thorn;at sweryng/ but yf it be lawefully doon / is so hiely defended / moch wers is for-sweryng falsly / and yitte natheles /</P>
<P>[601] what sey we / eke of hem <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> in sweryng / &thorn;at hold it as a gentrie or a manly dede to swere grete othes / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> all be the cause nat worth A strawe / Certes this is horrible synne / [602] Sweryng eke without avisement / is eke a Synne / [603] But let vs go now / to that horrible sweryng of Adiuracion and coniuracion as don thise fals en|chauntours or Nygromaunciens / in basyns full of water / or in a bright swerd / or in A Circle/or in a fire / or in the sholder bone of a shepe / [604] I can nat sey but &thorn;at &thorn;ey don cursedly and dampnablye / ayeinst Crist/ and all &thorn;e feyth of holy chirche /</P>
<P>[605] what seye we by hem / &thorn;at beleven on dyvynailles as by flight/ or by noise of birdes / or of bestes / or by sorte of Geomancye / by dremes / by chirkyng of dores / or crakkyng of howses / by gnawyng of Rattes / and soch maner of wrecchednesse / [606] certes all this thyng is defended by god / and by holy chirche / for which &thorn;ey ben accursed till they com to amendement/ &thorn;at on soch fylth setten her byleve [607] Charmes for woundes or maladye / of men / or of bestes / yf they taken ony effectes it may be perauenture / &thorn;at god suffreth it / for folk shold yeve &thorn;e more feith / and reuerence to his name /</P>
<P>[608] Nowe woll I speke of lesynges / which gener|ally is fals signifiaunce of worde / in entent/ to disceyve his even Cristen / [609] Som lesyng is of which &thorn;ere comth noon auauntage to no wight / And som lesyng turneth to the ease / and profite of o man and to 
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="632"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="639"> damage of another man / [610] Another lesyng / for to saven his lyf / or his catell / &thorn;at comth / of delite for to lye / in which delite &thorn;ey wollen forge a long tale / and peynte yt / with all &thorn;e circumstaunces where as all &thorn;e ground of the tale is fals / [611] Som lesyng comth for he wold sustene his worde / Som lesyng comth of rechelesnesse without avisement / and sem|blable thynges /</P>
<P>[612] let vs now touche the vice of flateryng/ which ne comth gladly / but for drede / or for Covetise / [613] <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="256b">fflatery is generally wrongfull preisyng/ fflater|ers ben the devels Norices that norisshen his children with mylk of losengrye / [614] fforsoth Salamon seith &thorn;at flaterie is wers than detraccion / for somtyme de|traccion maketh an hawteyn man / be the more humble / for he dredeth detraccion / but certes flaterie / &thorn;at maketh an hauteyn man in hert/ and countenaunce / [615] fflaterers ben the devels enchauntours ffor &thorn;ey make a man to wene of hym self belike &thorn;at he is nat like [616] they ben like Iudas / &thorn;at betrayeth . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> a man to sell hym to his enemye &thorn;at is the devyll/ [617] fflaterers ben the devels Chapellyng &thorn;at syngen euere Placebo / [618] I reken flaterie / in the vices of Ire for oft tyme yf o man be wroth with another / &thorn;an woll he flater som wight to sustene him in his quarell /</P>
<P>[619] Speke we now of soch cursyng/ as comth of Irous hert/ Malison generally may be seid / euery maner power of harme / soch cursyng byreveth man from &thorn;e reigne of god As seith Seint Poule / [620] and oft tyme soch cursyng wrongfully retourneth / ayein to hym / &thorn;at curseth as a bird &thorn;at retourneth ayein to his owen nest/ [621] And ouer all thyng men ought eschewe to curse her children / and yeven to &thorn;e devill her engendrure/ as ferforth / as in hym is / certes it is grete perill and grete synne /
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="633"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="640"></P>
<P>[622] Let vs than speke of chidyng and repreef/ which ben full grete woundes in mannes hert/ . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [623] for certes vnnethes may a man pleinlye be accorded with hym / &thorn;at hath hym openly reviled and repreved and disclaundred / this is a full grisly synne / as crist seith in the gospell / [624] and take kepe now / &thorn;at he &thorn;at repreveth his neighbour/ eyther he repreueth hym by som harme of peyne / &thorn;at he hath on his body / as Mesell / Croked Harlot / on by som synne &thorn;at he doth / [625] Now yf he repreue hym by harme of peyne / &thorn;an turneth the repreef to Ihesu Crist/ for peyne is sent by ryghtwys sonde of god / and by his suffraunce / be it meselrie / or mahayme or maladye / [626] And yf he repreue hym vncharitablye of synns / as &thorn;ou drunk|lewe Harlot/ and so forth / &thorn;an apperteneth &thorn;at / to &thorn;e reioisyng of &thorn;e devyll / &thorn;at euere hath ioye / &thorn;at men doon synne / [627] And certes chidyng may nat com / but out of a veleyns hert/ for after the habundaunce of the hert/ speketh &thorn;e mouth full oft/ [628] And ye shull vnderstonde / &thorn;at loke by ony weye whan ony man / shall chastise another / &thorn;at he be ware from chidyng/ or reprevyng/ ffor truly but he be ware / he may full lightly qwyk &thorn;e fire of Angre and of wratth / &thorn;at he shold qwenche and perauenture sleeth hym / &thorn;at he myght chastise with benig|nytee [629] ffor as seith Salamon / the Amyable tung / is the tree of lyf / &thorn;at is to sey lyf spirituell/ And sothly a dislaue tung sleeth &thorn;e sperit of hym that repreveth / and eke of hym &thorn;at is repreued [630] loo what seith Seint Austyn / ther is no thing so like the devels child / as he &thorn;at oft chideth Seint Poule seith eke / I seruaunt of god byhoueth nat to chide [631] <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="257a">And though &thorn;at chidyng be a veleyns thyng bitwene all manere folk/ yitte is it certes most vncouenable / bitwene a man and his wyf / for &thorn;ere is neuer rest/ 
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="634"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="641"> And therfore seith Salamon / An hous &thorn;at is vncouered and droppyng and a chidyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>MS. repeats</I> and a chidyng]</NOTE>/ wyf / ben like [632] a man &thorn;at is in a droppyng hous / in many places / &thorn;ough he eschew the droppyng in oo place it droppeth on hym in another place / So fareth it by a chidyng wyf/ but she chide hym in oo place / she woll chide him / in another / [633] and therfore better is A morsell brede with ioye / &thorn;an an hous full of delices / with chidyng/ seith Salamon / [634] Seint Poule seith / O ye Wommen / be ye subiectes to your housbondes / as byhoueth in god / and ye men loueth your wyfes / Ad Colonisences 3<SUP>o</SUP>.</P>
<P>[635] Afterward speke we of scornyng/ which is a wykked synne And namely whan he skorneth a man for his gode werkes / [636] ffor certes soch scorners / faren like the foule tode / &thorn;at may nat endure / to smell the swete sauour / of the vyne whan it florissheth / [637] &thorn;e scorners ben partyng felawes with the devyll/ for &thorn;ey han Ioye whan &thorn;e devyll wynneth / and sorow whan he leseth / [638] they ben aduersaries of Ihesu Crist/ for they haten &thorn;at he loueth / &thorn;at is to sey sauacion of soule /</P>
<P>[639] Speke we now of wykked counseill / for he &thorn;at wikked counseill yeveth is a traytour / for he disceyueth / hym &thorn;at trusteth hym / . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> But natheles yitte is his wykked counseill/ first ayeinst hym self/ [640] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> &thorn;at he &thorn;at woll anoye another man / he anoyeth first hym self/ [641] And men shull vnderstonde &thorn;at man shall nat take his counseill of fals folk/ ne of angrye folk or greuous / folk/ &thorn;at loven specially to moch her owen profite / ne to moch worldly folk/ namely in counseillyng of soules /</P>
<P>[642] Now comth &thorn;e Synne of hem / &thorn;at sowen and maken discorde amonges folk/ which is a synne/ &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="635"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="642"> Crist hateth vtterly / and no wonder is / for he dyed to make concorde / [643] And more shame do they to crist/ &thorn;an dyd &thorn;ey &thorn;at hym crucefied / for god loueth better / &thorn;at frendshippe be amonges folk/ &thorn;an he did his owen body / which &thorn;at he yaaf for vnytee / &thorn;erfore ben &thorn;ey lykned to &thorn;e devyll/ &thorn;at euer is about to make discorde</P>
<P>[644] Now comth &thorn;e synne of double tung / soch as speken faire byfore folk/ and wikkedly behynde / or elles they make semblant/ As though &thorn;ey speke of gode intencion / or elles in game and pleye / and yitte they speke of wykked intent /</P>
<P>[645] Now comth bywreying of Counseill thurgh which a man is defamed / certes vnethe may he restore &thorn;e damage</P>
<P>[646] Now comth manace / &thorn;at is an open folye / for he &thorn;at oft manaceth he threteth more &thorn;an he may perfourme / full ofte tyme</P>
<P>[647] Now comth ydell wordes / &thorn;at is without profite of hym / &thorn;at speketh the wordes / and eke of hym / &thorn;at herkeneth the wordes / or elles ydell wordes / ben tho &thorn;at ben nedeles or elles withouten intent / of naturell <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="257b">Profite / [648] and all be it &thorn;at ydell wordes / ben som|tyme veniall synne / yitte shull men doute hem / for we shull yeve rekenyng of hem byfore god /</P>
<P>[649] Now Now comth Iangelyng &thorn;at may nat be with|outen synne / As seith Salamon it is a signe of pert folye / [650] And therfore A phili&yogh;ophre seid whan men axed how &thorn;at men shold plese &thorn;e peple / and he answerd Do many gode werkes / and speke fewe iangles /</P>
<P>[651] After this comth the synne of Iapers / &thorn;at ben the devels Apes / for &thorn;ey make folk to laugh at her Iaperye / as folk don at &thorn;e gawdes of ape / Soch iapes defendeth Seint Poule / [652] Loke How &thorn;at vertuous wordes and holy comforten hem 
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="636"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="643"> &thorn;at trauaillen in the seruice of Crist / right so comforten the veleyns wordes and knakkes of Iapers hem &thorn;at travaillen in &thorn;e seruice of the devill / [653] &thorn;ise ben the synnes &thorn;at commen of the tunges &thorn;at commen of Ire / and other synnes moo.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Ire tractus desinit / &amp; remedium eiusdem Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[654]</P>
<P>THe Remedye ayeinst Ire / is a vertue &thorn;at men clepen Mansuetude &thorn;at is debonairtee / and eke another vertue / &thorn;at men callen Pacience or suffraunce /</P>
<P>[655] Debonairtee withdraweth / and restreyneth / &thorn;e sterynges of &thorn;e meuynges of mannes corage in his hert/ in soch maner &thorn;at &thorn;ey ne skippe nat out by angre ne bi Ire / [656] Suffraunce suffreth swetely all the anoysaunces / and &thorn;e wronges / &thorn;at men doon to man outward/ [657] Seint Ierom seith thus of debonairtee / &thorn;at it dooth noon harme to no wight/ ne seith ne for noon harme / &thorn;at men doon or seyn / he ne eschaufeth nat his reson [658] This vertue somtyme comth of nature / for as seith the Philosophre / A man is a qwyk thyng / by nature debonaire and tretable to godenesse But whan debonairtee is enfourmed of grace / &thorn;an is it &thorn;e more worth /</P>
<P>[659] Pacience / &thorn;at is another Remedye / ayeinst Ire / for it is a vertue &thorn;at suffreth swetely / euery mannes godenesse/ and nat wroth / for noon harme / &thorn;at is don to hym / [660] The Philosophre seith / &thorn;at Pacience ys thilk vertue / &thorn;at suffreth / debonairlye all the outrages of aduersitee / and euery wykked worde / [661] this vertue maketh a man lyke to god / and maketh hym goddes owen dere child / as seith Crist / this vertue discomfyteth thyn enemy And therfore seith the wise man yf &thorn;ou wolt venqwyssh &thorn;yn enemy lerne to suffre [662] And &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde / &thorn;at man suffreth .iiij. maner 
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="637"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="644"> of thynges / and greuaunces / ayeinst &thorn;e which .iiij. he most have .iiij. maner of Paciences /</P>
<P>[663] The first greuaunce is / of wykked wordes tho suffred Ihesu Crist / without grucchyng full paciently / whan the Iewes despised hym / and repreued hym full ofte / [664] suffre &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore paciently ffor the wise man seith/ yf &thorn;ou stryve with a fooll/ &thorn;ough &thorn;e fole be wroth or &thorn;ough he laugh / all gate &thorn;ou shalt haue no rest / [665] &thorn;at other greuaunce <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="258a">Outward is to haue damage of thy catell/ &thorn;ere ayeinst suffred crist full paciently / whan he was despoyled of all that he hadde in this lyf/ and that nas but his clothes / [666] The thirde greuaunce is / a man to haue harme in his body &thorn;at suffred Crist full paciently in all his passion / [667] The ferthe grevaunce is in outrageous labour in werkes / wherfore I seye &thorn;at folk &thorn;at maken her seruauntes to travaillen to greuously or out of tyme / as on holidayes / sothly they doon grete synne / [668] here ayeinst suffred Crist full paciently / and taught vs pacience / whan he bare vp-on his blissed sholder the crosse / vp-on which he suffred dispitous deth/ [669] Here men mow lerne to be pacient/ for certes nat onely cristen men ben pacient/ for &thorn;e love of Ihesu Crist / and for the gwerdon / of &thorn;e blisfull lyf / &thorn;at is perdurable / But certes &thorn;e old Payens / &thorn;at neuer were cristen commendeden and vseden &thorn;e vertue of pacience /</P>
<P>[670] A Philosophre vp-on a tyme &thorn;at wold haue bette his disciple / for his grete trespace / for which he was gretely ameved / and brought a yerde to skoure the childe / [671] and whan &thorn;e child sawe the yerd / he seid to his maister / what thynk ye to doo / I woll bete the koth &thorn;e maister / for thy correccion / [672] forsoth koth the child / ye ought first correcte your self/ &thorn;at han lost all your Pacience for the gilt of a childe / [673] forsoth koth &thorn;e maister all wepyng/ &thorn;ou 
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="638"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="645"> seyst soth/ haue &thorn;ou the yerde my dere son and correcte me / for myn Inpacience / [674] Of Pacience comth Obedience &thorn;urgh which a man is obedient to Crist/ and to all hem / the which he ought to be obedyent too / [675] And vnderstonde well &thorn;at obedience is perfite / whan &thorn;at a man doth gladly and hastely with gode hert entierly / all &thorn;at he shold do / [676] Obedience generally / is to perfourme hastely the doctrine of god / and of his soueraignes to which hym ought to be obeysant/ in all rightwosnesse /.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Remedium contra Ire peccatum desinit &amp; tractus Accidie Incipit.</HEAD>
<P>[677]</P>
<P>After the synnes of Envye and Ire / now woll I speke of the synne of Accidie / for Envye blyndeth &thorn;e hert of man / and Ire troubleth a man / and Accidie maketh hym hevy / &thorn;oughtfull and wrawe [678] Envye and Ire maken bitternesse in hert/ which bitternesse is moder of Accidie/and benymmeth/hym &thorn;e loue of all godenesse / Than is Accidie the Angwyssh of troubled hert / And seint Austyn seith it is anoye of godenesse / and anoye of harme [679] Certes this is a dampnable synne for it doth wrong to Ihesu Crist/ in asmoch as it benymmeth the seruice / &thorn;at men doon to Crist / with all diligence As seith Salamon / [680] But Accidie doth no soch diligence / he doth all thyng with anoye / and with wrawenesse / slaknesse and excusacion / and with ydelnesse and vnlust/ for which the boke seith A-cursed be he / that doth &thorn;e ser|uice of god necligently / [681] &thorn;an is Accidie enemye <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="258b">To euery astate of man / for certes the <NOTE PLACE="inline">blotch in MS.</NOTE> man / is in .iij. maners [682] The first astate that is is the astate of Innocence / as was the state of Adam byfore &thorn;at he fell in-to synne / in which astate / he was holden to werche as in heryng and adhouryng of god / [683] Another astate is the astate of synfull men/in which astate/men ben holden 
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="639"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="646"> to labour in praying to god / for amendement of her synnes / and &thorn;at he woll graunt hem / to rise out of her synnes / [684] Another estate is / thestate of grace / in which astate / he is hold to do werkes of Penitence / And certes to all thise thynges / is Accidie enemye and con|trarie / for he loueth no besynesse at all/ [685] Now certes &thorn;is foule synne Accidye is eke a full grete enemye / to &thorn;e lyflode of &thorn;e body for it ne hath / no purveaunce ayeinst temporell necessitee / for it forsleutheth and for|sluggeth and destroyeth all godes temporels by rechelesnesse</P>
<P>[686] The .iiij<SUP>th</SUP> thyng is &thorn;at Accidie<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>The MS. repeats</I> &thorn;at Accidie]</NOTE> / is like hem &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e peyne of hell / by cause of her sleuth / and of her hevynesse / for &thorn;ey &thorn;at ben Dampned ben so bound / &thorn;at &thorn;ey mow neither wele do / ne wele &thorn;ynk [687] Of Accidie comth first / &thorn;at a man is anoyed / and encombred for to do ony godenesse / and maketh &thorn;at god hath abhominacon of soch Accidie /</P>
<P>[688] Now comth Slouth &thorn;at woll nat suffre noon Hardnesse / ne no penaunce for sothly Slouth is so tender and so delicate / as seith Salamon / &thorn;at he woll nat suffre noon Hardnesse ne penaunce / and &thorn;erfore he shendeth all &thorn;at he doth [689] Ayeinst &thorn;is roten and hurted synne of Accidie and slouth shold men exercise hem self/andvse hem self/to do godewerkes and manly and vertuously / cacchen corage well to doo / thynk|yng &thorn;at our lord Ihesu Cryst qwyteth euery gode dede/ be it neuer so litle / [690] vsage of labour is a grete thyng/ for it maketh/ as seith Seint Bernard / the laborer to have strong Armes / and harde senewes / And slouth maketh hym feble and tendre [691] Than comth drede to begynne to werke ony gode werkes / for certes / he that is enclyned to synne / hym thynketh it is so grete an emprise / for to vndertake to do werkes of godenes / [692] and casteth in his hert / &thorn;at &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="640"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="647"> circumstaunces of godenesse ben so greuous / and so chargeant for to suffre / &thorn;at he dare nat vndertake / to do werkes of godenesse / as seith Seint Gregorie /</P>
<P>[693] Now comth wanhope &thorn;at is dispeire of the mercy of god &thorn;at comth somtyme of to moch out|rageous sorow / and som tyme of to moch drede / ymagen|yng &thorn;at he hath doon so moch synne / &thorn;at it wold nat availl/ &thorn;ough he wold repent hym and forsake synne / [694] thurgh which Dispeire or drede he haboundeneth all his hert/to euery maner synne/ as seith Seint Austyn / [695] which dampnable synne / yf &thorn;at it contynue vn-to his lyves ende / it is cleped synne in the hooly goost / [696] This horrible synne is so perlious / &thorn;at he &thorn;at is dispeired / &thorn;ere nys no felonye ne no synne / &thorn;at he douteth for to doo. <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="259a">As shewed wele by Iudas / [697] Ce[<I>ink gone</I>]ve all synnes / &thorn;an is this synne most displesant to Crist/ and moost [aduer]sarie / [698] Certes he that dispeyreth hym is like the Coward Champion/ recreant/ &thorn;at seith creaunt withouten nede Allas Allas nedeles is he recreaunt/ and nedeles dispeirant / [699] Certes &thorn;e mercy of god is euer redy / to the penitent / and is aboven all his werkes / [700] Allas can nat a man bethynk hym / on the gospell of Seint Luke .15. where as Crist seith/ &thorn;at aswele shall there be ioye in heven / vp-on a synfull man &thorn;at doth Penitence / &thorn;an vp-on .90. and .9. rightfull men / &thorn;at . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> neden no Penitence / [701] loke ferther in the same gospell/ &thorn;e ioye and the feest / of &thorn;e gode man / &thorn;at hade lost his son / whan his son with repentaunce was retourned to his fader/ [702] kan they nat eke remembre hem / &thorn;at as seith Seint luke 23<SUP>o</SUP>. how &thorn;at &thorn;e theef &thorn;at was hanged beside Ihesu Crist/ seid lord remember the of me / whan &thorn;ou comst in-to thy reigne / [703] forsoth seid Crist/ I sey to &thorn;e to day / shalt &thorn;ou be with me in paradys / [704] Certes &thorn;ere is noon so horrible a synne of 
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="641"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="648"> man / &thorn;at it ne may in his lyf / be destroyed by penitence / &thorn;urgh vertue of the passion / and of &thorn;e deth of Crist/ [705] Allas what nedeth man &thorn;an / to be dispeyred / seth &thorn;at his mercy so redy is / and large / axe and haue / [706] Than comth Sompnolence / &thorn;at is sluggy slombryng/ which maketh a man be hevy / and dulle in body and soule / and &thorn;is synne comth of slouth / [707] and certes the tyme / &thorn;at by weye of reson / man shold nat slepe / &thorn;at is by &thorn;e morow but yf there were cause resonable / [708] for sothly in the morowtide / is most couenable / a man to seye his prayers / and for to thynk on god / and to honour god / and to yeve almesse to the pore / &thorn;at first comth in &thorn;e name of Crist/ [709] loo what seith Salamon / who-so woll by &thorn;e morow awake and seke me he shall fynde me [710] Than comth Necligence / or Rechelesnesse &thorn;at rekketh of no thing/ And how &thorn;at ignoraunce is moder of all harme Certes Necligence is the Norice / [711] Necligence ne doth no force / whan he shall do a thyng / whether he do it wele or badly</P>
<P>[712] Of Remedie of &thorn;ise two synnes / as seith &thorn;e wise man / &thorn;at he &thorn;at dredeth god / he spareth nat to do / &thorn;at hym ought to do / [713] And he that loueth god / he woll do dyligence to please god / by his werkes / and abunden hym self/ with all his myght wele for to doo / [714] Than comth Ydelnesse / &thorn;at is &thorn;e yate of all harmes An ydell man is like a place / &thorn;at hath no walles / &thorn;ere as deuels now entren on euery side / or shete at hym / at discouert by temptacon on euery side / [715] This ydelnesse is &thorn;e thurrok / of all wikked and veleyns thoughtes / and of all iangles / trifles / and of all ordre / [716] Certes &thorn;e heven is yeven to hem / &thorn;at woll labouren and nat to ydle folk / Eke Dauid seith / &thorn;ey ne be nat in the labour of men / ne they ne shull nat ben whipped with men / &thorn;at is to sey in Purgatorie 
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="642"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="649"> [717] Certes &thorn;an semeth it that they shull ben turmented with the devill in hell / but yf &thorn;ey <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="259b">Do Penitence</P>
<P>[718] Than comth the Synne &thorn;at men clepen Traditas / as whan a man is to latered or tariyng/ or he woll turne to god / and certes &thorn;at is a grete folye / he is like hym / &thorn;at falleth in &thorn;e dyche / and woll nat arise / [719] and this vice comth of fals hope &thorn;at he thynketh / &thorn;at he shall lyve long / but &thorn;at hope fayleth full ofte</P>
<P>[720] Than comth Lacchesse / &thorn;at is he / &thorn;at whan he begynneth ony gode werk/ anone he shall forlete it/ and stynt/ as don &thorn;ey / &thorn;at han ony wyght / to gouerne and ne taken of hem no more kepe / anone as they fynden / ony contrarie / or ony anoye [721] Thise ben &thorn;e new Sheperdes / &thorn;at leten her shepe wetyngly go renne / to &thorn;e wolf / &thorn;at is in the breres / or do no force of her owen gouernaunce / [722] Of this comth Pouertee and destruccion / both of spirituell / and temperell thynges Than comth a maner coldenesse / &thorn;at fressheth at &thorn;e hert of man [723] Than comth vndeuocion / thurgh which a man is blent/ as seith Seint Barnard / and hath soch langour in soule / &thorn;at he may neither rede ne syng in holy chirche / ne here ne thynk of no deuocion ne travaill with his hondes in no gode werke / &thorn;at it nys to hym vnsauerie / and all appalled [724] &thorn;an wexeth he slowe / and slombrye / and sone wold he wroth and sone is enclyned to hate / and to envye [725] Than comth the synne of worldly sorow / soch as is cleped Tristicia &thorn;at sleeth man / as seith seint Poule / [726] ffor certes soch sorow werketh to the deth of &thorn;e soule / and of the body / Also ferther / of &thorn;at comth / &thorn;at a man is anoyed of his owen lyf / [727] Wherfore soch sorow shorteth full ofte the lyf of man / or &thorn;at his tyme be com / by weye of kynde /.
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000665.tif" N="643"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="650">
<HEAD>Hic tractus Accidie desinit &amp; Remedium eiusdem Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[728]</P>
<P>A Yeinst this horrible Synne of Accidie / and &thorn;e braunches of the same / there is a vertue &thorn;at is called ffortitudo or Strength / &thorn;at is an affeccion / &thorn;urgh which a man despiseth annoyous &thorn;ynges / [729] this vertue is so myghty and so vigorous &thorn;at it dare withstonde myghtely and wisely kepe hym self / from perels / &thorn;at ben wykked and wrastle ayeinst the assawtes of the devell / [730] for it enhaunceth and enforceth the soule Right as Accidie abateth it / and maketh it feble ffor this ffortitudo may endure by long suffraunce / &thorn;e travailles &thorn;at ben couenable /</P>
<P>[731] This vertue hath many spices / The first is Magnanimitee / &thorn;at is to sey / grete corage ffor certes &thorn;ere behoveth grete corage ayeinst Accidie / lest &thorn;at it ne swolow the soule by &thorn;e synne of sorow or destroye it / by wanhope / [732] this vertue maketh folk vndertake harde thynges / and greuous thynges / by her owen will/ wisely and resonablye / [733] And for|asmoch as the devill fyghteth / ayeinst a man <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="260a">More by qweyntise and by sleight/ &thorn;an by strength/ &thorn;erfore shall man withstonde hym / by witte and by reson / and by dis|crecion / [734] &thorn;an are the vertues of feith and hope in god / and in his seyntes / to atteyne and accomplice the gode werkes in the which he purposeth fermely to contynue / [735] Than comth sewertee / or sekernesse / and &thorn;at is whan a man ne douteth no travaile / in tyme commyng / of &thorn;e gode werkes / &thorn;at a man hath bygon / [736] Than comth magnificence / &thorn;at is to sey / whan a man doth and perfourmeth grete werkes of godenesse / and that is the ende / why that men shold do gode werkes / for in the accomplisyng of grete gode werkes / lyth the grete gwerdon / [737] Than is &thorn;ere Constaunce that is stablenesse of corage / and &thorn;is shold be in hert/ by stedfast feith and in mouth and in 
<PB REF="00000666.tif" N="644"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="651"> beryng / and in chere and in dede / [738] Eke &thorn;er ben moo speciall remedies ayeinst Accidie in diuers werkes and in consideracions of the peynes of hell / and of &thorn;e Ioyes of heven / and in &thorn;e trust of &thorn;e grace / of &thorn;e holy goost/ &thorn;at woll yeve hym myght to perfourme his gode Intent/.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Remedium Accidie desinit / &amp; tractus Auaricie Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[739]</P>
<P>After Accidie woll I speke of Auarice and of Covetise / Of which synne seith Seint Poule / &thorn;at &thorn;e Rote of all harmes is Couetise / ad thumotheum 6&deg; [740] for sothly whan &thorn;e hert of man is confounded in it self/ and trouble / and &thorn;at &thorn;e soule hath lost &thorn;e comforte of god / &thorn;an seketh he an ydle place of worldly thynges /</P>
<P>[741] Auarice after &thorn;e discripcion of Seint Austyn is a lykerousnesse in hert to haue erthely thynges / [742] Som other folk seyn &thorn;at Auarice / is for to purchace many erthely thynges / and no &thorn;ing yeve to hem &thorn;at han nede [743] And vnderstonde &thorn;at Auarice / ne stant nat onely by lond ne cattell/ but som tyme in science and in glorie / and in euery maner of outrageous thyng/ is Auarice and Covetice / [744] And &thorn;e difference bitwene Auarice and Couetice is &thorn;is / Couetyce is to coveit soch thynges as &thorn;ou hast nat and Auarice is for to withhold and kepe / soch &thorn;ynges as &thorn;ou hast / without rightfull nede / [745] sothly &thorn;is Auarice is a synne / &thorn;at is full dampnable for all holy writte curseth it / and speketh ayeinst &thorn;at vice / for it doth wrong to Ihesu Crist / [746] for it byreveth hym &thorn;e love / &thorn;at men to hym owen / and turneth it bakward ayeinst/ all reson / [747] and maketh &thorn;at &thorn;e Auaricious man / hath more hope in his catell / &thorn;an in Ihesu Crist and doth more obseruaunce / in kepyng of his tresour / &thorn;an he doth to &thorn;e seruice of Ihesu Crist / [748] And therfore seith 
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="645"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="652"> Seint Poule ad Ephesios .i<SUP>o</SUP>. &thorn;at an Avaricious man / is &thorn;e thraldom of Idolatrie /</P>
<P>[749] what difference <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="260b">Is bitwene an Ydolastre and an Auaricious man / but that an ydolastre perauenture / ne hath but o Mawmet or two / and the Auaricious man hath manye / ffor certes euery ffloreyn in his coffre / is his mawemet / [750] And certes &thorn;e synne of Mawmettrye / is &thorn;e first thyng / &thorn;at god defended in &thorn;e .x commaunde|mentes / as bereth witnesse in Exodye c<SUP>o</SUP> 20&deg;. [751] &thorn;ou shalt haue no fals goddes byfore me / ne &thorn;ou shalt make to the / no grave thyng / &thorn;us is an Auaricious man / &thorn;at loveth his tresour byfore god / an ydolastre [752] &thorn;urgh this cursed synne of Auarice Of Covetise commen thise harde lordshipes &thorn;urgh which men ben distreyned by taillages / Custumes and cariages more &thorn;an her duetee / or reson is / and eke take &thorn;ey of her bonde men amercimentes which myghten more resonablye be cleped extorcions than mercimentes [753] Of which mercymentes and rawnsomyng of bonde men Som lordes Stewardes seyn / &thorn;at it is rightfull for-asmoch as a Cherle hath no temperell/ thyng/ &thorn;at it ne is / his lordes / as &thorn;ey seyn [754] But certes &thorn;ise lordshipes don wrong &thorn;at by-reven her bonde folk/ thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ey neuer yaaf hem / Augustinus de li<SUP>o</SUP>. 9&deg;. [755] Soth is / &thorn;at the condicion of thraldom / and &thorn;e first cause of thraldom. is for synne Genesis 9&deg;.</P>
<P>[756] &thorn;us now ye see / that &thorn;e gylt / deserued thraldom / but nat nature / [757] wherfore thise lordes / ne shold nat mochell glorifye hem in her lordshippe seth that by naturell condicion / &thorn;ey be nat lordes ouer thralles / but &thorn;at thraldom comth first/ by &thorn;e deserte of synne [758] And ferther ouer / &thorn;ere as &thorn;e lawe seith/ &thorn;at temperell godes of bonde folk/ ben &thorn;e godes of her lordshipes / ye &thorn;at is for to vnderstonde &thorn;e godes of the Emperour to defenden hem in her right/ but nat for to robben hem / ne reve hem [759] And therfore 
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="646"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="653"> seith Seneca Thy Prudence shold lyve benignely with thy thralles / [760] &thorn;oo &thorn;at &thorn;ou clopest / &thorn;y thralles ben goddes peple / for humble folk/ ben Cristes frendes / &thorn;ey ben contubernyall/ with the lord /</P>
<P>[761] thynk eke &thorn;at of soch seed as cherles spryngen of soch seed spryngen lordes / as wele may &thorn;e Charle be saved as the lord / [762] the same deth / &thorn;at taketh &thorn;e Cherll/ soch deth taketh &thorn;e lord Wherfore I rede / do right so with thy Cherll/ as &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;at &thorn;y lord did with the / yf &thorn;ou were in his plite / [763] Euery synfull man is a cherl to synne / I rede &thorn;e certes / &thorn;at &thorn;ou lord werke in soch wise with thy cherles &thorn;at &thorn;ey rather love the and drede &thorn;e / [764] I wote wele there is degree aboue degree / as reson is / and skyll/ is / &thorn;at men doon her devoir &thorn;ere as it is due But certes extorcions and despite of your vnderlynges / is dampnable /</P>
<P>[765] And ferther ouer vnderstonde wele &thorn;at conquerours or tyrauntes / maken full oft thralles / of hem &thorn;at ben born of as riall blode as ben &thorn;ey &thorn;at hem conqweren [766] This name of Cherldam was neuer erst couth till &thorn;at Noe seid / &thorn;at his son Chayme shold <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="261a">be thrall to his brethern / for his synne / [767] What sey we &thorn;an of hem / &thorn;at pelen and don extorcions / to holy chirche / Certes the swerd &thorn;at men yeven first to a knyght/ whan he is newe dubbed signefyeth / &thorn;at he shold defende holy chirche / and nat robbe it / ne pyl it / and who so doth is traytour to Crist/ [768] and as seith Seint Austyn / &thorn;ey ben &thorn;e devels wolfes / &thorn;at stranglen &thorn;e shepe of Ihesu Crist/ and don wers &thorn;an wolves [769] for sothly whan a woolf/ hath full his wombe / he stynteth to strangle shepe / But sothly the pylours and destroy|ers of holy chirche godes / ne do nat soo / for they ne stynt neuer to pill/ [770] Now as I haue seid / seth so is / &thorn;at synne was first cause of thraldom / &thorn;an is it 
<PB REF="00000669.tif" N="647"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="654"> thus / &thorn;at thylk tyme &thorn;at all &thorn;e world was in synne / &thorn;an was all the world in thraldom / and subieccion [771] But certes seth the tyme of grace cam / god ordeyned &thorn;at som folk / shold be more hye in estate and degree / and som folk more lowe / and &thorn;at euerycch shold be serued in his astate / . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> [772] and therfore in som cuntrees / &thorn;ere &thorn;ey ben thralles / whan &thorn;ey han turned hem to &thorn;e feith &thorn;ey make her thralles free / out of thraldom / and &thorn;erfore certes / &thorn;e lord oweth to his man / &thorn;at &thorn;e man oweth to his lord / [773] The pope calleth hym seruaunt of the seruauntes of god / but for-asmoch as the state of holy Chirche / ne myght nat have be / ne the commune profite / ne myght nat have be kept / ne pees and rest/ in erth / but yf god hade ordeyned &thorn;at som man hade hyer degree / and som man lower [774] &thorn;erfore was souerayntee was ordeyned to kepe and mayntene and de|fend her vnderlynges / or her subiectes / in reson / as fer|forth as lyeth in her power and nat to destroye hem ne confound / [775] wherfore I sey / &thorn;at &thorn;oo lordes / &thorn;at ben like wolfes &thorn;at devouren the possessions / or the catell / of poure folk wrongfully withouten mercy or mesure/ [776] &thorn;ey shull resceyue by the same mesure / &thorn;at &thorn;ey han mesured to poure folk/ the mercy of Ihesu Crist / but yf it be amended / [777] Now comth disceite bitwene merchaunt and merchaunt/ and &thorn;ou shalt vnder|stonde / &thorn;at merchandise is in many maners / &thorn;at one is bodely and &thorn;at other is gostely / &thorn;at one honest and leefull / and &thorn;at other dishonest / and vnlieffull / [778] Of &thorn;at merchandise / &thorn;at is lieffull and honest / is this / &thorn;at there as god hath ordeyned &thorn;at a regne or a cuntree / is suffisant to hymself/ &thorn;an is honest and lieffull/ &thorn;at of habundaunce of &thorn;is Contre &thorn;at men help another contree / &thorn;at is more nedy [779] And &thorn;erfore &thorn;er mot be merchauntes / to bryng from &thorn;at oo contree to &thorn;at other her merch|andise 
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="648"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="655"> / [780] That other merchaundise / &thorn;at men haunt/ with fraude and trecherie / and disceyte with lesynges / and fals othes is cursed and dampnable / [781] Espirituel merchandise / is proprely Symonye &thorn;at is ententyf desire / to bye thyng espirituell/ &thorn;at is thyng that apperteneth to the Sentuarie of god / and to Onre of &thorn;e soule [782] &thorn;is desire / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="261b">Yf so be / &thorn;at a man do his diligence / to perfourme it/ all be it/ &thorn;at his desire take noon effecte / yitte is it to hym a dedely synne / and yf he be ordred He is irregulere / [783] Certes Symonye is cleped of Symond Magus / &thorn;at wold have bought for temperell gode / &thorn;e yift &thorn;at god hade yeven by &thorn;e holy goost to seint Petir / and to the Appostles / [784] And therfore vnderstonde / &thorn;at both he / &thorn;at selleth and he &thorn;at byeth / thynges espirituels / ben cleped Symonyales / be it by catell/ be it by procuryng / or by flesshly prayer / of his frendes / flesshly frendes or spirituell frendes / [785] flesshly in two maners as by kynrede or other frendes / sothly yf &thorn;ey pray for hem / &thorn;at is nat worthy and able / it is Simonye / yf he take the benefice / and yf he be worthy and able / &thorn;ere is none [786] That other maner is whan men or wommen / prayen for folk to avauncen hem onely / for wykked flesshly affeccion / &thorn;at &thorn;ey han to the persones / and &thorn;at is foule Symonye / [787] But certes in seruice / for which men yeven thyng espirituell/ vn-to her seruauntes it mot be vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e seruice mot ben honest / and elles nat/ and eke &thorn;at it be without bargeynyng / and &thorn;at &thorn;e persone be able / [788] ffor as seith Seint Damasie / all &thorn;e synnes of &thorn;e world at regarde of &thorn;is synne arn as a thyng of nought / for it is the grettest synne / &thorn;at may be / after ye synne of lucifere / and of Antecrist / [789] for by this synne / god forleseth &thorn;e Chirche / and &thorn;e soule / &thorn;at he bought with his precious blode / by hem &thorn;at yeven chirches to hem / &thorn;at ben nat digne / [790] for &thorn;ey put in &thorn;efes &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="649"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="656"> stelen &thorn;e soules of Ihesu Crist / and destroyen his patri monye / [791] by soch vndigne prestes and curates / han lewde men &thorn;e lesse reuerence / of &thorn;e sacramentes of holy chirche / And soch yevers of chirches putten out / the children of Crist / and putten in the devels owen son/ [792] &thorn;ey sellen the soules &thorn;at lambes shold kepen / to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;at strangleth hem / and &thorn;erfore shull &thorn;ey neuer haue parte / of &thorn;e pasture of lambes &thorn;at is the blys of heuen / [793] Now comth hasardrye with his appur|tenaunces as tables and raafles / of which comth disceite / fals othes / chidynges and all ravynes / blasfemyng and reneying / of god / and hate of his neighbours / wast of godes / myspendyng oft tyme / and somtyme man|slaughter [794] Certes hasardours ne mow nat be / without grete synne / . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> [795] Of Auarice commen lesynges / theft / and fals witnesse / and fals o&thorn;es And ye shull vnderstonde / &thorn;at &thorn;ise ben grete synnes / and expresse ayeinst &thorn;e commaundementes/of god/as I haue seid [796] ffals witnesse is in worde / and eke in dede / In worde / as for to byreve &thorn;y neighbours gode name by fals witnessyng/ or byreve hym / his catell/ or his heritage / by &thorn;y fals witnessyng/ whan &thorn;ou for Ire / or for mede / or for envye / berest fals witnesse / or els ex|cuseth &thorn;y self falsly / [797] ware yow qwest-mongers and Notaries / Certes for fals witnessyng was <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="262a">Susanna in full grete sorow and peyne / and many other moo/. [798] The synne of theft/ is eke expresse / ayeinst goddes heest/ in .ij. maners corporell or spirituell [799] [Corporell] as for to take thy neighbours catell/ ayeinst his will/ be it by force or by sleight/ be it by mete or by mesure / [800] By stelyng eke of fals endytementes / vp-on hym / and in borowyng eke of thy neighbours catell/ in entent neuere to paye / and semblable thynges / [801] Es|pirituell thynges / to stele; is sacrilegge / &thorn;at is to sey hurt|yng 
<PB REF="00000672.tif" N="650"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="657"> of holy thynges / or of thynges sacred to crist/ in two maners by reson of the holy place as chirches or chirchehawes [802] ffor which euery vileyns synne / &thorn;at men doon / in soch places / may be cleped sacrilegge / or euery violence / in the semblable places / Also they that with-drawen the rightes &thorn;at longen to holy chirche / [803] And pleinly and generally sacrilegge is to reve holy thyng from holy place / or vnholy &thorn;yng out of holy place / or holy thyng out of vn|holy place /.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Auaricie tractus desinit / &amp; Remedium eiusdem Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[804]</P>
<P>Now shull ye vnderstonde / &thorn;at &thorn;e Releuyng of Auarice is misericorde and pitee largely taken And men myght axe why / &thorn;at misericorde and pitee is relevyng of Auarice [805] Certes &thorn;e Auarous man sheweth no pitee ne misericorde / to &thorn;e nedefull man / for he deliteth hym / in the kepyng of his tresour and nought in the reskewyng ne relevyng of his even cristen / And therfore speke .I first of mysericorde / [806] . . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in MS.</NOTE> as seith the Philosophre / a vertue / by which &thorn;e corage of a man is stered by the mysease of hym / &thorn;at is myseased [807] vpon which misericorde foloweth pitee in perfourmyng of charitable werkes / of misericorde [808] and certes thise meven men / to misericorde of Ihesu Crist / &thorn;at yafe hym self for our gilt / and suffred deth/ for misericorde / and foryave vs our originall synnes [809] and thereby relesed vs / from &thorn;e peyne of hell/ and amenused the peynes of Purgatorie by Penitence / and yeveth grace wele to do / and at the last the ioye of heuen [810] The spices of misericorde ben as for to love and for to yeve / and to foryeve and relees / and for to haue pitee in hert/ and compassion of the myschief of his 
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="651"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="658"> even cristen / and eke chastise &thorn;ere as nede is / [811] Another maner of remedy ayeinst Auarice is resonable largesse / but sothly here byhoueth/ &thorn;e con|sideracion of the grace of Ihesu Crist / and of his temperell godes / and eke of &thorn;e godes perdurables / &thorn;at Crist yave vs / [812] and eke to haue remembraunce of &thorn;e deth &thorn;at he shall resceyve he note whan / and eke &thorn;at he shall forgoo all that he hath/ save onely &thorn;at he hath dispended in gode werkes /</P>
<P>[813] But for-asmoch / as som folk / ben mesur|able / men ought eschewe foollargesse &thorn;at men clepen waste / [814] Certes <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="262b">He &thorn;at is fool-large / he yeveth nat his catell/ but he leseth his catell sothly / what thyng that he yeveth / for veyne glorie / as to mynstrals / and to folk to bere his renoun / in &thorn;e world he hath synne and noon almesse [815] Certes he leseth foule his gode / &thorn;at he seketh with &thorn;e yift of his gode no &thorn;yng but synne / [816] he is like an hors / &thorn;at rather seketh to drynk drovy water or trouble &thorn;an for to drynk water of &thorn;e clere well/ [817] And for-asmoch/ as &thorn;ey yeven &thorn;ere as &thorn;ey shold nat yeven / to hem apperteneth &thorn;e malison / &thorn;at crist shall yeve at &thorn;e day of dome / to hem &thorn;at shull be dampned.&middot;.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Auaricie Remedium desinit &amp; tractus Gule nunc Incipit /.</HEAD>
<P>[818]</P>
<P>AFter Auarice comth Glotonye / which is expresse ayeinst the commaundement of god / Glotonye is vnmesurable appetite to ete / or drynk / or elles to do ynough to vnmesurable appetite or disordeyne Couetise / to ete or to drynk / [819] &thorn;is synne cor|rumpeth all &thorn;is werld as is wele shewed / in the synne of Adam / and of Eve / lo eke what seith seint Poule of Glotonye / [820] many seith seint Poule goon / of which 
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="652"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="659"> I haue oft seid to yow / and now I sey yitte wepyng/ to hem &thorn;at ben &thorn;e enemyes of &thorn;e crosse / of Crist / Of which &thorn;e ende is deth / and of which/ her wombe is her god and her glorie in confusion of hem / &thorn;at so deuouren erthely &thorn;ynges [821] He &thorn;at is vsant to this synne of glotonye he ne may no synne withstonde he mot be in seruage to all vices / for it is the devels horde / &thorn;ere he hideth hym and resteth / [822] this synne hath many spices / &thorn;e first is dronkenesse &thorn;at is &thorn;e horrible sepulture of mannes reson / and &thorn;er|fore whan a man is drunken / he hath lost his reson / and this is dedely synne / [823] But sothly whan &thorn;at a man is nat wont / to stronge drynk / and perauenture ne knoweth nat / the strength of &thorn;e drynk / or hath feblenesse in his hede / or haue travailled &thorn;urgh which he drynketh &thorn;e more / all be he sodenly caught with drynk it is no dedely synne / but veniall/ [824] The secunde spice of glotonye is / &thorn;at &thorn;e sperit of a man / wexeth all trouble / for dronkenesse/and byreveth hym the discrescion of his witte / [825] The iij<SUP>de</SUP>. spice of Glotonye is/ whan a man devoureth his mete / and hath no maner of rightfull etyng / [826] The iiij<SUP>th</SUP> is whan thurgh &thorn;e grete habund|aunce of his mete / &thorn;e humours in his body ben dis|tempered [827] The fyfte is foryetefulnesse / by to moch drynkyng for which som tyme a man / forgeteth or &thorn;e morow what he did at even or on the nyght byfore</P>
<P>[828] In o&thorn;er maners ben distynct / &thorn;e spices of Glotonye after Seint Gregorie / &thorn;e first is for to ete by|fore tyme to ete / &thorn;e secund is whan a man gete hym to delicate mete or drynk / [829] the thirde is whan men taken to moch ouere mesure / The iiij<SUP>th</SUP> is Curiositee with grete Intent/ to make and apparaill/ his mete / The fyfthe is / for to ete to gredely [830] <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="263a">Thise ben the fyngers / of the devels Hand / by Which he draweth folk to synne /.
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000675.tif" N="653"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="660">
<HEAD>Hic tractus Gule desinit / et Remedium eiusdem Incipit/.</HEAD>
<P>[831]</P>
<P>Ayeinst Glotonye is the Remedye of Abstinence / as seith Galyen but &thorn;at hold I nat meritorye / yf he do it onely / for hele of &thorn;e body Seint Austyn woll &thorn;at Abstinence be don / for vertue / and with pacience [832] Abstinence is litle worth / but yf a man haue gode wille there-to / and but it be enforced by Pacience / and by charitee / and &thorn;at men doon it for goddes sake / and in hope to haue the blysse of heven /</P>
<P>[833] The felawes of Abstinence ben attemper|aunce &thorn;at holdeth the meynee / in all thynges / Eke Shame that escheweth all dishonestee / Suffisaunce &thorn;at seketh no riche metes ne drynkes ne doth no fors of to outrageous apparaylyng of mete / [834] Mesure also / &thorn;at restreyneth by reson &thorn;e dislaue appetite of etyng/ Sobernesse also &thorn;at restreyneth &thorn;e outrage of drynk / [835] Sparyng also / &thorn;at restreyneth &thorn;e delicate case to sitte long at his mete and softly wherfore som folk stonden of her owen will / to ete at lesse leiser ./.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic Remedium Gule desinit / &amp; tractus Luxurie Incipit</HEAD>
<P>[836]</P>
<P>After Glotonye than comth lecherie / for &thorn;ise two synnes ben so nye Cosyns / &thorn;at oft tyme &thorn;ey woll nat departe / [837] god wote &thorn;is / synne / is full displesant thyng to god / for he seid hym|self / do no lecherie / and therfore he put grete peynes / ayeinst this synne / in &thorn;e old lawe [838] yf a wom|man thrall were and taken in this synne / she shold be beten with staves to &thorn;e deth / And yf she were a gentill womman she shold be slayn with stones And yf she were a bisshoppes doughter / she shold be brent by goddes commaundement / [839] fferther-ouer by the synne of lecherie / god dreynt all the world at the 
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="654"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="661"> deliuye and after &thorn;at he brent .v. Citees / with &thorn;onder leyte / and sonke hem in-to hell/</P>
<P>[840] Now let vs speke than of &thorn;at stynkyng synne of lecherie / &thorn;at men clepen Avoutree of wedded folk/ &thorn;at is to seye / yf &thorn;at one of hem be wedded or elles both / [841] Seint Iohn seith &thorn;at Avouterers shull ben in hell in a stynk brennyng of fire / and of brymstone / in fire for her lecherie / in brymstone for &thorn;e stynk of her ordre [842] Certes &thorn;e brekyng of this sacrament / is an horrible thyng / it was made of god hym-self in Paradys / and confermed by Ihesu Crist / as witnesseth Seint Mathew in the gospell / A man shall lete fader and moder / and take him to his wyf / and they shull be two in oo flessh / [843] &thorn;is sacrament bytoken|eth the knettyng to-geder of Crist/ and of holy Chirche [844] and nat onely &thorn;at / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="263b">God forbade Aduoutre in dede / but eke he commaunded &thorn;at &thorn;ou sholdest nat coueyte thy neighbours wyf/ [845] In this Heste seith seint Austyn / is forbode all maner Couetise / to do lecherie lo what seith Seint Mathewe in &thorn;e gospell/ that who-so seeth a womman / to Couetise of his lust/ he hath don lecherie with hir in his hert / [846] Here now ye se / &thorn;at nat onely / the dede of &thorn;is synne is forboden / but eke the desire / to do &thorn;at synne / [847] This cursed synne anoyeth greuously hem / &thorn;at it haunten / and first to her soule / for he obligeth it to synne / and to peyne of deth / &thorn;at is perdurable / [848] vn-to &thorn;e body / anoyeth it greuously / for it drieth hym / and wasteth hym / and shent hym/. and of his blode he maketh sacrifice to the feend of hell/ it wasteth eke his catell/ and his substaunce/ [849] And certes yitte / yfit be a foule thyng/ a man to waste his catell on wommen / yitte / it is a fouler thyng/ whan &thorn;at for soch &thorn;yng wommen dispenden vp-on men her catell and substaunce / [850] this synne as seith the prophete byreveth man and womman / her gode fame / and all her honour / and it is full plesaunt to &thorn;e devell/ for &thorn;ere-by 
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="655"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="662"> wynneth he / &thorn;e most partie of this world [851] And right as a Merchaunt / deliteth hym moost in chaffare / &thorn;at he hath most auauntage of / right so the fende deliteth in this ordure /</P>
<P>[852] &thorn;is is that other hande of the devill with .v. fyngers to cacche the peple to his velanye / [853] The first fynger is / &thorn;e foole lokyng on the foole womman / and of &thorn;e fool man &thorn;at sleeth right as the Basilicok / sleeth folk by the venymous lokyng/ for the Couetise of yien folowen &thorn;e Covetise / of &thorn;e hert/ [854] The secund fynger is &thorn;e veleyns touchyng/ in wikked maner And therfore seith Salamon &thorn;at who-so toucheth and handleth a womman / he fareth like hym &thorn;at handleth the Scorpion / &thorn;at styngeth and sodenly sleeth &thorn;urgh his envemenyng / And who-so toucheth warme pycche / it shent his fyngers / [855] The thirde is foule wordes / &thorn;at fareth lyke fire / &thorn;at right anone brenneth &thorn;e hert/ [856] The .iiij<SUP>th</SUP> is the kissyng/ and truely he were a grete fole / &thorn;at wold kisse the mouth of a brennyng oven / or of a fourneys / [857] And more fooles ben &thorn;ey &thorn;at kissen in velanye / for &thorn;at mouth / is the mouth of hell/ And namely thise old dotardes / holours yitte woll they kisse / &thorn;ough &thorn;ey may nought do ne smater hem. [858] Certes &thorn;ey ben like to houndes / ffor an hound whan he comth by &thorn;e roser / or by other beautees / &thorn;ough he may nat pisse / yitte woll he heue vp his legge / and make a coun|tenaunce to pisse / [859] And for &thorn;at many man weneth &thorn;at he may nat synne for no likerousnesse &thorn;at he doth with his wyf / Certes &thorn;at Opynyon is fals / god wote a man may slee hym-self / with his owen knyf / and make hym self dronken of his owen ton / [860] Certes be it wyf/ be it child / or ony worldly thyng <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="264a">That he loveth byfore god / it is Mawmette / and he is an Ydolastre [861] Man shold loue his wyf by discrecion paciently and attemprely / and &thorn;an is she / as though it 
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="656"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="663"> were his suster [862] The .v<SUP>ta</SUP>. fynger of the devels hande is the stynkyng dede of lecherie [863] Certes the .v. fyngers of glotonye / &thorn;e fende put in the wombe of man / and with his .v. fyngers of lecherie /. he grypeth hym by the Reines / for to throwe hym / in-to the fourneys of hell / [864] there as &thorn;ey shull haue the fire and the wormes / &thorn;at euere shull lasten and wepyng and waylyng/ sharpe hunger and therst/ grymlynesse of devels / &thorn;at shall all to-trede hem / without respite and with|outen ende / [865] Of lecherie as I seid surden diuers spices / as fornicacion / &thorn;at is bitwene man and womman / &thorn;at ben nat maried and this is dedely synne / and ayeinst nature / [866] All &thorn;at is enemye and destruccion to nature / is ayeinst nature [867] Perfay the Reson of a man / eke telleth hym wele / &thorn;at it is dedely synne for-asmoch as god forbade lecherie / And seint Poule seith Yeveth hem the reigne / &thorn;at nys due to no wight/ but to hem &thorn;at don dedely synne / [868] Another synne of lecherie is / for to byreve a maide of hir maydenhede / for he &thorn;at so doth / Certes he casteth a maiden out of the hiest degre &thorn;at is in this present lyf/ [869] and byreveth hir &thorn;at precious fruyt/ &thorn;at the boke clepeth &thorn;e hundred-fold fruyt / I ne can sey it non otherwise in englyssh / but in latyn it hight Centesimus fructus / [870] Certes he &thorn;at so doth / is cause of many damages / and velanyes moo &thorn;an ony man can reken / Right as he som tyme is cause of all damage / &thorn;at bestes don in the fold / &thorn;at breken the hegge or the closure / &thorn;urgh which he destroyeth &thorn;at may nat be restored / [871] ffor certes no more may maydenhode be re|stored &thorn;an an arme / &thorn;at is smyten from the body may retourne ayein to wexe [872] She may haue mercy this wote I wele / yf she do Penitence / but neuer shall it be / &thorn;at she nas corrupte [873] And all be it so / &thorn;at I haue spoke som what of Auoutrie / it is gode to shewe mo perels &thorn;at longen to Auoutrie for to eschewe &thorn;at foule 
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="657"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="664"> synne [874] Auoutrie in latyn is for-to seye / Approchyng of other mannes / &thorn;urgh which thoo that whilom<SUP>*</SUP> weren oo flessh Abundaunce her bodyes to other persones<SUP>*</SUP> [875] Of this synne as seith the wise man folowen many harmes ffirst brekyng of feith/ And certes in feith / is the keye of Cristendom / [876] And whan &thorn;at feith is broken and lorn sothly Cristendom stant veyne / and without fruyt / [877] This synne is eke a theef/ for theft generally is for to reve a wight his &thorn;yng ayeinst his will/ [878] Certes &thorn;is is &thorn;e foulest theft/ &thorn;at may be / whan a womman steleth her body from hir housbond and yeveth it to hir holour / to defoule hir / and steleth hir soule from Crist/ and yeueth it to &thorn;e devill [879] This is a fouler theft/ &thorn;an for to breke a chirche / and stele the Chalice ffor thise Auoutries breken &thorn;e temple of god/ spirituelly and stelen <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="264b">The vessell of grace / &thorn;at is the body and the soule / for which Crist shall destroye hem / as seith Seint Poule / [880] Sothly of this theft douted gretely Ioseph / whan that his lordes wyf/ prayed hym / of velanye / whan he seid. Lo my lady / how my lord hath take to me / vnder my warde / all &thorn;at he hath / in this world. ne no thing of his thynges / is out of my power but onely ye / &thorn;at ben his wyf / [881] And how shold I than do this wikkednesse / and synne so horribely ayeinst god and ayeinst my lorde / god it forbede / Allas all to lite / is soch trouth now yfound. [882] The thirde harme is the filth / thurgh which &thorn;ey breken &thorn;e commaundement of god / and defoulen the Auctor of his matrimonye / &thorn;at is crist/ [883] for certes in so moch/ as the sacrament of mariage / is so noble and so digne / so moch is it grete synne for to breke it / ffor god made mariage in paradys in the state of Innocence to multiplie mankynde / to the seruyce of god / [884] and therfore is &thorn;e brekyng more greuous / of which brekyng comen fals heires oft tyme / &thorn;at wrongfully occupien folkes heritage / and therfore woll crist put 
<PB REF="00000680.tif" N="658"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="665"> hem out of the regne of heuen / &thorn;at is heritage to gode folk/ [885] Of this brekyng comth eke oft tyme / &thorn;at folk vnware wedden or synnen / with her owen kynne / and namely thoo harlottes / &thorn;at haunten bordels of &thorn;ise fool wommen /&thorn;at mowen be lykkened to a commune gonge / where as men purgen her ordure / [886] what sey we eke of Putours / &thorn;at lyven by &thorn;e horrible synne of Puterie / and constreyne wommen / to yeld hem a certein rent/ of her bodely Puterye / ye somtyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>MS. repeats</I> of his bodely puterye / ye som tyme]</NOTE> of his owen wyf / or his child / as don thise baudes / Certes thise ben cursed synnes / [887] vnderstonde eke / &thorn;at auoutrie is sette in the .X. commaundementes / bitwene theft and man|slaughter / for it is the grettest theft &thorn;at may be / for it is theft of body and soule [888] and it is like homicide for it kerveth a two / and breketh a twoo / hem that first were maked oo flessh / And &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e old lawe of god they shold be slayn with stones / [889] Butnatheles by &thorn;e lawe of Ihesu Crist / &thorn;at is lawe of pitee / whan he seid to the womman / &thorn;at was founde in auoutrie / and shold haue be slayn / with stones / after the will of the Iewes / as was her lawe / Go koth Ihesu Crist / and haue no more will to synne / or will no more to do synne / [890] Sothly the vengeaunce of Auoutrie is awarded to the peynes of hell/ but yf it be distourbed by Penitence [891] yitte ben there mo spices of this cursed synne / as whan &thorn;at oon [of] hem is religious / or elles both/ or of folk &thorn;at ben entred in-to ordre / as subdeken or preest/ or hospitilers / And euere the hier &thorn;at he is in ordre the gretter is the synne [892] The thynges &thorn;at gretely aggreggen her synne is the brekyng of her avow / of chastitee / whan he hath resceyued &thorn;e ordre / [893] And ferther-ouer soth it is / &thorn;at holy ordre / is chief / of all tresorie / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="265a">Of god / and his especiall signe / and mark of chastitee / to shewe &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben ioyned to chastitee which &thorn;at is most precious lyf &thorn;at is / [894] And &thorn;ise ordred folk / ben specially titled to god / and of the 
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="659"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="666"> speciall meynee of god / for which whan &thorn;ey don dedely synne / &thorn;ey ben especiall traytours of god / and of his peple / for &thorn;ey lyuen of the peple / to praye for the peple / and while &thorn;ey ben soch traytours / her prayer avayleth nat to the peple [895] Prestes ben Aungels / as by the dignitee / of her misterie / But forsoth seint Poule / seith &thorn;at Sathanas transfourmeth / hym in Aungell of light/ [896] sothly the preest &thorn;at haunteth dedely synne / he may be lykkened to the Aungell of derknesse / transfourmed the Aungell of light/ he semeth Aungell of light / but forsoth he is Aungell of derknesse / [897] Soch prestes ben the son of Belie / as sheweth in the boke of kynges / &thorn;at they weren the sonnes of Beliall/ &thorn;at is the devill / [898] Beliall is to sey without Iuge / and so faren they hem &thorn;ynken &thorn;ey ben free / and han no Iuge / no more &thorn;an hath a free Bole / &thorn;at taketh soch a Cow / as hym liketh in the toun / [899] So faren &thorn;ey by wommen / for right as a free Bole / is ynough for all a toun / Right so is a wikked prest/ corrupcion ynough for all a paryssh / or for all a cuntree [900] Thise prestes as seith the boke ne kon nat &thorn;e misterie of presthode / shewe to &thorn;e peple ne god &thorn;ey knowe nat / &thorn;ey hold hem nat appayed as seith &thorn;e boke of soch flessh &thorn;at was to hem offred / but they toke by force &thorn;e flessh &thorn;at is rawe / [901] certes so thise old shrewes ne hold hem nat appayed of rosted flessh/ and sode flessh with which the peple feden hem / in grete reuerence but &thorn;ey woll haue rawe flessh of folkes wyfes / and her doughters [902] And certes thise wommen &thorn;at consenten to her harlotrye / don grete wrong to Crist/ and to holy chirche / and all halowes / and to all soules / for &thorn;ey byreve hym / all &thorn;ise &thorn;at shold worshippe Crist/ and holy chirche / and praye for Cristen soules / [903] And &thorn;erfore han soch prestes and her lemmans eke / &thorn;at consenten to her lecherie / &thorn;e malison of all Cristen court/ till &thorn;ey com to amendement/ 
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="660"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="667"> [904] The thirde spice of Auoutrie is somtyme bitwene a man and his wyf / and &thorn;at is whan &thorn;ey make no rewarde in her assemblyng/ but onely to her flesshly delite as seith Seint Ierom [905] and rekken nat/ of no thyng/ but &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben assembled / by cause / &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben maried/ all is gode ynough &thorn;ynketh to hem / [906] but in soch folk / hath &thorn;e devill power / As seid &thorn;e Aungell Raphael to Thobye / for in her assemblyng / &thorn;ey putten Ihesu Crist out of her hert/ and yeven hem self to all ordure / [907] The .iiij<SUP>th</SUP> spice is / &thorn;e assemble of hem &thorn;at ben of her kynrede / or of hem &thorn;at ben of one affinitee / or elles with hem / with which her faders / or her kynrede han deled in the synne of lecherie / This synne maketh hem like to houndes / &thorn;at taken no kepe to kynrede [908] and certes parentele is in <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="265b">Two maners either gostely or flesshly / gostely as for to delen with her gossibbes / [909] for right so as he &thorn;at engendreth a child is his flesshly fader right so is his godfader his espirituell/ for which a womman / may in no lesse synne / assemble with her gossipe / &thorn;an with hir owen flesshly bro&thorn;ere [910] The v<SUP>te</SUP> spice / is &thorn;at habhominable synne / of which &thorn;at no man vnneth ought speke ne write / Natheles it is openly reherced in holy writte / [911] this cursednesse doon men and wommen in diuers intent / and in diuers maner / But &thorn;ough &thorn;at holy writte speke of horrible synne / certes holy writte / may nat be defouled no more &thorn;an &thorn;e son &thorn;at shyneth on &thorn;e myxene / [912] Another synne / apperteneth to lecherie / &thorn;at comth in slepyng and &thorn;is synne comth oft to hem &thorn;at ben maydens / and eke to hem &thorn;at ben corrupte / and this synne men clepen Polucion / &thorn;at comth in .iij. maners / [913] som tyme of langwysshyng of body / for the humours ben to rank/ and to habundant in &thorn;e body of man / Som tyme for Infirmitee / for the feblenesse of &thorn;e vertue retentyf/ as phisik maketh mension Somtyme for surfet / of mete and drynk / [914] and somtyme of 
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="661"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="668"> veleyns &thorn;oughtes / that ben enclosed in mannes mynd / whan he goth to slepe / which may nat be without synne ffor which men most kepe hem wisely / or elles mow men synne full greuously. /</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hic tractus Luxurie desinit &amp; Remedium eiusdem Hic Incipit ./.</HEAD>
<P>[915]</P>
<P>Now comth the Remedie ayeinst lecherie / and &thorn;at is generally Chastite and continence / &thorn;at re|streyneth all &thorn;e disordeyne mevynges &thorn;at commen of flesshly talentes [916] and euer the gretter merite shall he haue / &thorn;at moste restreyneth the wykked chauf|ynges or ordure of this synne / and this is in two maners / &thorn;at is to sey Chastitee of mariage and chastitee of wydowhode [917] Now shalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde / &thorn;at matrimonye is leefull assemblyng of man / and of womman / &thorn;at resceyuen by vertue of the sacrament/ &thorn;e bonde &thorn;urgh which &thorn;ey mow nat be departed / in all her lyf / &thorn;at is to sey / while &thorn;at they lyven / both/ [918] &thorn;ys as seith the boke / is a full grete sacrament/ god made it in Paradys as I haue seid byfore / and wold hym self/be born in mariage / [919] And for to halowen mariage / he was at a weddyng / where as He turned water in-to wyne / which was &thorn;e first myracle / &thorn;at he wrought in erthe byfore his disciples / [920] Trewe effecte of mariage clenseth ffornicacion / and replenyssheth / holy chirche / of gode lynage for &thorn;at is the ende of mariage / and it chaungeth dedely synne in-to veniall synne / bitwene hem / &thorn;at ben ywedded / and maketh &thorn;e hertes all one of hem &thorn;at ben wedded / as wele as the bodies / [921] &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="266a">Is Verray mariage / that was establysshed by god / or that synne bygan whan naturell lawe was / in his right poynt in Paradys/ and it was ordeyned &thorn;at no man shold have but oo womman / and oo womman but oo man / As seith Seint Austyn by many resons /</P>
<P>[922] ffirst for mariage is first figured bitwene Crist and 
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="662"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="669"> holy chirche / And &thorn;at o&thorn;er is for a man is hede of a womman / all-gate by ordynaunce it shoold be soo / [923] for yf a womman hade mo men &thorn;an oon / &thorn;an shold she haue mo hedes &thorn;an oon / and &thorn;at were an horrible thyng byfore god / and eke a womman ne myght nat plese to many folk at ones / And also &thorn;ere ne shold neuer be pees ne rest amonges hem / for euerycch wold axe his owen thyng / [924] And ferther-ouere / no man ne shold knowe / his owen en|gendrure / ne who shold haue his heritage / and &thorn;e womman shold be the lesse beloved from &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at she were conioynte to many men /</P>
<P>[925] Now comth how &thorn;at a man shold bere him with his wyf / and namely in two thynges / &thorn;at is to seye in suffraunce / and reuerence as shewed Crist / whan he made first womman [926] for he ne made hir nat / of the heved of Adam / for she shold nat clayme to grete lordshipe / [927] for there as &thorn;e womman hath the maistrie / she maketh to moch disraye There neden noon ensaumples / of this / &thorn;e experience of day by day ought suffice / [928] Also certes god ne made nat/ womman of the fote of Adam / for she ne shold nat be holden to lowe / for she can nat paciently suffre / But god made womman of the ribbe of Adam / for womman shold be felawe vn-to man / [929] Man shold bere hym to his wyf/ in feith in trouth / and in love / as seith Seint Poule / &thorn;at a man shold love his wyf / as crist loved holy chirche / he loved it so wele / &thorn;at he dyed for it / so shold a man for his wyf / yf it were nede /</P>
<P>[930] Now how &thorn;at a womman shold be subgette to hir housbond &thorn;at telleth Seint Petir / in obedi|ence / [931] and eke as seith &thorn;e decree / A womman &thorn;at is wyf / as long as she is a wyf / she hath noon auctoritee to swere ne to bere witnesse / without leve of hir housbond / &thorn;at is hir lorde allgate he shold be soo by reson / [932] She shold eke serue hym in all 
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="663"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="670"> honestee and ben attempre of hir array / I wote wele / &thorn;ey shold sette her intentes to plese her hous|bondes / but nat by her qweyntise of arraye [933] Seint Ierom seith / &thorn;at wyfes &thorn;at ben apparayled in silk/ and in precious purpure / ne mow nat clothen hem in Ihesu Crist / loke what seith Seint Iohn eke in this mater [934] Seint Gregorie eke seith / &thorn;at no wight seketh precious array / but onely for vayneglorie to ben honoured the more byfore the peple / [935] it is a grete folie / a womman to haue a faire array outward / and in hir self foule inward [936] A wyf shold eke be mesurable in lokyng/ and in beryng/ and in laughyng/ and discrete in all her wordes and hir dedes / [937] and aboue all worldly thyng she <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="266b">Shold loue Hir housbond with all hir hert/ and to hym to be true of hir body [938] so shold an housbond eke be to his wyf/ for seth &thorn;at all the bodye is &thorn;e housbondes so shold hir hert ben / or elles &thorn;ere is bitwene hem two / as in &thorn;at no perfite mariage / [939] Than shull men vnder|stonde / &thorn;at for thre thynges/ A man and his wyf / flesshly mowen assemble / The first is in intent/ of engen|drure of children to the seruice of god / ffor certes &thorn;at is &thorn;e cause fynall of matrimonye / [940] Another cause is to yelden euerycch of hem to other / &thorn;e dette of his body / for neither of hem / hath power of his owen body The .iij.<SUP>de</SUP> is to eschewe lecherie and velanye The iiij<SUP>th</SUP> is forsoth dedely synne [941] As to &thorn;e first/ it is meritorie / the secunde also / for as seith the decree / &thorn;at he hath merite of chastitee / &thorn;at yeldeth to her housbond &thorn;e dette of hir body / ye &thorn;ough it be ayeinst hir likyng and &thorn;e lust of hir hert/ [942] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> And truely scarsly may ony of thise be / without veniall synne for &thorn;e corrupcon and for the delite [943] The .iiij.<SUP>th</SUP> maner is for to vnderstonde / as is they assemblen onely for amerous love / and for none of &thorn;e forseid causes / but 
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="664"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="671"> for to complyssh &thorn;ylk brennyng delite / &thorn;ey rek neuer how oft/ sothly it is dedely synne / and yitte with sorow / som folk woll peyne hem more to do / &thorn;an to her appetite suffiseth /</P>
<P>[944] The secunde maner of Chastitee / is for to ben a cleen wydow / and eschewe thembrasynges of man / and desiren thembrasyng of Ihesu Crist / [945] &thorn;ise ben thoo / &thorn;at haan been wyfes and han forgoon her hous|bondes / and eke wommen &thorn;at haan doon lecherie / and ben releved by Penitence / [946] And certes yf &thorn;at a wyf coude kepe hir all chaast / by licence of hir housbond / so &thorn;at she yave neuer occasion / &thorn;at he agilt/ it were to hir a grete meryte/ [947] Thise manere wommen &thorn;at obseruen chastitee / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> in clothyng and countenaunce / Abstinent in etyng and drynkyng/ in spekyng and in dede And &thorn;an is she &thorn;e vessell or the booyst/ of the blissed magdalene / &thorn;at fulfilleth holy chirche full of gode odour [948] The thirde maner of chastitee / is virginitee / and hit byhoueth &thorn;at she be holy in hert/ and clene of body / &thorn;an is shee spouse to Ihesu Crist/ and she is &thorn;e lyf of Aungels / [949] she is &thorn;e preysyng of this world. and she is as thise martirs / in egalitee / she hath in hir &thorn;at tung may nat tell/ [950] virginite bare our lord Ihesu Crist/ and virgyn was hym-self /</P>
<P>[951] Another Remedye ayeinst lecherie is specially to withdrawe soch thynges / as yeven occasion to thilk veulanye as ese / etyng/ and drynkyng/ for certes whan &thorn;e pot boyleth strongly / the best remedye is to with|drawe &thorn;e fire [952] Slepyng long in grete quyete is eke a grete Norice to lecherie /</P>
<P>[953] Another remedye is ayeinst lecherie &thorn;at a man or a womman eschewe the companye of hem / by which he douteth to be tempted / for all be it so / &thorn;at &thorn;e dede be withstonden yitte is &thorn;ere grete temptacon / 
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="665"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="672"> [954] Sothly a white wall/ all-&thorn;ough it <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="267a">Ne wenne nat fully / by stikkyng of a candell/ yitte is &thorn;e wall blak of the leyte / [955] full oft tyme / I rede &thorn;at no man trust in his owen perfeccion but he be strenger &thorn;an Sampson / or holyer than David and wiser than Salamon /</P>
<P>[956] Now after &thorn;at I haue declared yow as I can / the vij. dedely synnes / and som of her braunches / and her remedyes Sothly yf I coude I wold tell you / &thorn;e .x. commaundementes [957] but so hie a doctryne I lete to dyvynes / Natheles I hope to god / &thorn;ey ben touched in this tretyce euerycch of hem all/.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Hi[c] Sequitur secunda pars Penitence. /:</HEAD>
<P>[958]</P>
<P>Now for asmoch / as the secunde partie of Penitence stant in confession of mouth / as I began in the Chapitre I sey Seint Austyn seith [959] Synne is euery worde and euery dede and all &thorn;at men coveiten / ayeinst &thorn;e lawe of Ihesu Crist / And &thorn;is is for to synne / in hert in mouth and in dede by the .v. wittes / &thorn;at ben/ sight/ heryng/ smellyng tastyng or savouryng/ and felyng/ [960] Now it is gode to vnderstonde &thorn;at / &thorn;at agreggen mochell euery synne / [961] &thorn;ou shalt consider what &thorn;ou art/ &thorn;at doost the synne / whether &thorn;ou be male or female yong or olde / gentill or thrall/ free or seruaunt / hoole or sike / wedded or sengle ordred or vnordred wise or fooll/ Clerk or seculer [962] yf she be of thy kynrede / bodely or gostely or noo / yf ony of thy kynrede haue synned with hir or noon / and many thynges /</P>
<P>[963] That other circumstaunce is this whe&thorn;er it be doon in fornycacion or in auoutrie or noon / incest / or noon Mayde or noon / in maner of homicide or noon / horrible grete synnes or smale and how long &thorn;ou haast contynued in synne / [964] The thirde circumstaunce is the place where &thorn;ou haast done synne / whether in other 
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="666"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="673"> mennes houses or in thyn owen / in feeld or in chirche / or in chirche hawe / in chirche dedicat/ or noon / [965] for yf the chirche be halowed / and man or womman spilt his kynde within &thorn;at place by weye of synne or by wikked temptacion &thorn;e chirche is entredyted / . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [966] and yf he were a preeet / &thorn;at did soch a velanye / to terme of all his lyf / he shold no more synge masse / and yf he did / he shold do dedely synne / at euery tyme &thorn;at he song masse / [967] The .iiij<SUP>th</SUP> circumstaunce is / by soch media|tours / as by messagers / as for enticement/ or for consentment/ to bere companye with felaushipe / ffor many a wrecche for to bere companye / woll goo to the devill of hell / [968] for &thorn;ey &thorn;at eggen or con|senten to the synne / ben partiners of the synne / and of &thorn;e dampnacion of the synner</P>
<P>[969] The .v<SUP>te</SUP>. . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> is / how many tymes / &thorn;at he hath synned. yf it be in his mynde / and how oft &thorn;at he hath fall / [970] for he &thorn;at ofte falleth in synne / he despiseth the mercy of god / and encreceth his synne / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="267b">And is vnkynde to Crist/ and he wexeth the more feble to withstonde synne and synneth the more lightly / [971] and the latter ariseth / and is the more eschewe for to shryve hym / and namely to hym &thorn;at is his Con|fessour [972] ffor which &thorn;at folk/ whan they fall ayein / in her old folies / eyther &thorn;ey forleten her old Confessours all vttrely / or elles they departen her shryft / in diuers places But sothly soch departed shryft/ deserueth no mercy of god / of his synnes / [973] The sexte circum|staunce is / why / &thorn;at a man synneth / as by temptacion / and hymself procure thilk temptacion / or by the ex|cityng of other folk / or yf he synne with a womman / by force / or by hir owen assent / [974] or yf &thorn;e womman maugre hir hede hath be aforced or noon / this shall she tell / for couetise or for pouertee / and yf it was hir procuryng or noon / and soch manere 
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="667"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="674"> harneys [975] The .vij<SUP>th</SUP>. Circumstaunce is in what maner he hath doon his synne / or how &thorn;at she hath suffred &thorn;at folk han doon to hir / [976] and &thorn;e same shall man tell pleinly all circumstaunces / and whether he hath synned with commune bordell wommen or noon / [977] or doon his synne in holy tymes or noon / In fast|yng tyme or noon / or byfore his shryft/ or after his latter shryft/ [978] and hath perauenture broken therfore his penaunce enioyned by whoos help / and whoos counseill/ by sorcerie or Craft/ all most be tolde / [979] all thise thynges / after &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben grete or smale / engreggen the conscience of man / And eke the preest/ &thorn;at is thy Iuge may &thorn;e better ben avised of his Iugement/ in yevyng of &thorn;y penaunce / and &thorn;at is after thy contricion [980] ffor vnderstonde wele &thorn;at after the tyme &thorn;at a man hath defouled his baptisme / by synne / yf he woll com to savacion / &thorn;ere is noon other weye / but by Penitence and shrift/ and by satisfaccion / [981] and namely by the two / yf there be a Confessour to which he may shryue hym / and &thorn;e thirde / yf he may lyve to perfourme it /</P>
<P>[982] &thorn;an shull men loke and consider / &thorn;at yf he woll make a trewe and a profitable confession / &thorn;ere most be .iiij. condicions [983] ffirst it mot bee in sorowfull bitternesse / of hert/ as seid the kyng Ezechiell / to god / I woll/ remembre me all the yeres of my lyf / in bytternesse of myn hert / [984] &thorn;is condicion of bitter|nesse hath .v. signes / &thorn;e first is &thorn;at confession most be shamefast/ nat for to keuer ne hide his synne but for he hath agylt his god / and defouled his soule / [985] And here-of Seith Seint Austyn &thorn;e hert trauaileth / for shame of his synne and for he hath a grete shamefastnesse he is digne to haue grete mercy of god / [986] soch was &thorn;e confession of the Publican / &thorn;at wold nat heve vp his yien to heven / for he hade offended god of heven / ffor which shamefastnesse / he hade anoon / the mercy of god / [987] And &thorn;erfore seith 
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="668"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="675"> Seint Austyn / &thorn;at soch shamefast folk / be next foryevenesse and remission / [988] That other signe is humilitee / of Confession of which <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="268a">Seith Seint Petir / humbleth you vnder &thorn;e myght of god / &thorn;e hond of god is myghty in confession / for there-by god foryeveth &thorn;e &thorn;y synnes / for he allone hath the power / [989] and this humilitee shall ben in hert/ . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> right so shold he humble his body outward to the preest/ &thorn;at sitteth in goddes place / [990] for which in no maner seth &thorn;at Crist is soueraigne / and &thorn;e preest mene and mediatour / bi|twene Crist and &thorn;e synner it is &thorn;e last by weye of reson / [991] &thorn;an shold nat &thorn;e synner sitte as hie as his confessour / but knele byfore hym / or at his fete / but yf maladye destourbed it/ for he shall nat take kepe whoo sitte &thorn;ere / but in whoos place &thorn;at he sitteth/ [992] A man &thorn;at hath trespaced to a lorde / and cam for to axe mercy / and maken his accorde / and he sette hym doun anoon by the lord men wold hold hym outrageous / and nat worthy so sone for to haue remission / ne mercy / [993] The thirde signe is / &thorn;at &thorn;e shrift shold be full of teres / yf men myght/and yf &thorn;ey mow nat wepe with her bodely yien/ let hem wepe in hert/ [994] Soch was &thorn;e confession of Seint Petir / for after &thorn;at he hadde forsake Ihesu Crist/ he went out and wept full bitterly [995] The .iiij<SUP>th</SUP>. signe is / &thorn;at he ne lette nat for his shame to shewe his confession [996] soch was &thorn;e confession of &thorn;e magdalene &thorn;at ne spared for no shame of hem / &thorn;at weren at &thorn;e feest/ for to goo to our lord Ihesu Crist/ and byknowe to hym hir synne. [997] The .v<SUP>te</SUP>. signe is &thorn;at a man or womman / be obeysant/ to resceyue the penaunce / &thorn;at hym is enioyned. for certes Ihesu Crist / for &thorn;e gilt of oo man / was obedient to the deth</P>
<P>[998] The secunde condicion of verray confession is &thorn;at it be hastely doon / for certes yf a man hade a dedely wound euer &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at he tarieth to warissh 
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="669"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="676"> hym-self/ &thorn;e more wold it corrupte / and haste hym to his deth / and eke &thorn;e wound wold be &thorn;e wors for to hele / [999] and right so fareth synne &thorn;at long tyme is in a man vnshewed. [1000] Certes a man ought hastely shewe his synnes for many causes / as for drede of deth / &thorn;at comth oft sodenly and at no certeyn / what tyme it shall / be / ne in what place and eke &thorn;e drecchyng of oo synne draweth in another / [1001] and eke &thorn;e lenger &thorn;at he tarieth &thorn;e ferther he is from Crist/ And yf he abide till his last daye / scarsly may he shryve hym / or re|membre hym of his synnes / or repente for &thorn;e greuous maladye / of his deth [1002] And for-asmoch as he ne hath nat in his lyf herkened Ihesu Crist/ whan he hath spoken / he shall crye to Ihesu Crist at his last day / and scarsly woll he herken hym / [1003] And vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;is condicion most have .iiij. thynges / thy shryft most be purveid byfore / <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="268b">And avised for wikked haast do no perfite / and &thorn;at a man kon shryve hym of his synnes / be it of Pride or of Envye / and so forth with &thorn;e spices and &thorn;e circumstaunces/[1004] and &thorn;at he haue comprehended in his mynde / &thorn;e nombre and &thorn;e gretnesse of his synne / and how long &thorn;at he hath/ lyen in synne / [1005] and eke &thorn;at he be contrite of his synnes / and in stedfast purpose / by &thorn;e grace of god / neuere eft to fall in synne / and eke &thorn;at he drede and countre-waite hym-self &thorn;at he flee the occasions of synne / to which he is enclyned / [1006] Also &thorn;ou shalt shryve the of all thy synnes / to oo man / and nat a parcell to oo man / and a parcell to ano&thorn;ere &thorn;at is to vnderstonde / in entent to departe thy confession / and for shame or drede / for it nys nat but stranglyng of &thorn;y soule / [1007] for certes Ihesu Crist is entierly all gode / in hym is noon inperfeccion and &thorn;erfore he foryeueth all perfitely / or neuer a dele / [1008] I sey nat &thorn;at yf &thorn;ou be assigned to &thorn;y penytauncer / for certein synne / &thorn;at &thorn;ou art bound to shewe hym / all &thorn;e remenaunt of thy synnes of which 
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="670"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="677"> &thorn;ou hast ben shryven of thy curate / but yf it like the of thyn humilitee / &thorn;is is no departyng of shrift / [1009] ne I ne sey nat/ &thorn;ere as I speke of diuision / of confes|sion / &thorn;at yf &thorn;ou haue licence for to shryve the to a discrete and an honest preest/ where the liketh / and by licence eke of thy curate / &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne maist wele shryve the to hym / of all thy synnes / [1010] but let no blotte be behynde / let no synne be vntold as fer as &thorn;ou haast remem|braunce / [1011] And whan &thorn;ou shalt be shryven to &thorn;y curate / tell hym eke all thy synne / &thorn;at &thorn;ou haast doon / sen &thorn;ou were last yshryven / this is no wikked intent of diuision of shryft/</P>
<P>[1012] Also &thorn;e verray shryft/ axeth certeins con|dicions / ffirst &thorn;at &thorn;ou shryve the by thy free will / nat constreyned ne for shame of folk/ ne for maladye / ne soch thynges / for it is reson &thorn;at he that trespasseth / by his free will / he most by his free will confesse his trespace / [1013] noon other man shall tell / his synne / but he hym-self / ne he shall nay it / or denye his synne ne wratth hym ayeinst the preest/ for his ammonestyng to lete synne [1014] The secunde condicion is &thorn;at thy shryft be lawe-full &thorn;at is to sey / &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;at shryvest the / and eke the preest &thorn;at hereth thy confession be verrely In the feith of holy chirche [1015] and &thorn;at a man ne be nat dispeired of &thorn;e mercy of Ihesu Crist/ as Cayme or Iudas / [1016] and eke a man mot accuse hym-self of his owen trespace / and nat another but he shall blame and wite hym-self / and his owen malice of his synne and noon other / [1017] But natheles / yf &thorn;at another be occasion of his synne or the state of a persone be soch &thorn;urgh which he hath synned and &thorn;at his synne is agregged or els &thorn;at he may nat pleinly shryve hym / but he tell &thorn;e persone with which he hath synned / &thorn;an may he tell it [1018] so / &thorn;at his intent be nat to bakbite the persone but onely to declare his con|fession /
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="671"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="678"></P>
<P>[1019] &thorn;ou ne shalt nat eke make no lesynges / in thy <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="269a">Confession / for humilitee perauenture to seye / &thorn;at &thorn;ou haast do synnes / of which &thorn;ou were neuer gilty [1020] ffor seint Austyn seith yf &thorn;ou by cause of humylitee makest lesynges / on thy self/ &thorn;ough &thorn;ou ne were nat in synne byfore yitte art &thorn;ou in synne / &thorn;urgh &thorn;y lesynges / [1021] &thorn;ou most eke shewe thy synne / by thyn owen propre mouth / but &thorn;ou be woxe doumbe / and nat by no lettre / for &thorn;ou &thorn;at hast doon &thorn;e synne / &thorn;ou shalt haue the shame / [1022] Thow shalt nat eke paynt thy confession / by faire subtile wordes / to kouere &thorn;e more thy synne for &thorn;an begilest &thorn;ou &thorn;y-self / and nat &thorn;e preest/ &thorn;ou most tell it platly / be it neuer so foule / ne so horrible / [1023] &thorn;ou shalt eke shryve the to a preest/ &thorn;at is discrete to counceill the / and eke &thorn;ou shalt nat shryve the for vaynglorie ne for Ypocrisie / ne for no cause / but onely for the doute of Ihesu Crist / and the hele of thy soule / [1024] thow shalt nat eke renne to the preest sodenlye / to tell hym lightly thy synne / And who-so telleth a Iape or a tale but avisely and with grete deuocion / [1025] and generally shryve the oft / yf &thorn;ou oft falle / oft yf &thorn;ou arise by confession / [1026] and &thorn;ough &thorn;ou shryve &thorn;e ofter &thorn;an ones of syn of which &thorn;ow hast be shryven it is the more merite And as seith Seint Austyn / &thorn;ou shalt haue the more lightly releesyng / and grace of god both of synne and of peyne / [1027] and certes ones a yere / at &thorn;e leste weye / it is lawefull / for to be housled for sothly all thynges ones a yere renovellen /</P>
<P>[1028] Now have I told of verrey confession / &thorn;at is &thorn;e secunde partie of Penitence /<NOTE PLACE="inter">[no break in the MS.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="672"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="679"></P>
<P>[1029] The thirde partie of penitence is Satisfaccion and &thorn;at stant most generally in almesse / and in bodely peyne / [1030] Now ben there thre maner of Almesse Contricion of hert/ where a man offreth hym-self to god / Another is / to haue pitee of the defaute of his neighbours The thirde is in yevyng gode counceill / both gostely and bodely / where men han nede / and namely in sustenaunce of mannes fode / [1031] And take &thorn;at a man &thorn;at he hath nede of / Of thise thynges generally he hath nede / of fode he hath nede / clothyng and herborow / he hath nede of charitable counseill / and visityng in prison and maladye / and sepulture of his dede bodye / [1032] And yf &thorn;ou maist nat visite the nedefull / with thy persone visite hym by thy message / and thy yiftes / [1033] Thise ben generall almesses or werkes of charitee of hem that ben riche in temperall richesse / or discrecion in counseillyng of thise werkes shalt &thorn;ou heren / at the daye of dome /</P>
<P>[1034] Thise almesses shalt &thorn;ou doo of thyn owen propre thynges / and hastely and priuely yf &thorn;ou maist/ [1035] But natheles yf &thorn;ou maist nat do priuely &thorn;ou shalt nat forbere to do almesse / &thorn;ough men se it/ so &thorn;at it be nat doon for thank of the world but onely for thank of Ihesu Crist/ [1036] for witnesseth Seint Mathew capitulo 5<SUP>o</SUP> A citee may nat be hide / &thorn;at is sette on a mountayne / Ne men light nat a lanterne and put it vnder a busshell but men sette it on a Candel|stykke / to light the men in &thorn;e hous / [1037] <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="269b">Ryght so shall your light / lyghten byfore men / &thorn;at &thorn;ey mow see your gode werkes / and glorifye your fader &thorn;at is in heven</P>
<P>[1038] Now as to speke of bodely peyne / it stant in prayers in wakynges in fastynges in vertuous 
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="673"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="680"> techynges or orisons / [1039] ye shull vnderstonde / &thorn;at orisons or prayers / is for to seye / a pitous will of hert/ &thorn;at redresseth it in god / and expresseth it by worde outwarde to remeve harmes / and to haue thynges espirituell and durable / and somtyme temperell thynges / of which orisons / certes in the Orison of the <U>Pater noster</U> hath Ihesu Crist enclosed most thynges [1040] Certes privyleged it is of the thynges in his dignytee / for which it is more digne than ony prayer / for &thorn;at Ihesu Crist hym self made it/ [1041] and it is short/ for it shold be couthe more lightly / and for to withholde it/ more esely in hert/ and help hym self &thorn;e ofter with the orison / [1042] and for a man shold be &thorn;e lasse werie to seye it / and for a man / may nat excuse hym to lerne it/ it is so short / and so esy / and for it comprehendeth in it self all gode prayers [1043] The exposicion of this holy prayer / &thorn;at is so excellent and digne I betake to the maisters of Theologie / save &thorn;us moch woll I sey / &thorn;at whan &thorn;ou prayest / &thorn;at god shold foryeve the thy giltes / as &thorn;ou foryeuest/ hem &thorn;at agylten to the / be full wele ware / &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne be nat out of charitee / [1044] This holy orison amenuseth eke veniall synne / and &thorn;erfore it apperteneth specially to Penitence /</P>
<P>[1045] this prayer most be truely seid and in verrey feith and &thorn;at men praye to god ordinatelye and dis|cretely and deuoutly / and all-weye a man shall putte his wille to be subgette to &thorn;e will of god. [1046] this orison most eke be seide with grete humblesse and full pure honestly and nat to the anoysaunce of ony man or womman / it most eke be contynued with the werkes of charitee / [1047] it auayleth / ayeinst &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e soule ffor as seith Seint Ierom by fastyng ben salved &thorn;e vices of &thorn;e flessh and by prayer / the vices of the soule</P>
<P>[1048] After this &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde / &thorn;at bodely peyne stant in wakyng for Ihesu Crist seith waketh and prayeth/ &thorn;at ye ne entre in wykked 
<PB REF="00000696.tif" N="674"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="681"> temptacion / [1049] ye shull vnderstond &thorn;at fast|yng stant also in thre thynges / in forberyng of bodely mete and drynk and in forberyng of worldly iolitee / and in for|beryng of dedely synne / &thorn;is is to sey &thorn;at a man shall kepe hym from dedely synne with all his myght /</P>
<P>[1050] And &thorn;ou shalt vnderstonde eke / &thorn;at god ordeyned fastynges / and to fastyng appertenen iiij. thynges / [1051] largenesse to poure folk / gladnesse of hert spirituell/ nat to be angrye ne anoyed ne grucche for he fasteth and also resonable houre for to ete by mesure / &thorn;at is for to seye / a man shold nat ete in vntyme / ne sitte the lenger at his table to ete for he fasteth</P>
<P>[1052] Than shall &thorn;ou vnderstonde / &thorn;at bodely peyne stant in disciplyne or techyng by worde or by writyng or in ensaumple also in weryng of heires or of stamyn or of habergeons on her naked flessh<MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="270a">ffor Cristes sake / and soch manere of penaunces [1053] But ware &thorn;e wele &thorn;at soch maner penaunces / on thy flessh ne make nat thyn hert bitter or angrye / or anoyed of thy self / for better is to cast awey &thorn;yn heire &thorn;an for to cast aweye<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>MS. repeats</I> the heire &thorn;an for to cast awaye, <I>but draws a line under it</I>.]</NOTE> the swet|nesse of Ihesu Crist [1054] And therfore seith Seint Poule / Clothe yow as &thorn;ey &thorn;at ben chosen of god / in hert of misericorde / debonairtee suffraunce / and soch maner of clothyng of which Ihesu Crist is most appayed &thorn;an of his heyres or habergeons or hawberkes /</P>
<P>[1055] Than is disciplyne eke in knokkyng of &thorn;y brest/ in scourgyng with yerdes / in knelynges in tribulacions / [1056] in suffryng paciently wronges / &thorn;at ben don to hym / and eke in pacient suffraunce of maladyes / or lesyng of worldly catell/ or of wyf / or of child / or other frendes /</P>
<P>[1057] Than shalt &thorn;ou vnderstonde which &thorn;ynges destourben penaunce and &thorn;is is in .iiij. maners / &thorn;at is drede shame hope and wanhope / &thorn;at is desperacion [1058] And for to speke first of drede for which he 
<PB REF="00000697.tif" N="675"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="682"> weneth &thorn;at he may suffre no penaunce / [1059] there|ayeinst is remedye / for to thynk &thorn;at bodely penaunce is but shorte and litle / at regarde of &thorn;e peyne of hell/ &thorn;at is cruell and so long / &thorn;at it lasteth withouten ende /</P>
<P>[1060] Now ayeinst the Shame / &thorn;at a man hath to shryve hym / and namely thise Ypocrites &thorn;at wold be holden so perfite / &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue no nede to shryve hem [1061] ayeinst/ &thorn;at shame shold a man &thorn;ynk &thorn;at by weye of reson &thorn;at he &thorn;at hath nat ben a-shamed to do foule thynges Certes hym ought nat be ashamed to do faire thynges and &thorn;at is confessions / [1062] A man shold eke thynk / &thorn;at god seeth and woteth all thing &thorn;y thoughtes and all thy werkes / to hym may no thing be hidde / ne covered [1063] Men shold eke remembre hem of &thorn;e shame &thorn;at is to com / at &thorn;e day of dome to hem &thorn;at ne be nat penitent and shryven in this present lyf [1064] ffor all &thorn;e creatures in erthe and in hell shull seen appertely all &thorn;at he hideth in this world</P>
<P>[1065] Now for to speke of &thorn;e hope of hem / &thorn;at ben necligent/ and slowe to shryve hem / it stant in two maners [1066] &thorn;at one is / &thorn;at he hopeth/ for to lyve long/ and for to purchace moch ricchesse for his delite / and &thorn;an he woll shryue hym and as he seith/ he may as hym semeth &thorn;an tymely ynough / com to shryft/ [1067] Another is of Surquydrie &thorn;at he hath in cristes mercy / [1068] ayeinst &thorn;e first vice he shall thynk &thorn;at our lyf is in no sekirnesse / and eke &thorn;at all ther richesse in &thorn;is world ben in auenture / and passen as a shadow on a wall / [1069] And as seith Seint Gregorie / &thorn;at it apperteneth to &thorn;e rightwosnesse of god / &thorn;at neuer shall &thorn;e peyne stynt of hem &thorn;at neuer wold withdrawe hem / from synne her thankes / but ay contynue in synne / for thylk perpetuell will/ to do synne shull &thorn;ey han perpetuell peyne /</P>
<P>[1070] Wanhope is in two maners / &thorn;e first wan|hope is / in &thorn;e mercy <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="270b">Of Crist / that other is &thorn;at &thorn;ey 
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="676"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="683"> thynken / &thorn;at &thorn;ey myght nat long perseuere in gode|nesse / [1071] the first wanhope comth comth of &thorn;at he demeth/ &thorn;at he hath synned so gretely and so oft/ and so long lyen in synne / &thorn;at he shall nat be saved [1072] Certein ayeinst &thorn;at cursed wanhope shold he &thorn;ynk &thorn;at &thorn;e passion of Ihesu Crist/ is more strong/ for to vnbynde / &thorn;anne synne is strong for to bynde / [1073] Ayeinst the secund wanhope / he shall thynk &thorn;at as oft / as he falleth/ he may arise ayein by penitence / and &thorn;ough he neuere so long haue leye in synne / &thorn;e mercy of crist / is all-wey redy to resceyue him to mercy / [1074] Ayeinst &thorn;e wanhope &thorn;at he demeth/ &thorn;at he shold nat long perseuere in godenesse / he shall thynk/ &thorn;at &thorn;e feblenesse of the devyll may no &thorn;yng don / but men woll suffre hym/[1075] And eke he shall have strength of the helpe of god / and of all holy chirche / and of &thorn;e proteccion of Aungels / yf hym list/</P>
<P>[1076] Than shull men vnderstonde what is &thorn;e fruyt of penaunce and after the worde of Ihesu Crist/ it is the endeles blysse of heven / [1077] &thorn;e ioye hath no contraritee of woo ne greuaunce / &thorn;ere all harmes ben passed of this present lyf / &thorn;ere as is the sekirnesse / from the pyne of hell/ there as is the blisfull companye / &thorn;at reioysen hem euermoo euerycch of others ioye [1078] there as the bodye of man &thorn;at whilom was foule and derk/ is more clere &thorn;anne &thorn;e sonne / &thorn;ere as &thorn;e body &thorn;at whilom was seke frele and feble and mortall/ is ymmortall/ and so strong/ and so hole / &thorn;at &thorn;ere may no thing appeire it/ [1079] there as ne is neither hunger thirst ne colde / But euery soule replenysshed with the sight of &thorn;e perfite knowyng of god [1080] This blisfull/ regne mow men purchace by pouertee espirituell/ and &thorn;e glorie by lowe|nesse the plentee of Ioye / by hunger and therst/ and &thorn;e rest by trauaill/ and the lyf by deth and mortificacion of synne ./.
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000699.tif" N="677"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="684">
<HEAD>Here the maker taketh His Leue /</HEAD>
<P>[1081]</P>
<P>Now pray I to hem all / &thorn;at herken this litle tretice/ or reden &thorn;at yf there be ony thyng in it / &thorn;at liketh hem that &thorn;ere-of &thorn;ey thanken our lord Ihesu Crist / of whom procedeth all witte / and all godenesse / [1082] and yf &thorn;ere be ony thyng &thorn;at displese hem I praye hem also arette it/ to the defaute of myn vnkonnyng / and nat to my will &thorn;at wold fayn haue seid better yf I hade connyng / [1083] for our boke seith/ all that is writen / is writen for our doctryne and &thorn;at is myn entent/ [1084] wherfore I beseche you mekely for &thorn;e mercy of god &thorn;at ye praye for me / &thorn;at crist haue mercy on me / and foryeve me my giltes [1085] and namely for my translacions and of enditynges of worldly vanitees<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>The old MS. ends here; the rest of the text is in an</I> 18<I>th century hand</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Perhaps from MS. Laud K 50, from which the Tale of Gamelyn, in 8 leaves, was copied by the 18th century hand, and put into this Egerton MS. as leaves 56-63.</NOTE>]</NOTE> <MILESTONE UNIT="Eg. 2726 folio" N="271a">the which I revoke in my Retraxions [1086] As is the Book of Troylus, the Boke also of Fame, the Boke of y<SUP>e</SUP> 25 Ladies, the Boke of the Duchesse, the Boke of Seint Valentyns day, of the Parlement of Briddes, the Tales of Cauntor|bury, thilke that sownen in-to Synne, [1087] the Boke of the Leon, &amp; many other Bokes if thei wer in my remembrance. And many a Song, &amp; many a lecherous lay. Criste for his mercy forgiffe y<SUP>e</SUP> Synne. [1088] But of y<SUP>e</SUP> Translacion of Boece de Consolacion, of other Bokes of Legendes of Seintes, and Omelies, and Moralite and Devocion, [1089] that thank I our Lord Ihesu Criste and his blessid Mother and all the Seintes of Heven, [1090] beseke hem that thei fro henes forth on to my Lyves end send me grace to be-weale my Giltes, and to stodien to the Savacion of my Soule, and greaunte me spase of veray penitence, con|fession 
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="678"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="685"> and satisfaccion, to don in this present Liffe, [1091] thorow the benigne grace of him that is Kynge of Kyngs and Prest of all Prests, that bough[t] us with the precious blod of his hert, [1092] So that I mot be on of hem at the day of Dome that shulbe saved.</P>
<TRAILER>Deo Gracias.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>here endith the Canterbury Tales compiled by Geffrey Chaucer, of whose soule Ihesu Crist haue mercy. Amen.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in red ink]</NOTE></TRAILER>
