<PB REF="00000709.tif" N="687">
<HEAD>2. The Hymn of Chaucer's Oxford Clerk, NICHOLAS, "ANGELUS AD VIRGINEM."
(Miller's Tale, Group A. l. 3216, p. 92, abuv.)</HEAD>

<DIV3 TYPE="Latin version (omitted)">
<HEAD>THE LATIN ORIGINAL: 'ANGELUS AD VIRGINEM'</HEAD>
<P>
</P>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="English version"><PB REF="00000710.tif" N="688">
<HEAD>ENGLISHT (rymes <I>ababcc, dde, cec</I>). Arundel MS. 248, leaf 154. Ab. 1250-60, A.D.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>1</HEAD>
<L>Gabriel fram evene king</L>
<L>sent to &thorn;e maide swete,</L>
<L>broute<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>e</I> is an overline insertion. In lines 3, 4, 26, 28, 53, 60, &amp;c. the '&thorn;' of &thorn;e, &thorn;ire, &thorn;ie, &thorn;erde, &amp;c. stands for 'h'.</NOTE> &thorn;ire blisful tiding,</L>
<L N="4">And faire &thorn;e gan hire greten:</L>
<L>"Heil be &thorn;u, ful of grace arith!</L>
<L N="6">"for godes sone, &thorn;is evene lith,</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">A later overline 'so' is before 'for'; but the line should be only 2 measures.</NOTE>for mannes louen,</L>
<L>"wile man bicomen,</L>
<L N="9">"and taken</L>
<L>"fles of &thorn;e, maiden brith,</L>
<L>"ma[n]ken fre for to maken</L>
<L N="12">"of senne and deules mith."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>2</HEAD>
<L>Mildeliche im gan andsweren</L>
<L>&thorn;e milde maiden &thorn;anne:</L>
<L>'wiche wise sold ichs beren</L>
<L N="16">child with-huten manne?'</L>
<L>&THORN;angle seide, "ne dred te nout!</L>
<L N="18">"&thorn;urw &thorn;oligast sal ben iwrout</L>
<L>"&thorn;is ilche &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"warof tiding</L>
<L N="21">"ichs bringe:</L>
<L>"al manken wrth ibout</L>
<L>"&thorn;ur &thorn;i swete chiltinge,</L>
<L N="24">"and hut of pine ibrout."
<PB REF="00000710.tif" N="688"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>3</HEAD>
<L N="25">Wan &thorn;e maiden understud,</L>
<L>and &thorn;angles wordes &thorn;erde,</L>
<L>mildeliche, with milde mud,</L>
<L N="28">to &thorn;angle &thorn;ie andswerde:</L>
<L>'Hure lordes &thorn;enmaiden iwis</L>
<L N="30">'ics am, &thorn;at her abouen is;</L>
<L>'aneftis me</L>
<L>'fulfurthed be</L>
<L N="33">'&thorn;i sawe,</L>
<L>'&thorn;at ics, sithen <NOTE PLACE="foot">'h' is an overline insertion.</NOTE>his wil is,</L>
<L>'maiden, with-huten lawe,</L>
<L N="36">'of moder haue &thorn;e blis.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>4</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;angle wente a-wei mid &thorn;an,</L>
<L>al hut of hire sichte;</L>
<L>and<NOTE PLACE="foot">'and' underdotted and struck through: but see '&amp;' in Latin, st. 4, l. 2.</NOTE> &thorn;ire wombe arise gan,</L>
<L N="40">&thorn;urw &thorn;oligastes mithe;</L>
<L>in hire was crist biloken anon,</L>
<L>suth god, soth man, ine fleas and bon;</L>
<L>and of hir fleas</L>
<L>iboren was</L>
<L N="45">at time,</L>
<L>war-&thorn;urw us kam god won,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bout us hut of pine,</L>
<L N="48">and let im for us slon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The 'n' is a taild final <I>n</I>, like a <I>y</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>5</HEAD>
<L>Maiden moder makeles,</L>
<L>of milche ful ibunden,</L>
<L>Bid for hus, im &thorn;at &thorn;e ches,</L>
<L N="52">at wam &thorn;u grace funde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e forgiue hus senne and wrake,</L>
<L N="54">and clene of euri gelt us make,</L>
<L>and eune blis,</L>
<L>wan hure time is</L>
<L N="57">to steruen,</L>
<L>hus giue, for &thorn;ine sake,</L>
<L>him so her for to seruen,</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;at &thorn;e us to him take.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
